 Center]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thunderbay.noaa.gov/visit/welcome.html|title=Visiting Thunder Bay National Marine Sanctuary|work=noaa.gov}}</ref> also known as [[Thunder Bay National Marine Sanctuary]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northeasternmichiganonline.com/html/museums.html|title=Museums|work=northeasternmichiganonline.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624063347/http://www.northeasternmichiganonline.com/html/museums.html|archivedate=2016-06-24}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\n<!-- Note:\n\u00b7 Only people who already have a Wikipedia article may appear here. This establishes notability.\n\u00b7 The article must mention how they are associated with Alpena, whether born, raised, or residing.\n\u00b7 The fact of their association should have a reliable source cited.\n\u00b7 Alphabetical by last name please.\n\u00b7 All others will be deleted.\n-->\n{{div col}}\n* [[Jesse Besser]], inventor and benefactor of the [[Besser Museum for Northeast Michigan]]; lived in Alpena\n* [[Paul Bunker]], [[1901 College Football All-America Team|1901]] and [[1902 College Football All-America Team|1902 All-American]] football player; [[College Football Hall of Fame]]r; born in Alpena\n* [[William Comstock]], [[List of Governors of Michigan|33rd governor of Michigan]]; born in Alpena\n* [[Leon Czolgosz]], assassin of U.S. President [[William McKinley]]; born in Alpena\n* [[Bob Devaney]], football coach for [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football]] and [[Wyoming Cowboys football]]; [[College Football Hall of Fame]]r; lived in Alpena\n* [[Brian Dutcher]], basketball coach for [[San Diego State Aztecs men's basketball|San Diego State]]; born in Alpena\n* [[Jim Dutcher (basketball)|Jim Dutcher]], former basketball head coach for [[Minnesota Gophers men's basketball|University of Minnesota]]; born in Alpena\n* [[Robert L. Emerson]], Michigan state Senator; born in Alpena\n* [[The Frost]], psychedelic rock band of the '60s and '70s originated in Alpena. Several members were born there. \n* [[Stanley Grenz]], Christian theologian; born in Alpena\n* [[Blaise Ilsley]], pitcher for the [[Chicago Cubs]]; born in Alpena\n* [[Lloyd R. Leavitt, Jr.]], United States Air Force general; born in Alpena\n* [[Betty Mahmoody]], author of ''[[Not Without My Daughter (book)|Not Without My Daughter]]''; lived in Alpena\n* [[Harvey Marlatt]], shooting guard for the [[Detroit Pistons]]; born in Alpena\n* [[Arthur William McLeod]], member of the [[Wisconsin State Assembly]]; born in Alpena\n* [[Joel Potrykus]], filmmaker (''[[Ape (2012 film)]]''); born in Alpena\n* [[Dan Rohn]], infielder for the [[Chicago Cubs]] and [[Cleveland Indians]]; born in Alpena\n* [[Paul Fitzpatrick Russell]], Roman Catholic archbishop and diplomat; lived in Alpena\n* [[Michael Bailey Smith]], actor (''[[Charmed]]''); born in Alpena\n* [[K. J. Stevens]], novelist and short story writer; born in Alpena\n* [[Kevin Young (baseball)|Kevin Young]], first baseman for the [[Kansas City Royals]] and [[Pittsburgh Pirates]]; born in Alpena\n{{div col end}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n* [[Bruce Willis]] and the film crew of ''[[Die Hard 2]]'' used [[Alpena County Regional Airport|Alpena's airport]] to shoot several scenes of the film. Although the location was selected because snow was expected to be integral to the movie (and was moved from [[Denver]]'s [[Stapleton Airport]] which had no snow), a dearth of precipitation in Alpena necessitated the use of artificial snow.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/mediatechnologyandtelecoms/media/8249245/Ten-famous-films-shot-in-Michigan.html?image=4 |title=Ten famous films shot in Michigan |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.michiganbusiness.org/499486/globalassets/documents/film/die_hard_2_tour_2.pdf |format=PDF |title=Die Hard 2 |publisher=Michigan Business forums |accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Michigan}}\n* [[Alpena Light]]\n* [[Alpena Power Company]]\n* [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Gaylord]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=upper-alpha}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Alpena, Michigan}}\n* [http://www.alpena.mi.us/ City of Alpena's official website]\n* [http://www.michigansnowcams.com/webcams/alpena.htm Harbor webcam, Alpena]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080410053958/http://soildatamart.nrcs.usda.gov/Manuscripts/MI007/0/Alpena_MI.pdf Alpena County Soil Survey, U.S. Dept. of Agriculture, Michigan State University Extension Service (soil, history, good general information)]\n* [http://clarke.cmich.edu/localhistory/Alpena.htm Clarke Historical Library, Central Michigan University, Bibliography on Alpena, Michigan]\n\n{{Northern Michigan}}\n{{Alpena County, Michigan}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Alpena County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:County seats in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Populated places on Lake Huron in the United States]]\n[[Category:Micropolitan areas of Michigan]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1840]]\n[[Category:1840 establishments in Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "Notorious4life", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGeography and climate", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alpena,_Michigan"}
{"title_page": "Military parade", "text_new": "[[Image:Tag des Sieges 1.JPG|thumb|300px|Parade at the [[Victory Day (Turkey)|Victory Day]] (Zafer Bayram\u0131) in Istanbul]]\n[[File:US Navy 050120-F-3231D-692 he U.S. Navy Honor Guard marches past President George W. Bush during the 2005 Presidential Inaugural Parade held in Washington D.C.jpg|thumb|300px|[[United States]] Presidential Inaugural Parade held in [[Washington D.C.]]]]\n[[Image:ESM Saint-Cyr 14 07 07.jpg|thumb|300px|right|[[\u00c9cole sp\u00e9ciale militaire de Saint-Cyr|Saint-Cyr cadets]] at the [[Bastille Day Military Parade]] on the [[Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]]]]\n[[File:2june 2007 580.jpg|thumb|300px|right|[[Carabinieri Cavalry Regiment]] at the military parade of ''[[Festa della Repubblica]]'' 2007]]\n\nA '''military parade''' is a formation of soldiers whose movement is restricted by close-order manoeuvering known as '''drilling''' or '''marching'''. The military [[parade]] is now almost entirely ceremonial, though soldiers from time immemorial up until the late 19th century fought in formation. Massed parades may also hold a role for propaganda purposes, being used to exhibit the apparent military strength of one's nation.\n\n==History==\n\nThe terminology comes from the tradition of \n[[close order formation]] combat, in which soldiers were held in very strict formations as to maximise their combat effectiveness. Formation combat was used as an alternative to [[m\u00eal\u00e9e]] combat, and required strict discipline in the ranks and competent officers. As long as their formations could be maintained, regular troops could maintain a significant advantage over less organised opponents. Military parades are not to be confused with military show of force.\n\nAlthough the firepower of breechloading rifles and [[machine guns]] long ago rendered close formations in battle suicidal, modern armies still use parades for ceremonial purposes or in non-combat environments for their efficiency, ease of organization and encouragement of discipline. Roughly synonymous are \"drill\" and \"march\". The English word \"drill\" is of [[Middle Dutch]] origin, dating from the 16th-century drill of the Dutch army of prince [[Maurice of Orange]], which was widely copied throughout Europe at the time, decreasing the volley time of musket formations.\n\nIn ancient times, drilling increased in importance when men stopped fighting as individuals and began to fight together as units. Drilling as a vital component of a war machine further increased with the increases in the size of armies, for example when [[Phillip II of Macedon]] disciplined his army so they could swiftly form the [[Phalanx formation|phalanxes]] that were so critical to his successes as a general. Military drilling later was used by the [[Roman Army]] to maximise efficiency and deadliness throughout their long history. After the fall of the empire, and the [[Dark Ages (historiography)|Dark Ages]] set in Europe, most feudal lords more heavily relied on peasant levies and their wealthy [[knights]] to fight their wars, the knights for the most part reverting to fighting as individuals{{Citation needed|date=April 2015}}. Massed military drilling was used mostly by only the foremost armies and nations, such as the [[Normans]].\n\nThe U.S. drill is based on the contributions of [[Baron von Steuben]], a [[Prussian Army]] officer who served in the [[Continental Army]].<ref>Paul Lockhart, ''The Drillmaster of Valley Forge: The Baron de Steuben and the Making of the American Army'' (Washington, DC: Smithsonian Books, 2008)</ref> During the winter quarters in [[Valley Forge]], Pennsylvania, von Steuben taught a model company of 100 soldiers musket drill. These soldiers, in turn, taught the remainder of the Continental Army.\n\nThe most familiar form of [[melee weapon]] and [[unarmed combat]] drill in the modern world is the [[Kata]] and the [[Hyung]] in Eastern [[martial arts]]. However, there were once similar drills in the martial training of warriors in all cultures worldwide. They all had exactly the same purpose, to make instinctive an appropriate reaction to an attack or opening by conditioning the mind and body, through repeated and constant repetition of a series of actions (building up [[muscle memory]]). Probably one of the last survivors of such drills in the Western martial tradition are the reaction drills and rhythm exercises in the modern sport of [[fencing]].\n\n[[File:\u0411\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0434\u044b\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043c\u0430\u0448\u0438\u043d\u0430 SandCat.JPG|thumb|Parade during [[Defender of the Fatherland Day (Kazakhstan)|Defender of the Fatherland Day]] in [[Nur-Sultan]].]]\n\nThe oldest, largest and most famous regular military parade in [[Europe]] is the [[Bastille Day Military Parade]] which is held each 14 July, on the [[Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]] in [[Paris]], during [[Bastille Day|France's national day]] celebrations.<ref name=\"paris1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.paris.com/paris_city_guide/city_visits_of_paris/champs_elysees_arc_de_triomphe |title=Champs-Elys\u00e9es city visit in Paris, France - Recommended city visit of Champs-Elys\u00e9es in Paris |publisher=Paris.com |accessdate=2011-07-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807091009/http://www.paris.com/paris_city_guide/city_visits_of_paris/champs_elysees_arc_de_triomphe |archivedate=2011-08-07 }}</ref><ref name=\"paris-attractions1\">\n{{cite web\n |url=http://paris-attractions.net/celebrate-bastille-day-in-paris-this-year/\n |title=Celebrate Bastille Day in Paris This Year\n |publisher=Paris Attractions |date=2011-05-03\n |accessdate=2011-07-27 |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326174027/http://paris-attractions.net/celebrate-bastille-day-in-paris-this-year/\n |archivedate=2012-03-26 }}\n</ref>\n\n==Rationale==\n[[File:Queen's Birthday Parade, Hamilton Bermuda 2000.jpg|thumb|Queen's Birthday Parade, [[Hamilton, Bermuda]], 2000.]]\nA military drill is memorizing certain actions through repetition until the action is instinctive to the soldiers being drilled. Complex actions are broken down into simpler ones which can be practised in isolation so when the whole is put together the desired results are achieved. Such is necessary for a fighting force to perform at maximum efficiency in all manner of situations. However, depending on the army and the drills it adopts, drilling may destroy flexibility and initiative in exchange for predictability and cohesion.\n\nRecruits in most modern militaries are taught drill to teach them how to work and move as a team. In addition, formations are still used in [[riot control]], where m\u00eal\u00e9e combat is still the norm.\n\n==Four directions==\n[[File:2010 Moscow Victory Day Parade-5.jpeg|thumb|[[2010 Moscow Victory Day Parade]]]]\nParades consist of four directions:\n# Advance\n# Retire\n# Left\n# Right\n\nThe Advance is the primary direction of movement, regardless of which direction the soldiers are actually facing (similar to a ship's [[Bow (ship)|bow]].) On a parade square, the advance is determined by the position of the [[dais]] or flags. When these are not present, the direction of the drill commander is the advance.\n\nThe Retire is opposite to the advance, against the primary direction of movement (similar to a ship's [[stern]].)\n\nThe Left is to the left of the Advance (similar to a ship's [[Port (nautical)|port]].)\n\nThe Right is to the right of the Advance (similar to a ship's [[starboard]].)\n\nIf the Advance is changed, then all other directions are changed to be based on the new Advance.\n\nThere is only one person in charge of a parade at a time. Changing this person is very ceremonious. This is to make it obvious to the soldiers who is currently in command and therefore to whom to pay attention.\n\nDuring parades, unless explicitly told otherwise, soldiers have restricted movement, meaning they can move only exactly when they are told, and then doing only exactly what they are told to do. In most stances, any movement at all is disallowed and is held to such an extent as to have soldiers fainting on parade, although fainting under any conditions short of plural hours standing still in the hot sun is considered a sign of medical disability.<ref name=indianman>{{cite web|last=Srivastava|first=Vikram|title=Drills and Parades|url=http://bprd.nic.in/writereaddata/mainlinkFile/File965.pdf|work=Police Drill Manual|publisher=Bureau of Police Research and Development, Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India|accessdate=21 February 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206154713/http://bprd.nic.in/writereaddata/mainlinkFile/File965.pdf|archivedate=6 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nAmerican usage allows the service member to be at four states of alert:\n# [[At attention|Attention]]: standing straight, eyes forward, chest out, knees straight but not locked, feet together at a 45-degree angle.\n# Parade Rest: A modified position of attention in which the left foot is moved to shoulder width (typically measured as exactly 12 inches) and the hands are placed in the small of the back with the right hand placed inside the left with all fingers together and pointing rigidly straight (exception: U.S. Air Force usage is modelled after Commonwealth practice - see below).\n# Stand At Ease: Same as Parade Rest, but the soldier may look at the speaker.\n# At Ease: The service member is allowed to move around all but the right foot, but must remain silent.\n# Rest: Service member may talk, smoke (if command authorized) and may move as long as their right pivot foot remains grounded.\nA formation must be brought to the position of attention before it can go to a higher state of alert.<ref name=\"army\">FM 22-5, Drill and Ceremonies, Headquarters, Department of the Army, 1986</ref><ref name=\"marine\">NAVMC 2691 Marine Corps Drill and Ceremonies Manual, Headquarters, United States Marine Corps, 1981</ref>\n\n[[Commonwealth of Nations]] countries allow four states of alert:\n# Attention: standing straight, eyes forward, heels together, feet at a 30-degree angle (540 mils). The hands are held in tight fists with the thumbs aligned with the seam of the trousers.\n# At Ease: a modified position of attention in which the left foot is moved to shoulder width and the hands are placed behind the back with arms fully extended. The right hand is placed inside the left. [[United States|U.S.]] military usage is \"Parade Rest.\"\n# Stand-Easy: Legs remain in the At Ease position, arms are brought to the sides to a more natural standing position. Member may relax their muscles and make minimal movements. U.S. usage is \"At Ease,\" however a common mistake in U.S. military practice confuses \"At Ease\" with \"Rest\" (below).\n# Relax: Legs remain at position at ease, member may make more significant movements or look around. Members may not move the feet. If the troops are not being addressed by a commander, they are generally allowed to talk quietly. U.S. usage is \"Rest.\"\n\n==Common parade commands==\n*'''Fall In'''. Have designated troops move into an already existing formation on the parade square and/or ground.\n*'''Fall Out'''. Have designated troops wheel out and to the right of their formation, then halt facing the parade commander to be dismissed.\n*'''Dis -Miss'''. Telling designated units to leave the parade square and stop drilling. \n*'''[Parade Size]/Parade, [Parade Size], Atten-Tion (Shun)''' (U.S.: '''Atten - Tion (Shun)'''). Have the soldiers uniformly adopt the [[At attention|Attention position]], the most constrictive position (with feet together), but the only position from which soldiers can actually be made to move. In the United States military, the position is defined as heels together, feet at a 45-degree angle, arms straight, palms inward with fingers naturally curled, thumbs along the seams of trousers, shoulders square and head erect, looking forward. In the Royal Navy, the order \"Shun\" is replaced with the order \"Ho\". For Example, the most common usage is \"Guard Ho!\" With a small pause between words.\n\n===Alignment commands===\n\n====Commonwealth version====\n[[Image:Royal Military College of Canada cadets drill in parade square, Stone Frigate 1880s.jpg|thumb|right|220px|[[Royal Military College of Canada]] cadets drill in Military parade square, in front of [[HMCS Stone Frigate|Stone Frigate]] 1880s]]\n*'''Right Dress''', - all personnel in front row and right side column except the right marker take one step forward, pause, and only the front rank bring up their right arms parallel to the ground. At the same time, all members of the formation snap their heads so they are facing right. After this, they pause, and then shuffle back to a new position, where their hand is extremely close to the soldier's shoulder on their right, unless otherwise specified (Elbow Dressing, Shoulder Dressing).  Some Armies, e.g. the Australian Army, will raise the left arm (the right arm holding the service weapon).\n*'''Left Dress''', - all personnel in front row and left column except the left marker take one step forward, pause, and only the front rank bring up their left arms parallel to the ground. At the same time, all members of the formation snap their heads so they are facing left. After this, they pause, and then shuffle back to a new position, where their hand is extremely close to the soldier's shoulder on their right, unless otherwise specified (Elbow Dressing, Shoulder Dressing).\n*'''Inwards Dress/Centre Dress''', used when a parade is formed up in two or more groups with [[Military colours, standards and guidons|Colours, Guidons, or Banners]] on parade.  This is used so that dressing is off the colours.  The formations to the left of the Colour Party will dress to the right and the formations to the right of the Colour Party will dress to the left.   All personnel to the right of the Colours in front row and left column except the left marker take one step forward, pause, and only the front rank bring up their left arms parallel to the ground. At the same time, all members of the formation snap their heads so they are facing left. All personnel to the left of the colours in front row and right side column except the right marker take one step forward, pause, and only the front rank bring up their right arms parallel to the ground. At the same time, all members of the formation snap their heads so they are facing right. Some Armies, i.e. the Australian Army, will raise the left arm (the right arm holding the service weapon).  After this, they pause, and then shuffle back to a new position, where their hand is extremely close to the soldier's shoulder on their left or right (depending on the direction of dressing), unless otherwise specified (Elbow Dressing, Shoulder Dressing).\n*'''Eyes Front''', following Right/Left/Inwards Dress, the front rank snaps their arms down and faces forward, while all other ranks simply face forward.\n\n====American version====\n*'''Dress Right, DRESS''' - all personnel in the unit except the soldiers at the far left bring up their left arms parallel to the ground and at the same time snap their heads so they are facing right.  The person on the far right will keep his head straight. After this, they pause, and then shuffle back to a new position, where their hand is extremely close to the soldier's shoulder on their left.  If the command is preceded by '''\"At Close Interval\"''', the left arm is bent at the elbow rather than parallel to the ground.  If the command is preceded by '''\"At Double Interval\"''', both arms are extended.  '''\"Dress Left\"''' reverses the instructions (Right arm up, look left).\n*'''Ready, FRONT''' - all personnel snap their arms down and faces forward.\n*'''COVER''' - used after any movement is halted to realign the formation.  All personnel in the formation except the squad leaders make short, choppy steps to align themselves with their squad leaders, then come to attention.<ref name = \"army\"/><ref name = \"marine\"/>\n\n===Rest positions===\n[[File:A Member of the Queen's Guards, Guarding the Mall - geograph.org.uk - 1354107.jpg|thumb|190px|A British [[Household Division]] soldier in the position of at ease.]]\n[[File:120416-Z-KZ880-024 (7109575235).jpg|thumb|American honour guards in the ceremonial at ease position.]]\n*'''Stand at Ease''' (U.S.: '''PARADE REST'''). Have the soldiers adopt the more relaxed position At Ease position, with feet shoulder width apart, hands clasped behind back but with upper body half still in position of attention (chest out, shoulders back). This is typically used when soldiers must wait a short duration, ready to adopt the position of attention e.g. if waiting for an Officer to arrive for an inspection. Changing from At Ease to Attention and back again, or the converse, is standard when the command of a parade is transferred (typically between the commanding officer and his Sergeant-Major), since command of a formation is not actually transferred until the new commander makes a command. There is no talking allowed at Parade Rest; personnel must come to the position of attention before speaking.\n*'''Stand at Ease''' (U.S.) This is the same as Parade Rest, except that soldiers are expected to turn their heads to look at whoever is addressing them. This should not be confused with At Ease.\n*'''Stand Easy'''. (U.S.: '''AT EASE''') Have the soldiers adopt the next easiest stance, where hands are still clasped behind the back, however, the soldiers can relax their upper bodies (the shoulders can be slacked) and quietly speak. This is often, but not always, followed by an implicit 'Relax' ('Rest'). This is typically used when being addressed/lectured for a long period of time where the positions of attention or at ease would be too painful/uncomfortable to hold.\n*'''Relax''' (U.S.: '''REST''') The only parade instruction given in an ordinary voice, rather than the raised, emphatic parade voice. This is the only position that actually offers soldiers freedom of movement. Soldiers are typically allowed to move other than moving their feet, though, when it is given by a high-ranking officer, soldiers typically move a minimal amount after a bit of stretching.\n\n===Marching with weapons/saluting===\n'''[[Rifle]]s'''\n*'''Shoulder/Slope Arms''': Although Left and Right Shoulder Arms are both valid commands, left is assumed if it is unstated. Soldiers must be at attention to shoulder weapons. This is typically done through a throw rather than a carry. In British and Commonwealth parades, the command \"Slope Arms\" is used to order soldiers to place their rifles on the top of the shoulder. The command of \"Shoulder Arms\" in the Commonwealth and Britain, is done when a rifle is brought on the left or right sides by the shoulder with the carrying hand holding the pistol grip. In US ceremonies, if the soldiers have the weapons at the order, then it is brought up and carried on the right shoulder, and all shoulder commands must specify the shoulder, and may be performed while [[military step|marching in step]].\n*'''Port Arms''': The weapon is brought out in front of the soldier, and held by the right hand on small of the butt, or equivalent, and the left hand about the forestock, or equivalent. Usually this command is used for preparation of the Feu De Joie/Fire of Joy for parades. In the United States, Port Arms is the required carry position for marching at [[military step|double time]].\n*'''[[Present arms (command)|Present Arms]]''': The soldiers bring their weapons to the front of their bodies, and move adjust their right foot position. Soldiers without weapons use a salute appropriate for their headdress. Often officers can salute on behalf of their troops, and any such ambiguity will be discussed with the troops beforehand. This, in the case of the United Kingdom and the Commonwealth of Nations, is often used with the precautionary General/Commander's Salute or Royal/Presidential/Prime Minister's Salute, when appropriate. In U.S. usage, all soldiers salute, except if he or she is holding a weapon. Guidons and organizational colors are dipped to 90 degrees above the ground (but not touching the ground, but in the Commonwealth it is common practice). The U.S. national colors are never dipped (it is also the case in Colombia, Chile, Brazil and Spain) but the British or Commonwealth national colors are dipped to the ground when the salute is performed. This command is used whenever saluting during ceremonial inspections in most countries (like Germany, France, Russia, Poland, Italy, Serbia and Ukraine as well as in Chile, Argentina, Ecuador and Colombia), and eyes are pointed to either the left, on the front, or the right to the direction of the honors being paid to. The command for recovery is \"Shoulder/Slope Arms!\" or \"Order Arms!\" depending on the situation.\n*'''Order Arms''': If the soldiers are carrying a weapon which can be ordered they will lower it so that is resting on the ground, touching the outer toes of the right boot, and being supported by a slightly bent right arm. Usually given in Shoulder/Slope Arms or Present Arms position.\n*'''Ground Arms''': The soldier takes a full pace forward, bending their knees, so the right leg is parallel to the floor below the knee, and at the same time leaning forward and laying their rifles down to the ground (ejection port up). They then take the appropriate pause time, then stand up into attention.\n*'''Trail Arms''': Same as Order Arms but with hands holding on the rifle above the ground.\n*'''Sling Arms''': If the soldiers have a \"[[sling (firearms)|sling]]\" (strap) on their rifles, then this command can be called. The soldiers will loosen the sling so they can now have their rifles strapped around their shoulders.\n*'''Unsling Arms''': Servicemen will unloosen the sling so they can now have their rifles at the port or high port position.\n*'''Front Sling Arms''': Servicemen holding weapons with slings attached to the chest now sling those weapons in the Port or High Port Arms position.\n*'''High Port Arms''': This is a higher variant of Port Arms, with both arms holding the weapon high. \n*'''Fire of Joy, load weapons''': This command is used in parades such as the [[Singapore National Day Parade|National Day Parade in Singapore]], and [[Trooping the Colour]]. The soldier will load the rifle with the blank round in preparation of the [[Feu de joie]], French for Fire of Joy in parades. This is called in Polish as the ''Salwa Honorowa'' or Honor Volley.\n*'''Fix Bayonets''': In US ceremonies, whenever the bayonets are to be fixed to the weapons, this command is called out. In times, the accompanying bugle call for it is used before the order is done. The troops pull out their bayonets from their uniforms and attach them to the weapon.\n*'''Unfix Bayonets''': Soldiers in formation remove their bayonets from their rifles and return them to their uniforms.\n\n'''[[Sabre]]s'''\n*'''Draw Sabres''': used to draw the sabres.\n*'''Return Sabres''': used to return the sabres.\n*'''Present Sabres''': used for officers to salute using their sabres.\n*'''Shoulder/Slope Sabres''': used for officers to slope the sabre in their left-hand shoulder.\n*'''Order Sabres''': the sabre is lowered to the ground after presenting or sloping.\n\n=== Forming the parade for the march past/pass in review ===\n[[File:Pass and Review.jpg|thumb|Marine Corps General [[Joseph Dunford]], takes part in a pass in review of the [[Ceremonial Guard (Canada)|Ceremonial Guard]] in [[Ottawa]], [[Canada]].]]\n*'''Pass in Review''' - used in the US to denote the start of the march past segment of parades. When this command is said the parade prepares in readiness for the march past. It is also used as a way for a newly assigned commander to inspect the troops he/she commands.<ref>{{cite web | title=Air Force ROTC Detachment 225, Pass in Review | website=University of Notre Dame | date=2019-06-18 | url=https://afrotc.nd.edu/det-225-history/military-functions/pass-in-review/ | access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://idioms.thefreedictionary.com/pass+in+review|title=Pass in Rview|website=TheFreeDictionary.com}}</ref>\n* '''Parade, in close order, left/right dress''' - in the UK, this command is used to commence dressing of parade units in close order\n* '''Company, in close order, form three/four ranks''' - in the UK, this command is used to form companies into three or four ranks of personnel each\n* '''Staff behind me, (forward) march''' - in the US, this command is used by the parade commander to form his parade staff in readiness for the march past/pass in review segment of parades\n* '''Parade will now advance/retire in slow/quick time, about turn''' - in the Commonwealth the command is used to form parade formations when arranged in line formation for the march past\n\n===Compliments and Saluting===\n\n====Saluting on the march====\nIn the Commonwealth countries, the following saluting on the march commands are ordered with a preparatory command of ''''Saluting on the march...''''. For example, ''''Saluting on the march, to the front Salute'''' and always called on the left foot.\n*'''To the front Salute''' or '''Salute''': The parade is halted and the right arm is raised so the forearm is placed at a 90\u00b0 angle, while pointing at the temple. This is lowered and then repeated again, followed by an about turn and a resume in marching (off the left foot). The timing is: \"Call, Check, Halt, 2, 3, Up, 2, 3, Down, 2, 3, 4, 5, Up, 2, 3, Down, 2, 3, About, 2, 3, In, 2, 3, Left, Right, Left!\" It is one of, if not the longest drill movement in the military.\nIn British Corps, the drill movement for saluting to the front is the following. Two, three, up. Two, three, down.\n*'''To the Right Salute''': The right arm is raised so the forearm is placed at a 90\u00b0 angle, while pointing at the temple. It is generally to a count of \"Up, two, three, four, five, down, swing!\"\n:This is done while looking to the right, except the right marker, who must stay looking to the front, to keep the flight, squad, platoon, etc. staying straight.\n*'''To the Left Salute''': The right arm is raised so the forearm is placed at a 90\u00b0 angle, while pointing at the temple. It is generally to a count of \"Up, two, three, four, five, down, away!\"\n:This is done while looking to the left, except the left marker (as they are the front most of the saluting flank), who must stay looking to the front, to keep the flight, squad, platoon, etc. staying straight.\n\nIn the United States, the command for saluting on the march is \"Eyes, RIGHT/LEFT.\" The parade leader and other officers execute the hand salute, while everyone but the right file or left file in either case turns their heads to the right.\" The command for recovery is \"Ready, FRONT.\" If the command does not have rifles, they will salute if given the command '''present ARMS'''. The arms will be lowered back to their normal position on the commands '''Order ARMS'''. They can also salute if given the command '''Hand SALUTE'''. The salute is raised when the parade leader finishes saying \"salute\", and is lowered in after being held for the same amount of time elapsed between the words \"hand\" and \"salute.\"\n\n=== Compliments on the March ===\n\n*'''Eyes Right''': The parade turn their heads to the right after a check pace. The parade leader salutes while looking in the direction they gave.\n:This is done while looking to the right, except the right marker, who must stay looking to the front, to keep the flight, squad, platoon, etc. staying straight.\n*'''Eyes Left''': Similar to the '''Eyes Right''' except the parade looks to the left.\n:This is done while looking to the left, except the left marker, who must stay looking to the front, to keep the flight, squad, platoon, etc. staying straight.\n\n====Saluting at the halt (static)====\n*'''To the front Salute''' or '''Salute''': The right arm is raised so the forearm is placed at a 90\u00b0 angle, while pointing at the temple. It is generally to a count of \"Up, two, three, down!\"\n*'''To the Right Salute''': The right arm is raised so the forearm is placed at a 90\u00b0 angle, while pointing at the temple. It is generally to a count of \"Up, two, three, down!\" \n*'''To the Left Salute''': The right arm is raised so the forearm is placed at a 90\u00b0 angle, while pointing at the temple. It is generally to a count of \"Up, two, three, down!\"\nIn the United States, salutes at a halt are given on the command \"Hand Salute\". They are lowered in the same amount of time elapsed between the two words. The command \"present arms\" will cause the command to salute if the command is not given rifles for the ceremony, but the salute will be held until they are ordered to lower it with the command \"order arms\".\n*'''Advance in Review Order''': This is used to pay final compliments to the reviewing officer. On the command: ADVANCE IN REVIEW ORDER, BY THE CENTRE, QUICK...MARCH, the unit being reviewed advances 15 paces and halts automatically before presenting arms to the reviewing officer. It is usually employed by the [[British Army]] and the [[Canadian Army]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.2824cops.com/wp-content/uploads/Army-Cadet-Reference-Manual.pdf|title=Royal Canadian Army Cadets: Cadet Reference Book|publisher=National Defence|year=2001|location=Canada|oclc=289058362|id=A-CR-CCP-121/PT-001}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.napoleon-series.org/cgi-bin/forum/archive2006_config.pl?md=read;id=67469|title=Historical Need for Drill|website=www.napoleon-series.org}}</ref>\n\n===Colour commands===\n\n====Marching with colours====\n*'''Let Fly the Colours''': The colours are normally held in a semi-taut position. This is a simple, ceremonial letting fly and catching of the colours.\n*'''Slant Colours''': The colours are normally kept upright, but this can represent a problem both when dealing with standard doors. This slants the colours forward sufficiently to negate this, and they are brought back up afterward.\n*'''Slope/Shoulder Colours''': The normal method for carrying colours can be tiresome for the bearer. This has the colours taken out of their frogs and sloped over the right shoulder at about 45\u00b0.\n\n====Colour commands at the halt (static)====\n*'''Order Colours''': Essentially the same as Order Arms, except used exclusively for the Colour Party.\n*'''Carry Colours''': This is equivalent to Shoulder Arms. The right arm lifts the colours up so they line up with the body's centre line, with the right arm held in front of the soldier, at mouth level parallel to the ground. It is caught and guided into its frog with left hand, which is then returned to its side.\n*'''Change colours''': This is used when the senior flag officer decides that he/she and the other flag holding members, have held their flags for a long time, and that their arms are tired, so, when the command \"Change - colours!\" is given, the flag holders put their arms in line with the flag, their other hand on top of their first hand and move the first hand down to attention, so that the other hand is now at the first hands' original position.\n\n===Turning motions===\n\n===Turning motions at the march===\n*'''Right Turn''' (U.S.:'''Column right, MARCH'''): A 90\u00b0 turn to the right done by rotating on the right heel and left ball. The cautionary and executive are both called on the left foot. The left leg is then brought up to be parallel to the ground (although exceptions are made for kilted regiments) and slammed into the ground in the position of attention. This motion is done at a particular fixed point.\n*'''Left Turn''' (U.S.:'''Column left, MARCH'''): A 90\u00b0 turn to the left, done by rotation on the right ball and the left heel. The right leg is then brought up to be parallel to the ground and slammed down into attention. This motion is done at a particular fixed point.\n*'''About Turn''' (U.S.: '''To the rear, MARCH'''): A 180\u00b0 turn to the right, done as an exaggerated version of the right turn. United States units do not make exaggerated gestures with the legs or arms.\n*'''Right Flank MARCH''' or '''Right turn''', it is still the same even on the march for some countries: All members marching execute 90\u00b0 turn to the right done by rotating on the right heel and left ball.\n*'''Left Flank MARCH''' or '''Left turn''', it is still the same even on the march for some countries: All members marching 90\u00b0 turn to the left, done by rotation on the right ball and the left heel.\n*'''Right Incline''' (U.S.:'''Column half-right, MARCH'''), is a half turn to the right, usually used when a flight, squad, platoon, etc. is not in its proper alignment. All members marching turn by 45\u00b0 to the right, done by rotation on the left ball and the right heel.\n*'''Left Incline''' (U.S.:'''Column half-left, MARCH'''), is a half turn to the left, usually used when a flight, squad, platoon, etc. is not in its proper alignment. All members marching turn by 45\u00b0 to the left, done by rotation on the right ball and the left heel.\n*'''Right Wheel''', is a turn to the right, differentiated from a Right Turn in that the order of march remains the same. \n*'''Left Wheel''', is a mirror of the Right Wheel.\n\n====Turning motions at the halt (static)====\n\n'''[[United States Armed Forces]]:'''\n\n*'''Right Face''': The body is rotated on the heel of the right foot and then the left heel is brought forward to meet the right heel in the position of attention.\n*'''Left Face''': A mirror image of Right Face.\n*'''About Face''': The right toe is brought back to behind the left heel; the body pivots on the right toe and left heel 180\u00b0.\n*'''Half-Left Face''': Exactly the same as a left face, but one turns only 45\u00b0.\n*'''Half-Right Face''': Exactly the same as a right face, but one turns only 45\u00b0.\n\n'''[[Commonwealth of Nations]]'''\n\n*'''Right Turn''': The body is rotated 90\u00b0 to the right members shall bend the left knee, straighten it in double time and smartly place the left foot beside the right to assume the position of attention. In the Royal Navy, the heel movements mirror that of the US Armed Forces.\n*'''Left Turn''': A mirror image of Right Turn.\n*'''About Turn''': The body is rotated 180\u00b0 in a clockwise direction, knees locked. Members shall bend the left knee, straighten it in double time and smartly place the left foot beside the right to assume the position of attention. In the Royal Navy heel movements are the same for Right Face.\n*'''Right Incline''': Exactly the same as a right turn, but one turns only 45\u00b0.\n*'''Left Incline''': Exactly the same as a left turn, but one turns only 45\u00b0.\n\n===Marching motions===\n{{main|Military step}}\n*'''Quick March''': The standard pace is typically 116 beats/minute with a 30in. step.  There is also a '''Rifleman's Pace''', 140 beats/minute and a '''Highland Pace''', 110 beats/minute (typically done with a kilt.) The pace is based on the individual regiments, the pace given by the commander, and the speed of the band's rhythm. The way the march is performed depends on the regiment's nationality.\n*'''Slow March''': This is a ceremonial pace, used for funerals and when a unit's colours are marched out in front of the troops. The standard pace is 65 beats per minute.\n*'''Half Step March''' or '''Cut the pace''':\n:*This is a U.S. march pace. It is at the same tempo as Quick Time, but instead of 30 inches, the step is 15 inches.\n:*There is also a Canadian and Commonwealth version of this, used for when the front file/rank is getting too far ahead of the rest of the flight, squad, or platoon, it means that front file/rank should make their steps smaller, to allow for the rest of the flight, squad, or platoon, to get back into proper dressing.\n*'''Double March''': This is essentially a moderate jog at approximately 180 paces per minute. It creates a travel speed of approximately double that of Quick Time, designed to be used even when carrying heavy burdens. This is often erroneously used to describe a sprint or an ordinary run. The U.S. command is '''\"Double Time, MARCH.\"'''\n*'''Easy March''': This is an unrestricted march at approximately Quick Time. This is designed for field marches and other rough conditions, though is not used in combat areas. The U.S. command is '''\"Route Step, MARCH.\"''' In the Canadian Forces the command '''\"March at, EASE\"''' is given while the unit is on the march. It can not be given from the halt.\n*'''[[Military mark time|Mark Time]]''': This is essentially a [[Military mark time|stationary march]] with the knees coming up parallel to the ground or the foot dangling six inches off of the ground. This is designed to maintain the time of large parades when portions need no forward speed. The U.S. equivalent command is \"'''Mark Time, MARCH'''.\"\n*'''Step For -Ward''' or '''Forward''' or '''Forward, March''': This causes troops marking time to resume a normal march.\n\n==Modern era==\n[[File:2013. \u0414\u0435\u043d\u044c \u041f\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0434\u044b \u0432 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0435 181.jpg|thumb|Cadets parade in [[Donetsk]], [[Ukraine]].]]\n\nDrill is today used to demonstrate discipline and cohesion in a modern military force. Large military parades are today held on major holidays and military events around the world. It usually held on occasions of national importance such as a country's independence day, and therefore is presided over by the head of state who, in most cases, is the commander in chief of the combined national military forces of that country. Today, military parades include all aspects of military drill, from an [[exhibition drill]] of precision drill teams and [[military band]]s (in addition to the occasional [[corps of drums]], [[fanfare band]], and/or [[Drum and bugle corps (classic)|drum and bugle corps]]), as well as an exhibition of military weapons such as a mobile column, the occasional mounted cavalry column (led by a [[mounted band]]), a naval parade, and a fly past by the country's [[air force]]. When on parade, most of the participating soldiers wear their [[Full dress uniform|ceremonial uniforms]] and carry the standards/colours of their respective battalions/regiments/corps/academies. In many countries, the military contingent is joined by contingents from youth cadet organizations, personnel from the police and fire services and by occasion jail and border services, youth police and fire cadets, veterans and personnel of the civil service.\n\n===By country ===\n==== Albania ====\n[[Albania]] has long been influenced by Greek and Italian influences and even Soviet/Russian tradition. During the era of the [[People's Socialist Republic of Albania]], [[Liberation Day (Albania)|Liberation Day]], which then the main national holiday, was celebrated with a military parade of the [[Albanian People's Army]] on [[Tirana]]'s [[D\u00ebshmor\u00ebt e Kombit Boulevard]]. These parades have been held in 1954,<ref>{{cite book|title=The Current Digest of the Soviet Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QvMRAAAAIAAJ|volume=Vol 6|year=1954|publisher=American Association for the Advancement of Slavic Studies.}}</ref> 1959,<ref>{{cite book|author=United States Foreign Broadcast Information Service|title=Daily Report: Foreign Radio Broadcasts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wi0jAQAAMAAJ|year=1959}}</ref> 1964, 1974,<ref>{{cite book|title=Daily Report: People's Republic of China|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P5sbAQAAMAAJ|year=1974|publisher=U.S. Foreign Broadcast Information Service}}</ref> 1984<ref>{{cite book|title=Soviet Analyst|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PrVpAAAAMAAJ|volume=13-14|year=1984}}</ref> and 1989. They usually consist of veterans, [[schoolchildren]], militiamen alongside regular force personnel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazetadita.al/parada-ushtarake-forca-e-shtetit-tanke-dhe-raketa-ne-bulevard/|title=PHOTO: Here's how the military parades unfolded before 1990 |last=Veizi |first=Leonard |date=2019-01-13 |website=Gazeta Dita |language=sq|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://shekulli.com.al/7904/|title=70s-80s parades, tanks and rockets on the boulevard|last=Veizi|first=Leonard|date=2012-11-10|website=Shekulli|language=sq|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref>\n\nToday, military parades of the [[Albanian Armed Forces]] are held on [[Albanian Flag Day]] and [[Constitution of Albania|Constitution Day]] on 28 November. One of the more notable modern military parades was held on the [[100th Anniversary of the Independence of Albania]], in which a special unit of 65 soldiers from the [[Kosovo Security Force]] as well as other foreign contingents participated. The other took place on 4 December 2007 in honor of the 95th anniversary of the [[Albanian Armed Forces]].<ref>https://aaf.mil.al/index.php/arkivi/dhjetor-2007/1403-parade-ushtarake-madheshtore-me-rastin-e-95-vjetorit-te-krijimit-te-forcave-te-armatosura-shqiptare</ref>\n\n==== Argentina ====\nArgentina's long history of military parades are a heritage inherited from the times of the Spanish colonial Viceroyality of Rio de la Plata, with influences from Germany, France, Britain and Italy. Today the [[Armed Forces of the Argentine Republic]], together with the paramilitary [[Argentine National Gendarmerie]] and [[Argentine Naval Prefecture]] hosts massive military parades featuring armed companies, cadets, and military bands on the following days (national events unless otherwise noted):\n\n* January 24 - anniversary of the beginning of the Crossing of the Andes (local commemoration)\n* February 3 - anniversary of the [[Battle of San Lorenzo]] (local commemoration)\n* April 2 - [[Malvinas Day|Falklands War Veterans' Day]]\n* May 10 - anniversary of Air Force baptism of fire in the [[Falklands War]]\n* May 17 - Navy Day, anniversary of the victory at the [[Battle of Buceo]]\n* May 25 - [[First National Government|First National Government Anniversary Day]]\n* May 29 - Army Day\n* June 17 -  General Mart\u00edn Miguel de G\u00fcemes Memorial Day (local commemoration)\n* June 20 - [[Flag Day (Argentina)|Flag Day]]\n* June 30 - Naval Prefecture Day\n* July 9 - [[Argentine Independence Day|Independence Day]]\n* July 28 - National Gendarmerie Day\n* August 10 - Air Force Day\n* September 24 - Battle of Tucuman Day (local commemoration)\n* November 20 - [[National Sovereignty Day]]\n\n==== Australia and New Zealand ====\nAs both Commonwealth realms, Australia and New Zealand share the customs and traditions of parades of the British Armed Forces. The friendship and cooperation of the defence services of both countries can be seen in the annual [[Anzac Day]] parades every 25 April, in memory of the namesake [[Australian and New Zealand Army Corps]], which was heavily involved in the long [[Battle of Gallipoli]] and were the first Allied forces to land there on that day in 1915. On this day, in many major cities in these two countries, parades are held involving personnel of both the [[Australian Defence Force]] and the [[New Zealand Defence Force]], veterans' organizations, cadet organizations and other youth uniformed groups and personnel of the police and fire services, as well as students of schools and universities honoring many of their fallen alumni of the long campaign.\n\nParades are also held jointly in these two countries on 11 November, Remembrance Day.\n\nAside from these two days, the schedule of annual military and civil parades held in these two countries is as follows:\n\n* For parades in Australia:\n** National level parades are held on:\n*** 26 January, Australia Day\n*** The second  Monday of June, the Queen's Birthday, marked in most of Eastern Australia, South Australia and the Northern Territory\n**** typically the last Monday of September or the first Monday of October, Queen's Birthday Holiday for Western Australia\n**** 1st Monday in October, Queen's Birthday Holiday for Queensland\n** Local parades involving armed forces, police and fire personnel are held on:\n*** 2nd Monday in March in the ACT, Canberra Day\n*** 6 June in Queensland, Queensland Day\n*** first Monday in June in Western Australia, Western Australia Day\n*** first working day after Christmas Day, Proclamation Day in South Australia\n** Parades are also held in the following cases:\n*** during change of command, retirement and recruit and cadet [[Passing out (military)|passing out parades]] and regimental anniversaries within the service branches of the ADF and all military academies\n*** During holiday parades held in major cities as can be permitted by the commander of the unit taking part, including:\n**** the AFL Grand Final Parade in Melbourne\n* For parades in New Zealand:\n** National level parades are held on:\n*** 6 February, Waitangi Day\n*** on the 1st Monday in June, the Queen's Birthday\n** Local parades involving armed forces, police and fire personnel are held within the anniversary days of the former [[Provinces of New Zealand]], which were abolished in 1876, the days of which are as set by their respective district and city governments.\n** Change of command, retirement and recruit and cadet graduation parades, together with regimental anniversary parades, are also held occasionally within the service branches of the NZDF and its training institutions.\n\n==== Canada ====\nWithin Canada, the now tri-service [[Ceremonial Guard]] performs the marchpast for senior dignitaries of the [[Canadian Armed Forces]] during change of command ceremonies and state arrival ceremonies, typically held in [[Ottawa]], the national capital. The two [[Primary Reserve]] [[Canadian Army]] regiments that typically provide personnel for the guard, the [[Governor General's Foot Guards]] and [[The Canadian Grenadier Guards]], together with the [[Governor General's Horse Guards]] and guard of honour detachments from both the [[Royal Canadian Navy]] and the [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] take part in these events. In addition, the CG and optionally both the GGHG and the CGG take part in military parades such as the more common [[Trooping the Colour]], also in Ottawa and special parades during the jubilee years of the monarch or of national foundation. The CAF personnel, as well as the [[Canadian Cadet Organizations]] and military veterans also parade during national holidays such as [[Remembrance Day]], [[Victoria Day]], [[Canada Day]] or [[Canadian Forces Day]], as well as during parades celebrating anniversaries of regiments, brigade groups or wings, and divisional level formations and passing out parades of the [[Royal Military College of Canada]], [[Royal Military College Saint-Jean]] and recruit training bases, as well as in local holidays in the provinces and major cities. Across the country, the annual Warriors Day military parade has since 1921, been a traditional event of the [[Canadian National Exhibition]]. It is specifically devoted to formally recognizing veterans of the CF.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thewarriorsdayparade.ca/Parade%20History-Guide.html|title=The Warriors' Day Parade - History Guide}}</ref> Like in the UK, the [[Authorized marches of the Canadian Armed Forces|regimental march of the unit]] being honored is played by the band and/or [[pipe band]] if present.\n\n==== Chile ====\nThe tradition of military parades in Chile has origins not just in Spanish tradition, but also a mix between those of France, the United Kingdom, and particularly Germany, given the fact that Imperial German Army officers trained the army and navy in the mid-1890s in the Prussian-German traditions of military parades that are continued until today.\n\nCurrently, the [[Chilean Armed Forces]] and the [[Carabineros de Chile]] hold public parades in front of state leaders and the public on\n\n* 21 May - [[Navy Day (Chile)|Navy Day]] - honoring the fallen of the 1879 [[Battle of Iquique]], also marked as a day to celebrate the service personnel, veterans, heroes and martyrs of the [[Chilean Navy]]\n* 19 September - [[Great Military Parade of Chile|Army Day]] - while honoring the 1810 anniversary of the formal inauguration of the First Government Junta, is also marked as a day to celebrate the service personnel, veterans, heroes and martyrs of the [[Chilean Army]]\n\nLocal level parades are marked on the following days aside from 21 May:\n\n* 17 February  - anniversary of the victory in the [[Battle of Chacabuco]]\n* 21 March - Air Force Day\n* 2 April - anniversary of the victory in the [[Battle of Maipu]]\n* 27 April - Carabineros Day\n* 7 June - anniversary of the victory in the [[Battle of Arica]]\n* 9 July  - Flag Day\n* 20 August - birthday of [[Bernardo O'Higgins]]\n* 18 September - Independence Day\n* 2 October - anniversary of the [[Battle of Rancagua]]\n* 30 November - [[Chilean Gendarmerie]] Day\n\n==== China ====\nThe first military parade on the Chinese mainland can be dated to over 4,000 years ago, when [[Yu the Great]], a legendary ruler in [[History of China#Ancient China|ancient China]], hosted a gathering of tribal forces from northern and southern China.<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=llmCOvtWcUcC&pg=PA76&dq=chinese+military+parade+1984&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4wKiB1IXlAhUQIKwKHfsJBp8Q6AEISTAF#v=onepage&q=chinese%20military%20parade%201984&f=false</ref>\n\n===== People's Republic of China =====\n{{See also|Military parades in Hong Kong}}\n{{external media|align=right|width=250px|video1=Parts [https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=xtmnAg_e9Dk 1] [https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=Cy_Kyq5iCzE 2] [https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=Cy_Kyq5iCzE 3] and [https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=4WJNtiHiZJQ 4] of a documentary on the history of Chinese military parades|align2=right|width2=250px|video2=[https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=_2ZfByEEYmg 1981 \u65b0\u7586 \u5927\u9605\u5175 Chinese Uighur Military Parade in Xinjiang (Eng narration)]}}\nThe People's Republic of China holds extraordinary military parades in Beijing to celebrate [[National Day of the People's Republic of China|National Day]]. The first parade of this nature took place right after the [[Proclamation of the People's Republic of China]] by Chairman [[Mao Zedong]] on 1 October 1949. Originally celebrated annually, the parade was suspended in 1960, before returning in 1984 to mark the 35th anniversary of the founding of the [[China|People's Republic of China]]. It is now held to mark every tenth anniversary, starting in 1999. Parades were also held in 1964, 1966, 1969 and 1970.<ref>https://www.frstrategie.org/en/publications/strategic-imagery/military-parade-70th-anniversary-prc-revealing-example-chinese-strategic-power-2019</ref>\n\nIn 2015, China held a [[2015 China Victory Day Parade|military parade]] to celebrate the 70th anniversary of the [[Victory over Japan Day|Victory over Japan]]. This was the first time China held a military parade for an event other than its National Day. It is currently unknown if China will continue to celebrate the end of World War II, through.\n\nIn 2017, the 90th anniversary since the [[Nanchang Uprising]] and the beginning of the [[People's Liberation Army]] was marked by a [[2017 PLA Day Parade|military parade]], the first time ever that a military parade had been held in its honor and the first time it was held outside of the capital, having been held at [[Zhurihe Training Base]] in [[Inner Mongolia]] under the direction of General [[Han Weiguo]] of the [[Central Theater Command]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-defence/chinas-xi-calls-for-building-elite-forces-during-massive-military-parade-idUSKBN1AF00J|title=China's Xi calls for building elite forces during massive military parade|first=Michael|last=Martina|first2=Ben|last2=Blanchard|work=[[Reuters]]|date=July 29, 2017|editor-first=Kim|editor-last=Coghill|editor-first2=Sam|editor-last2=Holmes}}</ref><ref>https://www.chinadailyhk.com/articles/50/38/44/1501474883058.html</ref> This was also the first field parade to take place since September 1981 when a parade consisting of troops participating in an excersise in [[Zhangjiakou]] in the presence of [[Deng Xiaoping]] to commemorate Deng's assumption to the post of [[Chairman of the Central Military Commission]]. During that parade, Deng reportedly said \"Let\u2019s hold a large-scale one if we are to hold a military exercise, so that it can be of use\" in reference to the size of the parade.<ref>https://amp.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy-defence/article/2079193/massive-parade-tipped-plas-90th-birthday</ref> Naval parades have also been reintroduced in recent years with a [[2018 South China Sea Parade|parade]] (which was the biggest naval review since 1949 and according to the Chinese government, the biggest in 600 years.<ref>https://nationalinterest.org/blog/the-buzz/superpower-china-claims-biggest-naval-parade-600-years-25403</ref>) being held in the [[South China Sea]] in 2018 and a [[PLA Navy Platinum Jubilee Parade|parade]] for the [[platinum jubilee]] of the [[People's Liberation Army Navy]] being held in early 2019.\n\nSmaller scale parades are also periodically held in [[Hong Kong]], [[Macau]], [[Tibet]] and [[Xinjiang]]. Every year on 10 March ([[Tibetan Uprising Day]]), a military parade in [[Lhasa]] to mark the anniversary of the [[1959 Tibetan uprising|1959 Tibetan rebellion]].<ref>https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/03/20/china-marks-tibetan-anniversary-military-parade</ref> The first military parades in the HKSAR and the MSAR took place on their first and fifth anniversaries in 1998<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjnews.com.cn/news/2017/06/30/448719.html|title=\u4e60\u8fd1\u5e73\u68c0\u9605\u9a7b\u6e2f\u90e8\u961f\uff0c\u53d7\u9605\u5b98\u5175\u4e3a\u4f55\u558a\"\u4e3b\u5e2d\u597d\"?&#124;\u653f\u89e3 - \u56fd\u5185 - \u65b0\u4eac\u62a5\u7f51|website=www.bjnews.com.cn}}</ref> and 2004 respectively.\n\n===== Republic of China =====\nHowever, in the [[Taiwan|Republic of China (Taiwan)]], the [[Republic of China Armed Forces]] held its national parades in [[Taipei]] from 1949 until 1991 during the [[National Day of the Republic of China|Double Ten Day]] celebrations. This practice was abandoned in 1991 though parades were recently held every five years beginning in 2011 during the [[100th Anniversary of the Republic of China|Xinhai Revolution centenary]] and again in 2016. Special parades were held outside Taipei in 1995 and 2015 marking the 50th and 70th anniversaries, respectively, of both the Allied victory in the Second World War and the conclusion of the Second Sino-Japanese War.\n\n==== Colombia ====\nBoth the [[Military Forces of Colombia]] and the [[National Police of Colombia]] hold important national parades to celebrate the anniversary of national independence as well as of the Armed Forces. Such parades are a mix of the Spanish, German, French, American and British influences owing to the long history of the country's military and police forces. National level parades are held on:\n\n* February 15 - Air Force Day \n* July 20 - [[Colombian Independence Day parade|Independence Day]]\n* July 24 - Navy Day \n* August 7 - Army Day and [[Battle of Boyac\u00e1|Battle of Boyaca Victory Day]]\n* November 15 - National Police Day\n\nLocal level parades by the personnel and veterans of the armed forces and police are held on the following:\n\n* April 7 - Barranquilla Day\n* July 3 - Cali Independence Day\n* November 11 - Cartagena Independence Day\n\n==== Cuba ====\nThe [[Cuban Revolutionary Armed Forces]] generally holds military parades in honor of the [[Day of the Cuban Armed Forces]] and the [[Triumph of the Revolution]] on [[Havana]]'s [[Plaza de la Revoluci\u00f3n]]. The first parade took place in 1960 for the latter event and over time, importance was transferred to Armed Forces Day in relation to military parades. In 2011, a special honor parade was held on April 16 to commemorate the [[golden jubilee]] since the 1961 [[Bay of Pigs Invasion]].<ref>https://www.pri.org/stories/2011-04-16/cuba-marks-victory-socialism</ref> The largest parade to be held took place in December 1986 in honor of the 30th anniversary of the revolution, in which General [[Humberto Ortega]] from [[Nicaragua]] as well as officials from the [[Soviet Union]] attended.<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=7z1mvx29XMgC&pg=PA589&dq=military+parade+in+cuba+1986&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj8so7g9oHmAhUP2qwKHZwTBuUQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=military%20parade%20in%20cuba%201986&f=false</ref> The [[diamond jubilee]] parade planned for 2016 was postponed for 1 month due to the [[death and state funeral of Fidel Castro]], and took place during the Victory Day celebrations on 2 January 2017.<ref>http://www.cubagob.cu/otras_info/minfar/granma.htm</ref><ref>http://www.prensa-latina.cu/index.php?o=rn&id=135863&SEO=conmemoran-en-angola-dia-de-las-fuerzas-armadas-de-cuba</ref>\n\n==== Czech Republic ====\n[[File:Vojenska prehlidka 1985b.jpg|thumb|A parade of tanks of the \u010cSLA in Prague on [[Victory Day (9 May)|Victory Day]], 9 May 1985.]]\n{{external media|align=right|width=250px|video1=[https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=EApCYZR-NMk Czechoslovak Military Parade \"Shield-84\" - Vojensk\u00e1 p\u0159ehl\u00eddka \u010cSLA \"\u0160t\u00edt-84]}}\nLarge mlitary parades in the [[Czech Republic]] are today held every 10 years in the capital of [[Prague]], encompassing personnel from the [[Czech Army]] and the [[Police of the Czech Republic]]. The first of these parades occurred in 2008 in honor of the founding of [[Czechoslovakia]] on 28 October 1918.<ref>{{cite web | title=Hundreds of Soldiers Marched Through Prague, for the First Time Since 1985 | website=Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b | date=2008-10-28 | url=https://zpravy.aktualne.cz/domaci/prahou-pochodovaly-stovky-vojaku-poprve-od-roku-1985/r~i:article:620540/ | language=cs | access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> Another one took place in [[2018 Prague Military Parade|2018]] and included foreign troops.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.czdjournal.com/news/100th-anniversary-of-czechoslovakia-parade-2018-28th-october-118.html|title=100th Anniversary of Czechoslovakia \u2013 Parade 2018 (28th October) | website=Czech Defence Journal}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 1918, military parades followed the tradition of their larger sovereign entity, including the military tradition of [[Austria-Hungary]]. Regular military parades were held during the period of the [[Czechoslovak Socialist Republic]], with the first parades being organized in the 1950s. The first parade of the [[Czechoslovak People's Army]] (\u010cSLA) took place in 1951 in [[Letn\u00e1]]. Since then, parades were held every five years on 9 May to mark the end of [[World War II]] and the [[Prague uprising|Liberation of Czechoslovakia]]. To honor the latter's celebrations, the [[State Anthem of the Soviet Union]] would be performed by the massed bands on parade preceded by the [[Kde domov m\u016fj|Czechoslovakian national anthem]]. The last of these parades took place in 1985.<ref>{{cite web | title=Prague Experienced a Military Parade After 23 Years | website=Lidovky.cz | date=2008-10-28 | url=https://www.lidovky.cz/domov/praha-zazila-vojenskou-prehlidku-po-23-letech.A081028_130928_ln_praha_mtr | language=cs | access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.novinky.cz/domaci/clanek/prahou-ma-buracet-velkolepa-vojenska-prehlidka-40008504|title=A Spectacular Military Parade Should Roar Through Prague|last=Adami\u010dkov\u00e1|first=Na\u010fa|last2=K\u00f6nigov\u00e1|first2=Marie|date=2016-09-21|website=Novinky.cz|language=cs|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref>\n\n==== Ecuador ====\nBoth the [[Armed Forces of Ecuador]] and the [[National Police of Ecuador]] hold important national parades to celebrate the anniversaries of national independence as well as of the Armed Forces and Police. National level parades are held on the following days:\n\n* February 27 - Army Day\n* May 24 - Armed Forces Day, anniversary of the victory in the 1822 [[Battle of Pichincha]]\n* July 26 - Navy Day\n* August 10 - anniversary of the Luz de America\n* October 9 - Guayaquil Independence Day\n* October 27 - Air Force Day\n* November 3 - Cueca Independence Day\n* November 18 - Loja Independence Day\n\nLocal military and police parades are held on major city and provincial anniversaries.\n\n==== France ====\nThe annual [[Bastille Day military parade|military parade]] in the French capital of [[Paris]] is held on July 14 during the [[Bastille Day]] holiday. It is currently the oldest and largest military parade on the European continent. It is held on the Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es and passes from l'[[Arc de Triomphe]] to [[Place de la Concorde]]. Bastille Day parades are also held in smaller garrison towns such as [[Toulon]] and [[Belfort]]. The 1st Infantry Regiment of the [[French Republican Guard]] regularly performs ceremonial marchpasts in is role as the [[guard of honour]] for the [[President of the French Republic]]. Like the British, many French units have the ability to march in quick time, while only one - the [[French Foreign Legion]] - marches uniquely in slow time, while another unit of the armed forces marches in very quick time and that is of the Army's [[Chasseurs]], especially its [[Chasseurs alpins]].\n\nLocal parades are held on the following days:\n\n* May 8 - [[Victory in Europe Day]]\n* November 11 - Armistice Day\n* Anniversaries of important battles fought by the French Armed Forces\n\n==== Germany ====\nThe [[Germany]] has had a long tradition of military parades dating back to the days of [[Kingdom of Prussia]] and its army and navy. It was the Prussians who invented the [[goose step]], a style of marching that was used in many German armies as well as in the militaries of various countries, which were instructed by Prussian military training officers and instructors from the 19th century to the early 20th.\n\nDuring the [[Nazi era]], military parades were commonplace as they were held as a sort of victory parade for the German [[Wehrmacht]] as they invaded countries during the Second World War. The first major parades took place in [[Nuremberg]] in September 1938 and [[Adolf Hitler's 50th birthday]] in April 1939. In the months Immediately after the [[German invasion of Poland]], a [[German\u2013Soviet military parade in Brest-Litovsk|joint German\u2013Soviet military parade]] took place in [[Brest-Litovsk]] (now [[Brest, Belarus]]). In [[Allied-occupied Germany]], the major powers held parades through the center of Berlin to honor their victory. These include the [[Berlin Victory Parade of 1945]], [[1945 British Berlin Victory Parade]] and [[Berlin Victory Parade of 1946]].\n\nIn the communist [[German Democratic Republic]] (GDR), parades were held according to the Russian standard, although the [[Soviet Army]] allowed the East Germans to use the Prussian tradition, something that had been dropped by their West German counterparts in the 50s. In the GDR, parades were held on the following occasions:\n\n*NVA Day (3 March)\n*[[International Workers' Day]] (1 May)\n*[[Liberation Day|Tag der Befreiung]] (8 May)\n*[[Republic Day (East Germany)|Tag der Republik]] (7 October)\n\nThe first parade took place on 1 May 1956 in the presence of [[President of East Germany|President]] [[Wilhelm Pieck]].<ref>https://www.mdr.de/zeitreise/erster-mai-ddr-politparade-volksfest100.html</ref> In the 60s and early 70s, parades took place on the western half of the [[Palace of the Republic, Berlin|Palace of the Republic]], which was intended as a military parade ground, even though tremors from the heavy vehicles proved dangerous due to the glass facade. By 1979, the western half was used mainly as a parking lot and military parades were moved to [[Karl-Marx-Allee]] in central Berlin.\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F029232-0004, N\u00fcrburgring, Bundeswehrparade zum NATO-Jubil\u00e4um.jpg|thumb|[[Bundeswehr]] personnel on the [[N\u00fcrburgring]].]]\nIn 1969, the first military parade of [[West Germany]] and later the entire [[Federal Republic of Germany]] was held on the [[N\u00fcrburgring]] in the town of [[N\u00fcrburg]], [[Rhineland-Palatinate]].<ref>http://www.hawkies.de/chronik-39.html</ref> It took place on 6 June 1969 and was held to commemorate the 20th anniversary of the establishment of the [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization]] (NATO).<ref>https://www.deutsche-digitale-bibliothek.de/item/GJQUEWUHL6MHFEI7OOLMIOGW4VZT7UTU</ref> It was attended by [[Kurt Georg Kiesinger]] in his position as [[Federal Chancellor of Germany]]. Participating foreign and national units included those from the [[Bundeswehr]], [[Canadian Forces Europe]], [[United States Army Europe]], as well as army contingents from [[France]] and the [[United Kingdom]]. Allied parades were also held later in the country's 40-year existence.\n\nToday, military parades are held on the following holidays on a smaller scale:\n\n* Remembrance Day of [[July 20 plot|July 20]]\n* [[German Unity Day]] (October 3)\n* Passing out parades of NCO training schools and officer training institutions\n\n==== Greece ====\nThe long history of the [[Hellenic Armed Forces]] and the role played in the defense and progress of the country are recalled in splendid and grand military parades that are held in major cities in the country following a hybrid of the British, French, Danish and German traditions on the following dates:\n\n* 25 March - [[Greek Independence Day|Independence Day]]\n* 28 October - Ohi Day\n* On Liberation Days of major cities and towns, honoring the Greek fallen of the Second World War and the later Greek Civil War\n\n==== India ====\nThe [[Delhi Republic Day parade|Republic Day Parade]] is held annually in [[Delhi]] to mark the Republic Day of [[India]]. Parades are also held on the service holidays: [[Army Day (India)|Army Day]], Navy Day and Air Force Day.\n\n==== Mongolia ====\nMilitary parades in [[Mongolia]] have a long tradition that dates back to the era of the [[Mongol Empire]]. Today they closely follow the Russian model with sone modifications such as trooping of the [[Flag of Mongolia]] in a car rather than by foot. A Dangjiren is based off a cavalry military parade of the Mongols that were held in the 17th century.<ref>http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-08/10/c_137381600.htm</ref>\n\nThe first official military parade in Communist Mongolia took place in 1921 in honor of the victories of [[Damdin S\u00fckhbaatar]] in the People's Revolution. The anniversary parades that followed have been held on jubilee years (specifically in 1946, 1951, 1956, 1961, 1966, 1971, 1976, 1981, 1986 and 1991).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tolgoilogch.mn/_c863obv6vd/mt|title=Rare Images of the People's Revolution |website=tolgoilogch.mn |language=mn |access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> After 1991, the practice was abandoned with the exception of 1996 when a parade in the [[National Sports Stadium (Mongolia)|National Sports Stadium]] commemorated the 790th anniversary of the founding of Mongolia and the 75th anniversary of the People's Revolution. After a 9-year break, the 2005 inauguration ceremony of [[Nambaryn Enkhbayar]] served as an event to hold a military parade on the central square. This took place again in 2009 for the inauguration of [[Tsakhiagiin Elbegdorj]]. That same year, State Flag Day was introduced as a national holiday, which would also be celebrated with a parade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.zindaa.mn/rbs|title=The History of the Military Ceremony|last=\u0411\u0430\u044f\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0430|first=A|date=1908-10-04|website=Zindaa.mn|language=mn|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref>\n\nMilitary parades of the [[Mongolian Armed Forces]] on [[S\u00fckhbaatar Square]] take place on the following occasions:<ref>{{cite book|last=Rossabi|first=Morris|title=From Yuan to Modern China and Mongolia: The Writings of Morris Rossabi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GXejBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA503|year=2014|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-28529-3|page=503|oclc=915581801}}</ref>\n\n*18 March &ndash; [[Men's and Soldiers' Day|Soldiers Day]]\n*10 July &ndash; [[Mongolian State Flag Day]]\n*1 September &ndash; Anniversary of the [[Battle of Khalkin Gol]]\n*Inauguration of the [[President of Mongolia]]\n*Graduations of the [[National Defense University (Mongolia)|National Defense University]]\n\n{{external media|align=right|width=250px|video1=[https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=cFv0vF-gzxA The 70th anniversary parade of the People's Revolution of 1921]|align2=right|width2=250px|video2=[https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=S_mrMgbwwyQ Mongolian Military Parade 2011]}}\n\nDuring Mongolia's [[Mongolian People's Republic|socialist period]], annual civil/military parades of the [[Mongolian People's Army]] took place until 1991,<ref>{{cite book|last=Sanders|first=Alan J K|title=Historical Dictionary of Mongolia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5JN83EDDLl4C&pg=PR62|edition=3rd|year=2010|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-7452-7|page=62| oclc=939933261}}</ref> celebrating the following occasions:\n\n*1 May &ndash; [[International Workers Day]]\n*11 July &ndash; [[Mongolian Revolution of 1921|Day of the People's Revolution of 1921]]\n*7 November &ndash; [[October Revolution Day]]\n\nDuring these events, party and government leaders were viewed ascending to the top of [[S\u00fckhbaatar's Mausoleum]] to take the salute.\n\n==== North Korea ====\n{{Main|Military parades in North Korea}}\nAll military parades of the [[Korean People's Army]] (KPA) and the [[Worker-Peasant Red Guards]] (WPRG) are centered in the national capital of [[Pyongyang]] and have a long tradition that goes back to the DPRK's establishment in 1948. Between 1993 and 2011, the DPRK held over a dozen military parades, which was frequent compared to the 1960s\u201380s, during which only three parades were held.<ref>https://www.latimes.com/world/la-fg-north-korea-military-parades-20180908-story.html?_amp=true</ref> Known for its elaborate military drill, the country holds military parades annually on different dates (especially on jubilee years<ref>https://www.youngpioneertours.com/north-korean-military-parades/</ref>), which feature a combination of Chinese and Russian techniques.<ref>https://www.cbsnews.com/news/north-korea-military-parades-through-pyongyang/</ref> North Korean military parades are held on the following dates:\n\n*8 February &ndash; [[Military Foundation Day]] \n*15 April &ndash; [[Day of the Sun]] \n*25 April &ndash; Revolutionary Army Day\n*27 July &ndash; [[Day of Victory in the Great Fatherland Liberation War]]\n*15 August &ndash; [[Liberation Day (North Korea)|Liberation Day]]\n*9 September &ndash; [[Day of the Foundation of the Republic (North Korea)|Day of the Foundation of the Republic]]\n*10 October &ndash; [[Party Foundation Day]]\n\n[[File:Parade - North Korea.webm|thumb|Drill rehearsals for female soldiers participating in the 2011 Republic Day Parade.]]\nRehearsals for these parades usually take place 3\u20136 weeks prior to the actual parade at the [[Mirim Airport|Mirim Parade Training Facility]] in the capital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beyondparallel.csis.org/is-north-korea-preparing-for-a-military-parade/|title=Is North Korea Preparing for a Military Parade?|date=April 10, 2019|website=Beyond Parallel}}</ref><ref>https://www.foxnews.com/world/past-goose-steppers-proud-of-place-in-north-korean-parades</ref> The actual parades are held in the capital's [[Kim Il-sung Square]].\n\nIn addition, non-jubilee holiday parades have been mounted on the grounds of the [[Kumsusan Palace of the Sun]] on these days plus on:\n\n*16 February &ndash; [[Day of the Shining Star]]\n*25 August &ndash; [[Day of Songun|Day of ''Songun'']]\n*21 December &ndash; Death Anniversary of [[Kim Jong-il]]\n\n==== Peru ====\nThe [[Peruvian Armed Forces]] and the [[National Police of Peru]] holds the yearly [[Great Military Parade of Peru]] every July 29 in Lima as the armed services' way of honoring the anniversary of national independence and the role they have played in shaping the history of the country. Local level Independence Day parades are held on pre-determined days before July 28 and 29 as set by their respective local governments.\n\nParades held by service personnel and veterans of the armed forces are also marked on:\n\n* June 7 - Flag Day and Battle of Arica Memorial Day \n* June 26 - Air Force Day\n* September 24 - Armed Forces Day \n* October 8 - Navy Day\n* December 9  - Army Day and anniversary of the [[Battle of Ayacucho]]\n\n==== Poland ====\n[[File:August 15, 2018. Celebration of the Polish Army Day. Air force of Poland.jpg|thumb|A [[Polish Air Force]] ceremonial guard during the Armed Forces Day parade.]]\nThe [[Polish Armed Forces]] and the [[Police of Poland]] holds two yearly military parades ({{lang-pl|Defilada wojskowa}}) in the capital of [[Warsaw]]: The [[Armed Forces Day (Poland)|Armed Forces Day]] parade through [[Ujazd\u00f3w Avenue]] and the [[National Independence Day (Poland)|National Independence Day]] parade near the [[Tomb of the Unknown Soldier, Warsaw|Tomb of the Unknown Soldier]] on [[Pi\u0142sudski Square]]. Both of these parades include [[NATO]] personnel stationed near or inside the country. The Armed Forces Day Parade was introduced in 2007 and 2008 as first grand military parades since the holiday was reinstated and have been held yearly since 2013. The first Polish military parade took place on 17 January 1945. Prior to 1989, parades were held in front of the [[Palace of Culture and Science]] on [[Parade Square]] on 22 July commemorate the [[National Day of the Rebirth of Poland]] celebrations, honoring the anniversary of the signing of the [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]]-sponsored [[PKWN Manifesto]]. Back then, the [[People's Republic of Poland]] used many Russian traditions in regards to military parades, especially the inspection by the Minister of Defence. In 1966, during the millennium celebrations of the [[Christianization of Poland]], a parade was held on 22 July which included cadets of military academies and personnel of Polish ceremonial units dressed in historical military uniforms dating back to the [[Piast dynasty]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Polish Chronicle | website=KronikaRP | url=http://www.kronikarp.pl/pop-up.php?id=58989&type=2 | language=pl | access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://phistory.info/photo-history/679-rycari-v-kinorekvizite-uchastvuyut-v-parade-v-chest-1000-letiya-polskogo-gosudarstva.html|title=Knights (in Film Props) Participate in a Parade in Honor of the 1000th Anniversary of the Polish State|date=2019-07-14|website=phistory.info|language=ru|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> A [[1985 Warsaw Victory Day Parade|special parade]] was held on 9 May 1985 to honor the 40th anniversary of the Victory in Europe and the servicemen of the Polish Armed Forces in the West and the East. In 2019, a 3rd was added when the yearly [[3 May Constitution Day]] parades, last held in 1939 and were held off and on since 1990, were officially reinstated.\n\n==== Russia and ex-Soviet countries ====\n[[File:Naval Academy 1983.jpg|thumb|The [[N. G. Kuznetsov Naval Academy]], led by Captain Anatoliy Karpenko, during a parade on [[Leningrad]]'s [[Palace Square]] in 1983.]]\nThe Western tradition of military parades in the [[Russian Empire]] was part of the many reforms made by [[Peter the Great]] as part of his many efforts to transform the army and the navy from traditional militias to a full-blown professional armed service that is a model for the people in discipline and obedience, courage, bravery, loyalty to the country and in bringing pride and glory to her people. During the Imperial period, national parades were alternated between [[Moscow]] and [[Saint Petersburg]] on major national civil and military holidays, anniversaries of the Romanov Dynasty and as part of the imperial coronation celebrations, celebrations and parades were also held in many major cities and provincial capitals.\n\nSo important was the value of these parades that even the [[Soviet Armed Forces]] made these parades a common tradition beginning in August 1918 when the first modern parade was held in Moscow's [[Red Square]] when Moscow area [[Vsevobuch]] detachments march past, earlier that May, a [[1918 May 1 Parade|military parade]], the first by the nascent [[Red Army]], was held outside the capital. Since that year, many innovations have been seen in the practice of annual parades held not just there but in the capital cities of the former [[Soviet Union]], as well as in major cities in the wide country, which were held on 1 May (1918-1941 and 1945-1968), [[October Revolution Day|7 November]] (1920-1941 and 1945-1990) and [[Victory Day Parades|9 May]] (1945, 1965, 1985 and 1990). Today, the [[Russian Armed Forces]] - and by extension countries of the former Soviet Union - host a variety of military parades held on important national holidays, honoring the men and women of their armed forces and military veterans. The celebrations in each of these countries carry on years of tradition, honor, discipline and prestige by the millions of men and women who serve and have served in the ranks of the armed forces of their respective home countries. These parades have extensive government funding and aside from the iconic wide march past columns and occasional historical formations, typically include a mobile column, and occasionally a naval fleet review and/or air force fly past segment, a legacy of the Soviet era.\n\n[[File:4Samarin.jpg|thumb|A Russian Armed Forces Honour Parade on [[Red Square]] in November 2018.]]\n\n===== Armenia =====\nWhile the country was a Soviet Republic from 1920 to 1991, Armenia was formerly independent from 1918 to 1920 and thus had armed forces composed of both veterans of the Imperial Army and guerillas fighting the Ottoman armed forces who had been enforcing the anti-Armenian massacres of 1914. Armenians fought bravery in the Eastern Front of the Second World War as part of the Soviet Armed Forces, retaining some of its traditions today. The last of the Soviet era parades took place in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1tv.am/hy/news/2015/07/10/%D4%B1%D6%80%D5%B1%D5%A1%D5%B6/19710|title=Talking Monuments. Statue of Lenin.|date=2015-10-07|website=1tv.am|language=hy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808084317/http://www.1tv.am/hy/news/2015/07/10/%D4%B1%D6%80%D5%B1%D5%A1%D5%B6/19710|archive-date=2016-08-08|url-status=dead|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> Today, the [[Armed Forces of Armenia]] hosts massive parades held in [[Yerevan]], the capital city, on the following days:\n\n* May 28 - [[Republic Day (Armenia)|Republic Day]]\n* September 21 - [[Independence Day (Armenia)|Independence Day]]\n\nIn recent years, national military parades have included drill units and military bands performing [[exhibition drill]] for the guests before the parade concludes.\n\n===== Azerbaijan =====\n{{Main|Military parades in Azerbaijan}}\nThe semi-annual parade on the [[Day of the Armed Forces of Azerbaijan]], 26 June, is one of the biggest in the Commonwealth of Independent States, held every 3 to 5 years at the [[Azadliq Square, Baku]], honoring the many Azerbaijanis who served faithful under the colours as part of her armed forces. The forces on parade are assembled based on a mix of the Turkish and Russian parade formation.\n\n===== Belarus =====\nThe [[Armed Forces of Belarus]] holds an annual military parade on 3 July along the [[Victors Avenue]] in the national capital [[Minsk]], marking the anniversary of the liberation of the country during the 1944 [[Minsk Offensive]], which coincides with the country's [[Independence Day (Belarus)|Independence Day]]. On special years of the victory in Europe, commemorative extraordinary parades are held there on 9 May to honor the millions of Belarusian military dead of the [[Second World War]]. Military parades in the country are based on the Russian/Polish model and tradition. Formerly, parades in the [[Republic of Belarus]] and the [[Belarusian Soviet Socialist Republic]] took place on [[Independence Square, Minsk|Independence Square]] (known in the Soviet era as Lenin Square). This changed in the early 2000s when the square was renovated and became incompatible with the parade format. Military parades in the BSSR also took place on [[October Square, Minsk|October Square]] from 1946 to 1984. Since 2004, military parades in the capital have taken place on [[Victors Avenue]]. In connection with the centennial of the Belarusian Armed Forces in 2018, a military parade was held in the Western city of [[Grodno]].\n\n===== Estonia =====\nWhile being formerly independent from 1918 to 1940 and as a component republic of the Soviet Union from that year to 1941 and yet again from 1944 to 1991, the current [[Estonian Defence Forces]] and the [[Estonian Defence League]], successor to both the military and reserve forces of the First Republic and republican formations under the Baltic Military District and Baltic Fleet of the Soviet Armed Forces, marches during a combination of Russian, Finnish and Western drill in parades held in the following days:\n\n* February 24 - [[Independence Day (Estonia)|Independence Day]]\n* June 24 - [[V\u00f5idup\u00fcha|Victory Day]]\n\nDuring the 2006 Victory Day Parade in [[Saaremaa]], the first ever Fleet Review of the [[Estonian Navy]] in Estonian history was conducted by the [[Estonian Defence League]].\n\n===== Georgia ===== \nThe [[Defense Forces of Georgia]], successor to the armed services of the Democratic Republic and Soviet formations stationed in the Georgian SSR, hosts military parades on May 26, [[Independence Day (Georgia)|Independence Day]], the anniversary of the formation of the republic in 1918, together with elements from:\n\n* [[National Police of Georgia]]\n* [[Border Police of Georgia]]\n* [[Georgian Coast Guard]]\n\nModern parades are a mix of the former Soviet and modern Western (British, US, Turkish and Israeli) traditions and drill owing to the modernization of the defense and public security forces to NATO and EU standards.\n\n===== Kazakhstan =====\nThe [[Armed Forces of Kazakhstan]] holds military parades ({{Lang-kk|\u04d8\u0441\u043a\u0435\u0440\u0438 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434}}) that resemble the parades of the Russian military in [[Moscow]], with one of the only exceptions being the inspection of the troops by the [[President of Kazakhstan|Supreme Commander of the Kazakh Armed Forces]], instead of the defense minister. It has never held yearly parades celebrating one occasion, with parades currently being held in honor of the [[Defender of the Fatherland Day (Kazakhstan)|Defender of the Fatherland Day]] holiday. In the past, large scale military parades in the former capital of [[Almaty]] and the current capital of [[Nur-Sultan]] were held on the following holidays:\n\n*[[Kazakhstan Independence Day]] (1996)\n*[[Victory Day (9 May)]] (1995, 2015)\n*[[Constitution Day (Kazakhstan)]] (2009, 2010, 2011)\n\nIn recent years, the Defender of the Fatherland Day parade was expanded to function as a so-called \"Battle Parade\" (\u0411\u043e\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434). So far, only two of these kinds of parades have been held; in 2013 and 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://informburo.kz/stati/kak-proshyol-boevoy-parad-2018-fotoreportazh.html|title=How was the Battle Parade 2018. Photoreport|last=Bedenko|first=Grigory|date=2018-05-07|website=Informburo.kz|language=ru|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> In contrast to usual military parades, the battle parade includes tactical exercises and military demonstrations. These parades usually are held at the 40th [[Otar Military Base]] in the [[Korday District]] and take place with the troops in full combat gear rather than a ceremonial [[full dress uniform]]. Like former Soviet republics, Kazakh military parades are led by a cadet [[Corps of drums|drum corps]], specifically from the [[Astana Zhas Ulan Republican School]].\n\n===== Kyrgyzstan =====\nKyrgyz military parades are based on Russian traditions, having been held on many different occasions in the history of the [[Armed Forces of Kyrgyzstan]]. Currently, the only consistent military parade is held on [[Ala-Too Square]] in [[Bishkek]] every 5 years in honor of the country's [[Independence Day (Kyrgyzstan)|Independence Day]]. Other military parades have been held celebrating different occasions. On 24 March 2006, a parade was held on the same square celebrating the 1 year anniversary since the [[Tulip Revolution]] which overthrew President [[Askar Akayev]].<ref>https://amp.dw.com/ru/%D0%BF%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B2%D0%B0%D1%8F-%D0%B3%D0%BE%D0%B4%D0%BE%D0%B2%D1%89%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B0-%D1%82%D1%8E%D0%BB%D1%8C%D0%BF%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%BE%D0%B9-%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%B2%D0%BE%D0%BB%D1%8E%D1%86%D0%B8%D0%B8-%D0%B2-%D0%BA%D0%B8%D1%80%D0%B3%D0%B8%D0%B7%D0%B8%D0%B8/a-1943616</ref><ref>https://www.golos-ameriki.ru/amp/a-33-2006-04-03-voa5/638201.html</ref><ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=6fcVAQAAMAAJ&q=%D0%90%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B4%D0%B8%D0%BA+%D0%BF%D0%B0%D1%80%D0%B0%D0%B4,+%D0%91%D0%B8%D1%88%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%BA&dq=%D0%90%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B4%D0%B8%D0%BA+%D0%BF%D0%B0%D1%80%D0%B0%D0%B4,+%D0%91%D0%B8%D1%88%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%BA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjvy77r8-LkAhUFX60KHSznAUUQ6AEILTAB</ref> In May of that same year, a [[Day of the Armed Forces (Kyrgyzstan)|Day of the Armed Forces]] parade on the same square, later being deemed as \"irresponsible\" by opposition lawmaker [[Omurbek Tekebaev]] due to the fact that it coincided with opposition protests against President [[Kurmanbek Bakiyev]], which itself was described by Defence Minister [[Ismail Isakov]] as purely \"coincidental\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/1068556.html|title=Kyrgyz Opposition, Military Vie For Venue|website=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty|access-date=2019-09-21}}</ref> In 2015, a Victory Day Parade was held in the Kyrgyz capital, being presided by Prime Minister [[Temir Sariyev]] and [[General Staff of Armed Forces of the Kyrgyz Republic|Chief of General Staff]] [[Asanbek Alymkozhoev]] in place of President [[Almazbek Atambayev]], who was attending the [[2015 Moscow Victory Day Parade]] that same day.<ref>https://regnum.ru/news/polit/1922892.html</ref> The parade saw the appearance of veterans of the war in the mobile column as well as Russian troops from the local [[Kant Air Base]] taking part in the parade.\n\n===== Latvia =====\nLatvia, like its neighbors to the north and south, was also formerly independent from 1918 to 1940 and as a component republic of the Soviet Union from that year to 1941 and yet again from 1944 to 1991, and its armed forces, then as in the 90s, were formed up of Latvian born personnel who served in the Russian military and thus share some of the Russian drill and parade ceremonial in combination with Western practices. Today, the [[Latvian National Armed Forces]] hosts massive parades (with occasional participation by service personnel of NATO armed forces) on the following dates:\n\n* May 4, [[Day of the Restoration of Latvian Independence|Restoration of Independence Day]]\n* November 11, [[L\u0101\u010dpl\u0113sis Day]]\n* November 18, [[Proclamation Day of the Republic of Latvia]]\n\n===== Russia =====\nIn Russia, military parades are held in many parts of the country on the following days:\n\n* [[Defender of the Fatherland Day]] on 23 February\n* Victory Day on 9 May - Victory Day marks Germany's surrender to the Soviet Union in 1945 and is Russia's foremost national military holiday since 1995\n* Navy Day on the last Sunday of July\n* Air Force Day on 12 August\n* Ground Forces Day on 5 October\n\nAs well as on the following [[Days of Military Honour]]:\n\n* 27 January \u2013 the day of lifting of the [[Siege of Leningrad]], 1944\n* 2 February \u2013 victory in the [[Battle of Stalingrad]], 1943\n* 23 August \u2013 victory over [[Germany]] in the [[Battle of Kursk]], 1943\n* 2 September - [[Victory over Japan Day]]\n* 8 September - the anniversary of the [[Battle of Borodino]], 1812\n* 7 November \u2013 the anniversary of the [[1941 October Revolution Parade|historic 1941 military parades on the Red Square in Moscow and Kuybyshev Square in Samara]]<ref>7 November was a major holiday in the [[Soviet Union]] commemorating the [[October Revolution]]. In 1941, the troops that took part in the annual parade were sent from the [[Red Square]] directly to the front line which was situated less than a hundred kilometers from Moscow.</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Day of military glory of Russia - The day of the military parade on Red Square in 1941 | website=calendr.net | date=2018-01-25 | url=http://calendr.net/holiday/1731 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180125193640/http://calendr.net/holiday/1731 | archive-date=2018-01-25 | url-status=dead | access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref>\n\nMilitary parades were first held in 1702 as a troop review, but later grew into a ceremonial event held by order of the [[President of the Russian Federation]] in his constitutional duty as Supreme Commander of the Armed Forces. Alongside personnel and veterans of the Armed Forces, marching past in these parades are cadets of military high schools and middle schools and the [[Young Army Cadets National Movement]], cadets of military faculties of civil universities and battalions of [[Cossacks]], honoring their forebears who fought for their homeland in times past. Also, the following uniformed organizations take part in these parades:\n\n* [[Kremlin Regiment]] of the Federal Protective Service (in Moscow only)\n* [[National Guard of Russia]]\n* [[Police of Russia]] \n* [[Main Directorate for Drugs Control]]\n* [[Border Service of the Federal Security Service of the Russian Federation]]\n* [[Ministry of Emergency Situations (Russia)|Ministry of Emergency Situations]]\n* [[Federal Penitentiary Service]]\n* [[Investigative Committee of Russia]]\n\n===== Tajikistan =====\n{{See also|Tajikistan Independence Day Military Parade}}\n[[File:\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043d\u044f\u043b\u0438 \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0432 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0435 \u0432 \u0422\u0430\u0434\u0436\u0438\u043a\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435 01.jpg|thumb|A [[Victory Day Parades|Victory Day Parade]] in [[Victory Park, Dushanbe]].]]\nTajik military parades are held every 2 to 3 years on [[Dushanbe]]'s [[Dousti Square]]. They are either held on the occasion of [[Independence Day (Tajikistan)|Independence Day]] or [[Armed Forces Day (Tajikistan)|Armed Forces Day]]. They usually feature the entire Dushanbe Garrison and its hardware. The first parade in Dushanbe, which was at the time known as Stalinabad, took place on an area known as Red Square on 7 November 1945. Since then, Soviet military parades of the [[201st Motor Rifle Division]] in the [[Tajikistan SSR]] have been held on 9 May and 7 November in Lenin Square annually until 1990. The first military parade in the Republic of Tajikistan was held on armed forces day in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.tj/ru/node/232186|title='We were greeted as relatives.' From the Red Army to the military base|last=Shermatov|first=Gafur|date=2016-10-18|website=Tajikistan News|language=ru|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref><ref>https://asiaplustj.info/ru/news/life/person/20150930/70-let-vmeste-201-ya-rvb-prazdnuet-yubilei</ref><ref>https://stanradar.com/news/full/22568-ot-krasnoj-armii-do-rossijskoj-voennoj-bazy-v-tadzhikistane.html</ref>\n\n===== Turkmenistan =====\nThe principal parade hosted by the [[Armed Forces of Turkmenistan]] is held during the [[Turkmen Independence Day Parade|annual Independence Day Parade]] in Independence Square in [[Ashgabat]] every September 27, [[Independence Day (Turkmenistan)|Independence Day]], marking the day of the declaration of Turkmen independence from the Soviet Union in 1991. (From 1992 to 2017 the parade was held in October 27, the day of the independence plebiscite.)\n\n===== Ukraine =====\nUkrainian parades involve the active and reserve men and women and veterans of the [[Armed Forces of Ukraine]]. It holds parades on the following:\n\n* Second Sunday of July - [[Navy Day (Ukraine)|Navy Day]]\n* May 9 - [[Victory Day over Nazism in World War II]]\n* August 24 - [[Ukrainian Independence Day]]\n* October 13 - [[Defender of Ukraine Day]]\n\nSomething that distinguishes Ukrainian military parades from its other post-Soviet counterparts is, during the Kiev parade, the marchpast of the tri-service [[Kyiv Presidential Honor Guard Battalion]] with the [[Flag of Ukraine]] to raise at the flagpole while honors are rendered, which includes the playing of ''[[Shche ne vmerla Ukraina]]''. Since 2014, military bands have also played an integral part in these parades by marching with their units as part of the parade. Unlike their other counterparts, who use ''Hello Comrades'' as the official greeting during parades, Ukraine uses ''[[Glory to Ukraine]]'' as the official holiday greeting, with the troops responding by saying ''Glory to the Heroes''.<ref>{{cite web|title=President: The words \"Glory to Ukraine! Glory to the Heroes!\" will be the official greetings of the Armed Forces of our state|url=https://www.president.gov.ua/en/news/prezident-slova-slava-ukrayini-geroyam-slava-budut-oficijnim-48938|website=PRESIDENT OF UKRAINE Official website|publisher=Presidential Administration of Ukraine|accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe voice of military parades in Ukraine is [[Dmitry Khorkin]], who since 2011 has been the official master of ceremonies for the national parades held in Kiev's Independence Square.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ukr.radio/prog-presenter.html?id=66|title=\u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u043e \u0425\u043e\u0440\u043a\u0456\u043d {{!}} \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0434\u0456\u043e|website=ukr.radio|access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kp.ua/kiev/467334-kto-ozvuchyval-parad-v-kyeve|title=\u041a\u0442\u043e \u043e\u0437\u0432\u0443\u0447\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043b \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0432 \u041a\u0438\u0435\u0432\u0435?|website=kp.ua|language=ru-RU|access-date=2019-11-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fakty.com.ua/ru/ukraine/20190824-minimum-11-repetytsij-i-stsenariyi-na-vsi-vypadky-dmytro-horkin-pro-parady-u-den-nezalezhnosti/|title=\u0424\u0430\u043a\u0442\u044b ICTV \u0414\u0435\u043d\u044c \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0441\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438: \u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0425\u043e\u0440\u043a\u0438\u043d \u043e \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0447\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0440\u0435\u043f\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0446\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u0441\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u0441\u0435 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0438 {{!}} \u0424\u0430\u043a\u0442\u044b|date=2019-08-24|website=\u0424\u0410\u041a\u0422\u0418|access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref> Khorkin's voice became remarkable for official events with the participation of the country's top officials and for supporting the [[Armed Forces of Ukraine|Ukrainian army]], that's why he had received threats from [[Separatist forces of the war in Donbass|pro-Russian separatists]] before the 2016 military parade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gordonua.com/news/war/diktor-parada-v-kieve-iz-kryma-mne-napisali-chto-ya-prigovoren-146971.html|title=\u0414\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0432 \u041a\u0438\u0435\u0432\u0435: \u0418\u0437 \u041a\u0440\u044b\u043c\u0430 \u043c\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043b\u0438, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u044f \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0433\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0435\u043d|website=gordonua.com|access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref>\n\n====Serbia/Former Yugoslavia====\nMilitary parades in [[Serbia]] and the former [[Yugoslavia]] follow a close tradition that is significantly unique to the [[Balkan states]]. Their usage of the high step instead of the more European [[goose step]] is a notable display of heritage and tradition in their parades. The [[Yugoslav People's Army]] held its first military parade on [[Bulevar kralja Aleksandra|Bulevar revolucije]] just days before the conclusion of the Second World War on [[International Workers Day]]. Another parade on 20 October of that same year was held in honor of the one year anniversary of the end of the [[Belgrade Offensive]].<ref name=Parada>{{cite web | last=Radulovic | first=Mladen | title=Force of the Yugoslav National Army: Belgrade Thundered in the Last Military Parade in 1985! (Video) | website=kurir.rs | date=2014-10-10 | url=https://www.kurir.rs/vesti/drustvo/1586710/sila-jugoslovenske-narodne-armije-beograd-grmeo-na-poslednjoj-vojnoj-paradi-1985-video | language=bs | access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref>\n\nSince then military parades in the [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|SFRY]] were held on the following dates and occasions:\n\n*1 May 1946\n*19 October 1946\n*1 May 1947\n*1 May 1948\n*1 May 1949\n*1 May 1950\n*1 May 1951\n*1 May 1952\n*1 May 1953\n*1 May 1954\n*1 May 1955\n*1 May 1956\n*1 May 1957\n*1 May 1960\n*1 May 1961\n*1 May 1962\n*1 May 1963\n*1 May 1964\n*9 May 1965\n*9 May 1970\n*9 May 1975 &ndash; It was the first parade to feature the high-stepping march style, which was instituted by [[Josip Broz Tito|Marshal Josip Broz Tito]] to assert his [[Non-Aligned Movement|independence]] from Soviet influence.\n*9 May 1985 &ndash; The parade (branded as ''Parade 85'') was the last victory parade before the brake up of Yugoslavia in the early 90s. It was also significant as it was the first parade that was not presided by Marshal Tito as leader of Yugoslavia.\n\n[[File:Military Parade Belgrade 2014 - Serbian Soldiers with Russian Knights - The Swifts (15878267398).jpg|thumb|The [[Serbian Guards Unit]] during the [[Belgrade Military Parade]].]]\n\nThe first parade in the Republic of Serbia took place on Liberation Day on 16 October 2014. Known commonly as the [[Belgrade Military Parade|''March of the Victor'']], the parade took place on Nikola Tesla Boulevard and included 4,500 [[Serbian Army]] troops, the Russian [[Swifts (aerobatic team)|Swifts aerobatic team]] and even an appearance by Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] as the guest of honour.<ref>{{cite news|title=Putin guest of honour at Serbia military parade|publisher=BBC|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-29641642}}</ref> On 10 May 2019, the first [[Victory Day Parades|Victory Day Parade]] in close to 35 years was held in the city of [[Ni\u0161]]. Branded as the \"Defence of Freedom\" show, the parade also included personnel of the [[Police of Serbia]], which also marked the 20th anniversary of the Yugoslav resistance to the [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rs.n1info.com/English/NEWS/a482164/Serbia-prepares-4-000-soldiers-for-Victory-Day-parade.html|title=Serbia\u2019s army and police prepare for Victory Day parade|website=N1 Srbija}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://balkaninsight.com/2019/05/10/serbia-marks-victory-day-with-grand-military-parade/|title=Serbia Marks Victory Day with Grand Military Parade|date=May 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amp.dw.com/en/my-europe-serbias-military-parade-between-the-east-and-the-west/a-48692961|title=Serbia marches between the East and the West|website=amp.dw.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-05/11/c_138049369.htm|title=Serbia marks Victory Day with police, military parade|website=www.xinhuanet.com}}</ref> Outside of the [[Serbian Armed Forces]], the [[Army of the Republic of North Macedonia]], the [[Armed Forces of Montenegro]] and [[Armed Forces of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia and Herzegovina]] use the Serbian/Yugoslav parade format.\n\n==== Turkey ====\n[[Image:Tag des Sieges 1.JPG|thumb|300px|Parade at the [[Victory Day (Turkey)|Victory Day]] (Zafer Bayram\u0131) in Istanbul]]\nThe Turkish tradition of military parades was introduced in the 19th century as part of the Westernization and modernization of the army and navy of the then Ottoman Empire to modern standards of warfare and military ceremonial, a tradition carried on by the modern [[Turkish Armed Forces]], whose parade drill includes high stepping, a tradition introduced in the 1900s.\n\nToday parades held by the Turkish Armed Forces and its veterans are held in the following days:\n\n* April 23 - National Sovereignty and Children's Day\n* May 23 - Commemoration of Atat\u00fcrk, Youth and Sports Day\n* August 30 - Victory Day, also principal holiday of the Armed Forces\n* October 29 - Republic Day\n\n====United Kingdom====\n[[File:The Army celebrate the birthday of their Queen. MOD 45162711.jpg|thumb|The troops of the [[Household Division]] during the 2017 [[Trooping the Colour]]]]\nIn the [[United Kingdom]], a [[guard of honour]] traditionally performs the march past for whoever received the salute. In the capital of [[London]], traditional ceremonial units that  perform [[public duties]] (the [[Queens Guard]] for example) take part in military parades such as the more common [[Trooping the Colour]] on [[Horse Guards Parade]] and special parades during the jubilee years of the monarch in his or her capacity as commander-in-chief of the [[British Armed Forces]]. The [[Household Cavalry]] (Blues and Royals and Life Guards) traditionally perform trot pasts in mounted formation, together with the [[King's Troop, Royal Horse Artillery]]. These units have been known to parade in slow and quick time. Personnel of the armed forces, cadet organizations, [[The Royal British Legion]] and veterans' organizations also parade during national holidays such as [[Remembrance Day]] or [[Armed Forces Day (United Kingdom)|Armed Forces Day]]. During a regimental military parade, the [[Regimental marches of the British Army|regimental march of the unit]] is played.\n\n====United States====\n[[File:President Bush greets General H. Norman Schwarzkopf who leads the Desert Storm Homecoming Parade in Washington, D.C - NARA - 186434.jpg|thumb|President [[George H. W. Bush]] greeting [[Norman Schwarzkopf Jr.]] on the parade route.]]\nMilitary parades in the American capital are held quadrennially by servicemen of the [[United States Armed Forces]] during the [[United States presidential inauguration|Presidential inaugural parade]]. These are not considered to be regular military parades however, as the parading formations are actually not entirely composed of armed servicemen. The first known organized military procession in the [[United States]] was the [[Grand Review of the Armies]], on May 23 and May 24, 1865, following the end of the [[American Civil War]] (1861-1865). The [[New York City Victory Parade of 1946]] was held in mid-January in 1946 to commemorate the conclusion of [[World War II]] and the Allied victory over the Axis Powers in all theaters of the war, helped by the service of millions of Americans who served under the armed forces and the National Guard, in addition to the state defense forces. In the late 40s and the early 50s, massive parades in honor of Army Day and later Armed Forces Day were held in the capital.<ref>https://networks.h-net.org/node/28441/discussions/1341907/washington-loves-parade</ref> The most recently held military parade was the [[National Victory Celebration]] on June 8, 1991, to celebrate the conclusion of [[Gulf War]] in [[Iraq]]. In 2018, a national debate was sparked when President [[Donald Trump]] proposed to hold a [[2018 Washington Veterans Day Parade|military parade]] on 10 November 2018 in honor of the Veterans Day holiday the next day, commonly known as \"Trump's military parade\". This was seen as expensive and authoritarian-like and by August of that year, the Department of Defense announced that the military parade would be postponed until 2019.<ref>{{cite news|last1=News|first1=ABC|title=Trump's military parade is postponed until 2019|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/trumps-military-parade-estimated-cost-92-million/story?id=57218363|accessdate=17 August 2018|work=ABC News|date=16 August 2018|language=en}}</ref> The 2019 Fourth of July parade was the first attended by the [[President of the United States]] in his capacity as the constitutional commander-in-chief of the United States Armed Forces and the National Guard Bureau, with the parade route was changed to include the [[Lincoln Memorial]] complex within the greater area around the National Mall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2019/06/20/president-trump-finally-get-his-military-parade-july-4.html|title=President Trump to Finally Get His Military Parade on July 4|first=Richard|last=Sisk|date=June 20, 2019|website=Military.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/trump-s-desired-military-parade-analysts-blast-plan-north-korea-n845626|title=Analysts blast Trump's desired military parade as 'North Korea-style' event|website=NBC News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/05/us/politics/trump-4th-of-july.html|title=Trump Sets Off Fireworks of a Different Sort With Fourth of July Speech Plan|first=Peter|last=Baker|date=June 5, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> It was also the first time since the 1950s where units aside from the guards of honor, also included cadets from the [[military academies]], units of the Armed Forces and the [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] and the nationally produced [[military equipment]] of the services marching past in the national capital city in front of the members of government, [[US Congress|Congress]], veterans and the people of the capital.\n\nAnnual military parades, as well as armed forces and veterans' participation in civil parades are held in the following days in major cities in the country, in areas with military installations and in state capitals:\n\n* March 29: Vietnam Veterans Day\n* 3rd Saturday of May: Armed Forces Day \n* Last Monday of May: [[Memorial Day]]\n* 14 June: Flag Day and Army Birthday\n* 4 July - United States Independence Day\n* 11 November - Veterans Day \n* 4th Thursday of November - Thanksgiving Day\n\nParades are also held within the military academies, high schools, bases and installations of the Armed Forces, as well as by JROTC and ROTC units and youth uniformed cadet organizations on the following days aside from the aforementioned Army Birthday:\n\n* 4 August: Coast Guard Day (United States Coast Guard)\n* 17 September: Air Force Day (United States Air Force)\n* 13 October: US Navy Birthday (United States Navy)\n* 27 October: Navy Day (United States Navy)\n* 10 November: Marine Corps Day (United States Marine Corps)\n* 13 December: National Guard Day ([[National Guard of the United States]])\n* During a change of command, retirement and recruit and cadet graduation parades within the service branches of the armed forces and all military academies and high schools\n* During unitwide anniversaries and remembrance days of important battles of the Armed Forces\n* During holidays marked by each of the states and federal territories and major cities as well as in [[Puerto Rico]] as can be permitted by the commander of the unit taking part\n\nThe typical presidential inaugural or holiday parade hosted in Washington, D.C., is hosted by the [[Washington metropolitan area|National Capital Region]] of the Department of Defense, while local and state level parades are hosted by the local military installations and local area governments.\n\n==== Venezuela ====\n[[File:Venezuelan armed forces.jpg|thumb|Cadets of the [[Bolivarian Military University of Venezuela]] in their unique slow march in a military parade]]\nFull blown military parades by the [[National Bolivarian Armed Forces of Venezuela]] are held on the following days:\n\n* 13 April, National Militia Day\n* 19 April, 19 April National Day\n* 24 June, Army Day\n* 5 July, [[Caracas Independence Day parade|Independence Day]]\n* 24 July, Navy Day (including the occasional fleet review)\n* 7 August, National Guard Day\n* 27 November, Air Force Day\n* During change of command, retirement and recruit and cadet graduation parades within the service branches of the armed forces and all military academies and high schools \n* Following the presidential inauguration ceremony every 6 years in Caracas\n\nTaking part on these parades are active duty and reserve personnel of the NBAF and its service branches, and these are a mix of the German, British and later on Chinese and Russian traditions.\n\nIn August 2018, during a military parade and ceremony on the [[Venezuelan National Guard]]'s 81st anniversary, President [[Nicolas Maduro]] was targeted in a [[Caracas drone attack|drone attack]], which left him unharmed, and left 8\u20139 people injured.\n\n==See also==\n*[[At attention]]\n*[[Military band]]\n*[[Parade]]\n*[[Drill commands]]\n*[[Exhibition drill]]\n*[[March (music)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Military parades| ]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Tag des Sieges 1.JPG|thumb|300px|Parade at the [[Victory Day (Turkey)|Victory Day]] (Zafer Bayram\u0131) in Istanbul]]\n[[File:US Navy 050120-F-3231D-692 he U.S. Navy Honor Guard marches past President George W. Bush during the 2005 Presidential Inaugural Parade held in Washington D.C.jpg|thumb|300px|[[United States]] Presidential Inaugural Parade held in [[Washington D.C.]]]]\n[[Image:ESM Saint-Cyr 14 07 07.jpg|thumb|300px|right|[[\u00c9cole sp\u00e9ciale militaire de Saint-Cyr|Saint-Cyr cadets]] at the [[Bastille Day Military Parade]] on the [[Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]]]]\n[[File:2june 2007 580.jpg|thumb|300px|right|[[Carabinieri Cavalry Regiment]] at the military parade of ''[[Festa della Repubblica]]'' 2007]]\n\nA '''military parade''' is a formation of soldiers whose movement is restricted by close-order manoeuvering known as '''drilling''' or '''marching'''. The military [[parade]] is now almost entirely ceremonial, though soldiers from time immemorial up until the late 19th century fought in formation. Massed parades may also hold a role for propaganda purposes, being used to exhibit the apparent military strength of one's nation.\n\n==History==\n\nThe terminology comes from the tradition of \n[[close order formation]] combat, in which soldiers were held in very strict formations as to maximise their combat effectiveness. Formation combat was used as an alternative to [[m\u00eal\u00e9e]] combat, and required strict discipline in the ranks and competent officers. As long as their formations could be maintained, regular troops could maintain a significant advantage over less organised opponents. Military parades are not to be confused with military show of force.\n\nAlthough the firepower of breechloading rifles and [[machine guns]] long ago rendered close formations in battle suicidal, modern armies still use parades for ceremonial purposes or in non-combat environments for their efficiency, ease of organization and encouragement of discipline. Roughly synonymous are \"drill\" and \"march\". The English word \"drill\" is of [[Middle Dutch]] origin, dating from the 16th-century drill of the Dutch army of prince [[Maurice of Orange]], which was widely copied throughout Europe at the time, decreasing the volley time of musket formations.\n\nIn ancient times, drilling increased in importance when men stopped fighting as individuals and began to fight together as units. Drilling as a vital component of a war machine further increased with the increases in the size of armies, for example when [[Phillip II of Macedon]] disciplined his army so they could swiftly form the [[Phalanx formation|phalanxes]] that were so critical to his successes as a general. Military drilling later was used by the [[Roman Army]] to maximise efficiency and deadliness throughout their long history. After the fall of the empire, and the [[Dark Ages (historiography)|Dark Ages]] set in Europe, most feudal lords more heavily relied on peasant levies and their wealthy [[knights]] to fight their wars, the knights for the most part reverting to fighting as individuals{{Citation needed|date=April 2015}}. Massed military drilling was used mostly by only the foremost armies and nations, such as the [[Normans]].\n\nThe U.S. drill is based on the contributions of [[Baron von Steuben]], a [[Prussian Army]] officer who served in the [[Continental Army]].<ref>Paul Lockhart, ''The Drillmaster of Valley Forge: The Baron de Steuben and the Making of the American Army'' (Washington, DC: Smithsonian Books, 2008)</ref> During the winter quarters in [[Valley Forge]], Pennsylvania, von Steuben taught a model company of 100 soldiers musket drill. These soldiers, in turn, taught the remainder of the Continental Army.\n\nThe most familiar form of [[melee weapon]] and [[unarmed combat]] drill in the modern world is the [[Kata]] and the [[Hyung]] in Eastern [[martial arts]]. However, there were once similar drills in the martial training of warriors in all cultures worldwide. They all had exactly the same purpose, to make instinctive an appropriate reaction to an attack or opening by conditioning the mind and body, through repeated and constant repetition of a series of actions (building up [[muscle memory]]). Probably one of the last survivors of such drills in the Western martial tradition are the reaction drills and rhythm exercises in the modern sport of [[fencing]].\n\n[[File:\u0411\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0434\u044b\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043c\u0430\u0448\u0438\u043d\u0430 SandCat.JPG|thumb|Parade during [[Defender of the Fatherland Day (Kazakhstan)|Defender of the Fatherland Day]] in [[Nur-Sultan]].]]\n\nThe oldest, largest and most famous regular military parade in [[Europe]] is the [[Bastille Day Military Parade]] which is held each 14 July, on the [[Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]] in [[Paris]], during [[Bastille Day|France's national day]] celebrations.<ref name=\"paris1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.paris.com/paris_city_guide/city_visits_of_paris/champs_elysees_arc_de_triomphe |title=Champs-Elys\u00e9es city visit in Paris, France - Recommended city visit of Champs-Elys\u00e9es in Paris |publisher=Paris.com |accessdate=2011-07-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807091009/http://www.paris.com/paris_city_guide/city_visits_of_paris/champs_elysees_arc_de_triomphe |archivedate=2011-08-07 }}</ref><ref name=\"paris-attractions1\">\n{{cite web\n |url=http://paris-attractions.net/celebrate-bastille-day-in-paris-this-year/\n |title=Celebrate Bastille Day in Paris This Year\n |publisher=Paris Attractions |date=2011-05-03\n |accessdate=2011-07-27 |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326174027/http://paris-attractions.net/celebrate-bastille-day-in-paris-this-year/\n |archivedate=2012-03-26 }}\n</ref>\n\n==Rationale==\n[[File:Queen's Birthday Parade, Hamilton Bermuda 2000.jpg|thumb|Queen's Birthday Parade, [[Hamilton, Bermuda]], 2000.]]\nA military drill is memorizing certain actions through repetition until the action is instinctive to the soldiers being drilled. Complex actions are broken down into simpler ones which can be practised in isolation so when the whole is put together the desired results are achieved. Such is necessary for a fighting force to perform at maximum efficiency in all manner of situations. However, depending on the army and the drills it adopts, drilling may destroy flexibility and initiative in exchange for predictability and cohesion.\n\nRecruits in most modern militaries are taught drill to teach them how to work and move as a team. In addition, formations are still used in [[riot control]], where m\u00eal\u00e9e combat is still the norm.\n\n==Four directions==\n[[File:2010 Moscow Victory Day Parade-5.jpeg|thumb|[[2010 Moscow Victory Day Parade]]]]\nParades consist of four directions:\n# Advance\n# Retire\n# Left\n# Right\n\nThe Advance is the primary direction of movement, regardless of which direction the soldiers are actually facing (similar to a ship's [[Bow (ship)|bow]].) On a parade square, the advance is determined by the position of the [[dais]] or flags. When these are not present, the direction of the drill commander is the advance.\n\nThe Retire is opposite to the advance, against the primary direction of movement (similar to a ship's [[stern]].)\n\nThe Left is to the left of the Advance (similar to a ship's [[Port (nautical)|port]].)\n\nThe Right is to the right of the Advance (similar to a ship's [[starboard]].)\n\nIf the Advance is changed, then all other directions are changed to be based on the new Advance.\n\nThere is only one person in charge of a parade at a time. Changing this person is very ceremonious. This is to make it obvious to the soldiers who is currently in command and therefore to whom to pay attention.\n\nDuring parades, unless explicitly told otherwise, soldiers have restricted movement, meaning they can move only exactly when they are told, and then doing only exactly what they are told to do. In most stances, any movement at all is disallowed and is held to such an extent as to have soldiers fainting on parade, although fainting under any conditions short of plural hours standing still in the hot sun is considered a sign of medical disability.<ref name=indianman>{{cite web|last=Srivastava|first=Vikram|title=Drills and Parades|url=http://bprd.nic.in/writereaddata/mainlinkFile/File965.pdf|work=Police Drill Manual|publisher=Bureau of Police Research and Development, Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India|accessdate=21 February 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206154713/http://bprd.nic.in/writereaddata/mainlinkFile/File965.pdf|archivedate=6 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nAmerican usage allows the service member to be at four states of alert:\n# [[At attention|Attention]]: standing straight, eyes forward, chest out, knees straight but not locked, feet together at a 45-degree angle.\n# Parade Rest: A modified position of attention in which the left foot is moved to shoulder width (typically measured as exactly 12 inches) and the hands are placed in the small of the back with the right hand placed inside the left with all fingers together and pointing rigidly straight (exception: U.S. Air Force usage is modelled after Commonwealth practice - see below).\n# Stand At Ease: Same as Parade Rest, but the soldier may look at the speaker.\n# At Ease: The service member is allowed to move around all but the right foot, but must remain silent.\n# Rest: Service member may talk, smoke (if command authorized) and may move as long as their right pivot foot remains grounded.\nA formation must be brought to the position of attention before it can go to a higher state of alert.<ref name=\"army\">FM 22-5, Drill and Ceremonies, Headquarters, Department of the Army, 1986</ref><ref name=\"marine\">NAVMC 2691 Marine Corps Drill and Ceremonies Manual, Headquarters, United States Marine Corps, 1981</ref>\n\n[[Commonwealth of Nations]] countries allow four states of alert:\n# Attention: standing straight, eyes forward, heels together, feet at a 30-degree angle (540 mils). The hands are held in tight fists with the thumbs aligned with the seam of the trousers.\n# At Ease: a modified position of attention in which the left foot is moved to shoulder width and the hands are placed behind the back with arms fully extended. The right hand is placed inside the left. [[United States|U.S.]] military usage is \"Parade Rest.\"\n# Stand-Easy: Legs remain in the At Ease position, arms are brought to the sides to a more natural standing position. Member may relax their muscles and make minimal movements. U.S. usage is \"At Ease,\" however a common mistake in U.S. military practice confuses \"At Ease\" with \"Rest\" (below).\n# Relax: Legs remain at position at ease, member may make more significant movements or look around. Members may not move the feet. If the troops are not being addressed by a commander, they are generally allowed to talk quietly. U.S. usage is \"Rest.\"\n\n==Common parade commands==\n*'''Fall In'''. Have designated troops move into an already existing formation on the parade square and/or ground.\n*'''Fall Out'''. Have designated troops wheel out and to the right of their formation, then halt facing the parade commander to be dismissed.\n*'''Dis -Miss'''. Telling designated units to leave the parade square and stop drilling. \n*'''[Parade Size]/Parade, [Parade Size], Atten-Tion (Shun)''' (U.S.: '''Atten - Tion (Shun)'''). Have the soldiers uniformly adopt the [[At attention|Attention position]], the most constrictive position (with feet together), but the only position from which soldiers can actually be made to move. In the United States military, the position is defined as heels together, feet at a 45-degree angle, arms straight, palms inward with fingers naturally curled, thumbs along the seams of trousers, shoulders square and head erect, looking forward. In the Royal Navy, the order \"Shun\" is replaced with the order \"Ho\". For Example, the most common usage is \"Guard Ho!\" With a small pause between words.\n\n===Alignment commands===\n\n====Commonwealth version====\n[[Image:Royal Military College of Canada cadets drill in parade square, Stone Frigate 1880s.jpg|thumb|right|220px|[[Royal Military College of Canada]] cadets drill in Military parade square, in front of [[HMCS Stone Frigate|Stone Frigate]] 1880s]]\n*'''Right Dress''', - all personnel in front row and right side column except the right marker take one step forward, pause, and only the front rank bring up their right arms parallel to the ground. At the same time, all members of the formation snap their heads so they are facing right. After this, they pause, and then shuffle back to a new position, where their hand is extremely close to the soldier's shoulder on their right, unless otherwise specified (Elbow Dressing, Shoulder Dressing).  Some Armies, e.g. the Australian Army, will raise the left arm (the right arm holding the service weapon).\n*'''Left Dress''', - all personnel in front row and left column except the left marker take one step forward, pause, and only the front rank bring up their left arms parallel to the ground. At the same time, all members of the formation snap their heads so they are facing left. After this, they pause, and then shuffle back to a new position, where their hand is extremely close to the soldier's shoulder on their right, unless otherwise specified (Elbow Dressing, Shoulder Dressing).\n*'''Inwards Dress/Centre Dress''', used when a parade is formed up in two or more groups with [[Military colours, standards and guidons|Colours, Guidons, or Banners]] on parade.  This is used so that dressing is off the colours.  The formations to the left of the Colour Party will dress to the right and the formations to the right of the Colour Party will dress to the left.   All personnel to the right of the Colours in front row and left column except the left marker take one step forward, pause, and only the front rank bring up their left arms parallel to the ground. At the same time, all members of the formation snap their heads so they are facing left. All personnel to the left of the colours in front row and right side column except the right marker take one step forward, pause, and only the front rank bring up their right arms parallel to the ground. At the same time, all members of the formation snap their heads so they are facing right. Some Armies, i.e. the Australian Army, will raise the left arm (the right arm holding the service weapon).  After this, they pause, and then shuffle back to a new position, where their hand is extremely close to the soldier's shoulder on their left or right (depending on the direction of dressing), unless otherwise specified (Elbow Dressing, Shoulder Dressing).\n*'''Eyes Front''', following Right/Left/Inwards Dress, the front rank snaps their arms down and faces forward, while all other ranks simply face forward.\n\n====American version====\n*'''Dress Right, DRESS''' - all personnel in the unit except the soldiers at the far left bring up their left arms parallel to the ground and at the same time snap their heads so they are facing right.  The person on the far right will keep his head straight. After this, they pause, and then shuffle back to a new position, where their hand is extremely close to the soldier's shoulder on their left.  If the command is preceded by '''\"At Close Interval\"''', the left arm is bent at the elbow rather than parallel to the ground.  If the command is preceded by '''\"At Double Interval\"''', both arms are extended.  '''\"Dress Left\"''' reverses the instructions (Right arm up, look left).\n*'''Ready, FRONT''' - all personnel snap their arms down and faces forward.\n*'''COVER''' - used after any movement is halted to realign the formation.  All personnel in the formation except the squad leaders make short, choppy steps to align themselves with their squad leaders, then come to attention.<ref name = \"army\"/><ref name = \"marine\"/>\n\n===Rest positions===\n[[File:A Member of the Queen's Guards, Guarding the Mall - geograph.org.uk - 1354107.jpg|thumb|190px|A British [[Household Division]] soldier in the position of at ease.]]\n[[File:120416-Z-KZ880-024 (7109575235).jpg|thumb|American honour guards in the ceremonial at ease position.]]\n*'''Stand at Ease''' (U.S.: '''PARADE REST'''). Have the soldiers adopt the more relaxed position At Ease position, with feet shoulder width apart, hands clasped behind back but with upper body half still in position of attention (chest out, shoulders back). This is typically used when soldiers must wait a short duration, ready to adopt the position of attention e.g. if waiting for an Officer to arrive for an inspection. Changing from At Ease to Attention and back again, or the converse, is standard when the command of a parade is transferred (typically between the commanding officer and his Sergeant-Major), since command of a formation is not actually transferred until the new commander makes a command. There is no talking allowed at Parade Rest; personnel must come to the position of attention before speaking.\n*'''Stand at Ease''' (U.S.) This is the same as Parade Rest, except that soldiers are expected to turn their heads to look at whoever is addressing them. This should not be confused with At Ease.\n*'''Stand Easy'''. (U.S.: '''AT EASE''') Have the soldiers adopt the next easiest stance, where hands are still clasped behind the back, however, the soldiers can relax their upper bodies (the shoulders can be slacked) and quietly speak. This is often, but not always, followed by an implicit 'Relax' ('Rest'). This is typically used when being addressed/lectured for a long period of time where the positions of attention or at ease would be too painful/uncomfortable to hold.\n*'''Relax''' (U.S.: '''REST''') The only parade instruction given in an ordinary voice, rather than the raised, emphatic parade voice. This is the only position that actually offers soldiers freedom of movement. Soldiers are typically allowed to move other than moving their feet, though, when it is given by a high-ranking officer, soldiers typically move a minimal amount after a bit of stretching.\n\n===Marching with weapons/saluting===\n'''[[Rifle]]s'''\n*'''Shoulder/Slope Arms''': Although Left and Right Shoulder Arms are both valid commands, left is assumed if it is unstated. Soldiers must be at attention to shoulder weapons. This is typically done through a throw rather than a carry. In British and Commonwealth parades, the command \"Slope Arms\" is used to order soldiers to place their rifles on the top of the shoulder. The command of \"Shoulder Arms\" in the Commonwealth and Britain, is done when a rifle is brought on the left or right sides by the shoulder with the carrying hand holding the pistol grip. In US ceremonies, if the soldiers have the weapons at the order, then it is brought up and carried on the right shoulder, and all shoulder commands must specify the shoulder, and may be performed while [[military step|marching in step]].\n*'''Port Arms''': The weapon is brought out in front of the soldier, and held by the right hand on small of the butt, or equivalent, and the left hand about the forestock, or equivalent. Usually this command is used for preparation of the Feu De Joie/Fire of Joy for parades. In the United States, Port Arms is the required carry position for marching at [[military step|double time]].\n*'''[[Present arms (command)|Present Arms]]''': The soldiers bring their weapons to the front of their bodies, and move adjust their right foot position. Soldiers without weapons use a salute appropriate for their headdress. Often officers can salute on behalf of their troops, and any such ambiguity will be discussed with the troops beforehand. This, in the case of the United Kingdom and the Commonwealth of Nations, is often used with the precautionary General/Commander's Salute or Royal/Presidential/Prime Minister's Salute, when appropriate. In U.S. usage, all soldiers salute, except if he or she is holding a weapon. Guidons and organizational colors are dipped to 90 degrees above the ground (but not touching the ground, but in the Commonwealth it is common practice). The U.S. national colors are never dipped (it is also the case in Colombia, Chile, Brazil and Spain) but the British or Commonwealth national colors are dipped to the ground when the salute is performed. This command is used whenever saluting during ceremonial inspections in most countries (like Germany, France, Russia, Poland, Italy, Serbia and Ukraine as well as in Chile, Argentina, Ecuador and Colombia), and eyes are pointed to either the left, on the front, or the right to the direction of the honors being paid to. The command for recovery is \"Shoulder/Slope Arms!\" or \"Order Arms!\" depending on the situation.\n*'''Order Arms''': If the soldiers are carrying a weapon which can be ordered they will lower it so that is resting on the ground, touching the outer toes of the right boot, and being supported by a slightly bent right arm. Usually given in Shoulder/Slope Arms or Present Arms position.\n*'''Ground Arms''': The soldier takes a full pace forward, bending their knees, so the right leg is parallel to the floor below the knee, and at the same time leaning forward and laying their rifles down to the ground (ejection port up). They then take the appropriate pause time, then stand up into attention.\n*'''Trail Arms''': Same as Order Arms but with hands holding on the rifle above the ground.\n*'''Sling Arms''': If the soldiers have a \"[[sling (firearms)|sling]]\" (strap) on their rifles, then this command can be called. The soldiers will loosen the sling so they can now have their rifles strapped around their shoulders.\n*'''Unsling Arms''': Servicemen will unloosen the sling so they can now have their rifles at the port or high port position.\n*'''Front Sling Arms''': Servicemen holding weapons with slings attached to the chest now sling those weapons in the Port or High Port Arms position.\n*'''High Port Arms''': This is a higher variant of Port Arms, with both arms holding the weapon high. \n*'''Fire of Joy, load weapons''': This command is used in parades such as the [[Singapore National Day Parade|National Day Parade in Singapore]], and [[Trooping the Colour]]. The soldier will load the rifle with the blank round in preparation of the [[Feu de joie]], French for Fire of Joy in parades. This is called in Polish as the ''Salwa Honorowa'' or Honor Volley.\n*'''Fix Bayonets''': In US ceremonies, whenever the bayonets are to be fixed to the weapons, this command is called out. In times, the accompanying bugle call for it is used before the order is done. The troops pull out their bayonets from their uniforms and attach them to the weapon.\n*'''Unfix Bayonets''': Soldiers in formation remove their bayonets from their rifles and return them to their uniforms.\n\n'''[[Sabre]]s'''\n*'''Draw Sabres''': used to draw the sabres.\n*'''Return Sabres''': used to return the sabres.\n*'''Present Sabres''': used for officers to salute using their sabres.\n*'''Shoulder/Slope Sabres''': used for officers to slope the sabre in their left-hand shoulder.\n*'''Order Sabres''': the sabre is lowered to the ground after presenting or sloping.\n\n=== Forming the parade for the march past/pass in review ===\n[[File:Pass and Review.jpg|thumb|Marine Corps General [[Joseph Dunford]], takes part in a pass in review of the [[Ceremonial Guard (Canada)|Ceremonial Guard]] in [[Ottawa]], [[Canada]].]]\n*'''Pass in Review''' - used in the US to denote the start of the march past segment of parades. When this command is said the parade prepares in readiness for the march past. It is also used as a way for a newly assigned commander to inspect the troops he/she commands.<ref>{{cite web | title=Air Force ROTC Detachment 225, Pass in Review | website=University of Notre Dame | date=2019-06-18 | url=https://afrotc.nd.edu/det-225-history/military-functions/pass-in-review/ | access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://idioms.thefreedictionary.com/pass+in+review|title=Pass in Rview|website=TheFreeDictionary.com}}</ref>\n* '''Parade, in close order, left/right dress''' - in the UK, this command is used to commence dressing of parade units in close order\n* '''Company, in close order, form three/four ranks''' - in the UK, this command is used to form companies into three or four ranks of personnel each\n* '''Staff behind me, (forward) march''' - in the US, this command is used by the parade commander to form his parade staff in readiness for the march past/pass in review segment of parades\n* '''Parade will now advance/retire in slow/quick time, about turn''' - in the Commonwealth the command is used to form parade formations when arranged in line formation for the march past\n\n===Compliments and Saluting===\n\n====Saluting on the march====\nIn the Commonwealth countries, the following saluting on the march commands are ordered with a preparatory command of ''''Saluting on the march...''''. For example, ''''Saluting on the march, to the front Salute'''' and always called on the left foot.\n*'''To the front Salute''' or '''Salute''': The parade is halted and the right arm is raised so the forearm is placed at a 90\u00b0 angle, while pointing at the temple. This is lowered and then repeated again, followed by an about turn and a resume in marching (off the left foot). The timing is: \"Call, Check, Halt, 2, 3, Up, 2, 3, Down, 2, 3, 4, 5, Up, 2, 3, Down, 2, 3, About, 2, 3, In, 2, 3, Left, Right, Left!\" It is one of, if not the longest drill movement in the military.\nIn British Corps, the drill movement for saluting to the front is the following. Two, three, up. Two, three, down.\n*'''To the Right Salute''': The right arm is raised so the forearm is placed at a 90\u00b0 angle, while pointing at the temple. It is generally to a count of \"Up, two, three, four, five, down, swing!\"\n:This is done while looking to the right, except the right marker, who must stay looking to the front, to keep the flight, squad, platoon, etc. staying straight.\n*'''To the Left Salute''': The right arm is raised so the forearm is placed at a 90\u00b0 angle, while pointing at the temple. It is generally to a count of \"Up, two, three, four, five, down, away!\"\n:This is done while looking to the left, except the left marker (as they are the front most of the saluting flank), who must stay looking to the front, to keep the flight, squad, platoon, etc. staying straight.\n\nIn the United States, the command for saluting on the march is \"Eyes, RIGHT/LEFT.\" The parade leader and other officers execute the hand salute, while everyone but the right file or left file in either case turns their heads to the right.\" The command for recovery is \"Ready, FRONT.\" If the command does not have rifles, they will salute if given the command '''present ARMS'''. The arms will be lowered back to their normal position on the commands '''Order ARMS'''. They can also salute if given the command '''Hand SALUTE'''. The salute is raised when the parade leader finishes saying \"salute\", and is lowered in after being held for the same amount of time elapsed between the words \"hand\" and \"salute.\"\n\n=== Compliments on the March ===\n\n*'''Eyes Right''': The parade turn their heads to the right after a check pace. The parade leader salutes while looking in the direction they gave.\n:This is done while looking to the right, except the right marker, who must stay looking to the front, to keep the flight, squad, platoon, etc. staying straight.\n*'''Eyes Left''': Similar to the '''Eyes Right''' except the parade looks to the left.\n:This is done while looking to the left, except the left marker, who must stay looking to the front, to keep the flight, squad, platoon, etc. staying straight.\n\n====Saluting at the halt (static)====\n*'''To the front Salute''' or '''Salute''': The right arm is raised so the forearm is placed at a 90\u00b0 angle, while pointing at the temple. It is generally to a count of \"Up, two, three, down!\"\n*'''To the Right Salute''': The right arm is raised so the forearm is placed at a 90\u00b0 angle, while pointing at the temple. It is generally to a count of \"Up, two, three, down!\" \n*'''To the Left Salute''': The right arm is raised so the forearm is placed at a 90\u00b0 angle, while pointing at the temple. It is generally to a count of \"Up, two, three, down!\"\nIn the United States, salutes at a halt are given on the command \"Hand Salute\". They are lowered in the same amount of time elapsed between the two words. The command \"present arms\" will cause the command to salute if the command is not given rifles for the ceremony, but the salute will be held until they are ordered to lower it with the command \"order arms\".\n*'''Advance in Review Order''': This is used to pay final compliments to the reviewing officer. On the command: ADVANCE IN REVIEW ORDER, BY THE CENTRE, QUICK...MARCH, the unit being reviewed advances 15 paces and halts automatically before presenting arms to the reviewing officer. It is usually employed by the [[British Army]] and the [[Canadian Army]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.2824cops.com/wp-content/uploads/Army-Cadet-Reference-Manual.pdf|title=Royal Canadian Army Cadets: Cadet Reference Book|publisher=National Defence|year=2001|location=Canada|oclc=289058362|id=A-CR-CCP-121/PT-001}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.napoleon-series.org/cgi-bin/forum/archive2006_config.pl?md=read;id=67469|title=Historical Need for Drill|website=www.napoleon-series.org}}</ref>\n\n===Colour commands===\n\n====Marching with colours====\n*'''Let Fly the Colours''': The colours are normally held in a semi-taut position. This is a simple, ceremonial letting fly and catching of the colours.\n*'''Slant Colours''': The colours are normally kept upright, but this can represent a problem both when dealing with standard doors. This slants the colours forward sufficiently to negate this, and they are brought back up afterward.\n*'''Slope/Shoulder Colours''': The normal method for carrying colours can be tiresome for the bearer. This has the colours taken out of their frogs and sloped over the right shoulder at about 45\u00b0.\n\n====Colour commands at the halt (static)====\n*'''Order Colours''': Essentially the same as Order Arms, except used exclusively for the Colour Party.\n*'''Carry Colours''': This is equivalent to Shoulder Arms. The right arm lifts the colours up so they line up with the body's centre line, with the right arm held in front of the soldier, at mouth level parallel to the ground. It is caught and guided into its frog with left hand, which is then returned to its side.\n*'''Change colours''': This is used when the senior flag officer decides that he/she and the other flag holding members, have held their flags for a long time, and that their arms are tired, so, when the command \"Change - colours!\" is given, the flag holders put their arms in line with the flag, their other hand on top of their first hand and move the first hand down to attention, so that the other hand is now at the first hands' original position.\n\n===Turning motions===\n\n===Turning motions at the march===\n*'''Right Turn''' (U.S.:'''Column right, MARCH'''): A 90\u00b0 turn to the right done by rotating on the right heel and left ball. The cautionary and executive are both called on the left foot. The left leg is then brought up to be parallel to the ground (although exceptions are made for kilted regiments) and slammed into the ground in the position of attention. This motion is done at a particular fixed point.\n*'''Left Turn''' (U.S.:'''Column left, MARCH'''): A 90\u00b0 turn to the left, done by rotation on the right ball and the left heel. The right leg is then brought up to be parallel to the ground and slammed down into attention. This motion is done at a particular fixed point.\n*'''About Turn''' (U.S.: '''To the rear, MARCH'''): A 180\u00b0 turn to the right, done as an exaggerated version of the right turn. United States units do not make exaggerated gestures with the legs or arms.\n*'''Right Flank MARCH''' or '''Right turn''', it is still the same even on the march for some countries: All members marching execute 90\u00b0 turn to the right done by rotating on the right heel and left ball.\n*'''Left Flank MARCH''' or '''Left turn''', it is still the same even on the march for some countries: All members marching 90\u00b0 turn to the left, done by rotation on the right ball and the left heel.\n*'''Right Incline''' (U.S.:'''Column half-right, MARCH'''), is a half turn to the right, usually used when a flight, squad, platoon, etc. is not in its proper alignment. All members marching turn by 45\u00b0 to the right, done by rotation on the left ball and the right heel.\n*'''Left Incline''' (U.S.:'''Column half-left, MARCH'''), is a half turn to the left, usually used when a flight, squad, platoon, etc. is not in its proper alignment. All members marching turn by 45\u00b0 to the left, done by rotation on the right ball and the left heel.\n*'''Right Wheel''', is a turn to the right, differentiated from a Right Turn in that the order of march remains the same. \n*'''Left Wheel''', is a mirror of the Right Wheel.\n\n====Turning motions at the halt (static)====\n\n'''[[United States Armed Forces]]:'''\n\n*'''Right Face''': The body is rotated on the heel of the right foot and then the left heel is brought forward to meet the right heel in the position of attention.\n*'''Left Face''': A mirror image of Right Face.\n*'''About Face''': The right toe is brought back to behind the left heel; the body pivots on the right toe and left heel 180\u00b0.\n*'''Half-Left Face''': Exactly the same as a left face, but one turns only 45\u00b0.\n*'''Half-Right Face''': Exactly the same as a right face, but one turns only 45\u00b0.\n\n'''[[Commonwealth of Nations]]'''\n\n*'''Right Turn''': The body is rotated 90\u00b0 to the right members shall bend the left knee, straighten it in double time and smartly place the left foot beside the right to assume the position of attention. In the Royal Navy, the heel movements mirror that of the US Armed Forces.\n*'''Left Turn''': A mirror image of Right Turn.\n*'''About Turn''': The body is rotated 180\u00b0 in a clockwise direction, knees locked. Members shall bend the left knee, straighten it in double time and smartly place the left foot beside the right to assume the position of attention. In the Royal Navy heel movements are the same for Right Face.\n*'''Right Incline''': Exactly the same as a right turn, but one turns only 45\u00b0.\n*'''Left Incline''': Exactly the same as a left turn, but one turns only 45\u00b0.\n\n===Marching motions===\n{{main|Military step}}\n*'''Quick March''': The standard pace is typically 116 beats/minute with a 30in. step.  There is also a '''Rifleman's Pace''', 140 beats/minute and a '''Highland Pace''', 110 beats/minute (typically done with a kilt.) The pace is based on the individual regiments, the pace given by the commander, and the speed of the band's rhythm. The way the march is performed depends on the regiment's nationality.\n*'''Slow March''': This is a ceremonial pace, used for funerals and when a unit's colours are marched out in front of the troops. The standard pace is 65 beats per minute.\n*'''Half Step March''' or '''Cut the pace''':\n:*This is a U.S. march pace. It is at the same tempo as Quick Time, but instead of 30 inches, the step is 15 inches.\n:*There is also a Canadian and Commonwealth version of this, used for when the front file/rank is getting too far ahead of the rest of the flight, squad, or platoon, it means that front file/rank should make their steps smaller, to allow for the rest of the flight, squad, or platoon, to get back into proper dressing.\n*'''Double March''': This is essentially a moderate jog at approximately 180 paces per minute. It creates a travel speed of approximately double that of Quick Time, designed to be used even when carrying heavy burdens. This is often erroneously used to describe a sprint or an ordinary run. The U.S. command is '''\"Double Time, MARCH.\"'''\n*'''Easy March''': This is an unrestricted march at approximately Quick Time. This is designed for field marches and other rough conditions, though is not used in combat areas. The U.S. command is '''\"Route Step, MARCH.\"''' In the Canadian Forces the command '''\"March at, EASE\"''' is given while the unit is on the march. It can not be given from the halt.\n*'''[[Military mark time|Mark Time]]''': This is essentially a [[Military mark time|stationary march]] with the knees coming up parallel to the ground or the foot dangling six inches off of the ground. This is designed to maintain the time of large parades when portions need no forward speed. The U.S. equivalent command is \"'''Mark Time, MARCH'''.\"\n*'''Step For -Ward''' or '''Forward''' or '''Forward, March''': This causes troops marking time to resume a normal march.\n\n==Modern era==\n[[File:2013. \u0414\u0435\u043d\u044c \u041f\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0434\u044b \u0432 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0435 181.jpg|thumb|Cadets parade in [[Donetsk]], [[Ukraine]].]]\n\nDrill is today used to demonstrate discipline and cohesion in a modern military force. Large military parades are today held on major holidays and military events around the world. It usually held on occasions of national importance such as a country's independence day, and therefore is presided over by the head of state who, in most cases, is the commander in chief of the combined national military forces of that country. Today, military parades include all aspects of military drill, from an [[exhibition drill]] of precision drill teams and [[military band]]s (in addition to the occasional [[corps of drums]], [[fanfare band]], and/or [[Drum and bugle corps (classic)|drum and bugle corps]]), as well as an exhibition of military weapons such as a mobile column, the occasional mounted cavalry column (led by a [[mounted band]]), a naval parade, and a fly past by the country's [[air force]]. When on parade, most of the participating soldiers wear their [[Full dress uniform|ceremonial uniforms]] and carry the standards/colours of their respective battalions/regiments/corps/academies. In many countries, the military contingent is joined by contingents from youth cadet organizations, personnel from the police and fire services and by occasion jail and border services, youth police and fire cadets, veterans and personnel of the civil service.\n\n===By country ===\n==== Albania ====\n[[Albania]] has long been influenced by Greek and Italian influences and even Soviet/Russian tradition. During the era of the [[People's Socialist Republic of Albania]], [[Liberation Day (Albania)|Liberation Day]], which then the main national holiday, was celebrated with a military parade of the [[Albanian People's Army]] on [[Tirana]]'s [[D\u00ebshmor\u00ebt e Kombit Boulevard]]. These parades have been held in 1954,<ref>{{cite book|title=The Current Digest of the Soviet Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QvMRAAAAIAAJ|volume=Vol 6|year=1954|publisher=American Association for the Advancement of Slavic Studies.}}</ref> 1959,<ref>{{cite book|author=United States Foreign Broadcast Information Service|title=Daily Report: Foreign Radio Broadcasts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wi0jAQAAMAAJ|year=1959}}</ref> 1964, 1974,<ref>{{cite book|title=Daily Report: People's Republic of China|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P5sbAQAAMAAJ|year=1974|publisher=U.S. Foreign Broadcast Information Service}}</ref> 1984<ref>{{cite book|title=Soviet Analyst|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PrVpAAAAMAAJ|volume=13-14|year=1984}}</ref> and 1989. They usually consist of veterans, [[schoolchildren]], militiamen alongside regular force personnel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazetadita.al/parada-ushtarake-forca-e-shtetit-tanke-dhe-raketa-ne-bulevard/|title=PHOTO: Here's how the military parades unfolded before 1990 |last=Veizi |first=Leonard |date=2019-01-13 |website=Gazeta Dita |language=sq|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://shekulli.com.al/7904/|title=70s-80s parades, tanks and rockets on the boulevard|last=Veizi|first=Leonard|date=2012-11-10|website=Shekulli|language=sq|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref>\n\nToday, military parades of the [[Albanian Armed Forces]] are held on [[Albanian Flag Day]] and [[Constitution of Albania|Constitution Day]] on 28 November. One of the more notable modern military parades was held on the [[100th Anniversary of the Independence of Albania]], in which a special unit of 65 soldiers from the [[Kosovo Security Force]] as well as other foreign contingents participated. The other took place on 4 December 2007 in honor of the 95th anniversary of the [[Albanian Armed Forces]].<ref>https://aaf.mil.al/index.php/arkivi/dhjetor-2007/1403-parade-ushtarake-madheshtore-me-rastin-e-95-vjetorit-te-krijimit-te-forcave-te-armatosura-shqiptare</ref>\n\n==== Argentina ====\nArgentina's long history of military parades are a heritage inherited from the times of the Spanish colonial Viceroyality of Rio de la Plata, with influences from Germany, France, Britain and Italy. Today the [[Armed Forces of the Argentine Republic]], together with the paramilitary [[Argentine National Gendarmerie]] and [[Argentine Naval Prefecture]] hosts massive military parades featuring armed companies, cadets, and military bands on the following days (national events unless otherwise noted):\n\n* January 24 - anniversary of the beginning of the Crossing of the Andes (local commemoration)\n* February 3 - anniversary of the [[Battle of San Lorenzo]] (local commemoration)\n* April 2 - [[Malvinas Day|Falklands War Veterans' Day]]\n* May 10 - anniversary of Air Force baptism of fire in the [[Falklands War]]\n* May 17 - Navy Day, anniversary of the victory at the [[Battle of Buceo]]\n* May 25 - [[First National Government|First National Government Anniversary Day]]\n* May 29 - Army Day\n* June 17 -  General Mart\u00edn Miguel de G\u00fcemes Memorial Day (local commemoration)\n* June 20 - [[Flag Day (Argentina)|Flag Day]]\n* June 30 - Naval Prefecture Day\n* July 9 - [[Argentine Independence Day|Independence Day]]\n* July 28 - National Gendarmerie Day\n* August 10 - Air Force Day\n* September 24 - Battle of Tucuman Day (local commemoration)\n* November 20 - [[National Sovereignty Day]]\n\n==== Australia and New Zealand ====\nAs both Commonwealth realms, Australia and New Zealand share the customs and traditions of parades of the British Armed Forces. The friendship and cooperation of the defence services of both countries can be seen in the annual [[Anzac Day]] parades every 25 April, in memory of the namesake [[Australian and New Zealand Army Corps]], which was heavily involved in the long [[Battle of Gallipoli]] and were the first Allied forces to land there on that day in 1915. On this day, in many major cities in these two countries, parades are held involving personnel of both the [[Australian Defence Force]] and the [[New Zealand Defence Force]], veterans' organizations, cadet organizations and other youth uniformed groups and personnel of the police and fire services, as well as students of schools and universities honoring many of their fallen alumni of the long campaign.\n\nParades are also held jointly in these two countries on 11 November, Remembrance Day.\n\nAside from these two days, the schedule of annual military and civil parades held in these two countries is as follows:\n\n* For parades in Australia:\n** National level parades are held on:\n*** 26 January, Australia Day\n*** The second  Monday of June, the Queen's Birthday, marked in most of Eastern Australia, South Australia and the Northern Territory\n**** typically the last Monday of September or the first Monday of October, Queen's Birthday Holiday for Western Australia\n**** 1st Monday in October, Queen's Birthday Holiday for Queensland\n** Local parades involving armed forces, police and fire personnel are held on:\n*** 2nd Monday in March in the ACT, Canberra Day\n*** 6 June in Queensland, Queensland Day\n*** first Monday in June in Western Australia, Western Australia Day\n*** first working day after Christmas Day, Proclamation Day in South Australia\n** Parades are also held in the following cases:\n*** during change of command, retirement and recruit and cadet [[Passing out (military)|passing out parades]] and regimental anniversaries within the service branches of the ADF and all military academies\n*** During holiday parades held in major cities as can be permitted by the commander of the unit taking part, including:\n**** the AFL Grand Final Parade in Melbourne\n* For parades in New Zealand:\n** National level parades are held on:\n*** 6 February, Waitangi Day\n*** on the 1st Monday in June, the Queen's Birthday\n** Local parades involving armed forces, police and fire personnel are held within the anniversary days of the former [[Provinces of New Zealand]], which were abolished in 1876, the days of which are as set by their respective district and city governments.\n** Change of command, retirement and recruit and cadet graduation parades, together with regimental anniversary parades, are also held occasionally within the service branches of the NZDF and its training institutions.\n\n==== Canada ====\nWithin Canada, the now tri-service [[Ceremonial Guard]] performs the marchpast for senior dignitaries of the [[Canadian Armed Forces]] during change of command ceremonies and state arrival ceremonies, typically held in [[Ottawa]], the national capital. The two [[Primary Reserve]] [[Canadian Army]] regiments that typically provide personnel for the guard, the [[Governor General's Foot Guards]] and [[The Canadian Grenadier Guards]], together with the [[Governor General's Horse Guards]] and guard of honour detachments from both the [[Royal Canadian Navy]] and the [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] take part in these events. In addition, the CG and optionally both the GGHG and the CGG take part in military parades such as the more common [[Trooping the Colour]], also in Ottawa and special parades during the jubilee years of the monarch or of national foundation. The CAF personnel, as well as the [[Canadian Cadet Organizations]] and military veterans also parade during national holidays such as [[Remembrance Day]], [[Victoria Day]], [[Canada Day]] or [[Canadian Forces Day]], as well as during parades celebrating anniversaries of regiments, brigade groups or wings, and divisional level formations and passing out parades of the [[Royal Military College of Canada]], [[Royal Military College Saint-Jean]] and recruit training bases, as well as in local holidays in the provinces and major cities. Across the country, the annual Warriors Day military parade has since 1921, been a traditional event of the [[Canadian National Exhibition]]. It is specifically devoted to formally recognizing veterans of the CF.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thewarriorsdayparade.ca/Parade%20History-Guide.html|title=The Warriors' Day Parade - History Guide}}</ref> Like in the UK, the [[Authorized marches of the Canadian Armed Forces|regimental march of the unit]] being honored is played by the band and/or [[pipe band]] if present.\n\n==== Chile ====\nThe tradition of military parades in Chile has origins not just in Spanish tradition, but also a mix between those of France, the United Kingdom, and particularly Germany, given the fact that Imperial German Army officers trained the army and navy in the mid-1890s in the Prussian-German traditions of military parades that are continued until today.\n\nCurrently, the [[Chilean Armed Forces]] and the [[Carabineros de Chile]] hold public parades in front of state leaders and the public on\n\n* 21 May - [[Navy Day (Chile)|Navy Day]] - honoring the fallen of the 1879 [[Battle of Iquique]], also marked as a day to celebrate the service personnel, veterans, heroes and martyrs of the [[Chilean Navy]]\n* 19 September - [[Great Military Parade of Chile|Army Day]] - while honoring the 1810 anniversary of the formal inauguration of the First Government Junta, is also marked as a day to celebrate the service personnel, veterans, heroes and martyrs of the [[Chilean Army]]\n\nLocal level parades are marked on the following days aside from 21 May:\n\n* 17 February  - anniversary of the victory in the [[Battle of Chacabuco]]\n* 21 March - Air Force Day\n* 2 April - anniversary of the victory in the [[Battle of Maipu]]\n* 27 April - Carabineros Day\n* 7 June - anniversary of the victory in the [[Battle of Arica]]\n* 9 July  - Flag Day\n* 20 August - birthday of [[Bernardo O'Higgins]]\n* 18 September - Independence Day\n* 2 October - anniversary of the [[Battle of Rancagua]]\n* 30 November - [[Chilean Gendarmerie]] Day\n\n==== China ====\nThe first military parade on the Chinese mainland can be dated to over 4,000 years ago, when [[Yu the Great]], a legendary ruler in [[History of China#Ancient China|ancient China]], hosted a gathering of tribal forces from northern and southern China.<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=llmCOvtWcUcC&pg=PA76&dq=chinese+military+parade+1984&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4wKiB1IXlAhUQIKwKHfsJBp8Q6AEISTAF#v=onepage&q=chinese%20military%20parade%201984&f=false</ref>\n\n===== People's Republic of China =====\n{{See also|Military parades in Hong Kong}}\n{{external media|align=right|width=250px|video1=Parts [https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=xtmnAg_e9Dk 1] [https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=Cy_Kyq5iCzE 2] [https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=Cy_Kyq5iCzE 3] and [https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=4WJNtiHiZJQ 4] of a documentary on the history of Chinese military parades|align2=right|width2=250px|video2=[https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=_2ZfByEEYmg 1981 \u65b0\u7586 \u5927\u9605\u5175 Chinese Uighur Military Parade in Xinjiang (Eng narration)]}}\nThe People's Republic of China holds extraordinary military parades in Beijing to celebrate [[National Day of the People's Republic of China|National Day]]. The first parade of this nature took place right after the [[Proclamation of the People's Republic of China]] by Chairman [[Mao Zedong]] on 1 October 1949. Originally celebrated annually, the parade was suspended in 1960, before returning in 1984 to mark the 35th anniversary of the founding of the [[China|People's Republic of China]]. It is now held to mark every tenth anniversary, starting in 1999. Parades were also held in 1964, 1966, 1969 and 1970.<ref>https://www.frstrategie.org/en/publications/strategic-imagery/military-parade-70th-anniversary-prc-revealing-example-chinese-strategic-power-2019</ref>\n\nIn 2015, China held a [[2015 China Victory Day Parade|military parade]] to celebrate the 70th anniversary of the [[Victory over Japan Day|Victory over Japan]]. This was the first time China held a military parade for an event other than its National Day. It is currently unknown if China will continue to celebrate the end of World War II, through.\n\nIn 2017, the 90th anniversary since the [[Nanchang Uprising]] and the beginning of the [[People's Liberation Army]] was marked by a [[2017 PLA Day Parade|military parade]], the first time ever that a military parade had been held in its honor and the first time it was held outside of the capital, having been held at [[Zhurihe Training Base]] in [[Inner Mongolia]] under the direction of General [[Han Weiguo]] of the [[Central Theater Command]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-defence/chinas-xi-calls-for-building-elite-forces-during-massive-military-parade-idUSKBN1AF00J|title=China's Xi calls for building elite forces during massive military parade|first=Michael|last=Martina|first2=Ben|last2=Blanchard|work=[[Reuters]]|date=July 29, 2017|editor-first=Kim|editor-last=Coghill|editor-first2=Sam|editor-last2=Holmes}}</ref><ref>https://www.chinadailyhk.com/articles/50/38/44/1501474883058.html</ref> This was also the first field parade to take place since September 1981 when a parade consisting of troops participating in an excersise in [[Zhangjiakou]] in the presence of [[Deng Xiaoping]] to commemorate Deng's assumption to the post of [[Chairman of the Central Military Commission]]. During that parade, Deng reportedly said \"Let\u2019s hold a large-scale one if we are to hold a military exercise, so that it can be of use\" in reference to the size of the parade.<ref>https://amp.scmp.com/news/china/diplomacy-defence/article/2079193/massive-parade-tipped-plas-90th-birthday</ref> Naval parades have also been reintroduced in recent years with a [[2018 South China Sea Parade|parade]] (which was the biggest naval review since 1949 and according to the Chinese government, the biggest in 600 years.<ref>https://nationalinterest.org/blog/the-buzz/superpower-china-claims-biggest-naval-parade-600-years-25403</ref>) being held in the [[South China Sea]] in 2018 and a [[PLA Navy Platinum Jubilee Parade|parade]] for the [[platinum jubilee]] of the [[People's Liberation Army Navy]] being held in early 2019.\n\nSmaller scale parades are also periodically held in [[Hong Kong]], [[Macau]], [[Tibet]] and [[Xinjiang]]. Every year on 10 March ([[Tibetan Uprising Day]]), a military parade in [[Lhasa]] to mark the anniversary of the [[1959 Tibetan uprising|1959 Tibetan rebellion]].<ref>https://www.hrw.org/news/2019/03/20/china-marks-tibetan-anniversary-military-parade</ref> The first military parades in the HKSAR and the MSAR took place on their first and fifth anniversaries in 1998<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjnews.com.cn/news/2017/06/30/448719.html|title=\u4e60\u8fd1\u5e73\u68c0\u9605\u9a7b\u6e2f\u90e8\u961f\uff0c\u53d7\u9605\u5b98\u5175\u4e3a\u4f55\u558a\"\u4e3b\u5e2d\u597d\"?&#124;\u653f\u89e3 - \u56fd\u5185 - \u65b0\u4eac\u62a5\u7f51|website=www.bjnews.com.cn}}</ref> and 2004 respectively.\n\n===== Republic of China =====\nHowever, in the [[Taiwan|Republic of China (Taiwan)]], the [[Republic of China Armed Forces]] held its national parades in [[Taipei]] from 1949 until 1991 during the [[National Day of the Republic of China|Double Ten Day]] celebrations. This practice was abandoned in 1991 though parades were recently held every five years beginning in 2011 during the [[100th Anniversary of the Republic of China|Xinhai Revolution centenary]] and again in 2016. Special parades were held outside Taipei in 1995 and 2015 marking the 50th and 70th anniversaries, respectively, of both the Allied victory in the Second World War and the conclusion of the Second Sino-Japanese War.\n\n==== Colombia ====\nBoth the [[Military Forces of Colombia]] and the [[National Police of Colombia]] hold important national parades to celebrate the anniversary of national independence as well as of the Armed Forces. Such parades are a mix of the Spanish, German, French, American and British influences owing to the long history of the country's military and police forces. National level parades are held on:\n\n* February 15 - Air Force Day \n* July 20 - [[Colombian Independence Day parade|Independence Day]]\n* July 24 - Navy Day \n* August 7 - Army Day and [[Battle of Boyac\u00e1|Battle of Boyaca Victory Day]]\n* November 15 - National Police Day\n\nLocal level parades by the personnel and veterans of the armed forces and police are held on the following:\n\n* April 7 - Barranquilla Day\n* July 3 - Cali Independence Day\n* November 11 - Cartagena Independence Day\n\n==== Cuba ====\nThe [[Cuban Revolutionary Armed Forces]] generally holds military parades in honor of the [[Day of the Cuban Armed Forces]] and the [[Triumph of the Revolution]] on [[Havana]]'s [[Plaza de la Revoluci\u00f3n]]. The first parade took place in 1960 for the latter event and over time, importance was transferred to Armed Forces Day in relation to military parades. In 2011, a special honor parade was held on April 16 to commemorate the [[golden jubilee]] since the 1961 [[Bay of Pigs Invasion]].<ref>https://www.pri.org/stories/2011-04-16/cuba-marks-victory-socialism</ref> The largest parade to be held took place in December 1986 in honor of the 30th anniversary of the revolution, in which General [[Humberto Ortega]] from [[Nicaragua]] as well as officials from the [[Soviet Union]] attended.<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=7z1mvx29XMgC&pg=PA589&dq=military+parade+in+cuba+1986&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj8so7g9oHmAhUP2qwKHZwTBuUQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=military%20parade%20in%20cuba%201986&f=false</ref> The [[diamond jubilee]] parade planned for 2016 was postponed for 1 month due to the [[death and state funeral of Fidel Castro]], and took place during the Victory Day celebrations on 2 January 2017.<ref>http://www.cubagob.cu/otras_info/minfar/granma.htm</ref><ref>http://www.prensa-latina.cu/index.php?o=rn&id=135863&SEO=conmemoran-en-angola-dia-de-las-fuerzas-armadas-de-cuba</ref>\n\n==== Czech Republic ====\n[[File:Vojenska prehlidka 1985b.jpg|thumb|A parade of tanks of the \u010cSLA in Prague on [[Victory Day (9 May)|Victory Day]], 9 May 1985.]]\n{{external media|align=right|width=250px|video1=[https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=EApCYZR-NMk Czechoslovak Military Parade \"Shield-84\" - Vojensk\u00e1 p\u0159ehl\u00eddka \u010cSLA \"\u0160t\u00edt-84]}}\nLarge mlitary parades in the [[Czech Republic]] are today held every 10 years in the capital of [[Prague]], encompassing personnel from the [[Czech Army]] and the [[Police of the Czech Republic]]. The first of these parades occurred in 2008 in honor of the founding of [[Czechoslovakia]] on 28 October 1918.<ref>{{cite web | title=Hundreds of Soldiers Marched Through Prague, for the First Time Since 1985 | website=Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b | date=2008-10-28 | url=https://zpravy.aktualne.cz/domaci/prahou-pochodovaly-stovky-vojaku-poprve-od-roku-1985/r~i:article:620540/ | language=cs | access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> Another one took place in [[2018 Prague Military Parade|2018]] and included foreign troops.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.czdjournal.com/news/100th-anniversary-of-czechoslovakia-parade-2018-28th-october-118.html|title=100th Anniversary of Czechoslovakia \u2013 Parade 2018 (28th October) | website=Czech Defence Journal}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 1918, military parades followed the tradition of their larger sovereign entity, including the military tradition of [[Austria-Hungary]]. Regular military parades were held during the period of the [[Czechoslovak Socialist Republic]], with the first parades being organized in the 1950s. The first parade of the [[Czechoslovak People's Army]] (\u010cSLA) took place in 1951 in [[Letn\u00e1]]. Since then, parades were held every five years on 9 May to mark the end of [[World War II]] and the [[Prague uprising|Liberation of Czechoslovakia]]. To honor the latter's celebrations, the [[State Anthem of the Soviet Union]] would be performed by the massed bands on parade preceded by the [[Kde domov m\u016fj|Czechoslovakian national anthem]]. The last of these parades took place in 1985.<ref>{{cite web | title=Prague Experienced a Military Parade After 23 Years | website=Lidovky.cz | date=2008-10-28 | url=https://www.lidovky.cz/domov/praha-zazila-vojenskou-prehlidku-po-23-letech.A081028_130928_ln_praha_mtr | language=cs | access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.novinky.cz/domaci/clanek/prahou-ma-buracet-velkolepa-vojenska-prehlidka-40008504|title=A Spectacular Military Parade Should Roar Through Prague|last=Adami\u010dkov\u00e1|first=Na\u010fa|last2=K\u00f6nigov\u00e1|first2=Marie|date=2016-09-21|website=Novinky.cz|language=cs|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref>\n\n==== Ecuador ====\nBoth the [[Armed Forces of Ecuador]] and the [[National Police of Ecuador]] hold important national parades to celebrate the anniversaries of national independence as well as of the Armed Forces and Police. National level parades are held on the following days:\n\n* February 27 - Army Day\n* May 24 - Armed Forces Day, anniversary of the victory in the 1822 [[Battle of Pichincha]]\n* July 26 - Navy Day\n* August 10 - anniversary of the Luz de America\n* October 9 - Guayaquil Independence Day\n* October 27 - Air Force Day\n* November 3 - Cueca Independence Day\n* November 18 - Loja Independence Day\n\nLocal military and police parades are held on major city and provincial anniversaries.\n\n==== France ====\nThe annual [[Bastille Day military parade|military parade]] in the French capital of [[Paris]] is held on July 14 during the [[Bastille Day]] holiday. It is currently the oldest and largest military parade on the European continent. It is held on the Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es and passes from l'[[Arc de Triomphe]] to [[Place de la Concorde]]. Bastille Day parades are also held in smaller garrison towns such as [[Toulon]] and [[Belfort]]. The 1st Infantry Regiment of the [[French Republican Guard]] regularly performs ceremonial marchpasts in is role as the [[guard of honour]] for the [[President of the French Republic]]. Like the British, many French units have the ability to march in quick time, while only one - the [[French Foreign Legion]] - marches uniquely in slow time, while another unit of the armed forces marches in very quick time and that is of the Army's [[Chasseurs]], especially its [[Chasseurs alpins]].\n\nLocal parades are held on the following days:\n\n* May 8 - [[Victory in Europe Day]]\n* November 11 - Armistice Day\n* Anniversaries of important battles fought by the French Armed Forces\n\n==== Germany ====\nThe [[Germany]] has had a long tradition of military parades dating back to the days of [[Kingdom of Prussia]] and its army and navy. It was the Prussians who invented the [[goose step]], a style of marching that was used in many German armies as well as in the militaries of various countries, which were instructed by Prussian military training officers and instructors from the 19th century to the early 20th.\n\nDuring the [[Nazi era]], military parades were commonplace as they were held as a sort of victory parade for the German [[Wehrmacht]] as they invaded countries during the Second World War. The first major parades took place in [[Nuremberg]] in September 1938 and [[Adolf Hitler's 50th birthday]] in April 1939. In the months Immediately after the [[German invasion of Poland]], a [[German\u2013Soviet military parade in Brest-Litovsk|joint German\u2013Soviet military parade]] took place in [[Brest-Litovsk]] (now [[Brest, Belarus]]). In [[Allied-occupied Germany]], the major powers held parades through the center of Berlin to honor their victory. These include the [[Berlin Victory Parade of 1945]], [[1945 British Berlin Victory Parade]] and [[Berlin Victory Parade of 1946]].\n\nIn the communist [[German Democratic Republic]] (GDR), parades were held according to the Russian standard, although the [[Soviet Army]] allowed the East Germans to use the Prussian tradition, something that had been dropped by their West German counterparts in the 50s. In the GDR, parades were held on the following occasions:\n\n*NVA Day (3 March)\n*[[International Workers' Day]] (1 May)\n*[[Liberation Day|Tag der Befreiung]] (8 May)\n*[[Republic Day (East Germany)|Tag der Republik]] (7 October)\n\nThe first parade took place on 1 May 1956 in the presence of [[President of East Germany|President]] [[Wilhelm Pieck]].<ref>https://www.mdr.de/zeitreise/erster-mai-ddr-politparade-volksfest100.html</ref> In the 60s and early 70s, parades took place on the western half of the [[Palace of the Republic, Berlin|Palace of the Republic]], which was intended as a military parade ground, even though tremors from the heavy vehicles proved dangerous due to the glass facade. By 1979, the western half was used mainly as a parking lot and military parades were moved to [[Karl-Marx-Allee]] in central Berlin.\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F029232-0004, N\u00fcrburgring, Bundeswehrparade zum NATO-Jubil\u00e4um.jpg|thumb|[[Bundeswehr]] personnel on the [[N\u00fcrburgring]].]]\nIn 1969, the first military parade of [[West Germany]] and later the entire [[Federal Republic of Germany]] was held on the [[N\u00fcrburgring]] in the town of [[N\u00fcrburg]], [[Rhineland-Palatinate]].<ref>http://www.hawkies.de/chronik-39.html</ref> It took place on 6 June 1969 and was held to commemorate the 20th anniversary of the establishment of the [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization]] (NATO).<ref>https://www.deutsche-digitale-bibliothek.de/item/GJQUEWUHL6MHFEI7OOLMIOGW4VZT7UTU</ref> It was attended by [[Kurt Georg Kiesinger]] in his position as [[Federal Chancellor of Germany]]. Participating foreign and national units included those from the [[Bundeswehr]], [[Canadian Forces Europe]], [[United States Army Europe]], as well as army contingents from [[France]] and the [[United Kingdom]]. Allied parades were also held later in the country's 40-year existence.\n\nToday, military parades are held on the following holidays on a smaller scale:\n\n* Remembrance Day of [[July 20 plot|July 20]]\n* [[German Unity Day]] (October 3)\n* Passing out parades of NCO training schools and officer training institutions\n\n==== Greece ====\nThe long history of the [[Hellenic Armed Forces]] and the role played in the defense and progress of the country are recalled in splendid and grand military parades that are held in major cities in the country following a hybrid of the British, French, Danish and German traditions on the following dates:\n\n* 25 March - [[Greek Independence Day|Independence Day]]\n* 28 October - Ohi Day\n* On Liberation Days of major cities and towns, honoring the Greek fallen of the Second World War and the later Greek Civil War\n\n==== India ====\nThe [[Delhi Republic Day parade|Republic Day Parade]] is held annually in [[Delhi]] to mark the Republic Day of [[India]]. Parades are also held on the service holidays: [[Army Day (India)|Army Day]], Navy Day and Air Force Day.\n\n==== Mongolia ====\nMilitary parades in [[Mongolia]] have a long tradition that dates back to the era of the [[Mongol Empire]]. Today they closely follow the Russian model with sone modifications such as trooping of the [[Flag of Mongolia]] in a car rather than by foot. A Dangjiren is based off a cavalry military parade of the Mongols that were held in the 17th century.<ref>http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-08/10/c_137381600.htm</ref>\n\nThe first official military parade in Communist Mongolia took place in 1921 in honor of the victories of [[Damdin S\u00fckhbaatar]] in the People's Revolution. The anniversary parades that followed have been held on jubilee years (specifically in 1946, 1951, 1956, 1961, 1966, 1971, 1976, 1981, 1986 and 1991).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tolgoilogch.mn/_c863obv6vd/mt|title=Rare Images of the People's Revolution |website=tolgoilogch.mn |language=mn |access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> After 1991, the practice was abandoned with the exception of 1996 when a parade in the [[National Sports Stadium (Mongolia)|National Sports Stadium]] commemorated the 790th anniversary of the founding of Mongolia and the 75th anniversary of the People's Revolution. After a 9-year break, the 2005 inauguration ceremony of [[Nambaryn Enkhbayar]] served as an event to hold a military parade on the central square. This took place again in 2009 for the inauguration of [[Tsakhiagiin Elbegdorj]]. That same year, State Flag Day was introduced as a national holiday, which would also be celebrated with a parade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.zindaa.mn/rbs|title=The History of the Military Ceremony|last=\u0411\u0430\u044f\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0430|first=A|date=1908-10-04|website=Zindaa.mn|language=mn|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref>\n\nMilitary parades of the [[Mongolian Armed Forces]] on [[S\u00fckhbaatar Square]] take place on the following occasions:<ref>{{cite book|last=Rossabi|first=Morris|title=From Yuan to Modern China and Mongolia: The Writings of Morris Rossabi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GXejBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA503|year=2014|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-28529-3|page=503|oclc=915581801}}</ref>\n\n*18 March &ndash; [[Men's and Soldiers' Day|Soldiers Day]]\n*10 July &ndash; [[Mongolian State Flag Day]]\n*1 September &ndash; Anniversary of the [[Battle of Khalkin Gol]]\n*Inauguration of the [[President of Mongolia]]\n*Graduations of the [[National Defense University (Mongolia)|National Defense University]]\n\n{{external media|align=right|width=250px|video1=[https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=cFv0vF-gzxA The 70th anniversary parade of the People's Revolution of 1921]|align2=right|width2=250px|video2=[https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=S_mrMgbwwyQ Mongolian Military Parade 2011]}}\n\nDuring Mongolia's [[Mongolian People's Republic|socialist period]], annual civil/military parades of the [[Mongolian People's Army]] took place until 1991,<ref>{{cite book|last=Sanders|first=Alan J K|title=Historical Dictionary of Mongolia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5JN83EDDLl4C&pg=PR62|edition=3rd|year=2010|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-7452-7|page=62| oclc=939933261}}</ref> celebrating the following occasions:\n\n*1 May &ndash; [[International Workers Day]]\n*11 July &ndash; [[Mongolian Revolution of 1921|Day of the People's Revolution of 1921]]\n*7 November &ndash; [[October Revolution Day]]\n\nDuring these events, party and government leaders were viewed ascending to the top of [[S\u00fckhbaatar's Mausoleum]] to take the salute.\n\n==== North Korea ====\n{{Main|Military parades in North Korea}}\nAll military parades of the [[Korean People's Army]] (KPA) and the [[Worker-Peasant Red Guards]] (WPRG) are centered in the national capital of [[Pyongyang]] and have a long tradition that goes back to the DPRK's establishment in 1948. Between 1993 and 2011, the DPRK held over a dozen military parades, which was frequent compared to the 1960s\u201380s, during which only three parades were held.<ref>https://www.latimes.com/world/la-fg-north-korea-military-parades-20180908-story.html?_amp=true</ref> Known for its elaborate military drill, the country holds military parades annually on different dates (especially on jubilee years<ref>https://www.youngpioneertours.com/north-korean-military-parades/</ref>), which feature a combination of Chinese and Russian techniques.<ref>https://www.cbsnews.com/news/north-korea-military-parades-through-pyongyang/</ref> North Korean military parades are held on the following dates:\n\n*8 February &ndash; [[Military Foundation Day]] \n*15 April &ndash; [[Day of the Sun]] \n*25 April &ndash; Revolutionary Army Day\n*27 July &ndash; [[Day of Victory in the Great Fatherland Liberation War]]\n*15 August &ndash; [[Liberation Day (North Korea)|Liberation Day]]\n*9 September &ndash; [[Day of the Foundation of the Republic (North Korea)|Day of the Foundation of the Republic]]\n*10 October &ndash; [[Party Foundation Day]]\n\n[[File:Parade - North Korea.webm|thumb|Drill rehearsals for female soldiers participating in the 2011 Republic Day Parade.]]\nRehearsals for these parades usually take place 3\u20136 weeks prior to the actual parade at the [[Mirim Airport|Mirim Parade Training Facility]] in the capital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beyondparallel.csis.org/is-north-korea-preparing-for-a-military-parade/|title=Is North Korea Preparing for a Military Parade?|date=April 10, 2019|website=Beyond Parallel}}</ref><ref>https://www.foxnews.com/world/past-goose-steppers-proud-of-place-in-north-korean-parades</ref> The actual parades are held in the capital's [[Kim Il-sung Square]].\n\nIn addition, non-jubilee holiday parades have been mounted on the grounds of the [[Kumsusan Palace of the Sun]] on these days plus on:\n\n*16 February &ndash; [[Day of the Shining Star]]\n*25 August &ndash; [[Day of Songun|Day of ''Songun'']]\n*21 December &ndash; Death Anniversary of [[Kim Jong-il]]\n\n==== Peru ====\nThe [[Peruvian Armed Forces]] and the [[National Police of Peru]] holds the yearly [[Great Military Parade of Peru]] every July 29 in Lima as the armed services' way of honoring the anniversary of national independence and the role they have played in shaping the history of the country. Local level Independence Day parades are held on pre-determined days before July 28 and 29 as set by their respective local governments.\n\nParades held by service personnel and veterans of the armed forces are also marked on:\n\n* June 7 - Flag Day and Battle of Arica Memorial Day \n* June 26 - Air Force Day\n* September 24 - Armed Forces Day \n* October 8 - Navy Day\n* December 9  - Army Day and anniversary of the [[Battle of Ayacucho]]\n\n==== Poland ====\n[[File:August 15, 2018. Celebration of the Polish Army Day. Air force of Poland.jpg|thumb|A [[Polish Air Force]] ceremonial guard during the Armed Forces Day parade.]]\nThe [[Polish Armed Forces]] and the [[Police of Poland]] holds two yearly military parades ({{lang-pl|Defilada wojskowa}}) in the capital of [[Warsaw]]: The [[Armed Forces Day (Poland)|Armed Forces Day]] parade through [[Ujazd\u00f3w Avenue]] and the [[National Independence Day (Poland)|National Independence Day]] parade near the [[Tomb of the Unknown Soldier, Warsaw|Tomb of the Unknown Soldier]] on [[Pi\u0142sudski Square]]. Both of these parades include [[NATO]] personnel stationed near or inside the country. The Armed Forces Day Parade was introduced in 2007 and 2008 as first grand military parades since the holiday was reinstated and have been held yearly since 2013. The first Polish military parade took place on 17 January 1945. Prior to 1989, parades were held in front of the [[Palace of Culture and Science]] on [[Parade Square]] on 22 July commemorate the [[National Day of the Rebirth of Poland]] celebrations, honoring the anniversary of the signing of the [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]]-sponsored [[PKWN Manifesto]]. Back then, the [[People's Republic of Poland]] used many Russian traditions in regards to military parades, especially the inspection by the Minister of Defence. In 1966, during the millennium celebrations of the [[Christianization of Poland]], a parade was held on 22 July which included cadets of military academies and personnel of Polish ceremonial units dressed in historical military uniforms dating back to the [[Piast dynasty]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Polish Chronicle | website=KronikaRP | url=http://www.kronikarp.pl/pop-up.php?id=58989&type=2 | language=pl | access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://phistory.info/photo-history/679-rycari-v-kinorekvizite-uchastvuyut-v-parade-v-chest-1000-letiya-polskogo-gosudarstva.html|title=Knights (in Film Props) Participate in a Parade in Honor of the 1000th Anniversary of the Polish State|date=2019-07-14|website=phistory.info|language=ru|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> A [[1985 Warsaw Victory Day Parade|special parade]] was held on 9 May 1985 to honor the 40th anniversary of the Victory in Europe and the servicemen of the Polish Armed Forces in the West and the East. In 2019, a 3rd was added when the yearly [[3 May Constitution Day]] parades, last held in 1939 and were held off and on since 1990, were officially reinstated.\n\n==== Russia and ex-Soviet countries ====\n[[File:Naval Academy 1983.jpg|thumb|The [[N. G. Kuznetsov Naval Academy]], led by Captain Anatoliy Karpenko, during a parade on [[Leningrad]]'s [[Palace Square]] in 1983.]]\nThe Western tradition of military parades in the [[Russian Empire]] was part of the many reforms made by [[Peter the Great]] as part of his many efforts to transform the army and the navy from traditional militias to a full-blown professional armed service that is a model for the people in discipline and obedience, courage, bravery, loyalty to the country and in bringing pride and glory to her people. During the Imperial period, national parades were alternated between [[Moscow]] and [[Saint Petersburg]] on major national civil and military holidays, anniversaries of the Romanov Dynasty and as part of the imperial coronation celebrations, celebrations and parades were also held in many major cities and provincial capitals.\n\nSo important was the value of these parades that even the [[Soviet Armed Forces]] made these parades a common tradition beginning in August 1918 when the first modern parade was held in Moscow's [[Red Square]] when Moscow area [[Vsevobuch]] detachments march past, earlier that May, a [[1918 May 1 Parade|military parade]], the first by the nascent [[Red Army]], was held outside the capital. Since that year, many innovations have been seen in the practice of annual parades held not just there but in the capital cities of the former [[Soviet Union]], as well as in major cities in the wide country, which were held on 1 May (1918-1941 and 1945-1968), [[October Revolution Day|7 November]] (1920-1941 and 1945-1990) and [[Victory Day Parades|9 May]] (1945, 1965, 1985 and 1990). Today, the [[Russian Armed Forces]] - and by extension countries of the former Soviet Union - host a variety of military parades held on important national holidays, honoring the men and women of their armed forces and military veterans. The celebrations in each of these countries carry on years of tradition, honor, discipline and prestige by the millions of men and women who serve and have served in the ranks of the armed forces of their respective home countries. These parades have extensive government funding and aside from the iconic wide march past columns and occasional historical formations, typically include a mobile column, and occasionally a naval fleet review and/or air force fly past segment, a legacy of the Soviet era.\n\n[[File:4Samarin.jpg|thumb|A Russian Armed Forces Honour Parade on [[Red Square]] in November 2018.]]\n\n===== Armenia =====\nWhile the country was a Soviet Republic from 1920 to 1991, Armenia was formerly independent from 1918 to 1920 and thus had armed forces composed of both veterans of the Imperial Army and guerillas fighting the Ottoman armed forces who had been enforcing the anti-Armenian massacres of 1914. Armenians fought bravery in the Eastern Front of the Second World War as part of the Soviet Armed Forces, retaining some of its traditions today. The last of the Soviet era parades took place in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1tv.am/hy/news/2015/07/10/%D4%B1%D6%80%D5%B1%D5%A1%D5%B6/19710|title=Talking Monuments. Statue of Lenin.|date=2015-10-07|website=1tv.am|language=hy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808084317/http://www.1tv.am/hy/news/2015/07/10/%D4%B1%D6%80%D5%B1%D5%A1%D5%B6/19710|archive-date=2016-08-08|url-status=dead|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> Today, the [[Armed Forces of Armenia]] hosts massive parades held in [[Yerevan]], the capital city, on the following days:\n\n* May 28 - [[Republic Day (Armenia)|Republic Day]]\n* September 21 - [[Independence Day (Armenia)|Independence Day]]\n\nIn recent years, national military parades have included drill units and military bands performing [[exhibition drill]] for the guests before the parade concludes.\n\n===== Azerbaijan =====\n{{Main|Military parades in Azerbaijan}}\nThe semi-annual parade on the [[Day of the Armed Forces of Azerbaijan]], 26 June, is one of the biggest in the Commonwealth of Independent States, held every 3 to 5 years at the [[Azadliq Square, Baku]], honoring the many Azerbaijanis who served faithful under the colours as part of her armed forces. The forces on parade are assembled based on a mix of the Turkish and Russian parade formation.\n\n===== Belarus =====\nThe [[Armed Forces of Belarus]] holds an annual military parade on 3 July along the [[Victors Avenue]] in the national capital [[Minsk]], marking the anniversary of the liberation of the country during the 1944 [[Minsk Offensive]], which coincides with the country's [[Independence Day (Belarus)|Independence Day]]. On special years of the victory in Europe, commemorative extraordinary parades are held there on 9 May to honor the millions of Belarusian military dead of the [[Second World War]]. Military parades in the country are based on the Russian/Polish model and tradition. Formerly, parades in the [[Republic of Belarus]] and the [[Belarusian Soviet Socialist Republic]] took place on [[Independence Square, Minsk|Independence Square]] (known in the Soviet era as Lenin Square). This changed in the early 2000s when the square was renovated and became incompatible with the parade format. Military parades in the BSSR also took place on [[October Square, Minsk|October Square]] from 1946 to 1984. Since 2004, military parades in the capital have taken place on [[Victors Avenue]]. In connection with the centennial of the Belarusian Armed Forces in 2018, a military parade was held in the Western city of [[Grodno]].\n\n===== Estonia =====\nWhile being formerly independent from 1918 to 1940 and as a component republic of the Soviet Union from that year to 1941 and yet again from 1944 to 1991, the current [[Estonian Defence Forces]] and the [[Estonian Defence League]], successor to both the military and reserve forces of the First Republic and republican formations under the Baltic Military District and Baltic Fleet of the Soviet Armed Forces, marches during a combination of Russian, Finnish and Western drill in parades held in the following days:\n\n* February 24 - [[Independence Day (Estonia)|Independence Day]]\n* June 24 - [[V\u00f5idup\u00fcha|Victory Day]]\n\nDuring the 2006 Victory Day Parade in [[Saaremaa]], the first ever Fleet Review of the [[Estonian Navy]] in Estonian history was conducted by the [[Estonian Defence League]].\n\n===== Georgia ===== \nThe [[Defense Forces of Georgia]], successor to the armed services of the Democratic Republic and Soviet formations stationed in the Georgian SSR, hosts military parades on May 26, [[Independence Day (Georgia)|Independence Day]], the anniversary of the formation of the republic in 1918, together with elements from:\n\n* [[National Police of Georgia]]\n* [[Border Police of Georgia]]\n* [[Georgian Coast Guard]]\n\nModern parades are a mix of the former Soviet and modern Western (British, US, Turkish and Israeli) traditions and drill owing to the modernization of the defense and public security forces to NATO and EU standards.\n\n===== Kazakhstan =====\nThe [[Armed Forces of Kazakhstan]] holds military parades ({{Lang-kk|\u04d8\u0441\u043a\u0435\u0440\u0438 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434}}) that resemble the parades of the Russian military in [[Moscow]], with one of the only exceptions being the inspection of the troops by the [[President of Kazakhstan|Supreme Commander of the Kazakh Armed Forces]], instead of the defense minister. It has never held yearly parades celebrating one occasion, with parades currently being held in honor of the [[Defender of the Fatherland Day (Kazakhstan)|Defender of the Fatherland Day]] holiday. In the past, large scale military parades in the former capital of [[Almaty]] and the current capital of [[Nur-Sultan]] were held on the following holidays:\n\n*[[Kazakhstan Independence Day]] (1996)\n*[[Victory Day (9 May)]] (1995, 2015)\n*[[Constitution Day (Kazakhstan)]] (2009, 2010, 2011)\n\nIn recent years, the Defender of the Fatherland Day parade was expanded to function as a so-called \"Battle Parade\" (\u0411\u043e\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434). So far, only two of these kinds of parades have been held; in 2013 and 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://informburo.kz/stati/kak-proshyol-boevoy-parad-2018-fotoreportazh.html|title=How was the Battle Parade 2018. Photoreport|last=Bedenko|first=Grigory|date=2018-05-07|website=Informburo.kz|language=ru|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> In contrast to usual military parades, the battle parade includes tactical exercises and military demonstrations. These parades usually are held at the 40th [[Otar Military Base]] in the [[Korday District]] and take place with the troops in full combat gear rather than a ceremonial [[full dress uniform]]. Like former Soviet republics, Kazakh military parades are led by a cadet [[Corps of drums|drum corps]], specifically from the [[Astana Zhas Ulan Republican School]].\n\n===== Kyrgyzstan =====\nKyrgyz military parades are based on Russian traditions, having been held on many different occasions in the history of the [[Armed Forces of Kyrgyzstan]]. Currently, the only consistent military parade is held on [[Ala-Too Square]] in [[Bishkek]] every 5 years in honor of the country's [[Independence Day (Kyrgyzstan)|Independence Day]]. Other military parades have been held celebrating different occasions. On 24 March 2006, a parade was held on the same square celebrating the 1 year anniversary since the [[Tulip Revolution]] which overthrew President [[Askar Akayev]].<ref>https://amp.dw.com/ru/%D0%BF%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B2%D0%B0%D1%8F-%D0%B3%D0%BE%D0%B4%D0%BE%D0%B2%D1%89%D0%B8%D0%BD%D0%B0-%D1%82%D1%8E%D0%BB%D1%8C%D0%BF%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%BE%D0%B9-%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%B2%D0%BE%D0%BB%D1%8E%D1%86%D0%B8%D0%B8-%D0%B2-%D0%BA%D0%B8%D1%80%D0%B3%D0%B8%D0%B7%D0%B8%D0%B8/a-1943616</ref><ref>https://www.golos-ameriki.ru/amp/a-33-2006-04-03-voa5/638201.html</ref><ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=6fcVAQAAMAAJ&q=%D0%90%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B4%D0%B8%D0%BA+%D0%BF%D0%B0%D1%80%D0%B0%D0%B4,+%D0%91%D0%B8%D1%88%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%BA&dq=%D0%90%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B4%D0%B8%D0%BA+%D0%BF%D0%B0%D1%80%D0%B0%D0%B4,+%D0%91%D0%B8%D1%88%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%BA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjvy77r8-LkAhUFX60KHSznAUUQ6AEILTAB</ref> In May of that same year, a [[Day of the Armed Forces (Kyrgyzstan)|Day of the Armed Forces]] parade on the same square, later being deemed as \"irresponsible\" by opposition lawmaker [[Omurbek Tekebaev]] due to the fact that it coincided with opposition protests against President [[Kurmanbek Bakiyev]], which itself was described by Defence Minister [[Ismail Isakov]] as purely \"coincidental\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/1068556.html|title=Kyrgyz Opposition, Military Vie For Venue|website=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty|access-date=2019-09-21}}</ref> In 2015, a Victory Day Parade was held in the Kyrgyz capital, being presided by Prime Minister [[Temir Sariyev]] and [[General Staff of Armed Forces of the Kyrgyz Republic|Chief of General Staff]] [[Asanbek Alymkozhoev]] in place of President [[Almazbek Atambayev]], who was attending the [[2015 Moscow Victory Day Parade]] that same day.<ref>https://regnum.ru/news/polit/1922892.html</ref> The parade saw the appearance of veterans of the war in the mobile column as well as Russian troops from the local [[Kant Air Base]] taking part in the parade.\n\n===== Latvia =====\nLatvia, like its neighbors to the north and south, was also formerly independent from 1918 to 1940 and as a component republic of the Soviet Union from that year to 1941 and yet again from 1944 to 1991, and its armed forces, then as in the 90s, were formed up of Latvian born personnel who served in the Russian military and thus share some of the Russian drill and parade ceremonial in combination with Western practices. Today, the [[Latvian National Armed Forces]] hosts massive parades (with occasional participation by service personnel of NATO armed forces) on the following dates:\n\n* May 4, [[Day of the Restoration of Latvian Independence|Restoration of Independence Day]]\n* November 11, [[L\u0101\u010dpl\u0113sis Day]]\n* November 18, [[Proclamation Day of the Republic of Latvia]]\n\n===== Russia =====\nIn Russia, military parades are held in many parts of the country on the following days:\n\n* [[Defender of the Fatherland Day]] on 23 February\n* Victory Day on 9 May - Victory Day marks Germany's surrender to the Soviet Union in 1945 and is Russia's foremost national military holiday since 1995\n* Navy Day on the last Sunday of July\n* Air Force Day on 12 August\n* Ground Forces Day on 5 October\n\nAs well as on the following [[Days of Military Honour]]:\n\n* 27 January \u2013 the day of lifting of the [[Siege of Leningrad]], 1944\n* 2 February \u2013 victory in the [[Battle of Stalingrad]], 1943\n* 23 August \u2013 victory over [[Germany]] in the [[Battle of Kursk]], 1943\n* 2 September - [[Victory over Japan Day]]\n* 8 September - the anniversary of the [[Battle of Borodino]], 1812\n* 7 November \u2013 the anniversary of the [[1941 October Revolution Parade|historic 1941 military parades on the Red Square in Moscow and Kuybyshev Square in Samara]]<ref>7 November was a major holiday in the [[Soviet Union]] commemorating the [[October Revolution]]. In 1941, the troops that took part in the annual parade were sent from the [[Red Square]] directly to the front line which was situated less than a hundred kilometers from Moscow.</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Day of military glory of Russia - The day of the military parade on Red Square in 1941 | website=calendr.net | date=2018-01-25 | url=http://calendr.net/holiday/1731 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180125193640/http://calendr.net/holiday/1731 | archive-date=2018-01-25 | url-status=dead | access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref>\n\nMilitary parades were first held in 1702 as a troop review, but later grew into a ceremonial event held by order of the [[President of the Russian Federation]] in his constitutional duty as Supreme Commander of the Armed Forces. Alongside personnel and veterans of the Armed Forces, marching past in these parades are cadets of military high schools and middle schools and the [[Young Army Cadets National Movement]], cadets of military faculties of civil universities and battalions of [[Cossacks]], honoring their forebears who fought for their homeland in times past. Also, the following uniformed organizations take part in these parades:\n\n* [[Kremlin Regiment]] of the Federal Protective Service (in Moscow only)\n* [[National Guard of Russia]]\n* [[Police of Russia]] \n* [[Main Directorate for Drugs Control]]\n* [[Border Service of the Federal Security Service of the Russian Federation]]\n* [[Ministry of Emergency Situations (Russia)|Ministry of Emergency Situations]]\n* [[Federal Penitentiary Service]]\n* [[Investigative Committee of Russia]]\n\n===== Tajikistan =====\n{{See also|Tajikistan Independence Day Military Parade}}\n[[File:\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043d\u044f\u043b\u0438 \u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0435 \u0432 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0435 \u0432 \u0422\u0430\u0434\u0436\u0438\u043a\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435 01.jpg|thumb|A [[Victory Day Parades|Victory Day Parade]] in [[Victory Park, Dushanbe]].]]\nTajik military parades are held every 2 to 3 years on [[Dushanbe]]'s [[Dousti Square]]. They are either held on the occasion of [[Independence Day (Tajikistan)|Independence Day]] or [[Armed Forces Day (Tajikistan)|Armed Forces Day]]. They usually feature the entire Dushanbe Garrison and its hardware. The first parade in Dushanbe, which was at the time known as Stalinabad, took place on an area known as Red Square on 7 November 1945. Since then, Soviet military parades of the [[201st Motor Rifle Division]] in the [[Tajikistan SSR]] have been held on 9 May and 7 November in Lenin Square annually until 1990. The first military parade in the Republic of Tajikistan was held on armed forces day in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.tj/ru/node/232186|title='We were greeted as relatives.' From the Red Army to the military base|last=Shermatov|first=Gafur|date=2016-10-18|website=Tajikistan News|language=ru|access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref><ref>https://asiaplustj.info/ru/news/life/person/20150930/70-let-vmeste-201-ya-rvb-prazdnuet-yubilei</ref><ref>https://stanradar.com/news/full/22568-ot-krasnoj-armii-do-rossijskoj-voennoj-bazy-v-tadzhikistane.html</ref>\n\n===== Turkmenistan =====\nThe principal parade hosted by the [[Armed Forces of Turkmenistan]] is held during the [[Turkmen Independence Day Parade|annual Independence Day Parade]] in Independence Square in [[Ashgabat]] every September 27, [[Independence Day (Turkmenistan)|Independence Day]], marking the day of the declaration of Turkmen independence from the Soviet Union in 1991. (From 1992 to 2017 the parade was held in October 27, the day of the independence plebiscite.)\n\n===== Ukraine =====\nUkrainian parades involve the active and reserve men and women and veterans of the [[Armed Forces of Ukraine]]. It holds parades on the following:\n\n* Second Sunday of July - [[Navy Day (Ukraine)|Navy Day]]\n* May 9 - [[Victory Day over Nazism in World War II]]\n* August 24 - [[Ukrainian Independence Day]]\n* October 13 - [[Defender of Ukraine Day]]\n\nSomething that distinguishes Ukrainian military parades from its other post-Soviet counterparts is, during the Kiev parade, the marchpast of the tri-service [[Kyiv Presidential Honor Guard Battalion]] with the [[Flag of Ukraine]] to raise at the flagpole while honors are rendered, which includes the playing of ''[[Shche ne vmerla Ukraina]]''. Since 2014, military bands have also played an integral part in these parades by marching with their units as part of the parade. Unlike their other counterparts, who use ''Hello Comrades'' as the official greeting during parades, Ukraine uses ''[[Glory to Ukraine]]'' as the official holiday greeting, with the troops responding by saying ''Glory to the Heroes''.<ref>{{cite web|title=President: The words \"Glory to Ukraine! Glory to the Heroes!\" will be the official greetings of the Armed Forces of our state|url=https://www.president.gov.ua/en/news/prezident-slova-slava-ukrayini-geroyam-slava-budut-oficijnim-48938|website=PRESIDENT OF UKRAINE Official website|publisher=Presidential Administration of Ukraine|accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe voice of military parades in Ukraine is [[Dmitry Khorkin]], who since 2011 has been the official master of ceremonies for the national parades held in Kiev's Independence Square.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ukr.radio/prog-presenter.html?id=66|title=\u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u043e \u0425\u043e\u0440\u043a\u0456\u043d {{!}} \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0435 \u0440\u0430\u0434\u0456\u043e|website=ukr.radio|access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kp.ua/kiev/467334-kto-ozvuchyval-parad-v-kyeve|title=\u041a\u0442\u043e \u043e\u0437\u0432\u0443\u0447\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043b \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0432 \u041a\u0438\u0435\u0432\u0435?|website=kp.ua|language=ru-RU|access-date=2019-11-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fakty.com.ua/ru/ukraine/20190824-minimum-11-repetytsij-i-stsenariyi-na-vsi-vypadky-dmytro-horkin-pro-parady-u-den-nezalezhnosti/|title=\u0424\u0430\u043a\u0442\u044b ICTV \u0414\u0435\u043d\u044c \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0441\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438: \u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0425\u043e\u0440\u043a\u0438\u043d \u043e \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0447\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0440\u0435\u043f\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0446\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u0441\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u0441\u0435 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0438 {{!}} \u0424\u0430\u043a\u0442\u044b|date=2019-08-24|website=\u0424\u0410\u041a\u0422\u0418|access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref> Khorkin's voice became remarkable for official events with the participation of the country's top officials and for supporting the [[Armed Forces of Ukraine|Ukrainian army]], that's why he had received threats from [[Separatist forces of the war in Donbass|pro-Russian separatists]] before the 2016 military parade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gordonua.com/news/war/diktor-parada-v-kieve-iz-kryma-mne-napisali-chto-ya-prigovoren-146971.html|title=\u0414\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0432 \u041a\u0438\u0435\u0432\u0435: \u0418\u0437 \u041a\u0440\u044b\u043c\u0430 \u043c\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043b\u0438, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u044f \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0433\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0435\u043d|website=gordonua.com|access-date=2019-12-01}}</ref>\n\n====Serbia/Former Yugoslavia====\nMilitary parades in [[Serbia]] and the former [[Yugoslavia]] follow a close tradition that is significantly unique to the [[Balkan states]]. Their usage of the high step instead of the more European [[goose step]] is a notable display of heritage and tradition in their parades. The [[Yugoslav People's Army]] held its first military parade on [[Bulevar kralja Aleksandra|Bulevar revolucije]] just days before the conclusion of the Second World War on [[International Workers Day]]. Another parade on 20 October of that same year was held in honor of the one year anniversary of the end of the [[Belgrade Offensive]].<ref name=Parada>{{cite web | last=Radulovic | first=Mladen | title=Force of the Yugoslav National Army: Belgrade Thundered in the Last Military Parade in 1985! (Video) | website=kurir.rs | date=2014-10-10 | url=https://www.kurir.rs/vesti/drustvo/1586710/sila-jugoslovenske-narodne-armije-beograd-grmeo-na-poslednjoj-vojnoj-paradi-1985-video | language=bs | access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref>\n\nSince then military parades in the [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|SFRY]] were held on the following dates and occasions:\n\n*1 May 1946\n*19 October 1946\n*1 May 1947\n*1 May 1948\n*1 May 1949\n*1 May 1950\n*1 May 1951\n*1 May 1952\n*1 May 1953\n*1 May 1954\n*1 May 1955\n*1 May 1956\n*1 May 1957\n*1 May 1960\n*1 May 1961\n*1 May 1962\n*1 May 1963\n*1 May 1964\n*9 May 1965\n*9 May 1970\n*9 May 1975 &ndash; It was the first parade to feature the high-stepping march style, which was instituted by [[Josip Broz Tito|Marshal Josip Broz Tito]] to assert his [[Non-Aligned Movement|independence]] from Soviet influence.\n*9 May 1985 &ndash; The parade (branded as ''Parade 85'') was the last victory parade before the brake up of Yugoslavia in the early 90s. It was also significant as it was the first parade that was not presided by Marshal Tito as leader of Yugoslavia.\n\n[[File:Military Parade Belgrade 2014 - Serbian Soldiers with Russian Knights - The Swifts (15878267398).jpg|thumb|The [[Serbian Guards Unit]] during the [[Belgrade Military Parade]].]]\n\nThe first parade in the Republic of Serbia took place on Liberation Day on 16 October 2014. Known commonly as the [[Belgrade Military Parade|''March of the Victor'']], the parade took place on Nikola Tesla Boulevard and included 4,500 [[Serbian Army]] troops, the Russian [[Swifts (aerobatic team)|Swifts aerobatic team]] and even an appearance by Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] as the guest of honour.<ref>{{cite news|title=Putin guest of honour at Serbia military parade|publisher=BBC|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-29641642}}</ref> On 10 May 2019, the first [[Victory Day Parades|Victory Day Parade]] in close to 35 years was held in the city of [[Ni\u0161]]. Branded as the \"The Defence of Freedom\" show, the parade also included personnel of the [[Police of Serbia]], which also marked the 20th anniversary of the Yugoslav resistance to the [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rs.n1info.com/English/NEWS/a482164/Serbia-prepares-4-000-soldiers-for-Victory-Day-parade.html|title=Serbia\u2019s army and police prepare for Victory Day parade|website=N1 Srbija}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://balkaninsight.com/2019/05/10/serbia-marks-victory-day-with-grand-military-parade/|title=Serbia Marks Victory Day with Grand Military Parade|date=May 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amp.dw.com/en/my-europe-serbias-military-parade-between-the-east-and-the-west/a-48692961|title=Serbia marches between the East and the West|website=amp.dw.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-05/11/c_138049369.htm|title=Serbia marks Victory Day with police, military parade|website=www.xinhuanet.com}}</ref> Outside of the [[Serbian Armed Forces]], the [[Army of the Republic of North Macedonia]], the [[Armed Forces of Montenegro]] and [[Armed Forces of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia and Herzegovina]] use the Serbian/Yugoslav parade format.\n\n==== Turkey ====\n[[Image:Tag des Sieges 1.JPG|thumb|300px|Parade at the [[Victory Day (Turkey)|Victory Day]] (Zafer Bayram\u0131) in Istanbul]]\nThe Turkish tradition of military parades was introduced in the 19th century as part of the Westernization and modernization of the army and navy of the then Ottoman Empire to modern standards of warfare and military ceremonial, a tradition carried on by the modern [[Turkish Armed Forces]], whose parade drill includes high stepping, a tradition introduced in the 1900s.\n\nToday parades held by the Turkish Armed Forces and its veterans are held in the following days:\n\n* April 23 - National Sovereignty and Children's Day\n* May 23 - Commemoration of Atat\u00fcrk, Youth and Sports Day\n* August 30 - Victory Day, also principal holiday of the Armed Forces\n* October 29 - Republic Day\n\n====United Kingdom====\n[[File:The Army celebrate the birthday of their Queen. MOD 45162711.jpg|thumb|The troops of the [[Household Division]] during the 2017 [[Trooping the Colour]]]]\nIn the [[United Kingdom]], a [[guard of honour]] traditionally performs the march past for whoever received the salute. In the capital of [[London]], traditional ceremonial units that  perform [[public duties]] (the [[Queens Guard]] for example) take part in military parades such as the more common [[Trooping the Colour]] on [[Horse Guards Parade]] and special parades during the jubilee years of the monarch in his or her capacity as commander-in-chief of the [[British Armed Forces]]. The [[Household Cavalry]] (Blues and Royals and Life Guards) traditionally perform trot pasts in mounted formation, together with the [[King's Troop, Royal Horse Artillery]]. These units have been known to parade in slow and quick time. Personnel of the armed forces, cadet organizations, [[The Royal British Legion]] and veterans' organizations also parade during national holidays such as [[Remembrance Day]] or [[Armed Forces Day (United Kingdom)|Armed Forces Day]]. During a regimental military parade, the [[Regimental marches of the British Army|regimental march of the unit]] is played.\n\n====United States====\n[[File:President Bush greets General H. Norman Schwarzkopf who leads the Desert Storm Homecoming Parade in Washington, D.C - NARA - 186434.jpg|thumb|President [[George H. W. Bush]] greeting [[Norman Schwarzkopf Jr.]] on the parade route.]]\nMilitary parades in the American capital are held quadrennially by servicemen of the [[United States Armed Forces]] during the [[United States presidential inauguration|Presidential inaugural parade]]. These are not considered to be regular military parades however, as the parading formations are actually not entirely composed of armed servicemen. The first known organized military procession in the [[United States]] was the [[Grand Review of the Armies]], on May 23 and May 24, 1865, following the end of the [[American Civil War]] (1861-1865). The [[New York City Victory Parade of 1946]] was held in mid-January in 1946 to commemorate the conclusion of [[World War II]] and the Allied victory over the Axis Powers in all theaters of the war, helped by the service of millions of Americans who served under the armed forces and the National Guard, in addition to the state defense forces. In the late 40s and the early 50s, massive parades in honor of Army Day and later Armed Forces Day were held in the capital.<ref>https://networks.h-net.org/node/28441/discussions/1341907/washington-loves-parade</ref> The most recently held military parade was the [[National Victory Celebration]] on June 8, 1991, to celebrate the conclusion of [[Gulf War]] in [[Iraq]]. In 2018, a national debate was sparked when President [[Donald Trump]] proposed to hold a [[2018 Washington Veterans Day Parade|military parade]] on 10 November 2018 in honor of the Veterans Day holiday the next day, commonly known as \"Trump's military parade\". This was seen as expensive and authoritarian-like and by August of that year, the Department of Defense announced that the military parade would be postponed until 2019.<ref>{{cite news|last1=News|first1=ABC|title=Trump's military parade is postponed until 2019|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/trumps-military-parade-estimated-cost-92-million/story?id=57218363|accessdate=17 August 2018|work=ABC News|date=16 August 2018|language=en}}</ref> The 2019 Fourth of July parade was the first attended by the [[President of the United States]] in his capacity as the constitutional commander-in-chief of the United States Armed Forces and the National Guard Bureau, with the parade route was changed to include the [[Lincoln Memorial]] complex within the greater area around the National Mall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2019/06/20/president-trump-finally-get-his-military-parade-july-4.html|title=President Trump to Finally Get His Military Parade on July 4|first=Richard|last=Sisk|date=June 20, 2019|website=Military.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/trump-s-desired-military-parade-analysts-blast-plan-north-korea-n845626|title=Analysts blast Trump's desired military parade as 'North Korea-style' event|website=NBC News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/05/us/politics/trump-4th-of-july.html|title=Trump Sets Off Fireworks of a Different Sort With Fourth of July Speech Plan|first=Peter|last=Baker|date=June 5, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> It was also the first time since the 1950s where units aside from the guards of honor, also included cadets from the [[military academies]], units of the Armed Forces and the [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]] and the nationally produced [[military equipment]] of the services marching past in the national capital city in front of the members of government, [[US Congress|Congress]], veterans and the people of the capital.\n\nAnnual military parades, as well as armed forces and veterans' participation in civil parades are held in the following days in major cities in the country, in areas with military installations and in state capitals:\n\n* March 29: Vietnam Veterans Day\n* 3rd Saturday of May: Armed Forces Day \n* Last Monday of May: [[Memorial Day]]\n* 14 June: Flag Day and Army Birthday\n* 4 July - United States Independence Day\n* 11 November - Veterans Day \n* 4th Thursday of November - Thanksgiving Day\n\nParades are also held within the military academies, high schools, bases and installations of the Armed Forces, as well as by JROTC and ROTC units and youth uniformed cadet organizations on the following days aside from the aforementioned Army Birthday:\n\n* 4 August: Coast Guard Day (United States Coast Guard)\n* 17 September: Air Force Day (United States Air Force)\n* 13 October: US Navy Birthday (United States Navy)\n* 27 October: Navy Day (United States Navy)\n* 10 November: Marine Corps Day (United States Marine Corps)\n* 13 December: National Guard Day ([[National Guard of the United States]])\n* During a change of command, retirement and recruit and cadet graduation parades within the service branches of the armed forces and all military academies and high schools\n* During unitwide anniversaries and remembrance days of important battles of the Armed Forces\n* During holidays marked by each of the states and federal territories and major cities as well as in [[Puerto Rico]] as can be permitted by the commander of the unit taking part\n\nThe typical presidential inaugural or holiday parade hosted in Washington, D.C., is hosted by the [[Washington metropolitan area|National Capital Region]] of the Department of Defense, while local and state level parades are hosted by the local military installations and local area governments.\n\n==== Venezuela ====\n[[File:Venezuelan armed forces.jpg|thumb|Cadets of the [[Bolivarian Military University of Venezuela]] in their unique slow march in a military parade]]\nFull blown military parades by the [[National Bolivarian Armed Forces of Venezuela]] are held on the following days:\n\n* 13 April, National Militia Day\n* 19 April, 19 April National Day\n* 24 June, Army Day\n* 5 July, [[Caracas Independence Day parade|Independence Day]]\n* 24 July, Navy Day (including the occasional fleet review)\n* 7 August, National Guard Day\n* 27 November, Air Force Day\n* During change of command, retirement and recruit and cadet graduation parades within the service branches of the armed forces and all military academies and high schools \n* Following the presidential inauguration ceremony every 6 years in Caracas\n\nTaking part on these parades are active duty and reserve personnel of the NBAF and its service branches, and these are a mix of the German, British and later on Chinese and Russian traditions.\n\nIn August 2018, during a military parade and ceremony on the [[Venezuelan National Guard]]'s 81st anniversary, President [[Nicolas Maduro]] was targeted in a [[Caracas drone attack|drone attack]], which left him unharmed, and left 8\u20139 people injured.\n\n==See also==\n*[[At attention]]\n*[[Military band]]\n*[[Parade]]\n*[[Drill commands]]\n*[[Exhibition drill]]\n*[[March (music)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Military parades| ]]\n", "name_user": "Ira Leviton", "label": "safe", "comment": "Deleted a duplicate \"the\".", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Military_parade"}
{"title_page": "Malaysia Airlines Flight 17", "text_new": "{{short description|July 2014 airliner downing in rebel-controlled Donetsk, Ukraine}}\n{{For|the aircraft that disappeared over the Indian Ocean in March 2014|Malaysia Airlines Flight 370}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox aircraft occurrence\n| name = Malaysia Airlines Flight 17\n| image = Boeing 777-2H6ER 9M-MRD Malaysian (6658105143).jpg\n| image_upright = 1.1591\n| alt = \n| caption = 9M-MRD, the aircraft involved, 2011\n| occurrence_type = Shootdown\n| date = {{start date|2014|07|17|df=y}}\n| summary = Shot down by a [[surface-to-air missile]] transported from Russia on the day of the crash<ref name=\"SMH JIT\"/><ref name=\"BBC News 28 September 2016\" />\n| site = Near [[Hrabove, Donetsk Oblast]], Ukraine\n| coordinates = {{Coord|48|8|17|N|38|38|20|E|type:event|display=inline,title}}\n| aircraft_type = [[Boeing 777#777-200ER|Boeing 777-200ER]]<!-- The aircraft model is Boeing 777-200ER. The customer code used at Boeing was \"777-2H6ER\". \"H6\" is the Malaysia Airlines customer code to indicate certain preferences. Consensus is to use \"Boeing 777-200ER\" as the model number. -->\n| aircraft_name = \n| operator = [[Malaysia Airlines]]\n| IATA = MH17\n| ICAO = MAS17\n| callsign = MALAYSIAN 17\n| tail_number = 9M-MRD\n| origin = [[Amsterdam Airport Schiphol]], the Netherlands\n| stopover = \n| destination = [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport]], Malaysia\n| occupants = 298\n| passengers = 283\n| crew = 15\n| fatalities = 298<!-- don't need to add \"(all)\", we already have survivors=0 -->\n| survivors = 0\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Ukrainian crisis}}\n'''Malaysia Airlines Flight 17''' ('''MH17'''){{efn|MH is the [[IATA airline designator|IATA designator]]. The flight was also marketed as [[KLM]] Flight 4103 (KLM4103) through a [[codeshare agreement|codeshare]], and has been commonly referred to as \"MH17\", \"Flight 17\" or \"Flight MH17\".}} was a scheduled passenger flight from [[Amsterdam Airport Schiphol|Amsterdam]] to [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur]] that was [[List of airliner shootdown incidents|shot down]] on 17 July 2014 while flying over [[eastern Ukraine]]. All 283 passengers and 15 crew were killed.<ref name=\"dsb1\"/> Contact with the aircraft, a [[Boeing 777-200ER]], was lost when it was about {{convert|50|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the [[Ukraine\u2013Russia border]], and wreckage of the aircraft fell near [[Hrabove, Donetsk Oblast|Hrabove]] in [[Donetsk Oblast]], Ukraine, {{convert|40|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the border.<ref name=telegraph>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10974050/Malaysia-Airlines-plane-crashes-on-Ukraine-Russia-border-live.html |title=Malaysia Airlines plane crashes on Ukraine-Russia border \u2013 live |date=17 July 2014 |first=Harriet |last=Alexander |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=17 July 2014 |archivedate=18 July 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718001608/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10974050/Malaysia-Airlines-plane-crashes-on-Ukraine-Russia-border-live.html}}</ref> The shoot-down occurred in the [[War in Donbass]], during the [[Battle in Shakhtarsk Raion]], in an area controlled by [[2014 pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine|pro-Russian rebels]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/10/world/europe/malaysian-airliner-ukraine.html |title=Malaysian Jet Over Ukraine Was Downed by 'High-Energy Objects,' Dutch Investigators Say |last=Higgins |first=Andrew |last2=Clark |first2=Nicola |date=9 September 2014 |website=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> The crash was [[Malaysia Airlines|Malaysia Airlines']] second aircraft loss during 2014, after the disappearance of [[Malaysia Airlines Flight 370|Flight 370]] on 8 March.<ref name=\"Official nationalities\">{{cite web|url=http://www.malaysiaairlines.com/my/en/site/mh17.html|title=Saturday, July 19, 07:30&nbsp;pm GMT +0800 Media Statement 7 : MH17 Incident|date=19 July 2014|website=Malaysia Airlines|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717232838/http://www.malaysiaairlines.com/my/en/site/mh17.html|archive-date=17 July 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe responsibility for investigation was delegated to the [[Dutch Safety Board]] (DSB) and the Dutch-led [[#Criminal investigation|joint investigation team]] (JIT), who concluded that the airliner was downed by a [[Buk missile system|Buk]] [[surface-to-air missile]] launched from pro-Russian [[Novorossiya (confederation)|separatist-controlled territory]] in Ukraine.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\" /><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |title=MH17 crash report: Dutch investigators confirm Buk missile hit plane \u2013 live updates |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2015/oct/13/mh17-crash-report-ukraine-live-updates |newspaper=the Guardian |accessdate=13 October 2015 |first=Matthew |last=Weaver|date=13 October 2015 }}</ref> According to the JIT, the Buk that was used originated from the [[53rd Anti-Aircraft Missile Brigade]] of the [[Russia|Russian Federation]]<ref name=\"BBC 5.24.18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-44235402|work=[[BBC News]]|title=MH17 missile owned by Russian brigade, investigators say|date=24 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN 5.24.18\">{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/05/24/europe/mh17-plane-netherlands-russia-intl/index.html|work=[[CNN]]|title=Missile that downed MH17 'owned by Russian brigade'|first1=Laura|last1=Smith-Spark|first2=James|last2=Masters|date=24 May 2018}}</ref> and had been transported from Russia on the day of the crash, fired from a field in a rebel-controlled area and returned to Russia afterwards.<ref name=\"SMH JIT\" /><ref name=\"BBC News 28 September 2016\"/><ref name=\"BBC 5.24.18\"/> On the basis of the JIT's conclusions, the governments of the Netherlands and Australia held Russia responsible for the deployment of the Buk installation and were  pursuing legal routes to formalise this {{As of|2018|May|df=|lc=y}}.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.government.nl/latest/news/2018/05/25/mh17-the-netherlands-and-australia-hold-russia-responsible|title=MH17: The Netherlands and Australia hold Russia responsible|last=Algemene Zaken|first=Ministerie van|last2=Buitenlandse Zaken|first2=Ministerie van|website=www.government.nl|language=nl-NL|access-date=25 May 2018|date=25 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Evidence in The Australian\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/mh17-shot-down-by-missile-from-russia-by-its-military-report-finds/news-story/d3d1cafaa0033e7acc42d9b9fc38dbf4|title=MH17 evidence points to 'rogue state' Russia, Tony Abbott says|last=Bunnik|first=Jacquelin Magnay|last2=Riordan|first2=Primrose|date=25 May 2018|website=The Australian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The Russian government denies responsibility for shooting down the plane,<ref name=\"CNN 5.24.18\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tass.com/defense/1006070|title=No Russian air defense missile systems crossed Russia-Ukraine border \u2013 top brass|work=TASS|access-date=25 May 2018|language=ru}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-29140593|title=Ukraine crisis: Poroshenko offers rebels more autonomy|date=10 September 2014|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/europe/putin-claims-no-proof-russians-downed-mh17-20190621-p51ztv.html|title=Russians made a 'scapegoat' after MH17 report released, says Malaysia PM|last=Sipalan|first=Joseph|date=21 June 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-06-23}}</ref> and holds the Ukrainian government responsible for allowing civilian flights in a war zone.<ref>{{Citation|title=Putin Dismisses MH17 Charges|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/russia-putin-mh17/30010707.html|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> \n\nThe findings by the DSB and JIT are consistent with the earlier claims by American and German intelligence sources<ref name=\"LAtimes\"/><ref name=\"WaPoJuly22\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2014/07/20/the-evidence-that-may-prove-pro-russian-separatists-shot-down-mh17/ |title=The evidence that may prove pro-Russian separatists shot down MH17 |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> and claims by the Ukrainian government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/yatsenyuk-russia-is-not-planning-to-conduct-any-humanitarian-mission-live-361699.html|title=Yatsenyuk: 'We need to survive first'|date=22 August 2014|work=Kyiv Post}}</ref> \n\n==Aircraft==\nFlight 17, which was also marketed as [[KLM]] Flight 4103 (KL4103) through a [[codeshare agreement]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Statement Malaysia Airlines MH17 |url=http://news.klm.com/en/incident-with-malaysia-airlines-flight-mh017-e/ |website=[[KLM]] |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> was operated with a Boeing 777-2H6ER,{{efn|The aircraft is a Boeing 777-200ER (for Extended Range) model; Boeing assigns a [[List of Boeing customer codes|unique customer code]] for each company that buys one of its aircraft, which is applied as an [[infix]] in the model number at the time the aircraft is built. The code for Malaysia Airlines is \"H6\", hence \"777-2H6ER\".}} serial number 28411, registration 9M-MRD.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|30}} The 84th Boeing 777 produced, it first flew on 17 July 1997, exactly 17 years before the incident, and was delivered new to Malaysia Airlines on 29 July 1997.<ref name=\"airfleets1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.airfleets.net/ficheapp/plane-b777-28411.htm# |title=Malaysia Airlines 9M-MRD (Boeing 777&nbsp;\u2013 MSN 28411) &#124; Airfleets aviation |publisher=Airfleets.net |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Powered by two [[Rolls-Royce Trent 800|Rolls-Royce Trent 892]] engines and carrying 280 seats (33 [[Business class|business]] and 247 [[Economy class|economy]]), the aircraft had recorded more than 76,300 hours in 11,430 cycles before the crash.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|30}} The aircraft was in an airworthy condition at departure.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|31}}\n\nThe Boeing 777, which entered commercial service on 7 June 1995, has one of the best safety records among commercial aircraft.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/07/17/boeing-777-safe-track-record/12786181/ |title=Boeing 777 has excellent track record, experts say |author=Larry Copeland |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> In June 2014 there were about 1,212 aircraft in service, with 340 more on order.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://active.boeing.com/commercial/orders/displaystandardreport.cfm?cboCurrentModel=777&optReportType=AllModels&cboAllModel=777&ViewReportF=View+Report |title=777 Model Orders and Deliveries summary |publisher=Boeing |date=June 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Passengers and crew==\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"margin:0 0 0.5em 1em; float:right;\"\n|-\n|+People on board by nationality<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|27}}\n|-\n!Nation||data-sort-type=\"number\"|Number<!-- OFFICIAL LIST PER THE OFFICIAL DSB REPORT, DON'T MODIFY -->\n|-\n|Australia || style=\"text-align:center;\"|27\n|-\n|Belgium || style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|Canada{{efn|Including:\n* 1 dual Canadian-Romanian citizen}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Germany{{efn|Including:\n* 1 dual German-Dutch citizen}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|Indonesia || style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\n|-\n|Malaysia{{efn|28 passengers and 15 crew}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"|43\n|-\n|Netherlands{{efn|Including:\n* 1 dual Dutch-Belgian citizen\n* 1 dual Dutch-Israeli citizen\n* 1 dual Dutch-Italian citizen\n* 1 dual Dutch-American citizen\n* 1 dual Dutch-Malaysian citizen<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2014/09/09/remains-of-shell-worker-and-baby-coming-home-so-far-35-victims-have-been-brought-back/|title=Remains of Shell worker and baby coming home|newspaper=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|date=9 September 2014|accessdate=25 September 2017|quote=The 35, he added, included restaurateur Jenny Loh Yan Hwa, a passenger with dual citizenship, along with Dutch citizens Fan Shun Po and Paul Goes.}} \u2013 The Dutch-Malaysian <!--LOH/YANHWA MRS--> is counted as Dutch on [https://www.malaysiaairlines.com/content/dam/malaysia-airlines/mas/PDF/MH17/MH17%20PAX%20AND%20CREW%20MANIFEST%20200714.pdf the manifest]</ref>\n* 3 Dutch-Vietnamese citizen <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thanhniennews.com/society/vietnamese-family-friends-mourn-as-remains-of-mh17-victims-arrive-home-33948.html|title=Vietnamese family, friends mourn as remains of MH17 victims arrive home|date=13 November 2014|website=Thanh Nien Daily}}</ref>|name=|group=}}|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |193\n|-\n|New Zealand || style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Philippines || style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|United Kingdom{{efn|Including:\n* 1 dual British-South African citizen\n* 1 dual British-New Zealand citizen}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| '''Total''' || style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''298'''\n|}\n\nThe incident is the deadliest airliner shootdown incident to date.<ref name=reuters>{{cite news |url=http://www.financialexpress.com/news/malaysia-airlines-mh17-shot-down-top-5-deadliest-attacks-on-airliners/1271130 |title=Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17: Top 5 deadliest airliner shootdowns |agency=Reuters |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> All 283 passengers and 15 crew died.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|27}} By 19 July, the airline had determined the nationalities of all 298 passengers and crew.<ref name=\"Official nationalities\"/>\n\nThe crew were all Malaysian, while over two-thirds (68%) of the passengers were Dutch. Most of the other passengers were Malaysians and Australians, the remainder were citizens of seven other countries.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|27}}\n\nAmong the passengers were delegates en route to the [[XX International AIDS Conference, 2014|20th International AIDS Conference]] in Melbourne, including [[Joep Lange]], a former president of the [[International AIDS Society]], which organised the conference.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/crash-claims-top-aids-researchers-heading-to-melbourne-20140718-zuaw3.html |title=Crash claims top AIDS researchers heading to Melbourne |last=Lillebuen |first=Steve |date=18 July 2014 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> Many initial reports had erroneously indicated that around 100 delegates to the conference were aboard, but this was later revised to six.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Robin |first1=Myriam |title=100 AIDS researchers on MH17? Why and how the media got it wrong |url=http://www.crikey.com.au/2014/07/23/100-aids-researchers-on-mh17-why-and-how-the-media-got-it-wrong/ |website=[[Crikey]] |accessdate=23 July 2014 |date=23 July 2014}}</ref> Also on board were [[Senate (Netherlands)|Dutch Senator]] [[Willem Witteveen]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/2686/Binnenland/article/detail/3691664/2014/07/18/Senator-Witteveen-PvdA-omgekomen-bij-crash.dhtml |title=Senator Witteveen (PvdA) omgekomen bij crash \u2013 Binnenland \u2013 VK |work=De Volkskrant |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> Australian author [[Liam Davison]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Victorians among those killed in MH17 crash: Premier |url=http://www.bendigoadvertiser.com.au/story/2426085/victorians-among-those-killed-in-mh17-crash-premier/?cs=80 |work=[[Bendigo Advertiser]] |accessdate=19 July 2014|date=18 July 2014 }}</ref> and Malaysian actress [[Shuba Jay]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Malaysian actress, Dutch hubby and baby die with MH17 |url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/malaysian-actress-dutch-hubby-and-baby-die-with-mh17 |newspaper=The Malaysian Insider |accessdate=19 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140722064912/http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/malaysian-actress-dutch-hubby-and-baby-die-with-mh17 |archivedate=22 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\nAt least twenty family groups were on the aircraft and eighty passengers were under the age of 18.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/news/asia/south-east-asia/story/malaysia-airlines-mh17-crash-20-families-gone-one-shot-20140721 |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17 crash: 20 families gone in one shot |newspaper=[[The Straits Times]] |date=21 July 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RF430C7G?url=http://www.straitstimes.com/news/asia/south-east-asia/story/malaysia-airlines-mh17-crash-20-families-gone-one-shot-20140721 |archivedate=21 July 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Miranda |first1=Charles |first2=Cindy |last2=Wockner |first3=Ian |last3=McPhedran |author-link3=Ian McPhedran|first4=Jacquelin |last4=Magnay |url=http://www.news.com.au/world/mh17-train-in-kharkiv-as-tony-abbott-says-mh17-aftermath-is-evidence-tampering-on-industrial-scale/story-fndir2ev-1226996838429 |title=MH17 train in Kharkiv as Tony Abbott says MH17 aftermath is evidence tampering on industrial scale |publisher=[[News Corp Australia]] |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724092335/http://www.news.com.au/world/mh17-train-in-kharkiv-as-tony-abbott-says-mh17-aftermath-is-evidence-tampering-on-industrial-scale/story-fndir2ev-1226996838429|archivedate=24 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe flightcrew were captains Wan Amran Wan Hussin and Eugene Choo Jin Leong, and first officers Ahmad Hakimi Hanapi and Muhd Firdaus Abdul Rahim.<ref>\"[http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2014/08/22/The-crew-of-MH17/ The crew of MH17]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6S0tSU9RB?url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2014/08/22/The-crew-of-MH17/ Archive]). ''[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]''. 22 August 2014. Retrieved 22 August 2014.</ref>{{efn|The family name is Choo, as the Chinese name is Choo Jin Leong ({{zh|c=\u6731\u4ec1\u9686|p=Zh\u016b R\u00e9nl\u00f3ng}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.sina.com.cn/w/2014-07-18/170430543109.shtml |script-title=zh:MH17\u822a\u73ed\u534e\u88d4\u673a\u957f\u7236\u59bb\u5747\u66fe\u5c31\u804c\u9a6c\u822a |publisher=[[Sina Corp|Sina]] News |date=18 July 2014 |language=zh-hans <!--|archivelink=https://www.webcitation.org/6RWlHmVgT?url=http://news.sina.com.cn/w/2014-07-18/170430543109.shtml-->}} - The reference contains Choo's name in Chinese characters.</ref> - note that Ethnic Malays do not have family names.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2014/08/22/the-crew-of-mh17|title=The crew of MH17 &#124; The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my}}</ref>}}\n\n==Background==\n{{See also|2014 pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine|War in Donbass}}\n\nAn [[War in Donbass|armed conflict in Eastern Ukraine]] led some [[airlines]] to avoid eastern Ukrainian airspace in early March 2014 due to safety concerns.<ref name=20140718BBC>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-28356745 |title=MH17 crash: Airlines divert flights from eastern Ukraine |publisher=BBC |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/18/airlines-avoid-ukraine-airspace-mh17|title=Many airlines have avoided Ukrainian airspace for months|last=Neate|first=Rupert|last2=Glenza|first2=Jessica|date=18 July 2014|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=12 June 2018}}</ref> Military aircraft were deployed in the conflict, and [[List of Ukrainian aircraft losses during the Ukrainian crisis|several were shot down in the months and weeks preceding the MH17 incident]]. In April, the [[International Civil Aviation Organization]] warned governments that there was a risk to commercial passenger flights over south-eastern Ukraine.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|217}} The American [[Federal Aviation Administration]] issued restrictions on flights over [[Crimea]], to the south of MH17's route, and advised airlines flying over some other parts of Ukraine to \"exercise extreme caution\". This warning did not include the MH17 crash region.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/17/us-ukraine-crisis-airplane-warnings-idUSKBN0FM2BV20140717 |title=U.S. air carriers to avoid Russia-Ukraine border airspace |agency=Reuters |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=telegraph-20140717>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/law-and-order/10974823/Air-operators-belatedly-avoid-Ukraine-war-zone.html |title=Air operators belatedly avoid Ukraine war zone |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |first=Tom |last=Whitehead}}</ref> 37 airlines continued overflying eastern Ukraine and about 900 flights crossed the [[Donetsk Oblast|Donetsk region]] in the seven days before the Boeing 777 was shot down.<ref name=spiegel-981813>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/panorama/malaysia-airlines-mh17-lufthansa-ueberflog-ost-ukraine-56-mal-a-981813.html |title=Absturz von Flug MH17: Lufthansa flog zuletzt 56-mal \u00fcber Kriegsgebiet |trans-title=Crash of Flight MH17: Lufthansa lately flew 56 times over crisis region |work=Der Spiegel |language=German |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 June 2014, a [[Ukrainian Air Force]] [[Ilyushin Il-76]] military airlifter [[Ukrainian Air Force Ilyushin Il-76 shoot-down|was shot down]] on approach to [[Luhansk International Airport]], with loss of nine crew members and forty troops.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|183}} On 29 June, Russian news agencies reported that insurgents had obtained a [[Buk missile system]] after having taken control of a Ukrainian air defence base (possibly the former location of the 156th Anti-Aircraft Missile Regiment [156 zrp]).<ref name=vor-20140629>{{cite news |url=http://voiceofrussia.com/news/2014_06_29/Donetsk-militia-takes-control-of-Ukrainian-anti-air-installation-1561/ |title=Donetsk militia takes control of Ukrainian anti-air installation |newspaper=Voice of Russia |date=29 June 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=itar290614>{{cite news |url=http://itar-tass.com/mezhdunarodnaya-panorama/1287030 |script-title=ru:\u041e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0446\u044b \u0414\u041d\u0420 \u0432\u0437\u044f\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043b\u044c \u0432\u043e\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0443\u044e \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c \u041f\u0412\u041e \u0441 \u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u043d\u043e-\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0442\u043d\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043c\u0438 \"\u0411\u0443\u043a\" |trans-title=DNR militias seized an air defence base with anti-aircraft missile systems \"Buk\" |agency=[[Information Telegraph Agency of Russia]] |language=Russian |date=29 June 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ntv.ru/novosti/1085256/ |work=NTV News |publisher=[[NTV (Russia)|NTV]] |script-title=ru:\u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0446\u044b \u043e\u0431\u0437\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0441\u044c \u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u043d\u043e-\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0442\u043d\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043c\u0438 \"\u0411\u0443\u043a\" |trans-title=Donetsk militias acquired anti-aircraft missile systems \"Buk\" |language=Russian |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> On the same day, the [[Donetsk People's Republic]] claimed possession of such a system in a since-deleted [[Twitter|tweet]].<ref name=itar290614/><ref name=\"thediplomat\">{{cite news |url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/07/malaysian-airlines-flight-mh17-shot-down-over-donetsk-ukraine/ |title=Malaysian Airlines Flight MH17 Shot Down Over Donetsk, Ukraine |first=Ankit |last=Panda |date=17 July 2014 |work=The Diplomat |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 July 2014, a Ukrainian Air Force [[Antonov-26|An-26]] transport airplane flying at {{convert|6500|m|ft|abbr=on}} was shot down.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|183}} The militia reportedly claimed via social media that a Buk missile launcher had been used to bring down the aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vz.ru/news/2014/7/14/695525.html |title=\u041e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0446\u044b \u0441\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0438\u043b\u0438, \u0438\u0437 \u0447\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0441\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0410\u043d-26 |publisher=Vzglyad |quote=Today the self-defence destroyed An-26 airplane using SAM \"9\u041a37\u041c1\" (better known as 'Buk') ... said the militia, distributed in social networks [translation after ellipsis from Google translate] |date=14 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> American officials later said evidence suggested the aircraft had been shot down from [[Russia|Russian territory]].<ref name=\"BakerNYT\">[[Peter Baker (author)|Peter Baker]] (18 July 2014), [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/19/world/europe/malaysia-airlines-plane-ukraine.html U.S. Sees Evidence of Russian Links to Jet's Downing] ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref> On 16 July, a Ukrainian [[Sukhoi Su-25]] [[close air support]] aircraft was also shot down. The Ukrainian government said that the Russian military had shot down the aircraft with an [[air-to-air missile]] fired by a [[Mikoyan MiG-29|MiG-29]] jet in Russia; the [[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Russian defence ministry]] said that the accusations were false.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28345039 |title=Ukraine conflict: Russia accused of shooting down jet |date=17 July 2014 |work=BBC News |location=London |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"rfe/rl on rejection of accusation\">{{cite news |url=http://www.rferl.org/content/ukraine-russia-jet-shot-down-blame/25460575.html |title=Russia Rejects 'Absurd' Accusation Over Downed Ukrainian Jet |date=17 July 2014 |work=[[RFE/RL]] |publisher=RFE/RL |location=Prague |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> According to the Dutch newspaper ''[[De Telegraaf]]'', the Ukrainian government also warned the [[government of the Netherlands]] and other European countries about dangers in flying over the [[East Ukraine]] three days prior to the shootdown<ref>[http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2015/01/24/7056198/ Netherlands knew about dangers of flying over Donbas prior to the MH17 tragedy]. [[Ukrayinska Pravda]]. 24 January 2015</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150124134504/http://www.telegraaf.nl/binnenland/23592584/___Info_MH17_niet_geheim___.html Vertrouwelijkheid MH17 is onzin]. [[De Telegraaf]]. 23 January 2015</ref> due to the downing of the An-26 transport aircraft on 14 July.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150124134709/http://news.liga.net/news/politics/2526560-na_luganshchine_ischezla_svyaz_s_samoletom_ato_an_26.htm Communication was lost with the plane AN26 of ATO forces in the Luhansk region]. LIGANews. 14 July 2014</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150124135123/http://www.unian.ua/politics/939378-u-luganskiy-oblasti-boyoviki-zbili-ukrajinskiy-litak-lotchik-katapultuvavsya-ochevidtsi.html In Luhansk Oblast militants downed Ukrainian plane, pilot was ejected \u2013 witnesses]. [[Ukrainian Independent Information Agency]]. 14 July 2014</ref>\n\nOn 17 July, an [[Associated Press]] journalist saw a Buk launcher in [[Snizhne]], a town in [[Donetsk Oblast]], {{convert|16|km|mi|0}} southeast of the crash site. The reporter also saw seven separatist [[tank]]s near the town.<ref name=\"leonard\">{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/ukraine-air-force-jet-downed-russian-missile-102817809.html |author=Peter Leonard |title=Ukraine: Air Force jet downed by Russian missile |publisher=ABC News |agency=Associated Press |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113123101/http://news.yahoo.com/ukraine-air-force-jet-downed-russian-missile-102817809.html |archivedate=13 January 2016}}</ref> [[Associated Press]] journalists reported that the Buk M-1 was operated by a man \"with unfamiliar fatigues and a distinctive Russian accent\" escorted by two civilian vehicles.<ref name=Karmanau>{{cite news |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/what-happened-day-flight-17-was-downed |title=What happened? The day Flight 17 was downed |author1=Yuras Karmanau  |author2=Peter Leonard  |lastauthoramp=yes |work=Associated Press |date=25 July 2014 |accessdate=13 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009123439/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/what-happened-day-flight-17-was-downed |archivedate=9 October 2014}}</ref> The battle around [[Savur-Mohyla]] has been suggested as the possible context within which the missile that brought down MH17 was fired, as separatists deployed increasingly sophisticated [[anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft weaponry]] in this battle, and had brought down several Ukrainian [[jet aircraft|jets]] in July.<ref>Daily Telegraph, 14 November 2014,[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/11231333/The-unlikely-pilgrimage-site-of-Saur-Mogila.html the unlikely pilgrimage site of saur mogila]</ref>\n\nUkraine imposed restrictions to air traffic in the airspace of Donetsk Oblast, but did not close it. On 5 June 2014, traffic was restricted to altitudes above {{convert|26000|feet}} and on 14 July to above {{convert|32000|feet}}.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|179\u2013180}} This did not prevent commercial overflights as commercial traffic typically travels at altitudes of 33,000 to 44,000 feet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://traveltips.usatoday.com/altitude-plane-flight-100359.html|title=What Is the Altitude of a Plane in Flight?|website=traveltips.usatoday.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-24}}</ref> The Russian [[Air traffic control|ATC]] closed the [[airspace]] in the adjacent area over Russia below {{convert|53000|feet}}, effectively closing it to civilian traffic. The reason given was \"armed conflict in Ukraine\". The Dutch Safety Board asked for, but did not receive, a more detailed explanation for this restriction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/en/media/attachment/2018/7/10/debcd724fe7breport_mh17_crash.pdf |title=MH17 Crash|website=Dutch Safety Board|pages=180|access-date=16 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT Maps\">{{cite news |title=Maps of the Crash of Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/07/17/world/europe/maps-of-the-crash-of-malaysian-airlines-flight-mh17.html |date=21 July 2014 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref> As with other countries, Ukraine receives [[Freedoms of the air|overflight fees]] for commercial aircraft that fly through their borders and this may have contributed to the continued availability of civilian flight paths through the conflict zone over [[Flight level|FL]] 320.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/aviation/ukraine-responsible-for-airspace-safety-iata-20140720-zuzmp.html |title=Ukraine responsible for airspace safety: IATA |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |first=Jamie |last=Freed |date=20 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=smh-20140718>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/aviation/mh17-disaster-flights-over-war-zones-because-its-cheaper-20140718-zua0y.html |title=MH17 disaster: Flights over war zones 'because it's cheaper |author1=Tom Whitehead |author2=Nick Collins |author3=Martin Evans |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn the day of MH17 incident, a Ukrainian [[Antonov-26|An-26]] was scheduled to deliver [[paratrooper]]s to the battle arena.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novayagazeta.ru/inquests/68762.html|title=17 \u0438\u044e\u043b\u044f \u0432 \u0437\u043e\u043d\u0443 \u0410\u0422\u041e \u0434\u043e\u043b\u0436\u0435\u043d \u0431\u044b\u043b \u0432\u044b\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0442\u044c \u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0410\u043d-26 \u0441 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u043c\u0438 \u0434\u0435\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043c\u0438|date=10 June 2015|language=Russian|trans-title=On 17 July an An-26 transport was to fly with Ukrainian paratroopers|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Crash==\n[[File:MH17 map-en.svg|thumb|upright=1.364|Route of Malaysia Airlines Flight 17]]\n[[File:MH17 Flight Route (en).svg|thumb|upright=1.364|Routes of Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 (MH17) and Singapore Airlines Flight 351 (SQ351), including airspace restrictions]]\n\nOn Thursday, 17 July 2014, Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 departed from [[Amsterdam Airport Schiphol]] Gate G3 at 12:13&nbsp;[[Central European Summer Time|CEST]] (10:13&nbsp;[[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]])<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|23}} and took off at 12:31 local time (10:31 UTC). It was due to arrive at [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport]] at 06:10 [[Time in Malaysia|MYT]], Friday, 18 July (22:10 UTC, 17 July).<ref name=BBCbothsides/>\n\nAccording to the original flight plan, MH17 was to fly over Ukraine at [[flight level]] 330 (33,000&nbsp;feet or 10,060&nbsp;metres) and then change to FL 350 around the Ukrainian city of [[Dnipropetrovsk]]. When it reached the area as planned, at 15:53 [[Eastern European Summer Time|local time]] (12:53&nbsp;UTC), [[Dnipropetrovsk]] Air Control (''Dnipro Control'') asked MH17 if they could climb to FL 350 as planned, and also to avoid a potential [[Conflict (air traffic control)|separation conflict]] with another flight, [[Singapore Airlines]] Flight 351 (SQ351), also at FL 330. The crew asked to remain at FL 330 and the air traffic controller approved this request, moving the other flight to FL 350. At 16:00 local time (13:00&nbsp;UTC), the crew asked for a deviation of {{convert|20|nmi|km}} to the left (north) off course, on [[Airway (aviation)|airway]] L980, due to weather conditions. This request was also approved by ''Dnipro Control'' [[Air traffic control|ATC]]. The crew then asked if they could climb to FL 340, which was rejected as this flight level was not available, so MH17 remained at FL 330. At 16:19 local time (13:19 UTC), ''Dnipro Control'' noticed that the flight was {{convert|3.6|nmi|km}} north of the centreline of approved airway and instructed MH17 to return to the track. At 16:19 local time (13:19&nbsp;UTC), ''Dnipro Control'' contacted Russian ATC in [[Rostov-on-Don]] (''RND Control'') by telephone and requested clearance to transfer the flight to Russian [[airspace]]. After obtaining the permission, ''Dnipro Control'' attempted to contact MH17 for handing them off to ''RND Control'' at 16:20 local time (13:20&nbsp;UTC), but the aircraft did not respond. When MH17 did not respond to several calls, ''Dnipro Control'' contacted ''RND Control'' again to check if they could see the aircraft on their radar. ''RND Control'' confirmed that the airplane had disappeared.<ref name=\"dsb1\"/>\n\nThe Dutch Safety Board reported a last flight data recording at 16:20 local time (13:20&nbsp;UTC), located west of the [[urban-type settlement]] Rozsypne (\u0420\u043e\u0437\u0441\u0438\u043f\u043d\u0435), near [[Hrabove, Donetsk Oblast|Hrabove]] heading [[Points of the compass|east-southeast]] (ESE, 115\u00b0) at {{convert|494|kn|km/h mph}}.<ref name=\"dsb1\"/>\n\nAt exactly 16:20:03 local time (13:20:03 UTC) a [[Buk missile system|Buk]] [[surface-to-air|ground-to-air missile]], which had been launched from an area east from the aircraft, detonated outside the aircraft just above the cockpit to the left. An [[Uncontrolled decompression|explosive decompression]] occurred, resulting in both the cockpit and tail sections tearing away from the middle portion of the fuselage. All three sections disintegrated as they fell rapidly towards the ground.\n\nThe majority of debris landed near [[Hrabove, Donetsk Oblast|Hrabove]], a village located north of [[Torez]] in eastern Ukraine's [[Donetsk Oblast]]. The debris spread over a {{convert|50|km2|mi2}} area to the southwest of Hrabove.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\" />{{rp|53}} The fireball on impact is believed to have been captured on video.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10975094/Malaysia-Airlines-crash-video-believed-to-show-moment-of-planes-impact.html |title=Malaysia Airlines crash: video believed to show moment of plane's impact |work=The Telegraph |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Photographs from the site of the crash show scattered pieces of broken [[fuselage]] and [[Aircraft engine|engine]] parts, bodies, and passports.<ref name=\"huffington\">{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/07/17/malaysia-airlines-mh17-passenger-jet-crashes-ukraine-near-russian-border_n_5595450.html |title=Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17 'Shot Down in Ukraine Near Russian Border' |first=Sara C |last=Nelson |date=17 July 2014 |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |location=United Kingdom |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Some of the wreckage fell close to houses.<ref name=\"Telegraaf22866550\">{{cite web |url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/buitenland/22866550/__Vliegtuig_crasht_in_Oekraine__.html |title=Maleisisch passagiersvliegtuig in Oekra\u00efne neergestort |trans-title=Malaysian passenger aircraft shot down in Ukraine |work=[[De Telegraaf]] |language=Dutch |accessdate=17 July 2014 |date=17 July 2014}}</ref> Dozens of bodies fell into crop fields, and some fell into houses.<ref>{{cite news |author=Cahal Milmo |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/malaysia-airlines-mh17-crash-no-forensic-investigators-coordination-or-body-bags-as-locals-are-left-to-scour-the-gruesome-scene-9615895.html |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17 crash: No forensic investigators, co-ordination or body bags as Ukraine locals are left to scour gruesome scene |work=The Independent |date=19 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThree other commercial aircraft were in the same area when the Malaysian airplane crashed: [[Air India]] Flight 113 (AI113), a [[Boeing 787]] en route from [[Delhi]] to [[Birmingham]], [[EVA Air]] Flight 88 (BR88), a [[Boeing 777]] en route from [[Paris]] to [[Taipei]], and the closest aircraft [[Singapore Airlines]] Flight 351 (SQ351) was {{convert|33|km|mi}} away, a Boeing 777 en route from [[Copenhagen]] to [[Singapore]].<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|41}}\n\n==Recovery of bodies==\n[[File:Arrival of corpses from MH17 at Eindhoven Airport.jpg|thumb|First arrival of bodies at [[Eindhoven Airport]]]]\nA Ukraine Foreign Ministry representative said that the bodies found at the crash site would be taken to [[Kharkiv]] for identification, {{convert|270|km|mi}} to the north. By the day after the crash, 181 of the 298 bodies had been found.<ref name=ap-20140718>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/world/official-181-bodies-found-at-mh17-crash-site/article6225245.ece |title=Official: 181 bodies found at MH17 crash site |agency=Associated Press |work=The Hindu |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> Some were observed being placed in [[body bag]]s and loaded onto trucks.<ref name=APBodies>{{cite news |title=Raw: Crews begin moving bodies at jet crash site |url=https://www.usatoday.com/videos/news/nation/2014/07/19/12883715/ |accessdate=19 July 2014 |work=[[USA Today]] |agency=Associated Press |date=19 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=SMHBodies>{{cite news |last1=Miller |first1=Nick |title=MH17: 'Unknown groups' use body bags |url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/mh17-unknown-groups-use-body-bags-20140719-3c8dl.html |accessdate=19 July 2014 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=19 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=GuardianBodies>{{cite news |last1=Grytsenko |first1=Oksana |title=MH17: armed rebels fuel chaos as rotting corpses pile up on the roadside |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/19/mh17-armed-rebels-chaos-corpses-ukraine |accessdate=19 July 2014 |work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nDutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte complained about the lack of respect shown to the personal belongings of the dead which were reportedly being looted. He initially announced his disgust about the handling of the bodies that were reportedly being \"dragged around\" and \"thrown\", but later stated they had been handled with more care than originally thought.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nu.nl/vliegramp-oekraine/3832485/rutte-geschokt-respectloos-gedrag-rampplek.html |title=Rutte geschokt over 'respectloos gedrag' op rampplek |publisher=[[Nu.nl]] |date=19 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |language=Dutch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/31522/Vliegtuigcrash-in-Oekraine/article/detail/3693688/2014/07/21/Rutte-Zorgvuldiger-met-lichamen-omgegaan-dan-werd-gevreesd.dhtml |title=Rutte: 'Zorgvuldiger met lichamen omgegaan dan werd gevreesd' |author=Laura de Jong |date=21 July 2014 |website=[[de Volkskrant]] |language=Dutch}}</ref> On 20 July, Ukrainian emergency workers, observed by armed separatists, began loading the remains of the passengers of MH17 into [[Refrigerated van|refrigerated railway wagons]] for transport and identification.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/some-bodies-removed-from-mh17-crash-site-1405849163 |title=Bodies Removed From MH17 Crash Site Human Remains Moved to Railcars at Torez Station |last=Sonne |first=Paul |author2=Alexander Kolyandr, Margaret Coker |date=20 July 2014 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 July, pro-Russian rebels allowed Dutch investigators to examine the bodies. By this time, 272 bodies had been recovered, according to Ukrainian officials.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28399406 |title=MH17 plane crash: Dutch experts examine bodies |publisher=BBC |date=21 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> Remains left Torez on a train on the evening of 21 July, en route to Kharkiv to be flown to the Netherlands for identification.<ref name=bbc-train>{{cite news |title=MH17 plane crash: Train with bodies leaves Ukraine station |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28411225 |work=BBC News |accessdate=21 July 2014 |date=21 July 2014}}</ref> On the same day, Malaysian Prime Minister [[Najib Razak]] announced that the Malaysian government had reached a tentative agreement to retrieve the remains of the Malaysians who died in the crash, following any necessary forensic work.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marlow |first1=Iain |title=MH17: Malaysia reaches 'behind the scenes' deal to recover bodies |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/mh17-malaysia-reaches-deal-to-recover-bodies-in-race-for-muslim-burials/article19692413/ |accessdate=21 July 2014 |work=The Globe and Mail |date=21 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Convoy of MH-17 victims on the highway.jpg|thumb|Convoy of 40 hearses heading to [[Hilversum]], while other traffic stopped]]\nIt was reported on 21 July that with 282 bodies and 87 body fragments found, there were still 16 bodies missing.<ref name=\"AljazeeraObama7-21\">{{cite news |title=Obama calls for Russia 'pivot' on Ukraine as MH17 investigation begins |url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2014/7/21/obama-ukraine-russia.html |accessdate=21 July 2014 |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=21 July 2014}}</ref> An agreement had been reached that the Netherlands would co-ordinate the identification effort. A train carrying the bodies arrived at the [[Malyshev Factory]], Kharkiv on 22 July.<ref name=nyt-20140722>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/23/world/europe/malaysia-airlines-jet-ukraine.html |title=Bodies of Crash Victims Safely Moved Out of Combat Area |first=Andrew |last=Higgins |newspaper=The New York Times |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> Dutch authorities stated that they found 200 bodies on the train when it arrived at Kharkhiv, leaving almost 100 unaccounted for.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/world/mh17-crash-families-worst-fears-realised-as-bodies-go-missing-20140723-zvv9x.html |title=MH17 crash: families' worst fears realised as bodies go missing |work=The Age |first=Paul |last=McGeough |date=23 July 2014 |accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> In late July, the UK [[Metropolitan Police]] sent specialist officers to Ukraine to assist with the recovery, identification and repatriation of bodies.<ref name=hp-20140719 />\n\nThe first remains were flown to [[Eindhoven]] in the Netherlands on 23 July,<ref name=\"bbc-bodies-kharkiv\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-28416973 |title=MH17 bodies leave Ukraine rebel area and reach Kharkiv |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014 |work=BBC News}}</ref> moved there with Dutch air force [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|C-130]] and Australian [[Boeing C-17 Globemaster III|C-17]] transport aircraft,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/netherlands-to-coordinate-mh17-victim-identification-efforts-114072100077_1.html |title=Netherlands to coordinate MH17 victim identification efforts &#124; Business Standard News |work=Business Standard |date=21 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-07-22/operation-launched-to-recover-and-identify-mh17-victims/5615332 |title=MH17: Tony Abbott announces Operation Bring Them Home to secure and identify victims of Malaysia Airlines disaster \u2013 ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> which landed at [[Eindhoven Airport]] just before 16:00 local time.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/mh17-crash-social-media--blackout-tribute-continues-as-first-bodies-are-to-be-flown-to-netherlands-from-ukraine-9622288.html |title=MH17 crash victims: First bodies arrive in Netherlands from Ukraine |author=Heather Saul |date=23 July 2014 |website=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> The day after, another 74 bodies arrived.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nos.nl/artikel/679047-weer-74-kisten-naar-hilversum.html |title=Weer 74 kisten naar Hilversum |date=24 July 2014 |work=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]] |language=Dutch}}</ref> The examination and identification of the bodies was conducted at the [[Royal Netherlands Army#Services|Netherlands Army]] medical regiment training facility in [[Hilversum]] and was coordinated by a Dutch forensic team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nieuws.nl/algemeen/20140722/hilversum-treft-voorbereidingen-voor-lichamen-mh17/ |title=Hilversum treft voorbereidingen voor lichamen MH17 |work=Nieuws.nl |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140723204451/http://www.nieuws.nl/algemeen/20140722/Hilversum-treft-voorbereidingen-voor-lichamen-MH17 |archive-date=23 July 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 August it was announced that a search and recovery mission, including about 80 forensic police specialists from the Netherlands, Malaysia and Australia, and led by Colonel Cornelis Kuijs of the [[Royal Marechaussee]], would use [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drones]], [[Detection dog|sniffer dogs]], [[Underwater search and recovery|divers]] and [[Satellite imagery|satellite mapping]] to search for missing body parts at the crash site.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/11005039/Dutch-and-Australian-police-to-use-drones-divers-and-sniffer-dogs-in-perilous-search-for-victims.html |title=Dutch and Australian police to use drones, divers and sniffer dogs in perilous search for victims |publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]] (London) |date=1 August 2014 |accessdate=3 August 2014 |first=Tom |last=Parfitt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/05/mh17-investigators-frustrated-at-limited-access-due-to-fighting |title=MH17 investigators frustrated at limited access due to fighting |work=The Guardian |accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> Australian officials had believed that as many as 80 bodies were still at the site,<ref name=\"Guardian AP\" /> but after some days of searching the international team had \"found remains of only a few victims\" and concluded that \"the recovery effort undertaken by local authorities immediately after the crash was more thorough than initially thought.\"<ref name=\"FortunatelyMoreWasDone\">Toby Sterling, [http://bigstory.ap.org/article/dutch-premier-halts-search-ukraine-victims \"Dutch premier halts search for Ukraine victims,\"] Associated Press, 6 August 2014. Retrieved 6 August 2014. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141118080619/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/dutch-premier-halts-search-ukraine-victims|date=18 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 August the Dutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte announced that the recovery operation would be temporarily halted due to an upsurge in fighting around the crash site threatening the safety of crash investigators and recovery specialists, and that all international investigators and humanitarian forces conducting searches would leave the country leaving behind a small communications and liaison team.<ref>{{cite web |author=Helen Davidson and agencies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/07/mh17-crash-search-for-remains-halted |title=MH17 crash: search for remains halted as Australia begins day of mourning |work=The Guardian |date=6 August 2014 |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 August the bodies of 20 Malaysians (of 43 killed in the incident) arrived in Malaysia.<ref name=MH17Guardian>{{cite news |title=MH17 bodies arrive in Malaysia |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/22/mh17-bodies-arrive-in-malaysia |accessdate=22 August 2014 |agency=Agence France-Presse in Kuala Lumpur |date=21 August 2014}}</ref> The government announced a National Mourning Day, with a ceremony broadcast live on radio and television.<ref>{{cite news |author=TheStar |title=MH17 day of mourning: White hearses arrive at KLIA |url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2014/08/22/MH17-Day-of-mourning-white-hearses-at-KLIA/ |date=22 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 October a spokesman for the Dutch national prosecutor's office stated that one victim had been found with an oxygen mask around his neck; a forensic investigation of the mask for fingerprints, saliva and DNA did not produce any results and it is therefore not known how or when that mask got around the neck of the victim.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|99}}\n\nBy 5 December 2014, the Dutch-led forensic team had identified the bodies of 292 out of 298 victims of the crash.<ref>{{cite news |last=Grindstad |first=Ingrid |title=Six MH17 victims remain unidentified |url=http://www.nltimes.nl/2014/12/05/six-mh17-victims-remain-unidentified/ |date=5 December 2014 |accessdate=6 December 2014 |newspaper=NL Times}}</ref> In February and April 2015 new remains were found on the site,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/02/02/ukraine-crisis-mh-idUSL6N0VC3GC20150202 |title=Dutch search team recovers remains, MH17 wreckage in Ukraine |author=Anthony Deutsch |agency=Reuters |date=2 February 2015 |accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=Remains2015>{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/dutch-investigators-recover-human-remains-mh17-crash-110138676.html |title=Dutch investigators recover human remains from MH17 crash site |date=21 April 2015 |accessdate=23 April 2015 |agency=Agence France-Presse}}</ref> after which only 2 victims, both Dutch citizens, had not been identified.<ref name=Remains2015 />\n\n== Reporting in the mass media ==\n''[[De Telegraaf]]'', a large-circulation Dutch tabloid, published on 19 July a front-page photo-collage of pro-Russian rebel leaders, including Igor Girkin, under the one-word headline \"Murderers\" (\"Moordenaars\").<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/malaysia-airlines-mh17-crash-dutch-newspapers-respond-with-anger-and-despair-as-wait-for-return-of-bodies-continues-9618753.html|title=Malaysia Airlines MH17 crash: Dutch newspapers respond with anger and despair as wait for return of bodies continues \u2013 Europe \u2013 World|author=Adam Withnall|date=21 July 2014|accessdate=22 July 2014|newspaper=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nIt was suggested on other media that credit and debit cards may have been looted from the bodies of the victims, and the Dutch Banking Association said it would take \"preventative measures\" against any possible fraud.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/ukraine-plane-crash/dutch-banks-respond-reports-mh17-victims-looted-credit-cards-n160246|title=Dutch Banks Respond to Reports of MH17 Victims' Looted Credit Cards|date=19 July 2014|accessdate=20 July 2014|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> There were also accusations that other possessions had been removed and that evidence at the crash site had been destroyed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10978577/MH17-Malaysia-Airlines-crash-victims-robbed-of-their-dignity-by-rebels.html|title=MH17: Malaysia Airlines crash victims robbed of their dignity by rebels|last1=Mendick|first1=Robert|date=19 July 2014|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=20 July 2014|last2=Sawer|first2=Patrick|last3=Ross|first3=Time}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/heartless-looters-raid-malaysian-airlines-flight-mh17-crash-site-article-1.1872047|title=Heartless looters raid Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17 crash site, swipe victims' luggage, personal items|last1=Wagner|first1=Meg|date=18 July 2014|work=Daily News|accessdate=20 July 2014|location=New York}}</ref> Dutch prime minister [[Mark Rutte]] acknowledged on 6 August that early reports of chaos and criminality around the site may have been exaggerated.<ref name=\"FortunatelyMoreWasDone\" /> One eyewitness observed that valuable items like shoes and bottles of alcohol were untouched in the wreckage.<ref>Shaun Walker with Harriet Salem and Josh Halliday, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/20/mh17-victims-crash-site-anger-russia-grows \"MH17: world's anger at Russia grows as bodies pile on to train at crash site,\"] ''The Guardian'', 21 July 2014. Retrieved 6 August 2014.</ref>\n\nOn 3 July 1988, the [[guided missile cruiser]] {{USS|Vincennes|CG-49|6}} accidentally shot down [[Iran Air Flight 655]], killing 290 passengers.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jeremy |last= Hammond |title=The 'Forgotten' US Shootdown of Iranian Airliner Flight 655 |url=https://www.foreignpolicyjournal.com/2017/07/03/the-forgotten-us-shootdown-of-iranian-airliner-flight-655%C2%AD/ |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |date=3 July 2017}}</ref> In July 2014, when Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 was shot down in Ukraine, some commentators noted the discrepancy of U.S. official position and media coverage of the two similar incidents.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kaplan |first1=Fred |title=America\u2019s Flight 17: The time the United States blew up a passenger plane\u2014and tried to cover it up. |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2014/07/the-vincennes-downing-of-iran-air-flight-655-the-united-states-tried-to-cover-up-its-own-destruction-of-a-passenger-plane.html |work=Slate}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Gusterson |first1=Hugh |title=In Malaysia Airlines tragedy, echoes of a US act |url=https://thebulletin.org/2014/07/in-malaysia-airlines-tragedy-echoes-of-a-us-act/ |work=[[Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists]] |date=27 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Samarth|last=Gupta|title=Hidden Hypocrisy|url=http://harvardpolitics.com/world/hidden-hypocrisy/|date=28 July 2014|publisher=[[Harvard Political Review]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927063213/http://harvardpolitics.com/world/hidden-hypocrisy/|archive-date=27 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|first=Paul R.|last=Pillar|author-link=Paul R. Pillar|title=Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 and Iran Air Flight 655|url=http://nationalinterest.org/blog/paul-pillar/malaysia-airlines-flight-17-iran-air-flight-655-10954|date=24 July 2014|magazine=[[The National Interest]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151013072644/http://nationalinterest.org/blog/paul-pillar/malaysia-airlines-flight-17-iran-air-flight-655-10954|archive-date=13 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nAbout 90 minutes after the incident, Ukraine closed all routes in Eastern Ukrainian airspace, at all altitudes.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|101}} The incident dramatically heightened fears about airliner shootdowns,<ref>{{cite news |title=Air India flight with 126 on board was right behind MH 17 |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Air-India-flight-with-126-on-board-was-right-behind-MH-17/articleshow/38601142.cms |date=18 July 2014 |work=The Times of India |accessdate=12 November 2014 |quote=<!--\"But such fears did not exist over Europe, at least till Terrible Thursday.\"-->}}</ref> leading to some airlines announcing they would avoid overflying conflict zones.\n\nShortly after the crash, it was announced that Malaysia Airlines would retire [[flight number]] MH17 and change the Amsterdam\u2013Kuala Lumpur route to flight number MH19 beginning on 25 July 2014, with the outbound flight unchanged.<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/07/18/malaysia-flight-17-retired-numbers/12827633/ |title=Malaysia will stop using No. 17 next week |first=Bart |last=Jansen |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014 |work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref><ref name=\"ABCAust001\">{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-07-21/mh17-malaysia-airlines-retires-flight-number-out-of-respect-/5610864 |title=MH17: Malaysia Airlines retires flight number after Ukraine crash |date=21 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> In association with the retirement of the Boeing 777 aircraft type from Malaysia Airlines' fleet, Malaysia Airlines terminated service to Amsterdam, opting to codeshare with [[KLM Royal Dutch Airlines|KLM]] on the KUL-AMS route for service beyond 25 January 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://airlineroute.net/2015/12/03/mh-amscdg-jan16cxld/ |title=Malaysia Airlines Cancels Amsterdam / Paris Routes from late-Jan 2016 |work=Airlineroute.net |date=3 December 2015 |accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref> On 18 July 2014, shares in Malaysia Airlines dropped by nearly 16%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/malaysia-airlines-shares-tank-2014-7 |title=Malaysia Airlines Shares Tank |website=Business Insider |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 July 2014, two Ukrainian military jets were hit by missiles at the altitude of {{convert|17000|ft}} close to the area of the MH17 crash. According to the [[National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine|Ukrainian Security Council]], preliminary information indicated that the missiles came from Russia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.trust.org/item/20140723154118-im9dy |title=Ukraine: missiles that brought down jets may have been fired from Russia |accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, Malaysia proposed that the [[United Nations Security Council]] set up an international tribunal to prosecute those deemed responsible for the downing of the airplane. The Malaysian resolution gained a majority on the Security Council, but was vetoed by Russia.<ref name=\"churkin\" /> Russia had proposed its own rival draft resolution, which pushed for a greater U.N. role in an investigation into what caused the downing of the aircraft and demanded justice, but their proposal would not have set up a tribunal.<ref name=\"veto\" />\n\nOn 9 June 2016, a Russian businessman claimed that the shooting down of the airplane put an end to [[Novorossiya (confederation)|hopes of a Russian nation in Ukraine]] and prolonged the War in Donbass.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Loiko|first1=Sergei|title=The Unraveling of Moscow's 'Novorossia' Dream|url=http://www.rferl.mobi/a/unraveling-moscow-novorossia-dream/27772641.html|website=Radio Free Liberty}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nTwo parallel investigations were led by the Dutch, one into the technical cause of the crash, and a separate criminal inquiry.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/11/us-ukraine-mh17-bodies-idUSKCN0IV1NJ20141111?feedType=RSS&virtualBrandChannel=11563 |title=Where are the bodies, MH17 families ask |author=Anthony Deutsch |agency=Reuters |accessdate=11 November 2014 |date=11 November 2014}}</ref> The technical report was released on 13 October 2015,<ref name=\"FinalReportDate\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/final-report-on-downing-of-malaysia-airlines-flight-mh17-due-october-1440675525 |title=Final Report on Downing of Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17 Due October |last=Wall |first=Robert |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=27 August 2015}}</ref> while the criminal investigation reported some of their findings in September 2016.<ref name=\"BBC News 28 September 2016\"/><ref name=\"NLTimesJIT\"/> According to the [[Convention on International Civil Aviation]], the country in which an aviation incident occurs is responsible for the investigation, but that country may delegate the investigation to another state; Ukraine has delegated the leadership of both investigations to the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite news |title=MH17 investigation \u2013 why is Malaysia excluded? |first=Julie |last=L\u00e9vesque |newspaper=eTN Global Travel Industry News |date=3 December 2014 |accessdate=21 December 2014 |url=http://www.eturbonews.com/53217/mh17-investigation-why-malaysia-excluded}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Parker |first1=Andrew |last2=Olearchyk |first2=Roman |title=Netherlands to lead MH17 investigation |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/19c29f34-10e1-11e4-b116-00144feabdc0,Authorised=false.html?_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2F19c29f34-10e1-11e4-b116-00144feabdc0.html%3Fsiteedition%3Duk&siteedition=uk&_i_referer= |accessdate=22 July 2014 |work=Financial Times |agency=Financial Times Ltd |date=21 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Bewerkt door: redactie |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/31522/Vliegtuigcrash-in-Oekraine/article/detail/3698000/2014/07/24/Nederlandse-leidersrol-krijgt-juridische-basis.dhtml |title=Nederlandse leidersrol krijgt juridische basis \u22120 Vliegtuigcrash in Oekra\u00efne \u2013 VK |work=De Volkskrant |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dutch Safety Board heads investigation: investigation effort in full swing, black boxes currently being read out |url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/uploads/fm/2014_07_23_PB_OVV_neemt_leiding_over_ENG_DEF.pdf |website=onderzoeksraad.nl |publisher=[[Dutch Safety Board]], The Hague |accessdate=24 July 2014 |date=23 July 2014 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ShCuUTie?url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/uploads/fm/2014_07_23_PB_OVV_neemt_leiding_over_ENG_DEF.pdf |archivedate=19 September 2014 }} ()</ref>\n\n===On-site investigation===\n<!--{{2013\u20132014 unrest in Ukraine}} Already covered and more appropriate at bottom of article in a collapsible bar anyway -->\nIn the hours following the crash, a meeting was convened of the [[Trilateral Contact Group on Ukraine|Trilateral Contact Group]]. After they had held a video conference with representatives of insurgents affiliated with the Donetsk People's Republic (who controlled the area where the aircraft crashed), the rebels promised to \"provide safe access and security guarantees\" to \"the national investigation commission\" by co-operating with Ukrainian authorities and OSCE ([[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]]) monitors.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.osce.org/home/121390 |title=Press statement by the Trilateral Contact Group |publisher=Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140908053442/http://www.osce.org/home/121390 |archivedate=8 September 2014 }}</ref> During the first two days of investigation, the militants prevented the OSCE and the workers of [[State Emergency Service of Ukraine|Ukrainian Emergencies Ministry]] from freely working at the crash site. [[Andrei Purgin]], a leader of the Donetsk People's Republic, declared later that \"we will guarantee the safety of international experts on the scene as soon as Kiev concludes a ceasefire agreement\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Walker |first1=Shaun |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/20/mh17-pro-russia-rebels-crash-site-kiev-ceasefire |title=MH17: pro-Russia rebels will allow access to crash site if ceasefire agreed |work=The Guardian |accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Investigation of the crash site of MH-17.jpg|thumb|Dutch and Australian police at the crash site on 3 August 2014]]\nBy 18 July 2014, the [[flight data recorder]] and the [[cockpit voice recorder]] had been recovered by separatists,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/07/18/malaysia-airlines-mh17-black-boxes-reportedly-recovered-russia-denies-it-will-take-them-from-rebels/ |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17 black boxes reportedly recovered, Russia denies it will take them from rebels |work=National Post |date=22 May 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> and three days later were handed over to Malaysian officials in [[Donetsk]].<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|44}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Walker |first1=Shaun |last2=Salem |first2=Harriet |title=Ukraine rebels hand over MH17 black boxes and let train carrying bodies leave |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/22/mh17-black-boxes-handed-over-pro-russia-rebels |accessdate=21 February 2019 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> The voice recorder was damaged but there was no evidence that data had been tampered with.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|45}}\n\nThe [[National Bureau of Air Accidents Investigation of Ukraine]], which led investigations, both off-site and on-site, during the first days after the crash,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbaai.gov.ua/news.html?id=6&lang=ua |title=\u0420\u043e\u0437\u0441\u043b\u0456\u0434\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0438 \u043b\u0456\u0442\u0430\u043a\u0430 Boeing 777 |publisher=NBAAI |date=18\u201325 August 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref> had by August 2014 delegated the investigation to the DSB because of the large number of Dutch passengers and the flight having originated in [[Amsterdam]].<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|14}}<ref>\"[http://onderzoeksraad.nl/en/onderzoek/2049/investigation-crash-mh17-17-july-2014/onderzoek/1559/questions-and-answers-concerning-the-investigation-into-flight-mh17#fasen Investigation crash MH17, 17 July 2014].\" [[Dutch Safety Board]]. Retrieved 22 August 2014. \"Ukraine has transferred responsibility for investigating the cause of the crash to the Dutch Safety Board. The request came from Ukraine. This request was made because the flight departed from the Netherlands, and due to the large number of Dutch nationals who died in the crash\"</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://nos.nl/nieuwsuur/artikel/2139769-mh17-misbruikt-voor-opvoeren-spanning-met-rusland.html |title=MH17 misbruikt voor opvoeren spanning met Rusland |access-date=17 July 2019 |work=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]] |date=26 October 2016 |language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 July 2014, a Malaysian team of 133 officials, search and recovery personnel, and forensics, technical and medical experts arrived in Ukraine.<ref>{{cite news |title=MH17 plane crash: Dutch experts examine bodies |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-28399406 |accessdate=22 July 2014 |publisher=BBC |date=21 July 2014}}</ref> Also Australia sent a 45-member panel headed by former [[Air chief marshal (Australia)|Air Chief Marshal]] [[Angus Houston]], who had earlier supervised the [[Malaysia Airlines Flight 370|MH 370 probe]].<ref>{{cite news |title=MH370 search coordinator to lead Australia's MH17 probe Panel |url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/07/mh370-search-coordinator-to-lead-australias-mh17-probe-panel/ |agency=Indo-Asian News Service |publisher=news.biharprabha.com |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> Approximately 200 special forces soldiers from Australia were also deployed to provide support for the JIT investigators.<ref name=\"smhabbotttroops\">{{cite web|last1=Wroe|first1=David|title=Tony Abbott's office floated sending Australian troops into Ukraine conflict, defence expert claims|url=https://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/federal-election-2016/tony-abbotts-office-floated-sending-australian-troops-into-ukraine-conflict-defence-expert-claims-20160612-gphbab.html|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=Fairfax Media|accessdate=13 October 2017|date=13 June 2017|quote=In the end, Australia quietly deployed about 200 special forces soldiers in a low-key role supporting police investigators.}}</ref> The United Kingdom sent six investigators from the [[Air Accidents Investigation Branch]] (AAIB) and the UK [[Foreign Office]] sent extra consular staff to Ukraine.<ref name=hp-20140719>{{cite news |title=Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17: British Investigators Join Probe in Ukraine Amid Fears of Evidence Tampering |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/07/19/malaysia-airlines-flight-mh17_n_5601582.html |accessdate=19 July 2014 |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=19 July 2014}}</ref> It took until late July before the full international team could start working at the crash site,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/01/mh17-investigators-reach-crash-site-ukraine-search-bodies |title=MH17 investigators reach crash site two weeks after plane brought down |work=The Guardian |date=1 August 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref> under the leadership of the [[Ministry of Defence (Netherlands)|Dutch Ministry of Defence]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.houseofrepresentatives.nl/sites/www.houseofrepresentatives.nl/files/news_items/140728ambtelijke_briefing_mh17_beknopt_engels_1.doc |title=Summary Report of a Briefing at Civil Service Level |publisher=[[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|House of Representatives]] |date=28 July 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 July 2014, a Ukrainian representative said that pro-Russian rebels had mined approaches to the crash site and moved heavy artillery.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/still-no-safe-passage-to-malaysia-airlines-crash-site-1406714025 |title=Still No Safe Passage to Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 Crash Site in Eastern Ukraine |first1=Alexander |last1=Kolyandr |first2=Gabriele |last2=Steinhauser |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |date=30 July 2014 |accessdate=2 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 August 2014, the experts left the crash site due to concerns about their safety.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Outlook India |agency=Press Trust of India |title=21 More MH17 Crash Victims Identified, Experts Leave Site |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/news/article/21-More-MH17-Crash-Victims-Identified-Experts-Leave-Site/854102 |date=8 August 2014 |accessdate=17 August 2014}}</ref> In mid-September they unsuccessfully attempted to regain access to the site.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!-- no author--> |title=Netherlands deploys more experts to probe MH17 crash |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/netherlands-deploys-more-experts-to-probe-mh17-crash/498540-2.html |agency=Press Trust of India |newspaper=CNN-IBNLive |date=13 September 2014 |accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.oneindia.in/international/additional-mh17-crash-investigators-return-to-netherlands-1525660.html#infinite-scroll-1 |title=Additional MH17 crash investigators return to Netherlands |publisher=[[Oneindia.in]] |date=20 September 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref> On 13 October 2014, a Dutch-Ukrainian team resumed recovery of victims' personal belongings.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newsweek.com/dutch-experts-help-recover-mh17-crash-items-despite-nearby-clashes-277024 |title=Dutch Experts Help Recover MH17 Crash Items Despite Nearby Clashes |work=Newsweek |date=13 October 2014 |accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref> In mid-November 2014, work was undertaken to remove part of the wreckage from the crash site. Earlier efforts by the recovery team to salvage the MH17 wreckage had been frustrated by disagreements with the local rebels.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-30000967 |title=MH17 crash: Dutch salvage team 'unable to start' |accessdate=2 December 2014 |publisher=BBC |date=11 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-26248275 |title=Ukraine crisis: Timeline |accessdate=2 December 2014 |publisher=BBC |date=13 November 2014}}</ref> The recovery operation took one week to complete. The debris was transported to the Netherlands where investigators reconstructed parts of the airplane.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-11-24/dutch-complete-mh17-wreckage-recovery-in-ukraine/5912572 |title=MH17: Dutch complete recovery of Malaysia Airlines wreckage in eastern Ukraine |date=24 November 2014 |accessdate=24 November 2014 |agency=Agence France-Presse |publisher=ABC News}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, possible [[Buk missile system|Buk missile launcher]] parts were found at the crash site by the Dutch led [[#Criminal investigation|joint investigation team]] (JIT).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dearden |first1=Lizzie |title=MH17 crash: Investigators find possible parts of Buk missile used to shoot plane down |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/mh17-crash-investigators-find-parts-of-buk-missile-possibly-used-to-shoot-plane-down-10450053.html |accessdate=11 August 2015 |work=The Independent |date=11 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Investigation into possible Buk-missile-parts |url=https://www.om.nl/vaste-onderdelen/zoeken/@90384/investigation-into/ | work=Landelijk Parket |publisher=Openbaar Ministerie (Dutch public prosecution service) |accessdate=11 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Cause of the crash===\n[[File:Buk-M1-2 9A310M1-2.jpg|thumb|upright|A mobile [[Buk missile system|Buk surface-to-air missile]] launcher, similar to that concluded to have been used in the incident]]\n<!-- The audio has been widely published/played in media coverage and is a significant & noteworthy piece of evidence. Discuss on the talk page section: \"Deletion of External Link to Wiretaps Audio\" and \"YouTube ref\" -->\n{{external media| float  = right| width  =| image1 =| audio1 = {{YouTube|BbyZYgSXdyw|Pro-Russian rebels discuss the shooting down of an aircraft}} Intercepted phone calls, verified with voice recognition by the National Security Agency,<ref name=\"Landay\"/> between rebels discussing which rebel group shot down the aircraft and initial reports that it was a civilian aircraft. Audio (in Russian) released by [[Security Service of Ukraine]] with English subtitles.<ref name=\"ONE News\"/><ref name=\"Demirjian\"/>}}\n\nSoon after the crash both American and Ukrainian officials said that a 9M38 series surface-to-air missile strike was the most likely cause.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ensor |first=Josie |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10977644/MH17-what-we-know-two-days-after-Malaysia-Airlines-crash-over-Ukraine.html |title=MH17: what we know two days after Malaysia Airlines crash over Ukraine |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=19 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> If so, then the missile was fired from a mobile Soviet-designed [[Buk missile system]] ([[NATO reporting name]]: SA-11 \"Gadfly\"). At the time, Buk was the only surface-to-air missile system known to be deployed in the region that was capable of reaching the cruising altitude of commercial air traffic.<ref name=\"BakerNYT\"/><ref>{{cite web |first=Wil |last=Thijssen |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/31522/Vliegtuigcrash-in-Oekraine/article/detail/3692229/2014/07/19/De-bewijsstukken-Wie-schoot-MH17-neer.dhtml |title=De bewijsstukken: Wie schoot MH17 neer? |newspaper=[[de Volkskrant]] |date=19 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |language=Dutch}}</ref><ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\">{{cite news |first1=Ralph |last1=Vartabedian |first2=W.J. |last2=Hennigan |title=High-tech spycraft tracked missile's path to Malaysia Airlines jet |url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-fg-satellites-ukraine-missile-20140717-story.html |accessdate=21 July 2014 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=17 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">Robert Mendick (27 July 2014) [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10993020/MH17-why-the-culprits-may-never-be-caught.html MH17: why the culprits may never be caught] ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''</ref><ref name=\"Aust-ABC002\">{{cite web |title=MH17 likely shot down by mistake by Russian separatists, US intelligence official says |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-07-23/mh17-likely-shot-down-by-accident-by-russian-separatists/5616748 |publisher=ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |date=23 July 2014 |accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"kyivpost1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/sbu-releases-more-conversations-implicating-russia-in-shooting-down-malaysia-airlines-flight-video-transcript-2-356778.html |title=SBU releases more conversations implicating Russia in shooting down Malaysia Airlines flight (VIDEO, TRANSCRIPT) |work=Kyiv Post |date=14 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> Such systems, unless they receive information from larger networks, have limited capacity to distinguish between military and civilian airplanes. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/529156/how-can-a-civilian-plane-accidentally-be-shot-down/|title=Design of Surface-to-Air Missile Systems Makes Accidents Far from Improbable|last=Majumdar|first=Dave|website=MIT Technology Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/the-flaw-in-the-buk-missile-system-2014-7|title=This Flaw In The Buk Missile System Makes It Really Easy To Accidentally Shoot Down A Passenger Jet|last=Rosen|first=Armin|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2014/07/18/did-the-ukrainian-rebels-even-know-they-were-shooting-at-a-civilian-aircraft/|title=Did the Ukrainian rebels even know they were shooting at a civilian aircraft?|last=Fung|first=Brian|last2=|date=|website=Washington Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-12|last3=}}</ref> \n\nAccording to defence analyst Reed Foster (from [[Jane's Information Group]]), the contour of the aluminium and the blistering of the paint around many of the holes on the aircraft fragments indicate that small, high-velocity [[Fragmentation (weaponry)|fragments]] entered the aircraft externally, a damage pattern indicative of an SA-11.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/07/21/world/europe/wreckage-offers-clues-on-why-flight-17-went-down.html |title=Wreckage Offers Clues on Why Flight 17 Went Down |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> Ballistics specialist Stephan Fruhling of the [[Australian National University]]'s [[Strategic and Defence Studies Centre]] concurred with this, explaining that since it struck the cockpit rather than an engine it was probably a radar guided, rather than heat seeking, missile equipped with a [[proximity fuze]]d [[warhead]] such as an SA-11.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/photo-of-mh17-wreckage-proves-missile-attack-claims-report-20140722-zvjur.html |title=Photo of MH17 wreckage proves missile attack, claims report |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |author=Rose Powell |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> \n\nShortly after the crash, [[Igor Girkin]], leader of the Donbass separatists, was reported to have posted on social media network [[VKontakte]], taking credit for downing a Ukrainian An-26.<ref name=\"VK Wall\">{{cite web|url=https://vk.com/wall-57424472_7256 |title=Wall \u2013 VK |date=17 July 2014 |work=archive.org |accessdate=22 October 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717155720/https://vk.com/wall-57424472_7256 |archivedate=17 July 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.interpretermag.com/evidence-of-separatists-possession-of-buk-system-before-downing-of-mh17/ |title=Evidence of Separatists' Possession of Buk System Before Downing of MH17 |work=The Interpreter Magazine |date=27 July 2014 |accessdate=25 February 2015 |author=Catherine A. Fitzpatrick}}</ref><ref name=\"Boroday20140813\"/> This news was repeated by channels in Russia, with LifeNews reporting \"a new victory of Donetsk self-defence who shot down yet another Ukrainian airplane\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bbc.com/russian/features-37496581|title=\u041a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0430 MH17: \u043a\u0430\u043a \u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u043b\u0438\u0441\u044c \u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0421\u041c\u0418|last=\u0411\u0443\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430|first=\u041e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0430|date=28 September 2016|newspaper=BBC \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430|language=en-GB|access-date=29 September 2016}}</ref> Russian news agency [[TASS]] also reported eyewitness accounts claiming that the Donbass militia had just shot down a Ukrainian An-26 military airplane with a missile.<ref name=tassan26/> The separatists later denied involvement, saying they did not have the equipment or training to hit a target at that altitude.<ref>{{cite news |author=Rick Feneley |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/attack-on-flight-mh17-after-the-tragedy-the-accusations-rain-down-20140718-zumq4.html |title=Attack on Flight MH17: After the tragedy, the accusations rain down |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/comment/smh-editorial/mh17-ultimate-responsibility-lies-with-putin-20140718-zuc0v.html |title=MH17: Ultimate responsibility lies with Putin |work=The Age |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Europe/2014/0717/Web-evidence-points-to-pro-Russia-rebels-in-downing-of-MH17-video |title=Web evidence points to pro-Russia rebels in downing of MH17 (+video) |work=The Christian Science Monitor |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref> Russian media also reported that [[Alexander Borodai]] called one of the Moscow media managers 40 minutes after the crash, saying that \"likely we shot down a civilian airliner\".<ref name=\"Boroday20140813\">{{cite web |url=http://www.interpretermag.com/novaya-gazeta-editor-boroday-called-moscow-press-about-downing-of-civilian-airliner/ |title=Novaya Gazeta Editor: Boroday Called Moscow Press About Downing of Civilian Airliner |work=The Interpreter Magazine |date=13 August 2014 |accessdate=25 February 2015 |author=Catherine A. Fitzpatrick}}</ref>\n\nWitnesses in [[Torez]] reported sightings on the day of the incident of what appeared to be a [[Buk missile system|Buk missile launcher]],<ref name=walker>{{cite web |last1=Walker |first1=Shaun |title=Ukrainians report sightings of missile launcher on day of MH17 crash |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/22/ukraine-sightings-missile-launcher-mh17?CMP=twt_gu |work=The Guardian |accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> and [[Associated Press|AP]] journalists reported sightings of a Buk system in separatist controlled [[Snizhne]].<ref name=Karmanau/> The witness reports backed up photographs and videos which had been posted online, of the Buk launcher in rebel-held territory.<ref name=walker/>\n\nOn 19 July 2014, Vitaly Nayda, the chief of the Counter Intelligence Department of the [[Security Service of Ukraine]] (SBU), told a news conference, \"We have compelling evidence that this terrorist act was committed with the help of the Russian Federation. We know clearly that the crew of this system were Russian citizens.\"<ref>{{cite news |agency=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/19/us-ukraine-crisis-intelligence-idUSKBN0FO0GD20140719 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |date=19 July 2014 |title=Ukraine says has 'compelling evidence' Russian crew shot down Malaysian plane |first1=Pavel |last1=Polityuk |first2=Elizabeth |last2=Piper|editor1-first=Louise|editor1-last=Ireland |archivedate=19 July 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719125225/https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/19/us-ukraine-crisis-intelligence-idUSKBN0FO0GD20140719}}</ref><ref name=espreso-20140719>{{cite news |url=http://espreso.tv/news/2014/07/19/raketnym_kompleksom_buk_yakyy_zbyv_boeing_777_keruvaly_rosiyany___sbu |title=\u0420\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043c \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u043e\u043c \"\u0411\u0443\u043a\", \u044f\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0437\u0431\u0438\u0432 Boeing-777 \u043a\u0435\u0440\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0456\u044f\u043d\u0438, \u2013 \u0421\u0411\u0423 (Missile complex \"BUK\", that shot Boeing-777 was managed by Russian citizens) \u2013 Espreso.tv (leading Ukrainian news agency) |agency=[[Espreso.tv]] |date=19 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Schofield |first=Matthew |url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/2014/07/19/233825/ukraine-video-claims-proof-of.html?sp=/99/100/&ihp=1 |title=Ukraine video claims proof of Russia-supplied anti-aircraft system |publisher=Mcclatchydc.com |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref> He cited what he said were recorded conversations in which separatists expressed satisfaction to Russian intelligence agents that they brought down an aircraft.<ref name=\"ForbesPRG1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paulroderickgregory/2014/07/18/smoking-guns-russian-separatists-shot-down-malaysian-plane/ |work=[[Forbes]] |title=Smoking Guns: Russian Separatists Shot Down Malaysian Flight MH17; Putin Must Be Held Responsible |first=Paul Roderick |last=Gregory |date=18 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ForbesPRG2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paulroderickgregory/2014/07/19/what-more-smoking-guns-are-needed-for-mh17-the-worlds-first-sam-terrorism/ |title=Here Are The Intercepted Transcripts Indicating Russian Rebels Shot Down Malaysian Flight MH17 |work=Forbes |first=Paul Roderick |last=Gregory |date=19 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> While one of the involved persons acknowledged that these conversations took place, the separatists denied that they were related to the crash of MH17 and blamed the Ukrainian government for shooting it down.<ref name=BBCbothsides>{{cite news |title=MH17 Malaysia plane crash in Ukraine: What we know |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28357880 |work=BBC News |accessdate=21 July 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718121104/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28357880 |archivedate=18 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0411\u0435\u0441 \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0433 \u043e\u0431\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0432 \u0443\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0442\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \"\u0411\u043e\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0430\" |url=http://lenta.ru/news/2014/07/18/bezler/ |publisher=[[Lenta.ru]] |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=APbothsides>{{cite news |title=Both sides in Ukraine deny shooting down plane |url=http://hosted2.ap.org/PASCR/a5050f4ad4f44dafab85bb41a15281cf/Article_2014-07-17-EU--Ukraine-Plane/id-080a6229c3e249c3b05226215d0da426 |work=Associated Press |accessdate=21 July 2014 |first1=Peter |last1=Leonard |first2=Mstyslav |last2=Chernov}}</ref><ref name=\"nationalpost1\">{{cite news |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/07/17/malaysian-passenger-plane-was-shot-down-by-rebels-intercepted-phone-calls-prove-ukraines-president-says/ |title=Malaysian plane was shot down by rebels, intercepted phone calls prove, Ukraine's president says |work=[[National Post]] |publisher=Associated Press via [[Postmedia Network]] |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> According to Nayda, a Buk launcher used in the shootdown was moved back into Russia the night after the attack.<ref name=Karmanau/> The SBU released another recording, which they said was of pro-Russian-separatist leader [[Igor Bezler]] being told of an approaching aircraft two minutes before MH17 was shot down. Bezler said the recording was real, but referred to a different incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/29/-sp-ukraine-rebel-igor-bezler-interview-demon |title=The Guardian 29 July 2014 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> The head of the SBU, [[Valentyn Nalyvaichenko]], later concluded that rebels intended to shoot down a Russian airliner in a [[false flag|false flag operation]] to give Russia a pretext to invade Ukraine, but shot down MH17 by mistake.<ref>{{citation |title=Separatists planned terrorist attacks against Aeroflot aircraft on day of MH17 crash as pretext for Russian invasion into Ukraine- SBU chief |work=[[Radio Ukraine International]] |date=7 August 2014 |accessdate=21 November 2014 |url=http://www.nrcu.gov.ua/en/148/573400/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129041421/http://www.nrcu.gov.ua/en/148/573400/ |archivedate=29 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ukraine Says Rebels Mistook Doomed Flight MH17 for Aeroflot Plane |first=Anna |last=Dolgov |newspaper=Moscow Times |date=8 August 2014 |accessdate=21 November 2014 |url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/ukraine-says-rebels-mistook-doomed-flight-mh17-for-aeroflot-plane/504793.html}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Terrorists and militants planned cynical terrorist attack at Aeroflot civil aircraft |work=[[Security Service of Ukraine]] |date=7 August 2014 |accessdate=7 June 2015 |url=http://www.sbu.gov.ua/sbu/control/en/publish/article?art_id=129860 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721074226/http://www.sbu.gov.ua/sbu/control/en/publish/article?art_id=129860 |archive-date=21 July 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nJournalists from the [[Associated Press]] in Snizhne, Ukraine reported seeing a Buk M-1 enter the town operated by a man \"with unfamiliar fatigues and a distinctive Russian accent\" escorted by two civilian vehicles, which then moved off in the direction where the shootdown later occurred.  According to Ukrainian counterterrorism chief, Vitaly Nayda, after downing the airplane under separatist direction, the launcher's Russian crew quickly moved it back across the border into Russia.<ref name=\"Karmanau\"/>\n\nOn 22 July 2014, a rebel fighter revealed to an Italian reporter that fellow separatists had told his unit the aircraft had been shot down under the assumption that it was Ukrainian.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.corriere.it/esteri/14_luglio_22/cosi-stato-colpito-l-aereo-0a7e5f9e-115f-11e4-affb-3320a03d21e8.shtml |title=Cos\u00ec \u00e8 stato colpito l'aereo |trans-title=So the plane was struck |language=Italian |newspaper=[[Corriere della Sera]] |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014 |first=Lorenzo |last=Cremonesi}}</ref> This information was verified and confirmed on the same day by a German newspaper.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/ausland/europa/separatisten-sollten-piloten-der-mh17-festnehmen-13059009.html |title=Separatisten am Abschussort sollten Piloten festnehmen |trans-title=Separatists at the crash site should capture pilots |work=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]] |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014 |author=Konrad Schuller}}</ref> Unnamed American intelligence officials stated that sensors that traced the path of the missile, [[Fragmentation (weaponry)|shrapnel]] patterns in the wreckage, voice print analysis of separatists' conversations in which they claimed credit for the strike, and photos and other data from social media sites all indicated that Russian-backed separatists had fired the missile.<ref name=\"WaPoJuly22\"/>\n\nAmerican officials said that satellite data from infrared sensors detected the explosion of Flight MH17.<ref name=\"ReutersIndia\">{{cite news |url=http://in.reuters.com/article/idINKBN0FN2QK20140718 |title=U.S scrambles to determine who fired Russian-made missile at jet |first=Phil |last=Stewart |first2=Mark |last2=Hosenball |date=19 July 2014 |agency=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> American intelligence agencies said that analysis of the launch plume and trajectory suggested the missile was fired from an area near Torez and Snizhne.<ref name=\"BakerNYT\"/><ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\"/> The British ''[[The Daily Telegraph|Daily Telegraph]]'' said: \"''The Telegraph''{{'}}s own inquiries suggest the missile, an SA-11 from a Buk mobile rocket launcher, was possibly fired from a cornfield about {{convert|12|mi|km|order=flip}} to the south of the epicentre of the crash site.\"<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/> Other sources suggest the missile was launched from the separatist-controlled town of Chernukhino.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/easternapproaches/2014/07/flight-mh17 |title=Flight MH17: The Evidence |author=M.J.S. |work=The Economist |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> Several other media outlets including ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and the ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]'' reported that the aeroplane is believed to have been downed by a rebel-fired missile.<ref name=\"Guardian AP\">{{cite news |agency=Australian Associated Press |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/01/australia-mh17-bodies-retrieved-from-crash-site-within-days |title=Australia says all MH17 bodies should be retrieved from crash site within days |work=The Guardian |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Washington Post Tharoor\">Ishaan Tharoor \u2013 [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2014/07/20/the-evidence-that-may-prove-pro-russian-separatists-shot-down-mh17/ The evidence that may prove pro-Russian separatists shot down MH17] \u2013 The Washington Post \u2013 20 July 2014. Retrieved 3 August 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Paul McGeough |url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/ukraine-war-zone-tempers-federal-police-attempts-to-access-mh17-crash-site-20140801-zzkxy.html |title=Ukraine war zone tempers Federal Police attempts to access MH17 crash site |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=14 June 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAn unnamed American intelligence official stated that Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17 may have been shot down in error by pro-Russian separatists, citing evidence that separatists launched an SA-11 surface-to-air missile that blew up the Malaysian airliner. They said it was possible the rebel was a former member of the [[Armed Forces of Ukraine]] who had [[Defection|defected]] to the pro-Russian separatists.<ref name=\"LAtimes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/world/europe/la-fg-ukraine-intelligence-us-20140722-story.html |title=U.S. officials believe attack against Malaysian plane was mistake |work=Los Angeles Times |date=22 July 2014}}</ref> The official dismissed Russian allegations that MH17 took evasive action and said the claim that the Ukrainian government had shot down MH17 was not realistic, as Kiev had no such missile systems in that area, which was rebel-controlled.<ref name=\"Aust-ABC002\"/> American intelligence officials also said that Russia was attempting to disguise the flow of weaponry it was delivering to the rebels by sending older weapons that matched Ukraine's inventory.<ref name=\"WaPoJuly22\"/> The British [[Foreign Office]] stated that it was \"highly likely\" that the missile was fired from an area controlled by Russian-backed separatists.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2014/07/26/ukraine-crisis-britain-mh17-plane-idINKBN0FV0J720140726 |title=Britain says highly likely MH17 shot down by Russian-supplied missile |agency=Reuters |date=26 July 2014 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Russian Ministry of Defence]] has maintained that American claims of separatist responsibility were \"unfounded\", and said that the American intelligence agencies have not released any of the data on which they based their conclusions.<ref>{{cite news |title=US Claims of Flight MH17 Downing by Militia Remain Unfounded \u2013 Russia's Defense Ministry |url=http://en.ria.ru/russia/20140724/191186319/US-Claims-of-Flight-MH17-Downing-by-Militia-Remain-Unfounded-.html |agency=RIA Novosti |date=24 July 2014 |quote=The United States has not yet provided any documented evidence to prove that the rocket that brought down the Malaysia Airlines Boeing 777 was launched from militia-controlled territory, Russian Deputy Defence Minister Anatoly Antonov said on Thursday.}}</ref> According to the Russian military, in what the ''[[New York Magazine]]'' called \"Russia's Conspiracy Theory\", MH17 was shot down by the Ukrainians, using either a surface-to-air missile or a fighter aircraft.<ref name=newyork>{{citation |title=Russia's 'Conspiracy Theory': MH17 Shot Down by Ukrainian Fighter Jet or Missile |work=New York |first=Margaret |last=Hartmann |url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2014/07/russia-mh17-downed-by-ukrainian-jet-missile.html |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=20 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Russia Presents Its Account of Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 Crash |first=Olga |last=Razumovskaya |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=21 July 2014 |accessdate=20 September 2014 |url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/russia-presents-its-account-of-malaysia-airlines-flight-17-crash-1405952441?mod=e2tw}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 July 2014, the Russian Ministry of Defence (MoD) held a press conference and said that while the Boeing 777 was crashing, a Ukrainian Su-25 ground-attack aircraft approached to within {{convert|3|to|5|km|mi}} of the Malaysian airliner. The MoD also claimed that satellite photographs showed that the Ukrainian army moved a Buk SAM battery to the area close to the territory controlled by the rebels on the morning of 17 July, hours before the crash. They said the installation was then moved away again by 18 July.<ref name=\"wsj russian version\">{{cite news |author=Razumovskaya, Olga |title=Russia Presents Its Account of Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 Crash |url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/russia-presents-its-account-of-malaysia-airlines-flight-17-crash-1405952441 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> Promoted by Russian media, the idea that a Su-25 could have downed the Boeing 777 with an [[air-to-air missile]] was dismissed by chief designer of the Su-25, Vladimir Babak.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uatoday.tv/news/general-designer-of-su-25-says-aircraft-couldn-t-have-shot-down-mh17-414628.html |title=General designer of Su-25 says aircraft couldn't have shot down MH17 |publisher=Ukraine Today |date=11 March 2015 |accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref> In 2015 [[Bellingcat]] purchased satellite photos from the same area and time as used by the MoD and demonstrated that they had used older photos (May and June 2014) in their presentation that were edited to make a Ukrainian Buk launcher appear as if it was removed after the attack.<ref>{{cite news |title=MH17-Absturz kontert Kritik mit neuen Satellitenbildern |url=http://www.zeit.de/politik/ausland/2015-06/bellingcat-russland-mh17-satellitenfotos-manipulation |language=German |date=12 June 2015 |accessdate=17 June 2015 |newspaper=De Zeit}}</ref> In the report published by the Dutch Safety Board, an air-to-air missile strike was ruled out.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nIn an interview with [[Reuters]] on 23 July 2014, [[Alexander Khodakovsky]], the commander of the pro-Russian [[Vostok Battalion (Donbass)#Vostok Battalion|Vostok Battalion]], acknowledged that the separatists had an anti-aircraft missile of the type the Americans had said was used to shoot down the aircraft, and said that it could have been sent back to Russia to remove proof of its presence;<ref name=\"ReutersKho\">{{cite news |agency=Reuters |date=23 July 2014 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/23/us-ukraine-crisis-commander-exclusive-idUSKBN0FS1V920140723 |title=Ukraine rebel commander acknowledges fighters had Buk missile |author=Anton Zverev}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Shaun Walker in Donetsk |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/23/mh17-ukraine-separatists-buk-missile-system |title=MH17: Ukraine separatist commander 'admits' rebels had Buk missile system |work=The Guardian |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Buckley |first=Neil |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/26fe789c-126e-11e4-a581-00144feabdc0.html |title=Separatist leader admits Ukraine rebels held Buk missile system |work=Financial Times |date=4 July 2014 |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> he later retracted his comments, saying that he had been misquoted and stating that rebels never had a Buk.<ref name=\"GuardianKho\">{{cite web |last1=Walker |first1=Shaun |title=MH17: Ukraine separatist commander 'admits' rebels had Buk missile system |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/23/mh17-ukraine-separatists-buk-missile-system |work=The Guardian |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> In November 2014 he repeated that the separatists had a Buk launcher at the time, but stated that the vehicle, under control of fighters from Luhansk, had still been on its way to Donetsk when MH17 crashed. It was then withdrawn to avoid being blamed.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lanting |first=Bert |title=Wij hadden raket, maar haalden MH17 niet neer |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/dossier-rampvlucht-mh17/wij-hadden-raket-maar-haalden-mh17-niet-neer~a3782013 |language=Dutch |newspaper=de Volkskrant |date=4 November 2014 |accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 July 2014, Ukrainian security official Andriy Lysenko announced, at a press conference, that black box recorder analysis had revealed that the aircraft had been brought down by shrapnel that caused \"massive explosive decompression.\" Dutch officials were reported to be \"stunned\" by what they saw as a \"premature announcement\" and said that they had not provided this information.<ref>{{cite news |author=Natasha Culzac |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/mh17-crash-black-boxes-show-plane-suffered-massive-explosive-decompression-following-shrapnel-hit-9632881.html |title=MH17 crash: Black boxes show plane suffered 'massive explosive decompression' following shrapnel hit \u2013 Europe \u2013 World |work=[[The Independent]] |date=28 July 2014 |accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 September 2014, the [[BBC]] released new material by [[John Sweeney (journalist)|John Sweeney]] who cited three civilian witnesses from Donbass who saw the Buk launcher in the rebel-controlled territory on the day when MH17 crashed. Two witnesses said the crew of the launcher and a military vehicle escorting it did not have local accents and spoke with [[Moscow|Muscovite]] accents.<ref name=bbc29109398>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-29109398 |title=MH17 disaster: Russians 'controlled Buk missile system' |work=BBC News |date=8 September 2014 |accessdate=9 September 2014 |author=Sweeney, John}}</ref> On the same day Ignat Ostanin, a Russian journalist, published an analysis of photos and films of Buk units moving in Russia and Ukraine in the days before and after the MH17 crash. According to Ostanin, the markings on the specific launcher suspected of being used to shoot MH17, together with the number plates of the [[large goods vehicle]] that carried the launcher, suggested that it belonged to the 53rd Anti-Aircraft Missile Brigade of the Air Defence Forces of the [[Russian Ground Forces]].<ref name=\"FBS2APRIL\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paulroderickgregory/2015/04/02/is-the-mh17-joint-investigation-team-avoiding-the-question-of-kremlin-guilt/ |title=Is The MH17 Joint Investigation Team Avoiding The Question of Kremlin Guilt? |work=Forbes |date=2 April 2015 |accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ostanin\">{{cite web |url=https://bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2014/09/08/images-show-the-buk-that-downed-flight-mh17-inside-russia-controlled-by-russian-troops/ |title=Images Show the Buk that Downed Flight MH17, Inside Russia, Controlled by Russian Troops |publisher=[[Bellingcat]] |date=8 September 2014 |accessdate=9 September 2014 |last=Ostanin |first=Iggy}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 October 2014 the president of the German [[Bundesnachrichtendienst|Federal Intelligence Service]] (BND) gave a presentation about MH17 to a German parliamentary committee overseeing intelligence activities.  According to ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', the report contained a detailed analysis which concluded that pro-Russian separatists had used a captured Ukrainian Buk system to shoot down Flight MH17. The report also noted that \"Russian claims the missile had been fired by Ukrainian soldiers and that a Ukrainian fighter jet had been flying close to the passenger jet were false\".<ref name=spiegel-bnd-de>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/mh17-laut-bnd-waren-separatisten-fuer-absturz-verantwortlich-a-997885.html |title=Ostukraine: BND macht Separatisten f\u00fcr MH17-Absturz verantwortlich|trans-title=Eastern Ukraine: BND says separatists are responsible for MH17 crash |work=Der Spiegel |language=German |date=19 October 2014 |accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2014/10/20/world/germany-says-ukraine-rebels-downed-mh17-seized-missiles-report/ |title=Germany says Ukraine rebels downed MH17 with seized missiles: report |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=20 October 2014 |accessdate=20 October 2014}} \"He also said Ukrainian photos had been \"manipulated\", the magazine reported but did not elaborate on what the pictures showed, who had provided them or altered them.\"</ref> The [[Attorney General of Germany]] opened an investigation against unknown persons due to a suspected [[war crime]].<ref name=spiegel-bnd>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/german-intelligence-blames-pro-russian-separatists-for-mh17-downing-a-997972.html |title=Deadly Ukraine Crash: German Intelligence Claims Pro-Russian Separatists Downed MH17 |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |date=19 October 2014 |accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nBetween November 2014 and May 2016, UK-based investigative collective [[Bellingcat]] made a series of conclusions, based on their examination of photos in social media and other open-source information. Bellingcat said that the launcher used to shoot down the aircraft was a Buk 332 of the Russian [[53rd Anti-Aircraft Missile Brigade]] based in [[Kursk]], Russia, which had been transported from [[Donetsk]] to [[Snizhne]] and was controlled by separatists in Ukraine on the day of the attack.<ref name=\"Bellingcat\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Origin-of-the-Separatists-Buk-A-Bellingcat-Investigation1.pdf|title=MH17: Source of the Separatists' Buk|author=Bellingcat MH17 Investigation Team|date=8 November 2014|publisher=Bellingcat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109132619/https://www.bellingcat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Origin-of-the-Separatists-Buk-A-Bellingcat-Investigation1.pdf|archive-date=9 November 2014|url-status=live|access-date=16 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/journalists-find-solid-russian-ties-to-missile-that-hit-mh17-371161.html|title=Journalists find 'solid' Russian ties to missile that hit MH17|last=Gorchinskaya|first=Katya|date=9 November 2014|work=Kyiv Post|accessdate=18 June 2015|last2=Lavrov|first2=Vlad}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/meet-eliot-higgins-putins-mh17-nemesis-345485|title=Meet Eliot Higgins, Putin's MH17 Nemesis|last=Tucker|first=Maxim|date=22 June 2015|work=Newsweek|accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/bellingcat-new-evidence-against-russian-soldiers-on-mh17/a-18959585|title=Bellingcat: New evidence against Russian soldiers on MH17|work=DW.COM|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2016/05/03/the_lost_digit/|title=bellingcat \u2013 The Lost Digit: Buk 3x2 \u2013 bellingcat|work=bellingcat|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 December 2014 the Dutch news service [[RTL Nieuws]] published a statement of an unnamed local resident who witnessed the shooting down of MH17, indicating that the aircraft was shot down by a missile from rebel territory. He took photographs of what appeared to be the vapour trail of a ground-launched missile which he passed to the [[Security Service of Ukraine|SBU]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rtlnieuws.nl/nieuws/binnenland/ooggetuige-mh17-mijn-doel-rechtvaardigheid |title=Ooggetuige MH17: 'Mijn doel is rechtvaardigheid' |trans-title=Eyewitness of MH17: \"My goal is justice\" |newspaper=RTL News |date=22 December 2014 |accessdate=23 December 2014 |language=Dutch}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New Competing Claims on Downing of MH17 |publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |date=24 December 2014 |url=http://www.rferl.org/content/new-competing-claims-on-downing-of-mh17/26760591.html}}</ref> On 24 December Russia's state-operated domestic news agency [[RIA Novosti]] quoted the leader of the self-proclaimed Donetsk People's Republic, [[Alexander Zakharchenko]], saying he saw MH17 shot out of the sky by two Ukrainian jets.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0413\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u0414\u041d\u0420 \u043e \u043a\u0440\u0443\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 MH17: \"\u042f \u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043b, \u043a\u0430\u043a \u044d\u0442\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0441\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043b\u043e\" |trans-title=Head of the DPR about the crash of MH17: \"I saw how it happened\" |date=25 December 2014 |accessdate=26 December 2014 |language=Russian |newspaper=RIA News |url=http://ria.ru/mh17/20141225/1040130183.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Kremlin-backed insurgent leader claims personally witnessing Ukrainian aircraft shooting down MH17 |newspaper=Ukraine Today |date=25 December 2014 |url=http://uatoday.tv/news/kremlin-backed-insurgent-leader-claims-personally-witnessing-ukrainian-aircraft-shooting-down-mh17-399664.html}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015 a report produced by the German investigative team CORRECT!V concluded a Buk surface-to-air missile launcher operated by the [[53rd Anti-Aircraft Missile Brigade]] shot down MH17.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/kyiv-post-plus/new-report-says-it-proves-russian-forces-downed-flight-mh17-377063.html |title=New report says it proves Russian forces downed flight MH17 |date=10 January 2015 |first=Maxim |last=Tucker |work=Kyiv Post |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> Large amounts of other [[circumstantial evidence]] were presented separately by various parties that supports this version, identifying specific launcher vehicle, operator name, truck transporting it and its alleged route through Russia and Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/evidence-mounts-that-russia-supplied-the-missiles-that-shot-down-mh17-in-ukraine-2015-5?IR=T |title=Evidence mounts that Russia supplied the missiles that shot down MH17 in Ukraine |website=Business Insider |date=13 May 2015 |accessdate=13 June 2015 |author=Robert Coalson}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015 Reuters published statements from named witnesses from Chervonyi Zhovten ({{lang-uk|[[:uk:\u0427\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0416\u043e\u0432\u0442\u0435\u043d\u044c|\u0427\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0416\u043e\u0432\u0442\u0435\u043d\u044c]]}}), a village close to Torez and Snizhne, who said they saw the Buk rocket passing over the village when it was fired from a field around 1.5&nbsp;km away. It also published a statement from a witness who was said to be a separatist fighter (referred to by first name only) who confirmed that the launcher was placed in that area on the day of the Boeing crash to prevent Ukrainian airstrikes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/12/us-ukraine-crisis-airliner-idUSKBN0M81XF20150312 |title=Exclusive: From 'Red October' village, new evidence on downing of Malaysian plane over Ukraine |agency=Reuters |accessdate=12 March 2015 |author=Anton Zverev}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, [[News Corp Australia]] published the transcript of a 17-minute video recorded at the scene shortly after the crash. The transcript and published segments of the video indicated that Russian-backed rebels arrived at the crash site in the expectation of finding the wreckage of a military aircraft and of locating crew that had parachuted from the aircraft.<ref name=\"NC150717\">{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/full-transcript-russian-backed-rebels-ransack-the-wreckage-of-mh17-in-shocking-17-minute-video/story-e6frfkp9-1227444629703|title=Full transcript: Russian-backed rebels ransack the wreckage of MH17 in shocking 17-minute video|date=17 July 2015|accessdate=17 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150717004444/http://www.news.com.au/national/full-transcript-russian-backed-rebels-ransack-the-wreckage-of-mh17-in-shocking-17-minute-video/story-e6frfkp9-1227444629703|archive-date=17 July 2015|url-status=dead|work=[[news.com.au]]}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, [[Stratfor]] released satellite imagery taken 5 hours before the crash which showed a Russian Buk system travelling on a flatbed truck east through the town of [[Makiivka]], 40&nbsp;km away from Snizhne. Stratfor's concluded that a Buk system had moved from the Russian border toward Donetsk on 15 July 2014, and then moved back to the east on the afternoon of 17 July 2014, hours before Flight MH17 was shot down.<ref>{{cite news|title=Examining the Evidence of Russia's Involvement in a Malaysia Airlines Crash|url=https://www.stratfor.com/analysis/examining-evidence-russias-involvement-malaysia-airlines-crash|accessdate=16 May 2016|publisher=Stratfor}}</ref>\n\n===Dutch Safety Board reports===\n====Preliminary report====\nOn 9 September 2014, the preliminary report was released by the Dutch Safety Board (DSB).<ref name=\"dsb1\">{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/09/09/world/europe/netherlands-ukraine-mh17-report/index.html?hpt=hp_t2 |title=Report: MH17 hit by burst of 'high-energy objects' from outside |date=9 September 2014 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=25 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"dsbprelim\">{{citation |title=Preliminary report \u2013 Crash involving Malaysia Airlines Boeing 777-200 Flight MH17 |work=DSB |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=24 September 2014 |url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/uploads/phase-docs/701/b3923acad0ceprem-rapport-mh-17-en-interactief.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|16}} This preliminary report concluded that there was no evidence of any technical or operational failure in the aircraft or from the crew prior to the ending of the [[Flight recorder|CVR and FDR]] recordings at 13.20:03 hrs (UTC). The report also said that \"damage observed on the forward fuselage and cockpit section of the aircraft appears to indicate that there were impacts from a large number of high-energy objects from outside the aircraft\". According to the investigators, this damage probably led to a loss of structural integrity that caused an in-flight break-up first of the forward parts of the aircraft and then of the remainder with an expansive geographic spread of the aircraft's pieces.\n\n[[Tjibbe Joustra]], Chairman of the Dutch Safety Board, explained that the investigation thus far pointed \"towards an external cause of the MH17 crash\", but determining the exact cause required further investigation. They also said that they aimed to publish the final report within a year of the crash date.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Prof. mr. dr. Erwin Muller |title=Investigation crash MH17, 17 July 2014 Donetsk |url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/en/onderzoek/2049/investigation-crash-mh17-17-july-2014/preliminary-report/1562/preliminary-report-points-towards-external-cause-of-mh17-crash#fasen |website=Dutch Safety Board |publisher=Onderzoeksraad voor Veiligheid |accessdate=14 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Final report====\n[[File:MH17 Missile Impact.webm|thumb|thumbtime=43|right|upright=1.273|Narrated reconstruction of the missile impact, produced by the [[Dutch Safety Board]]]]\nThe Dutch Safety Board (DSB) issued its final report on the crash on 13 October 2015. The report concluded that the crash was caused by a [[Buk missile system|Buk 9M38-series surface-to-air missile]] with a 9N314M [[warhead]]. The warhead detonated outside and above the left-hand side of the cockpit. The impact killed the three people in the cockpit and caused structural damage to the airplane leading to an in-flight break-up resulting in a wreckage area of 50 square kilometres and loss of the lives of all 298 occupants.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/> Based on evidence they were able to exclude meteor strikes, the airplane having technical defects, a bomb, and an air-to-air attack as causes of the crash. The DSB calculated the trajectory of the missile and found it was fired within a {{convert|320|km2|sqmi|adj=on}} area southeast of [[Torez]]. Narrowing down a specific launch site was outside the DSB's mandate.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\">{{cite report|url=https://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/en/media/attachment/2018/7/10/debcd724fe7breport_mh17_crash.pdf |title=Crash of Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17 |publisher=[[Dutch Safety Board]] |date=13 October 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6cFSGnsRg?url=http://cdn.onderzoeksraad.nl/documents/report-mh17-crash-en.pdf |archivedate=13 October 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref>{{rp|147}} The findings do not specify who launched the Buk missile but according to Al Jazeera, the area identified by the DSB was controlled by separatists at the time of the downing.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2015/10/dutch-board-russian-missile-downed-mh17-151013112210934.html |title=Dutch board says Russian-made missile downed MH17 |date=13 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the technical investigation, the selection of the flight route was also investigated by the DSB.<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigation crash MH17, 17 July 2014 |url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/en/onderzoek/2049/investigation-crash-mh17-17-july-2014/onderzoek/1543/dutch-safety-board-heads-investigation-investigation-effort-in-full-swing-black-boxes-currently-being-read-out |website=onderzoeksraad.nl |publisher=[[Dutch Safety Board]] |accessdate=24 July 2014 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ShD1V2ae?url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/en/onderzoek/2049/investigation-crash-mh17-17-july-2014/onderzoek/1543/dutch-safety-board-heads-investigation-investigation-effort-in-full-swing-black-boxes-currently-being-read-out |archivedate=19 September 2014 }} ()</ref> Many airlines had avoided the Eastern Ukrainian airspace for months prior to the MH17 disaster. Many others, including 62 operators from 32 countries, continued to use this route.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|224}}<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Abeyratne|first1=Ruwantissa|title=Flight MH 17 and State Responsibility for Ensuring Safety and Security of Air Transport|journal=Journal of Transportation Security|date=1 December 2014|volume=7|issue=4|pages=347\u2013348|doi=10.1007/s12198-014-0148-0|language=en|issn=1938-7741}}</ref> The DSB stated that authorities should have closed the airspace above eastern Ukraine prior to the incident due to the ongoing conflict.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dutch Safety Board: MH17 brought down by missile in airspace that should have been closed |url=https://news.aviation-safety.net/2015/10/13/dutch-safety-board-mh17-brought-down-by-missile-in-airspace-that-should-have-been-closed/ |accessdate=4 October 2019 |publisher=ASN News |date=13 October 2015}}</ref> It recommended that states involved in armed conflicts should exercise more caution when evaluating their airspace, and operators should more thoroughly assess the risks when selecting routes over conflict areas.<ref name=\"BBC13OCT15_1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-34518473 |title=MH17 report: Five key findings from the Dutch Safety Board |newspaper=BBC News |accessdate=13 October 2015|date=13 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===Criminal investigation===\nThe criminal investigation into the downing of MH17 is being led by the [[Openbaar Ministerie|Public Prosecution Service]] of the [[Dutch Ministry of Justice]], and is the largest in Dutch history, involving dozens of prosecutors and 200 investigators.<ref name=\":0\">{{citation |title=MH17 criminal investigation largest ever in the Netherlands |agency=Xinhua News Agency |date=15 August 2014 |accessdate=27 October 2014 |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/world/2014-08/15/c_126873336.htm |editor=Mu Xuequan |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826002055/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/world/2014-08/15/c_126873336.htm |archive-date=26 August 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Investigators interviewed witnesses and examined forensic samples, satellite data, intercepted communications, and information on the Web.<ref>{{citation |title=MH17 crash: Investigation focuses on '25 metal shards' |publisher=BBC News |date=12 September 2014 |accessdate=27 October 2014 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-29180887}}</ref> Participating in the investigation along with the Netherlands, are the four other members of the [[joint investigation team]] (JIT),<ref name=\"TheStarJIT\" /> Belgium, Ukraine, Australia, and lastly, Malaysia,<ref>{{cite news |title=Speculation on MH17 is damaging to investigations |newspaper=Free Malaysia Today |agency=[[Bernama]] |date=22 November 2014 |accessdate=22 November 2014 |url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2014/11/22/speculation-on-mh17-is-damaging-to-investigations/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129091900/http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2014/11/22/speculation-on-mh17-is-damaging-to-investigations/ |archive-date=29 November 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> which joined in November 2014.<ref name=\"TheStarJIT\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2014/12/01/mh17-malaysia-to-be-part-of-investigating-team/ |title=MH17: Malaysia accepted as full member of probe team |newspaper=The Star |location=Petaling Jaya, Malaysia |date=1 December 2014 |accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref> Early in the investigation, the JIT eliminated accident, internal terrorist attack or air-to-air attack from another aircraft as the cause of the crash.<ref name=\"SMH JIT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/malaysia-airlines-flight-mh17-was-shot-down-from-prorussian-rebel-controlled-territory-investigation-finds-20160928-grqter.html|title=Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17 was shot down from pro-Russian rebel controlled territory, investigation finds|first=Nick|last=Miller|date=29 September 2016|work=Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, in a letter to the [[United Nations Security Council|Security Council]], the Netherlands [[United Nations|UN]] representative wrote that \"The Dutch government is deliberately refraining from any speculation or accusations regarding legal responsibility for the downing of MH17.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Letter to President of the UNSC |first=Karel J.G |last=van Oosterom |date=16 December 2014 |accessdate=21 December 2014 |url=http://www.tweedekamer.nl/downloads/document?id=adbae747-b7f0-4713-ad97-1a7e1b75dcd2&title=Brief%20van%20Permanent%20Representative%20of%20the%20Kingdom%20of%20the%20Netherlands.pdf }}</ref> Also in December, the assistant secretary of the [[United States Department of State]]'s European and Eurasian Affairs said America had given all of its information, including classified information to the Dutch investigators and to the [[ICAO]].<ref>{{cite news |title=US Submits Classified Information on MH17 to Investigators: State Dep't |newspaper=[[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] |date=17 December 2014 |accessdate=21 December 2014 |url=http://sputniknews.com/military/20141217/1015956748.html}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March 2015, the JIT released a Russian-language video calling for witnesses in the [[Donetsk Oblast|Donetsk]] and [[Luhansk Oblast|Luhansk regions]] who might have seen a [[Buk missile system]].<ref name=\"JITMH17\">{{cite web |url=http://jitmh17.com/ |title=Call for witnesses |publisher=Joint Investigation Team |accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref> The video included some previously undisclosed recordings allegedly of tapped phone conversations between rebel fighters about the Buk. In one recording, of a conversation a few hours after the shoot down, a fighter says that a member of the Buk's accompanying crew had been left behind at a checkpoint. In another recording, dated the day after the shootdown, a rebel allegedly says the Buk system and its crew had been brought from Russia by \"the Librarian.\"  The video presents a \"scenario\" whereby a Buk missile was transported on a [[Volvo]] low loader truck from Sievernyi (\u0421\u0454\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0439), a town located within a kilometre of the Russian border (near [[Krasnodon]]), to [[Donetsk]] during the night of 16/17 July.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=olQNpTxSnTo MH17] ''Politie [Police]''  International Joint Investigation Team</ref>\nIn the week following the public appeal, the JIT received more than 300 responses resulting in dozens of \"serious witnesses\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/binnenland/23903198/__Bruikbare_tips_over_daders_MH17__.html|trans-title=Dozens of useful tips about MH17 |title=Tientallen bruikbare tips over MH17 |last=van der Graaf |first=Jolande |language=Dutch |newspaper=De Telegraaf |date=9 April 2015 |accessdate=17 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nltimes.nl/2015/04/09/hundreds-respond-to-call-for-mh17-witnesses-tips/ |title=Hundreds respond to call for MH17 witnesses |last=Van Jaarsveldt |first=Janene |date=9 April 2015 |accessdate=17 June 2015 |newspaper=NL Times}}</ref> In 2016 the presence of the [[transloading|transloader]] of matching color with a Buk missile was confirmed on a satellite photo of the area taken just a few hours before the downing of the airplane, which was described as \"correlating with other evidence\" by [[Stratfor]] who found the photo in [[DigitalGlobe]] archive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stratfor.com/analysis/examining-evidence-russias-involvement-malaysia-airlines-crash|title=Examining the Evidence of Russia's Involvement in a Malaysia Airlines Crash|website=Stratfor|access-date=13 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/travel/travel-updates/incidents/mh17-the-satellite-images-russia-doesnt-want-us-to-see/news-story/8c03f8e87971d36f70b5402ffbda16ff|title=The image Russia doesn't want the world to see|website=NewsComAu|access-date=16 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April 2015 Dutch authorities made available 569 documents concerning the shoot-down. Personal information and official interviews had been redacted. A further 147 documents were not made public.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rtlnieuws.nl/nieuws/binnenland/wat-we-niet-mogen-zien-147-documenten-mh17-blijven-geheim |title=Wat we niet mogen zien: 147 documenten MH17 blijven geheim |work=RTL Nieuws |accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Findings of the joint investigation team (JIT)====\nOn 28 September 2016, the JIT gave a press conference in which it concluded that the aircraft was shot down with a [[Buk missile system|9M38 Buk missile]] fired from a rebel-controlled field near Pervomaisky (\u041f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439), a town {{convert|6|km|mi|abbr=on}} south of [[Snizhne]].<ref name=\"NLTimesJIT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nltimes.nl/2016/09/28/jit-mh17-shot-down-by-a-9m38-buk-missile-from-russian-origin/|title=JIT: MH17 shot down with missile fired from pro-Russian rebel controlled field}}</ref> It also found the Buk missile system used had been transported from Russia into Ukraine on the day of the crash, and then back into Russia after the crash, with one missile less than it arrived with.<ref name=\"SMH JIT\"/><ref name=\"BBC News 28 September 2016\">{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-37495067 |title= MH17 missile 'came from Russia', Dutch-led investigators say |author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 28 September 2016|website= [[BBC News Online]] |publisher= [[BBC]] | accessdate= 2 October 2016 }}</ref> The JIT said they had identified 100 people, witnesses as well as suspects, who were involved in the movement of the Buk launcher, though they had not yet identified a clear chain of command to assess culpability, which was a matter for ongoing investigation. The Dutch chief prosecutor said \"the evidence must stand before a court\" which would render final judgement.<ref name=\"SMH JIT\"/> During the investigation, the JIT recorded and assessed five billion internet pages, interviewed 200 witnesses, collected half a million photos and videos, and analysed 150,000 intercepted phone calls.<ref name=\"NLTimesJIT\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.om.nl/onderwerpen/mh17-crash/@96066/presentation/|title=Presentation preliminary results criminal investigation MH17 28-09-2016}}</ref> According to JIT head prosecutor Fred Westerbeke the criminal investigation is based on \"immense body of evidence,\" including testimonies of live witnesses who saw the \"Buk\" launcher, primary radar data, original photos and videos.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.novayagazeta.ru/articles/2017/10/16/74192-the-purpose-is-to-bring-this-matter-to-court|title=\"The purpose is to bring MH17 matter to court\"|work=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u2013 Novayagazeta.ru|access-date=16 October 2017|language=ru-RU}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Engineering Technologies 2010 Part3 0031 copy.jpg|thumb|A Buk SAM of the type used by the [[53rd Anti-Aircraft Missile Brigade]]]]\nOn 24 May 2018, after extensive comparative research, the JIT concluded that the Buk that shot down the flight came from the Russian [[53rd Anti-Aircraft Missile Brigade]] in [[Kursk]].<ref name=\"jit\">{{cite web | url =https://www.om.nl/onderwerpen/mh17-crash/@103196/update-criminal-0/ |title=Update in criminal investigation MH17 disaster|publisher=[[Openbaar Ministerie]]| date=24 May 2018| accessdate =24 May 2018}}</ref> The head of the National Investigation Service of the Dutch police asked the eyewitnesses and insiders to share information about the identities of the Buk crew members, the instruction the crew members followed and persons responsible for the operational deployment of the involved Buk on 17 July 2014.<ref name=\"jit\"/> According to Dutch [[Openbaar Ministerie|Public Prosecution Service]], by 24 May 2018 \"the authorities of the Russian Federation have ... not reported to the JIT that a Buk of the 53rd Brigade was deployed in Eastern Ukraine and that this Buk downed flight MH17.\"<ref name=\"jit\"/> In response, Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] stated that Russia will analyze the JIT conclusion, but will acknowledge it only if it becomes a party in the investigation.<ref name=\"kommersant\">{{cite web | url = https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/3638260|title=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u043f\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0449\u0430\u043b \u0438\u0437\u0443\u0447\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0432\u044b\u0432\u043e\u0434\u044b \u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0438\u044f \u043e \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0435 Boeing MH17|work=[[Kommersant]]| language=Russian|date=24 May 2018| accessdate =24 May 2018}}</ref> The [[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Russian Ministry of Defence]] in turn stated that no Russian Buk crossed the border with Ukraine.<ref name=\"kommersant\"/>\n\nOn 25 May 2018 the governments of the Netherlands and Australia issued a joint statement in which they laid responsibility on Russia \"for its part\" in the crash.<ref name=\":1\" /> The Netherlands and Australian foreign ministers stated that they would hold Russia legally responsible for shooting the airliner down. Netherlands Foreign Minister [[Stef Blok]] stated that \"the government is now taking the next step by formally holding Russia accountable,\" and, \"The Netherlands and Australia today asked Russia to enter into talks aimed at finding a solution that would do justice to the tremendous suffering and damage caused by the downing of MH17. A possible next step is to present the case to an international court or organization for their judgment.\"<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/netherlands-australia-flight17-statement-russia-1.4677473|title = Netherlands, Australia holding Russia 'accountable' for downing of MH17|access-date = 25 May 2018|author=[[The Associated Press]] |work = [[CBC News]]|date = 25 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeveral other countries and international organisations expressed their support for the JIT's conclusions and the joint statement by the Netherlands and Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2233506-internationale-reacties-op-mh17-rusland-moet-verantwoordelijkheid-nemen.html |title=Internationale reacties op MH17: Rusland moet verantwoordelijkheid nemen |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]] |date=25 May 2018 |language=Dutch}}</ref> UK Foreign Secretary [[Boris Johnson]] said the United Kingdom \"fully supports Australia and the Netherlands,\" calling on Russia to cooperate.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/foreign-secretary-statement-on-the-mh17-investigation |title=Foreign Secretary statement on the MH17 investigation |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[Foreign & Commonwealth Office]] |date=25 May 2018}}</ref> High Representative [[Federica Mogherini]] of the EU stated that the European Union \"calls on the Russian Federation to accept its responsibility\" and to cooperate as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2018/05/25/declaration-by-the-high-representative-on-behalf-of-the-eu-on-the-findings-of-the-joint-investigation-team-on-the-downing-of-flight-mh17/ |title=Declaration by the High Representative on behalf of the EU on the findings of the Joint Investigation Team on the downing of flight MH17 |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[European Council]] |date=25 May 2018}}</ref> The German government called on Russia to \"fully explain the tragedy.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bundesregierung.de/Content/DE/Artikel/2018/05/2018-05-25-ukraine-mh17-gutachten.html |title=Die Schuldigen ermitteln |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[Bundesregierung]] |date=25 May 2018 |language=German}}</ref> The US Department of State issued a statement saying that the United States \"strongly support the decisions by the Netherlands and Australia,\" requesting Russia to acknowledge its involvement and to \"cease its callous disinformation campaign.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2018/05/282502.htm |title=Calling Russia To Account for Malaysia Airlines Flight MH-17 |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[United States Department of State]] |date=25 May 2018}}</ref> NATO Secretary General [[Jens Stoltenberg]] called on Russia to \"accept responsibility and fully cooperate ... in line with [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 2166]].\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_154585.htm |title=Statement by the NATO Secretary General on MH17 investigation |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[NATO]] |date=25 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the JIT's conclusions, Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] reiterated that the Russians are \"not involved in it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/57556 |title=St Petersburg International Economic Forum plenary session |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[Kremlin]] |date=25 May 2018}}</ref> Following release of the JIT report, Malaysian Prime Minister [[Mahathir Mohamad|Mahathir]] said the JIT was making Russia a \"scapegoat\" and that he did not believe the Russians whom the JIT had charged were involved. Conversely the Malaysian prosecutor supported the investigation by saying the findings \"are based on extensive investigations and also legal research\".<ref name=\"reuters_20-06-2019\">{{cite news |last1=Sipalan |first1=Joseph |title=Malaysian PM says Russia being made a scapegoat for downing of flight MH17 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-ukraine-crisis-mh17-malaysia/malaysian-pm-says-russia-being-made-a-scapegoat-for-downing-of-flight-mh17-idUSKCN1TL0OW |accessdate=5 July 2019 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Proposed international tribunal====\nIn June 2015, the Netherlands, supported by the other JIT members, sought to create an international tribunal to prosecute those suspected of downing the Malaysian airliner, which would take up the case after the closing of the criminal investigation. The Dutch hoped that an international tribunal would induce Russian cooperation, which was considered critical.<ref>{{cite news |title=Exclusive: International tribunal looks like best chance for MH17 justice \u2013 Dutch sources |agency=Reuters |date=23 June 2015 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/06/23/us-ukraine-crisis-mh-idUSKBN0P326E20150623 |first=Anthony |last=Deutsch |accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> In late June 2015, the Russian government rejected a request by the five countries on the investigative committee to form a UN tribunal which would try those responsible for the shooting down of the aircraft, calling it \"not timely and counterproductive.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jun/26/russia-rejects-calls-for-un-tribunal-malaysia-airlines-flight-mh17 |title=Russia rejects calls for UN tribunal to prosecute MH17 suspects |work=The Guardian |agency=Agence France-Presse |accessdate=28 June 2015 |date=26 June 2015}}</ref> On 8 July 2015, Malaysia, a member of the [[UN Security Council]], distributed a draft resolution to establish such a tribunal. This resolution was jointly proposed by the five JIT member countries. Russian UN Ambassador [[Vitaly Churkin]] responded, \"I don't see any future for this resolution. Unfortunately, it seems that this is an attempt to organize a grandiose, political show, which only damages efforts to find the guilty parties.\"<ref name=churkin>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/malaysia-airlines-mh17-russia-rebukes-push-for-un-tribunal-1.3146029 |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17: Russia rebukes push for UN tribunal |date=10 July 2015 |publisher=[[CBC News]] |accessdate=10 July 2015}}</ref> Russia later circulated a rival resolution which criticised the international investigation's lack of \"due transparency\" and demanded those responsible be brought to justice, but which did not call for a tribunal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Russia's UN Draft on MH17 Crash Doesn't Call for Tribunal |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/russias-draft-mh17-crash-call-tribunal-32575088 |agency=Associated Press |date=20 July 2015 |author=Edith M. Lederer |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722201823/http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/russias-draft-mh17-crash-call-tribunal-32575088 |archivedate=22 July 2015 }}</ref> In a vote, Malaysia's resolution gained majority support of the UNSC, but was [[United Nations Security Council veto power|vetoed]] by Russia.<ref name=veto>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/07/29/us-ukraine-crisis-mh17-un-idUSKCN0Q32GS20150729 |title=Russia vetoes bid to set up tribunal for downed Flight MH17 |author=Michelle Nichols |agency=Reuters |date=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Criminal prosecution====\nIn a statement made on 5 July 2017 by the Dutch Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Bert Koenders]], it was announced that the JIT countries would prosecute any suspects identified in the downing of flight MH17 in the Netherlands and under Dutch law.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.government.nl/latest/news/2017/07/05/statement-by-the-minister-of-foreign-affairs-on-mh17-5-july-2017 |title=Statement by the minister of Foreign Affairs on MH17, 5 July 2017 |work=Government of the Kingdom of the Netherlands |agency=Ministry of Foreign Affairs |date= 7 July 2017}}</ref> A treaty between the Netherlands and Ukraine made it possible for the Netherlands to prosecute in the cases of all 298 victims, regardless of their nationality. This treaty was signed on 7 July 2017,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.government.nl/topics/mh17-incident/news/2017/07/07/minister-of-security-and-justice-signs-mh17-treaty-with-ukraine |title=Minister of Security and Justice signs MH17 treaty with Ukraine |work=Government of the Kingdom of the Netherlands |agency=Ministry of Security and Justice |date= 7 July 2017}}</ref> and went into force on 28 August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zoek.officielebekendmakingen.nl/trb-2018-162.HTML|title=Verdrag tussen het Koninkrijk der Nederlanden en Oekra\u00efne inzake internationale juridische samenwerking met betrekking tot misdrijven die verband houden met het neerhalen van vlucht MH17 van Malaysia Airlines op 17 juli 2014|date=7 September 2018|website=Tractatenblad van het Koninkrijk der Nederlanden}}</ref> On 21 March 2018, the Dutch government sent legislation to the parliament, allowing the suspects involved to be prosecuted in the Netherlands under [[Law of the Netherlands|Dutch law]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-21/legislation-clears-way-for-mh17-trials-in-the-netherlands|title=Legislation Clears Way for MH17 Trials in the Netherlands|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=21 March 2018|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=22 March 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.unian.info/world/10052111-dutch-court-may-be-allowed-to-prosecute-those-involved-in-mh17-crash-by-video-link.html|title=Dutch court may be allowed to prosecute those involved in MH17 crash by video link|agency=[[Ukrainian Independent Information Agency|UNIAN]]|access-date=13 April 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nA joint investigation between Bellingcat, ''The Insider'' and McClatchy DC Bureau identified another person of interest to the investigation. The person known as 'Andrey Ivanovich', or by the call sign 'Orion', according to Bellingcat, is a Russian [[GRU (G.U.)|GRU]] officer named Oleg Vladimirovich Ivannikov.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2018/05/25/mh17-russian-gru-commander-orion-identified-oleg-ivannikov/|title=MH17 - Russian GRU Commander 'Orion' Identified as Oleg Ivannikov|date=25 May 2018|website=bellingcat|accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref> Ivannikov has a distinct, high-pitched voice. The Kremlin denied this allegation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/europe/how-an-online-purchase-helped-find-the-russian-blamed-for-downing-mh17-20180526-p4zho2.html|title=How an online purchase helped find the Russian blamed for downing MH17|first=Kevin|last=Hall|date=26 May 2018|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 June 2019, the [[Dutch Public Prosecution Service]] charged four people with murder in connection with the shooting down of the aircraft: three Russians, [[Igor Strelkov (officer)|Igor Girkin]], Sergey Dubinsky, and Oleg Pulatov, and one Ukrainian, Leonid Kharchenko. International arrest warrants were issued in respect of each of the accused.<ref name=\"BBC48691488\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-48691488|title=Four charged with shooting down MH17 plane|work=BBC News Online|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> Their [[trial in absentia]] is scheduled to be held on 9 March 2020 in the District Court of [[The Hague]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.om.nl/onderwerpen/mh17-crash/@106096/prosecution-four/|title=Prosecution of four suspects for downing flight MH17|date=19 June 2019|publisher=[[Openbaar Ministerie]]|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019 SBU arrested Vladimir Tsemakh, head of air-defence in DPR-controlled Snizhne during the attack on MH17. [[Bellingcat]] described him as an important eye-witness to the events surrounding the downing of flight MH17. Bellingcat analysed his possible role and said that a video showed Tsemakh making \"what appears to be a damning admission to his personal involvement in hiding the Buk missile launcher in the aftermath of its use on 17 July 2014\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2019/07/09/the-arrest-of-vladimir-tsemakh-and-its-implications-for-the-mh17-investigation/|title=The Arrest of Vladimir Tsemakh and Its Implications for the MH17 Investigation|date=9 July 2019|website=bellingcat|language=en-GB|access-date=31 August 2019}}</ref> In August 2019 Russia reportedly added Tsemakh to its list in a previously agreed exchange of prisoners of war with Ukraine. In an article, ''The Insider'' website commented on Russia's motives in requesting the exchange of a Ukrainian citizen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theins.ru/politika/173069|title=\u041a\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043b\u044c \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043b \"\u0441\u0432\u043e\u0438\u043c\" \u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f \"\u0411\u0443\u043a\u0430\" \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043c\u0430\u0445\u0430 \u0438 \u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0443\u0435\u0442 \u043e\u0431\u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c \u0435\u0433\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u0421\u0435\u043d\u0446\u043e\u0432\u0430|date=30 August 2019|website=The Insider|language=ru-RU|access-date=31 August 2019}}</ref> On 4 September 2019, an appeals court in Kiev ruled to release Tsemakh.<ref name=MoscowTimes20190907>{{cite news|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2019/09/07/signaling-readiness-for-thaw-russia-and-ukraine-swap-prisoners-a67090|title=Signaling Readiness for Thaw, Russia and Ukraine Swap Prisoners: The exchange brings peace talks between the neighboring countries closer, analysts say.|newspaper=[[The Moscow Times]]|last=Gershkovich|first=Evan|date=7 September 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref> On 7 September 2019, Volodymyr Tsemakh was released during a Ukraine-Russia prisoner exchange.<ref name=CNN20190907>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/07/europe/ukraine-russia-prisoner-swap-intl/index.html|title=Film director Oleg Sentsov and MH17 suspect among those freed in Russia-Ukraine prisoner swap|work=[[CNN]]|last1=Lapin|first1=Denis|last2=Pavlova|first2=Olga|last3=Britton|first3=Bianca|last4=Dean|first4=Sarah|date=7 September 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref> According to the [[List of Ministers of Foreign Affairs of the Netherlands|Dutch Foreign Minister]] [[Stef Blok]], the exchange had been delayed for a week so that Vladimir Tsemakh could be questioned by the Dutch Public Prosecution Service as a witness about the events surrounding the downing of flight MH17.<ref name=CNN20190907/> The [[Dutch Prime Minister]] [[Mark Rutte]], the [[List of Ministers of Justice of the Netherlands|Minister of Justice and Security]] [[Ferdinand Grapperhaus|Ferd Grapperhaus]], the JIT, and Blok added that the Netherlands regretted Tsemakh, who is a 'person of interest', being included in the exchange due to pressure on Ukraine from Russia.<ref name=MoscowTimes20190907/><ref name=CNN20190907/><ref>{{cite news| last1=Olearchyk| first1=Roman | last2=Foy| first2=Henry| url=https://www.ft.com/content/1cf7478e-cfbf-11e9-99a4-b5ded7a7fe3f| title=Ukraine court releases man of interest to MH17 probe on bail: Move raises speculation he could be part of imminent prisoner swap between Kiev and Moscow| work=[[Financial Times]]| date=5 September 2019| access-date=13 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=AD20190907>{{cite news| url=https://www.ad.nl/buitenland/nederland-vraagt-rusland-om-mh17-verdachte~a953df4d/| title=Nederland vraagt Rusland om MH17-verdachte: Het Openbaar Ministerie heeft Rusland gevraagd MH17-verdachte Vladimir Tsemach uit te leveren. Dat liet het OM de nabestaanden van de vliegramp vanmiddag weten. Nederland betreurt zeer dat Oekra\u00efne de Oekra\u00efense separatist \u00fcberhaupt aan Rusland heeft overgedragen| trans-title=The Netherlands asks Russia for MH17 suspect: The Public Prosecution Service has asked Russia to extradite MH17 suspect Vladimir Tsemach. The OM informed the relatives of the plane crash this afternoon. The Netherlands deeply regrets that Ukraine has handed over the Ukrainian separatist to Russia at all.| work=[[Algemeen Dagblad|AD.nl]]| language=Dutch| date=7 September 2019| access-date=13 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Dutch did question MH17 witness before he was returned to Russia: minister |url=https://www.dutchnews.nl/news/2019/09/dutch-did-question-mh17-witness-before-he-was-returned-to-russia-minister/ |accessdate=9 September 2019 |work=DutcNews.nl |date=8 September 2019}}</ref> Others including Chairman Piet Ploeg of Stichting Vliegramp MH17 which is the organization of the victims' relatives called the release of Tsemach \"unacceptable\".<ref name=AD20190907/> The Dutch Public Prosecution Service (OM) requested that Tsemach, who is not a Russian citizen, be extradited from Russia to the Netherlands.<ref name=AD20190907/> On 14 November 2019 the JIT published a new witnesses appeal and simultaneously released a number of recorded conversations of rebel leaders. JIT was particularly interested in \"the command structure and the role that Russian government officials may have played.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=MH17 Witness Appeal November 2019 |url=https://www.politie.nl/themas/flight-mh17/witness-appeal-crash-mh17.html |website=politie.nl |accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=MH17 disaster: Phone-taps 'show Russia directed Ukraine rebels' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-50419669 |accessdate=15 November 2019 |work=BBC News |date=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Dutch Prosecution formally charged four suspects and summoned them for investigation. One of them, Lieutenant Colonel Oleg Pulatov, expressed his intention to join the legal process by being represented in court. The trial began on 9 March 2020, with none of the accused in attendance.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-polytics/2868589-netherlands-public-prosecution-service-brings-charges-against-four-suspects-in-mh17-case.html|title=Netherlands Public Prosecution Service brings charges against four suspects in MH17 case|accessdate=4 February 2020 |work=Ukrinform |date=3 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-polytics/2863987-one-of-suspects-in-mh17-case-wants-to-join-legal-proceedings.html |title =One of suspects in MH17 case wants to join legal proceedings|accessdate=4 February 2020 |work=Ukrinform |date=4 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=MH17 trial starts with four accused facing murder charges |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/mh17-trial-start-accused-facing-murder-charges-200309000652546.html |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Al Jazeera |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==British ISC report==\nOn 20 December 2017, the [[Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament|Intelligence and Security Committee]] of the UK Parliament published its annual report. It contains a short section entitled \"Russian objectives and activity against UK and allied interests\" which quotes MI6 as stating: \"Russia conducts information warfare on a massive scale... An early example of this was a hugely intensive, multichannel propaganda effort to persuade the world that Russia bore no responsibility for the shooting down of [Malaysian Airlines flight] MH-17 (an outright falsehood: we know beyond any reasonable doubt that the Russian military supplied and subsequently recovered the missile launcher)\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Toler|first1=Aric|title=British Intelligence Report Confirms Russian Military Origin of MH17 Murder Weapon|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2017/12/20/british-intelligence-report-confirms-russian-military-origin-mh17-murder-weapon/|website=Bellingcat|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=ISCP Annual Report 2016-2017|url=https://b1cba9b3-a-5e6631fd-s-sites.googlegroups.com/a/independent.gov.uk/isc/files/2016-2017_ISC_AR.pdf?attachauth=ANoY7cqS8WVJqzXucCjkPcD1PkT4M4RJspBV9tHBYEJAZLobTFw2rG67hpLh55zoZsZ9_9Xrmtqiq4CzbwmhAUpzCTh3AW-lBjOdmWFYJds1-EYzBgJGRmPWubVpg_Yl0SrMUrYTcKGn-8HtPvf5AARiu60msxtT2SpjJfdv78EEeqkINZBUythVem1KHFtKbbziZLQNdiiOymaCinv1pUa1FIpSVaHOkjNwmyfFteiMvnTRX00Qz_0%3D&attredirects=0}}</ref>\n\n==Civil cases==\nIn July 2015 a writ was filed in an American court by families of 18 victims accusing the separatist leader Igor Girkin of \"orchestrating the shootdown\" and the Russian government of being complicit in the act. The writ was brought under the [[Torture Victim Protection Act of 1991]].<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/11742865/MH-17-Russian-separatist-leader-sued-for-900-million-by-crash-victims.html]. MH-17-Russian-separatist-leader-sued-for-900-million-by-crash-victims</ref> In May 2016 families of 33 victims of the crash filed a claim against Russia and president Vladimir Putin in the [[European Court of Human Rights]], arguing Russian actions violated the passengers' right to life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-36350520|title=MH17 crash: Victims' families sue Putin and Russia|website=BBC News|access-date=22 May 2016}}</ref><ref>Blakkarly, Jarni (22 May 2016). [http://in.reuters.com/article/australia-mh-idINL3N18J00O UPDATE 1-Australian firm names Russia, Putin in MH17 compensation claim -report.] ''Reuters.'' Retrieved: 22 May 2016.</ref> A group of 270 relatives of Dutch victims joined the claim in May 2018 after the JIT concluded that Russia was involved.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2233480-nabestaanden-mh17-naar-europees-hof-voor-schadeclaim-tegen-rusland.html|title=Nabestaanden MH17 naar Europees Hof voor schadeclaim tegen Rusland|work=NOS|access-date=30 May 2018|date=25 May 2018|language=Dutch}}</ref> In July 2016, Malaysia Airlines was sued in Malaysia by 15 passengers' families in two separate writs, each brought under the [[Montreal Convention]], arguing that the airline should not have chosen that route.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/mh17-kin-sue-malaysia-airlines-seek-damages-ahead-of-lawsuit-deadline|title=MH17 kin sue Malaysia Airlines, seek damages ahead of lawsuit deadline|author=Yap Tzu Ging|date=15 July 2016|newspaper=Malay Mail Online}}</ref> A month earlier, a separate lawsuit was brought by the families of 6 crew members who alleged negligence and breach of contract by the airline.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/missing-malaysia-plane-crew-lawsuit-1.3612177|title=Malaysia Airlines sued by relatives of MH17 crew shot down over Ukraine|agency=The Associated Press|date=2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n{{main|International reactions to the Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 shootdown}}\n<!--PLEASE DON'T ADD ANY PICTURES OF WORLD LEADERS IN THIS SECTION A/P TALK PAGE DISCUSSION AND ARCHIVES-->\n<!-- Please don't add \"condolences\" per WP:MEMORIAL. Please don't add tiny flags or bullet points; consensus is that it is better as prose. Thanks. -->\n\n===Countries===\nUkrainian President [[Petro Poroshenko]] called the crash the result of an act of terrorism, and also called for an international investigation into the crash.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10974784/Malaysia-Airlines-crash-President-Poroshenko-calls-shooting-down-of-Malaysian-plane-an-act-of-terrorism.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |title=Malaysia Airlines crash: President Poroshenko calls shooting down of Malaysian plane an 'act of terrorism' |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nMalaysian Deputy Foreign Minister [[Hamzah Zainuddin]] said that the foreign ministry would be working with the Russian and Ukrainian governments with regard to the incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.cri.cn/12394/2014/07/18/2941s836537.htm |title=Malaysia to Work with Russia, Ukrainian Governments on MH17 |publisher=English.cri.cn |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Najib Razak]] said that Malaysia was unable yet to verify the cause of the crash but that, if the airplane was shot down, the perpetrators should be swiftly punished.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.voanews.com/east-asia/malaysian-pm-demands-swift-justice-if-plane-was-shot-down |title=Malaysian PM Demands Swift Justice if Plane Was Shot Down |publisher=[[Voice of America]] |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref> The [[Government of Malaysia|Malaysian government]] flew the [[Flag of Malaysia|national flag]] at [[half-mast]] from 18 July until 21 July.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stasiareport.com/news/asia/south-east-asia/story/malaysia-airlines-mh17-crash-flags-fly-half-mast-over-next-three-day |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17 crash: Flags to fly at half-mast over next three days, says Najib |author=Yong Yen Nie |publisher=Straits Times Asia Report |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Nederlandse vlag halfstok voor stadhuis Hoorn.jpg|thumb|upright|Flag at half mast in front of [[Hoorn]] city hall during the national day of mourning on 23 July]]\n\nDutch Prime Minister [[Mark Rutte]] and King [[Willem-Alexander]] voiced their shock at the crash,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/binnenland/22867019/__Verklaring_Rutte_over_MH17__.html |title=Verklaring premier Rutte over crash MH17 &#124; Binnenland |language=Dutch |work=De Telegraaf |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://dc.the-netherlands.org/news/2014/07/statement-king-willem-alexander.html |title=Statement of His Majesty King Willem-Alexander on Malaysian Flight MH17 |work=Kingdom of the Netherlands |publisher=The Netherlands Embassy in Washington, D.C., United States |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718002846/http://dc.the-netherlands.org/news/2014/07/statement-king-willem-alexander.html |archive-date=18 July 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Frans Timmermans]] joined the Dutch investigation team sent to Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/2668/Buitenland/article/detail/3691806/2014/07/18/Timmermans-mee-met-onderzoekers-naar-Oekraine.dhtml |title=Timmermans mee met onderzoekers naar Oekra\u00efne |language=Dutch |work=ANP |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> Dutch government buildings flew the flag at half-mast on 18 July.<ref name=\"nieuws.nl\">{{cite web |url=http://nieuws.nl/algemeen/20140717/vlaggen-overheidsgebouwen-halfstok-na-vliegramp/ |title=Vlaggen overheidsgebouwen halfstok na vliegramp |language=Dutch |author=Novum |publisher=Nieuws.nl |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726214011/http://www.nieuws.nl/algemeen/20140717/Vlaggen-overheidsgebouwen-halfstok-na-vliegramp |archive-date=26 July 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Music was cancelled and festivities were toned down on the last day of the [[Nijmegen Marches]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nieuws.nl/algemeen/20140718/vierdaagse-nijmegen-muziek-geschrapt-wegens-vliegramp/ |title=Vierdaagse Nijmegen: muziek geschrapt wegens vliegramp |language=Dutch |author=Novum |publisher=nieuws.nl |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402114956/http://nieuws.nl/algemeen/20140718/vierdaagse-nijmegen-muziek-geschrapt-wegens-vliegramp/ |archive-date=2 April 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref> On 21 July the Netherlands opened a war crimes investigation on the downing of the aircraft and a Netherlands public prosecutor went to Ukraine as part of this investigation. Rutte threatened tough action against Russia if it did not help in the investigation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/netherlands-opens-investigation-airliner-shoot-down-131650202.html |title=Netherlands opens war crimes investigation into airliner downing |author1=Thomas Escritt |author2=Angus MacSwan |date=21 July 2014 |website=[[Yahoo! News]]}}</ref> On the same day, Timmermans spoke at the UN Security Council Meeting, after the Council had unanimously condemned the shooting down of MH17.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2014/07/22/terugluisteren-en-lezen-de-bewogen-speech-van-timmermans-a1423587|title=Terugluisteren en -lezen: de indrukwekkende speech van Timmermans |author=Marije Willems |date=22 July 2014 |website=[[NRC Handelsblad|NRC]]}}</ref> An increase in negative emotions and somatic complaints was observed in the Dutch population during the first four days after the MH17 crash.<ref>{{Cite journal |author= Jeronimus|display-authors=etal| year = 2018 | title = Acute stress responses after indirect exposure to the MH17 airplane crash| journal = British Journal of Psychology| volume = 0 | pages = 1\u201324 | doi=10.1111/bjop.12358}}</ref>\n\nAustralian Prime Minister [[Tony Abbott]] said in an address to parliament that the aircraft was downed by a missile which seemed to have been launched by Russian-backed rebels.<ref name=DT>{{cite news |last1=Maiden |first1=Samantha |title=MH17: Russia says Tony Abbott 'operating only on speculation' in his tough stance over separatist involvement in plane tragedy |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/mh17-russia-says-tony-abbott-operating-only-on-speculation-in-his-tough-stance-over-separatist-involvement-in-plane-tragedy/story-fni0cx12-1226994356506 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=Australia |date=19 July 2014}}</ref> [[Julie Bishop]], the Australian Minister for Foreign Affairs, said in an interview on an Australian television programme that it was \"extraordinary\" that her Russian counterparts had refused to speak to her over the shootdown after the Russian ambassador was summoned to meet her.<ref name=DT/> The Russian government was critical of Abbott's response; Abbott was one of the first world leaders to publicly connect the shootdown to Russia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-07-19/russia-says-abbott-comments-mh17-downing-unacceptable/5608852?pfm=ms |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17: Russia says Tony Abbott's comments blaming separatists are 'unacceptable', Julie Bishop criticises Moscow for lack of talks \u2013 ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> Abbott later criticised the recovery efforts as \"shambolic\", and \"more like a garden clean-up than a forensic investigation\"; Bishop publicly warned separatist forces against treating the victims' bodies as hostages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-07-21/government-considers-declaring-mh17-disaster-a-terrorist-act/5610908?pfm=ms |title=MH17: Prime Minister Tony Abbott hits out at 'shambolic' recovery effort; Government considers listing outrage as terrorist act; rebels move bodies to refrigerated train \u2013 ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> Abbott also said in an interview on 13 October 2014, in anticipation of Russia's President [[Vladimir Putin]]'s attendance at the [[2014 G20 Brisbane summit|2014 G20 summit]], scheduled for mid-November 2014 in [[Brisbane]], Australia: \"Australians were murdered. They were murdered by Russian-backed rebels using Russian-supplied equipment. We are very unhappy about this.\"<ref>{{cite news |author1=Sabra Lane |title=Tony Abbott promises to 'shirtfront' Putin at G20 Summit |url=http://www.abc.net.au/7.30/content/2014/s4106143.htm |accessdate=14 October 2014 |work=7:30 |date=13 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nRussian President Putin said that Ukraine bore responsibility for the incident which happened in its territory, which he said would not have happened if hostilities had not resumed in the south-east of Ukraine.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://ria.ru/society/20140718/1016472533.html|script-title=ru:\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d: \u0437\u0430 \u0430\u0432\u0438\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0443 \u043d\u0435\u0441\u0435\u0442 \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0430 |trans-title=Putin: Ukraine responsible for the crash |language=Russian |date=18 July 2014 |agency=RIA Novosti |quote=\"\u0411\u0435\u0437\u0443\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e, \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e, \u043d\u0430\u0434 \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0435\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043e \u044d\u0442\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u043e\u0448\u043b\u043e, \u043d\u0435\u0441\u0435\u0442 \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0437\u0430 \u044d\u0442\u0443 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0448\u043d\u0443\u044e \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0433\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044e\", \u2013 \u0441\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u0420\u0424 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"biden\">{{cite news |url=https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/biden-malaysia-airlines-crash |publisher=MSNBC |title=Joe Biden: Malaysia Airlines flight 'apparently' shot down |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> He also said that it was important to refrain from reaching hasty conclusions and politicised statements before the end of the investigation. He said that Russia would help an international inquiry led by the ICAO.<ref name=RT-live>{{cite news |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17 plane crash in Ukraine LIVE UPDATES |url=http://rt.com/news/173628-malaysian-plane-crash-ukraine/ |accessdate=21 July 2014 |publisher=RT |date=17 July 2014}}</ref> At the end of July a [[Duma]] deputy [[Ilya Ponomarev]] said in an interview for ''[[Die Welt]]'' that the separatists had shot down the airplane by mistake and that Putin now realised he had supplied the weapon to the \"wrong people\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.welt.de/politik/ausland/article130579514/Putin-realisiert-dass-er-die-Falschen-bewaffnete.html |title=Putin realisiert, dass er die Falschen bewaffnete |work=Die Welt |language=German |date=26 July 2014 |accessdate=1 August 2014 |author=Silke M\u00fclherr und Inga Pylypchuk}}</ref> The [[Danish Institute for International Studies]] has pointed out to the similarities of Russian reaction to the downing of [[Korean Air Lines Flight 007|Korean Airlines flight KAL-007]] in 1983 where the USSR initially denied any involvement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pure.diis.dk/ws/files/950041/DIIS_RP_2017_6_web.pdf|title=Russian Hybrid Warfare|website=Danish Institute for International Studies|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824221700/http://pure.diis.dk/ws/files/950041/DIIS_RP_2017_6_web.pdf|archive-date=24 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nUnited States President [[Barack Obama]] said the United States would help determine the cause.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/> In a press statement, White House spokesman [[Josh Earnest]] called for an immediate ceasefire in Ukraine to allow for a full investigation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mason |first1=Jeff |last2=Holland |first2=Steve |title=White House urges Ukraine ceasefire for plane probe, Obama talks to Putin |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/18/us-ukraine-crisis-obama-idUSKBN0FN0D420140718 |accessdate=18 July 2014 |agency=Reuters |date=18 July 2014}}</ref> Vice-President [[Joe Biden]] said the airplane appeared to have been deliberately shot down, and offered American assistance for the investigation into the crash.<ref name=\"biden\"/> [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations|American&nbsp;Ambassador to the United Nations]] [[Samantha Power]] called on Russia to end the war.<ref name=nytimes1>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/19/world/europe/malaysia-airlines-plane-ukraine.html |title=Obama Points to Pro-Russia Separatists in Downing of Malaysia Airlines Plane |first=Michael D. |last=Shear |first2=Somini |last2=Sengupta |first3=Sabrina |last3=Tavernise |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> The British government requested an emergency meeting of the [[United Nations Security Council]] and called an emergency [[Cabinet Office Briefing Room|Cobra]] meeting after the incident.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leonard |first1=Peter |title=Ukraine: 295 on Malaysia plane shot down over east |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/official-malaysian-plane-shot-down-over-ukraine |work=Associated Press |publisher=The Big Story |accessdate=17 July 2014 |ref=APBigStory |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717190514/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/official-malaysian-plane-shot-down-over-ukraine |archivedate=17 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10975874/MH17-plane-crash-David-Cameron-urges-those-responsible-for-downing-jet-to-be-held-to-account.html |title=MH17 plane crash: David Cameron urges those responsible for downing jet to be 'held to account' |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> Chairman of the US [[Joint Chiefs of Staff]] [[Martin E. Dempsey]] said that instead of backing away from supporting the rebels in the wake of the airliner shootdown, Putin had \"taken a decision to escalate.\"<ref>David M. Herszenhorn (25 July 2014), [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/26/world/europe/russian-artillery-fires-into-ukraine-kiev-says.html ''Russia Steps Up Help for Rebels in Ukraine War,''] ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\n[[File:Nationaal Monument MH17.jpg|thumb|Memorial for the victims of Flight MH17 located in [[Vijfhuizen]], the Netherlands]]\n\nOn 17 July 2017, exactly three years after the crash, a [[memorial]] in memory of the victims was unveiled in [[Vijfhuizen]], the Netherlands. The opening of the memorial, which is located just outside Schiphol Airport, was attended by more than 2000 relatives of victims, King Willem-Alexander and his wife [[Queen M\u00e1xima of the Netherlands|Queen M\u00e1xima]], Dutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte, Minister of Security and Justice [[Stef Blok]] and the speakers of the Dutch Senate and House of Representatives. The memorial includes 298 trees, one tree for each victim.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2183659-onthulling-nationaal-monument-mh17-deze-dag-sloeg-een-gat-in-ons-leven.html |title=Onthulling Nationaal Monument MH17: 'Deze dag sloeg een gat in ons leven' |access-date=17 July 2019 |work=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]] |date=17 July 2017 |language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\n===Organisations===\nOn 17 July the European Union's representatives [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso]] and [[Herman Van Rompuy]] released a joint statement calling for an immediate and thorough investigation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_STATEMENT-14-231_en.htm?locale=en |title=EUROPA PRESS RELEASES \u2013 Press release \u2013 Joint statement by the President of the European Commission, Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso, and the President of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy, on the crash of the Malaysian airliner in Ukraine |publisher=Europa (web portal) |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> The EU officials also said that Ukraine has first claim on the aircraft's black boxes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/malaysian-plane-mh17-crash-investigators-face-struggle/1/373127.html |title=Malaysian plane MH17 crash investigators face struggle : Asia, News |work=India Today |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[International Civil Aviation Organization]] announced, on 18 July, that it was sending its team of experts to assist the [[National Bureau of Air Accidents Investigation of Ukraine]] (NBAAI), under Article 26 of the [[Convention on International Civil Aviation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.icao.int/Newsroom/Pages/Ukraine-requests-ICAO-assistance-in-MH17-accident-investigation.aspx |title=Ukraine Requests ICAO Assistance in MH17 Accident Investigation |publisher=ICAO |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref> The [[United Nations Security Council]] adopted [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 2166|Resolution 2166]] on 21 July, regarding an official crime investigation into the incident. On 24 July 2014 the ICAO issued a State Letter reminding signatory states of their responsibilities with respect to the safety and security of civil aircraft operating in airspace affected by conflict.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.icao.int/Newsroom/Pages/ICAO-clarifies-State-responsibilities-arising-from-conflict-zones.aspx |title=ICAO Clarifies State Responsibilities Arising from Conflict Zones |publisher=ICAO |date=24 July 2014 |accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Amsterdam Airport- Flight MH17 Memorial (14675744526).jpg|thumb|A makeshift memorial at [[Schiphol Airport]] for the victims of Flight MH17]]\nAfter the crash, memorial services were held in Australia<ref name=\"itv-memorial\">{{cite news |url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2014-07-20/memorial-service-held-for-mh17-victims-in-australia/ |title=Australia mourns MH17 victims at memorial service |work=ITV News |date=20 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> and in the Netherlands, which declared 23 July, the day when the first victims arrived in the country, a [[national day of mourning]], the first since 1962.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nu.nl/binnenland/3834822/woensdag-23-juli-dag-van-nationale-rouw.html |title=Woensdag 23 juli dag van nationale rouw &#124; nu.nl/binnenland &#124; Het laatste nieuws het eerst op |publisher=Nu.nl |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ibt-mourning\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/netherlands-declares-national-day-mourning-mh17-victims-1457454 |title=Malaysian Airlines Flight MH17: Netherlands Declares National Day of Mourning For MH17 Victims |work=International Business Times |date=20 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> The opening ceremony of the AIDS 2014 conference, on 20 July, of which several delegates had been on board Flight MH17, began with a tribute to the victims of the crash.<ref name=\"starobserver\">{{cite news |url=http://www.starobserver.com.au/news/local-news/aids-2014-opening-ceremony-tinged-with-sombre-mood/125442 |title=AIDS 2014 opening ceremony tinged with sombre mood |first=Elias |last=Jahshan |work=Star Observer |date=20 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> In Malaysia, makeshift memorials were created in the capital city of [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref name=\"bbc memorials\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-28397889 |title=MH17 crash: Malaysians mourn at makeshift memorials |work=BBC News |first=Sharanjit |last=Leyl |date=21 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Russian media coverage==\n{{See also|Media portrayal of the Ukrainian crisis}}\nIn July 2014, shortly after the crash, the liberal Russian opposition newspaper ''[[Novaya Gazeta]]'' published a headline in Dutch that read \"Vergeef ons, Nederland\" (\"Forgive Us, Netherlands\").<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/world/russian-newspaper-novaya-gazeta-prints-frontpage-apology-for-mh17-disaster-in-dutch/story-fndir2ev-1227001958997|title=Russian newspaper Novaya Gazeta prints front-page apology for MH17 disaster in Dutch|date=25 July 2014|accessdate=25 July 2014|work=News.com.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2014/07/25/russian_paper_issues_front_page_apology_to_netherlands_for_mh17|title=Russian Paper Issues Front Page Apology to Netherlands for MH17|last1=Groll|first1=Elias|date=25 July 2014|website=Foreign Policy|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nCoverage by official media and bodies has however differed from coverage in most other countries and significantly changed over time<ref>{{cite news |title=Russia offers alternate scenarios for Malaysia Airlines crash |url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2014/07/22/Russia-offers-alternate-scenarios-for-Malaysia-Airlines-crash/2701406045751/ |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=2 November 2014 |first=Ed |last=Adamczyk |agency=United Press International |quote=Russian media offers explanations conflicting with the information provided by the rest of the world.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ioffe |first1=Julia |title=The Russian Public Has a Totally Different Understanding of What Happened to Malaysia Airlines Flight 17: And it's more of a problem than you think |url=https://newrepublic.com/node/118782 |accessdate=21 July 2014 |work=New Republic |date=20 July 2014 |quote=The picture of the catastrophe that the Russian people are seeing on their television screens is very different from that on screens in much of the rest of the world, and the discrepancy does not bode well for a sane resolution to this stand-off |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140721015346/http://www.newrepublic.com/node/118782 |archive-date=21 July 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> usually in response to new evidence published by DSB and the investigation team.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2018/01/05/kremlins-shifting-self-contradicting-narratives-mh17/|title=The Kremlin's Shifting, Self-Contradicting Narratives on MH17 - bellingcat|date=5 January 2018|work=bellingcat|access-date=5 January 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the poll conducted by the [[Levada Center]] between 18 and 24 July in 2014, 80% of Russians surveyed believed that the crash of MH17 was caused by the Ukrainian military. Only 3% of respondents to the poll blamed the disaster on pro-Russian separatists in eastern Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.levada.ru/30-07-2014/katastrofa-boinga-pod-donetskom|title=\u041a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0430 \"\u0411\u043e\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0430\" \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u043e\u043c|date=30 July 2014|publisher=Levada.ru|accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/30/mh17-vast-majority-russians-believe-ukraine-downed-plane-poll|title=MH17: vast majority of Russians believe Ukraine downed plane, poll finds|last1=Luhn|first1=Alec|work=The Guardian|accessdate=2 August 2014|agency=Guardian News and Media Limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/more-than-80-of-russians-blame-ukrainian-army-for-malaysia-airlines-crash/504333.html|title=More Than 80% of Russians Blame Ukrainian Army for MH17 Crash|work=The Moscow Times|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, the Russian portal ''The Insider'', the news agency [[McClatchyDC]], and Bellingcat performed a joint investigation that confirmed the identity of a high-rank military officer using a call-sign \"Dolphin\" to be colonel general Nikolai Fedorovich Tkachev. Tkachev is frequently heard in the wiretaps acquired by JIT supervising the operation of \"Buk\" delivery and set-up.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2017/12/08/russian-colonel-general-delfin/|title=Russian Colonel General Identified as Key MH17 Figure \u2013 bellingcat|date=8 December 2017|work=bellingcat|access-date=8 December 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/world/article188720184.html|title=Russian general ID'd in activity around shootdown of Malaysian passenger jet|website=mcclatchydc|accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Initial reactions and \"An-26 downing\" version ===\nOn the evening of the crash, the [[Life (news agency, Russia)|LifeNews]] portal released a statement from the separatists saying that a \"Ukrainian Air Force [[An-26]] transport plane\" had been shot down by a missile and crashed.<ref name=\"lifenews 136801\">{{cite news|script-title=ru:\u041e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0446\u044b \u0441\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043e \u0441\u0431\u0438\u0442\u043e\u043c \u0410\u043d-26 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a\u0435 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u044b |url=http://lifenews.ru/news/136801 |quote=On July 17 near the village of Rassypnoye over the Torez city in Donetsk region an An-26 transport plane of Ukrainian Air Force was taken down, said the militia. According to them, the plane crashed somewhere near the \"Progress\" mine, away from residential areas. According to one of the militias, at about 17:30 local time an An-26 flew over the city. It was hit by a rocket, there was an explosion and the plane went to the ground, leaving a black smoke. Debris fell from the sky |accessdate=17 July 2014 |date=17 July 2014 |language=Russian}}</ref> [[ITAR-TASS]] and [[RIA Novosti]] also reported that an An-26 had been shot down by the separatist militia near Torez at around 16:00 local time in what it described as \"yet another victory of DPR self-defence\".<ref name=\"tassan26\">{{cite news|title=Donetsk People's Republic militia downs another Ukraine's An-26 plane \u2013 eyewitnesses |url=http://en.itar-tass.com/world/741164 |accessdate=18 July 2014 |agency=[[Information Telegraph Agency of Russia]] |date=17 July 2014 |ref=TASS2 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RA3m6ZDd?url=http://en.itar-tass.com/world/741164 |archivedate=18 July 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=\u0422\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0410\u043d-26 \u0441\u0431\u0438\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a\u0435 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u044b, \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043e\u0447\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0446\u044b |url=http://ria.ru/world/20140717/1016409306.html |website=ria.ru |agency=RIA Novosti |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=13 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RR2Ynt9a?url=http://ria.ru/world/20140717/1016409306.html |archivedate=29 July 2014 }}</ref> There was no evidence about altitude and weapons used.\n\nShortly after it became evident that it was a civilian aircraft which had crashed, the separatist media denied any responsibility and possession of anti-aircraft missiles capable of reaching the necessary altitude.<ref name=\"vk.com\">{{cite web |title=\u0421\u0432\u043e\u0434\u043a\u0438 \u043e\u0442 \u0421\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044f \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447\u0430 |url=http://vk.com/strelkov_info |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717152222/http://vk.com/strelkov_info |archivedate=17 July 2014 |website=VKontakte |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Arthur Bright\">{{cite web |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Europe/2014/0717/Web-evidence-points-to-pro-Russia-rebels-in-downing-of-MH17-video |title=Web evidence points to pro-Russia rebels in downing of MH17 (+video) |author=Arthur Bright |date=17 July 2014 |website=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\" />\n\n=== Conspiracy theories ===\nOn 18 July, Commander of the [[Donbass People's Militia]] [[Igor Strelkov (officer)|Igor Girkin]] was quoted as stating that \"a significant number of the bodies weren't fresh\". He followed up by saying \"Ukrainian authorities are capable of any baseness\"; and also claimed that blood serum and medications were found in the airplane's wreckage in large quantities.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/rebel-leader-gives-bizarre-account-plane-crash-182256709.html|title=Rebel leader gives bizarre account of plane crash|date=18 July 2014|accessdate=18 July 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140721032149/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/rebel-suggests-malaysia-plane-victims-long-dead|archivedate=21 July 2014|url-status=dead|work=Yahoo! News|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Girkin also claimed that some of the passengers had died a few days before the crash.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rusvesna.su/news/1405676334|author=\u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044c \u0421\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u043a\u043e\u0432|date=18 July 2014|publisher=RusVesna|language=Russian|script-title=ru:\u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044c \u0421\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u043a\u043e\u0432: \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043b\u044e\u0434\u0435\u0439 \u0438\u0437 \u0411\u043e\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0430 \u0443\u043c\u0435\u0440\u043b\u0438 \u0437\u0430 \u043d\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043a\u043e \u0441\u0443\u0442\u043e\u043a \u0434\u043e \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u044b|trans-title=Some of the Boeing's passengers died a few days before the crash|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RBLozt4P?url=http://rusvesna.su/news/1405676334|archivedate=19 July 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Russian government-funded<ref>{{cite news |last=Squires |first=Nick |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10976920/British-journalist-working-for-Russian-TV-resigns-over-bias-in-Ukraine-MH17-coverage.html |title=British journalist working for Russian TV resigns over bias in Ukraine MH17 coverage |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> outlet [[RT (TV network)|RT]] initially said that the airplane may have been shot down by Ukraine in a failed attempt to assassinate Vladimir Putin, in a plot which was organised by Ukraine's \"Western backers\". This was quickly dismissed as Putin's flight route was hundreds of kilometres north of Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wyborcza.pl/1,75477,16347795,Moskwa_obwinia_Ukraine.html?piano_t=1 |title='Zamach na Putina', 'Ile odszkodowa\u0144 zap\u0142ac\u0105 Ukrai\u0144cy' i zmiany w Wikipedii. Ofensywa propagandowa Moskwy |language=Polish|trans-title=\"The attempt on Putin\", \"How much compensation will pay Ukrainians\" and changes in Wikipedia. Moscow's propaganda offensive |url-access=subscription  |work=Gazeta Wyborcza |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |first=Wac\u0142aw |last=Radziwinowicz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.co.id/rt-malaysia-airlines-ukraine-2014-7/ |title=Here's The Ridiculous Way Russia's Propaganda Channel Is Covering The Malaysia Airlines Crash |last1=Szoldra |first1=Paul |website=Business Insider |date=18 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720054152/http://www.businessinsider.co.id/rt-malaysia-airlines-ukraine-2014-7/ |archivedate=20 July 2014  }}</ref>\n\nOther conspiracy theories propagated by Russian media included that the Ukrainians shot down the airplane by mistake, drawing parallels to downing [[Siberia Airlines Flight 1812]] in 2001 (reported in July{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} and in December 2014<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-30597555 |title=MH17: Russia reveals 'witness' who blames Ukraine pilot |publisher=BBC |date=24 December 2014 |accessdate=27 December 2014}}</ref>); that Ukrainian air traffic controllers purposefully redirected the flight to fly over the war zone (proven false by the DSB investigation); and that the Ukrainian government organised the attack on the airplane to bring infamy upon the pro-Russian rebels.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/russians-fed-conspiracy-theories-ukraine-crash-064400429.html |title=Russians Fed Conspiracy Theories on Ukraine Crash |work=Yahoo News |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014 |first=Laura |last=Mills |agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref>\n\nThe number of alternative theories disseminated in Russian mass media started growing as the DSB and JIT investigations increasingly pointed towards the separatists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://buran.ru/htm/mh17.htm|title=\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u043c\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0431 \u0440\u0435\u0439\u0441 \u041c\u041d17 \u043d\u0430\u0434 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0431\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043e\u043c? \u0411\u0440\u0438\u0444\u0438\u043d\u0433 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|website=buran.ru|access-date=6 August 2016}}</ref> On 15 November 2014, Russia's [[Channel One Russia|Channel One]] reported on a supposedly leaked spy satellite photo which showed the airplane being shot from behind by a Ukrainian Su-25 fighter jet.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.1tv.ru/news/social/271864 |title=\u0421\u043d\u0438\u043c\u043e\u043a \u043c\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0439\u0437\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \"\u0411\u043e\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0430\", \u0441\u0431\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u043e\u043c, \u043e\u0431\u0441\u0443\u0436\u0434\u0430\u044e\u0442 \u0432\u043e \u0432\u0441\u0435\u043c \u043c\u0438\u0440\u0435 |date=15 November 2014 |website=Channel One Russia}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Russia's Channel One show satellite photo evidencing MH17 was downed by fighter jet |work=TASS |date=14 November 2014 |accessdate=15 November 2014 |url=http://en.itar-tass.com/world/759835}}</ref> Many other Russian media reprinted the photo but its authenticity was immediately dismissed as the airplanes were out of scale which indicated poor copy-and-paste.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/world/sensational-russian-photo-of-mh17-being-shot-debunked-by-citizen-journalist-group-20141115-11nbqs.html |title='Sensational' Russian photo of MH17 being shot debunked by citizen journalist group |last=Miller |first=Nick |date=15 November 2014 |accessdate=15 November 2014 |newspaper=The Age}}</ref> Later it was disclosed, that the photo had been initially emailed to the Vice-President of the [[Russian Union of Engineers]] by a self-described aviation expert who had found it on a Russian online forum.<ref name=\"BUZZnov2014\">{{citation |title=Russian TV Airs Clearly Fake Image To Claim Ukraine Shot Down MH17 |first=Max |last=Seddon |date=15 November 2014 |accessdate=15 October 2014 |work=BuzzFeed |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/maxseddon/russian-tv-airs-clearly-fake-image-to-claim-ukraine-shot-dow}}</ref> The aviation expert later apologised, saying that he was unhappy with how the information had been used.<ref name=\"BUZZnov2014\" /> In a later interview by magazine ''[[The New Yorker]]'', Channel One CEO [[Konstantin Ernst]] admitted that reporting on the satellite photo was a \"simple error\", saying that it was a human mistake not made on purpose.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/12/16/the-kremlins-creative-director|title=The Kremlin\u2019s Creative Director|date=9 December 2019|work=The New Yorker|first=Joshua|last=Yaffa|accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, Sara Firth, who had worked as a correspondent with RT for the previous five years, resigned in protest at the channel's coverage of the crash, which she described as \"lies\".<ref name=\"sarafirth\">{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/travel/travel-updates/mh17-fallout-russian-reporter-sara-firth-quits-over-ukraine-lies/story-fnizu68q-1226994372531|title=MH17 fallout: Russian reporter Sara Firth quits over Ukraine 'lies'|date=28 March 2014|work=News.com.au|accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> RT said Firth had left to take another job.<ref name=\"ReporterResigns\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/jul/18/mh17-russia-today-reporter-resigns-sara-firth-kremlin-malaysia|title=Russia Today reporter resigns in protest at MH17 coverage|work=The Guardian|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Dutch newspaper ''[[NRC Handelsblad]]'' described how false stories about the MH17 crash had been propagated with the support of [[Christian Democratic Appeal]] politician [[Pieter Omtzigt]], who introduced a Russian-speaking Ukrainian man as an \"eyewitness\" to the crash on a public expert debate in May 2017. The man, who was an asylum-seeker from Ukraine, did not witness the crash and his speech, texted to him by Omtzigt prior to the interview, repeated the Russian-promoted version that Ukrainian jets downed the Boeing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2017/11/10/hoe-twijfel-rond-mh17-in-de-hand-wordt-gewerkt-13959091-a1580806|title=Hoe twijfel rond MH17 in de hand wordt gewerkt|work=NRC|access-date=13 November 2017|language=nl}}</ref>\n\n=== The \"Ukrainian Buk\" version ===\nIn May 2015, ''Novaya Gazeta'' published a report by \"a group of Russian military engineers\" that came to the conclusion that the airplane was shot down by a [[Buk missile system|Buk-M1 launcher]] with 9M38M1 missile. The authors also analysed the visible impact traces on the surface of the airplane and suggested that the missile couldn't have been fired from [[Snizhne]], but was instead fired from [[Zaroshchenske]] and claimed that a Ukrainian anti-air unit was located there at that time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.novayagazeta.ru/inquests/68332.html |title=\u042d\u0442\u043e \u0431\u044b\u043b \"\u0411\u0443\u043a-\u041c1\" |publisher=Novaya Gazeta |date=5 May 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2015 |trans-title=This was \"Buk-M1\"}}</ref> In June 2015, the report was the subject of a press conference and was attributed to Mikhail Malisevskiy, chief engineer at Moscow-headquartered [[Almaz-Antey]], the Buk missile manufacturer.<ref name=\"TheAgeAlmaz\">{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/world/mh17-plane-was-shot-down-by-a-buk-missile-russian-weapons-manufacturer-says-20150602-ghfdco.html |title=MH17 plane was shot down by a Buk missile, Russian weapons manufacturer says |author=Nick Miller |date=2 June 2015}}</ref> The [[Security Service of Ukraine]] said that there were inaccuracies in this version, and called part of the report a fake.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stopfake.org/sbu-novye-dokazatelstva-krusheniya-boeing-na-donbasse-osnovany-na-fejkovyh-snimkah/ |title=\u0421\u0411\u0423: \u041d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \"\u0434\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430\" \u043a\u0440\u0443\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f Boeing \u043d\u0430 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0431\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0435 \u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u044b \u043d\u0430 \u0444\u0435\u0439\u043a\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u043d\u0438\u043c\u043a\u0430\u0445 |date=6 May 2015 |accessdate=6 May 2015 |website= |publisher=StopFake.org|trans-title = SBU called the Russian analysis on Boeing based on fake photos}}</ref> Russian military expert Vadim Lukashevich argued on [[TV Rain]] that the spatial orientation of the rocket at the moment of explosion did not exclude the possibility that it was launched from Snizhne, as the report claimed. Lukashevich also noted that the report admitted a Buk missile as the cause of the crash, discrediting the previous theories about the crash (Su-25 etc.) circulated in Russian media.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.tvrain.ru/teleshow/here_and_now/ja_ne_uvidel_v_etom_doklade_ekspertov_vpk_aviatsio-386961/ |title=\u042f \u043d\u0435 \u0443\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043b \u0432 \u044d\u0442\u043e\u043c \u0434\u043e\u043a\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0435 \u044d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u0412\u041f\u041a\". \u0410\u0432\u0438\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u044d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0442 \u041b\u0443\u043a\u0430\u0448\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u043e \u0442\u043e\u043c, \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0438 \u0437\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043c \u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043b \u0434\u043e\u043a\u0443\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442, \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0434\u043e\u0431\u044b\u0442\u044b\u0439 \"\u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0439 |date=6 May 2015 |accessdate=6 May 2015 |website= |publisher=TV Rain |last=Lukashevich |first=Vadim|trans-title = \"I haven't seen military experts in that report\", aviation expert Lukashevich who and why published the report leaked by Novaya Gazeta}}</ref> ''[[Ukrainska Pravda]]'' questioned claims about the Ukrainian anti-aircraft unit and stated that Zaroshchenske was under control of pro-Russian forces on the day of shootdown.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2015/05/6/7066943/ |title=\u0417\u041c\u0406: \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0456 \u0435\u043a\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0438 \u0432 \u0441\u0435\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0442\u043d\u0456\u0439 \u0434\u043e\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u0456 \u043f\u0456\u0434\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0434\u0438\u043b\u0438, \u0449\u043e \u0411\u043e\u0457\u043d\u0433 \u0437\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0437 \"\u0411\u0443\u043a\u0430\" |date=6 May 2015 |accessdate=6 May 2015 |website= |publisher=Ukrainska Pravda|trans-title = Media: Russian experts confirmed in secret report, that Boeing was shot by \"Buk\"}}</ref> ''Novaya Gazeta'' published a long analysis by Mark Solonin, also denying the Almaz-Antey version,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.novayagazeta.ru/inquests/68376.html |title=\u0421\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043c \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0438 |date=12 May 2015 |website=Novaya Gazeta |last=Solonin |first=Mark}}</ref> interviewed inhabitants of Zaroshchenske who denied claims that Ukrainian forces and Buk launchers were present in the village at that time.<ref>{{cite web |title=There Was No Buk in Our Field |url=http://www.interpretermag.com/there-was-no-buk-in-our-field/ |website=The Interpreter |accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u041d\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0448\u0435\u043c \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0435 \"\u0411\u0443\u043a\u0430\" \u043d\u0435 \u0431\u044b\u043b\u043e. \u041d\u0438 \u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0430 \u2013 \u043d\u0438 \u043e\u0442 \u0433\u0443\u0441\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0446, \u043d\u0438 \u043e\u0442 \u0432\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0441\u0438\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0430 |url=http://www.novayagazeta.ru/inquests/68728.html |accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref> According to [[Bellingcat]], Russia's satellite images were from June and showed signs of editing.<ref name=\"Bell150531\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2015/05/31/mh17-forensic-analysis-of-satellite-images-released-by-the-russian-ministry-of-defence/ |title=MH17 \u2013 Forensic Analysis of Satellite Images Released by the Russian Ministry of Defence |work=Bellingcat |date=31 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"DW150601\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dw.de/forensic-report-russia-faked-mh17-satellite-photos/a-18490259 |title=Forensic report: Russia faked MH17 satellite photos |first=Conor |last=Dillon |publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]] |date=1 June 2015}}</ref> ''[[Bild]]'' described the Russian satellite image as \"fake\".<ref name=\"Bild150508\">{{cite news |url=http://www.bild.de/politik/ausland/flug-mh-17/russische-beweise-gefaelscht-40861842.bild.html |title=BILD entlarvt falsche Satellitenaufnahme |language=German |trans-title= BILD exposes false satellite image |first=Julian |last=R\u00f6pcke |work=[[Bild]] |date=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 September 2018, Russia's Ministry of Defence held a press conference that aimed to cast doubt on Moscow's culpability for the tragedy. Lt. Gen. Nikolai Parshin, chief of the Missile and Artillery Directorate, said that after Dutch investigators displayed parts of the missile and their serial numbers, they studied and declassified archives at the research center that produced the Buk missiles. Parshin said the Russian archives show that the missile that was made of these parts was transported to a military unit in western Ukraine in 1986, and to Russia's knowledge never left Ukraine. Officials also claimed that video evidence presented by the Joint Investigation Team (JIT), in which the missile that allegedly shot down the airplane was shown being moved from Russia into Ukraine, was fabricated.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/09/17/world/europe/ap-eu-russia-mh17.html |title= Russia: Missile That Shot Down Flight MH17 Was Ukrainian |date= 17 September 2018 |work= The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nJIT responded that it had requested details about recovered missile parts from Russia in May 2018, but had received no answer. It said, information from the Russian Ministry of Defence would be carefully studied as soon as the documents were made available, as requested in May 2018 and required by [[United Nations Security Council|UNSC]] in 2016. JIT stated it had always carefully analysed information provided by Russia, but information presented to the public was inaccurate on several points. Russia had given differing accounts over time of how MH17 was shot down; for example claiming to have evidence (radar images) that a Ukrainian fighter fired an air-to-air missile at MH17.<ref>{{cite news |title=MH17 crash: Dutch ask Russia to submit new claims |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45546611 |accessdate=18 September 2018 |work=BBC News |date=18 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= Landelijk Parket |title=Reaction JIT to press conference of Russian Ministry of Defense |url=https://www.om.nl/actueel/nieuwsberichten/@104053/reaction-jit-to/ |website=Openbaar Ministerie |accessdate=18 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Oleksandr Turchynov]], secretary of [[National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine]], said in September 2018 that Russia's claim was \"yet another failed fake report that the Kremlin made up in order to cover up their crime that has been proven by the official investigation as well as independent experts.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.newsweek.com/russian-propaganda-moscow-releases-audio-blaming-ukraine-downing-mh17-flight-1124371 |title= Russian propaganda? Moscow releases audio blaming Ukraine downing MH17 flight that killed almost 300 |date= 17 September 2018 |work= Newsweek}}</ref>\n\n==Maps==\n{{col-float|width=320px}}\n{{Location map many\n| Afro-Eurasia\n| relief      = 1\n| width       = 300\n| float       = none\n| caption     = Location of departure, crash site and destination\n| alt         = Location of crash site; departure and destination airports\n| <!--first label/marker-->\n| label1      = {{nowrap|Amsterdam Airport Schiphol}}\n| label1_size = <!-- or: label_size -->\n| position1   = <!-- or: position, pos1, pos -->\n| background1 = <!-- or: background, bg1, bg -->\n| mark1       = Green pog.svg\n| mark1size   =\n| link1       = <!-- or: link -->\n| lat1_deg    = 52\n| lat1_min    = 18\n| lat1_sec    = 29\n| lat1_dir    = N\n| lon1_deg    = 4\n| lon1_min    = 45\n| lon1_sec    = 51\n| lon1_dir    = E\n| <!--second label/marker-->\n| label2      = Crash site\n| label2_size =\n| position2   = bottom\n| background2 = <!-- or: bg2 -->\n| mark2       = Airplane Crash.svg\n| mark2size   = 10\n| link2       =\n| lat2_deg    = 48\n| lat2_min    = 8\n| lat2_sec    = 17\n| lat2_dir    = N\n| lon2_deg    = 38\n| lon2_min    = 38\n| lon2_sec    = 20\n| lon2_dir    = E\n| <!--third label/marker-->\n| label3      = {{nowrap|Kuala Lumpur}} {{nowrap|International Airport}}\n| label3_size =\n| position3   =\n| background3 = <!-- or: bg2 -->\n| mark3       =\n| mark3size   =\n| link3       =\n| lat3_deg    = 2\n| lat3_min    = 44\n| lat3_sec    = 36\n| lat3_dir    = N\n| lon3_deg    = 101\n| lon3_min    = 41\n| lon3_sec    = 53\n| lon3_dir    = E\n}}\n{{col-float-break|width=320px}}\n{{Location map many\n| Europe\n| relief      = 1\n| width       = 300\n| float       = none\n| caption     = Location of departure and crash site\n| alt         = Location of departure and crash site\n| <!--first label/marker-->\n| label1      = {{nowrap|Amsterdam Airport Schiphol}}\n| label1_size = <!-- or: label_size -->\n| position1   = <!-- or: position, pos1, pos -->\n| background1 = <!-- or: background, bg1, bg -->\n| mark1       = Green pog.svg\n| mark1size   =\n| link1       = <!-- or: link -->\n| lat1_deg    = 52\n| lat1_min    = 18\n| lat1_sec    = 29\n| lat1_dir    = N\n| lon1_deg    = 4\n| lon1_min    = 45\n| lon1_sec    = 51\n| lon1_dir    = E\n| <!--second label/marker-->\n| label2      = Crash site\n| label2_size =\n| position2   = <!-- or: pos2 -->right\n| background2 = <!-- or: bg2 -->\n| mark2       = Airplane Crash.svg\n| mark2size   = 10\n| link2       =\n| lat2_deg    = 48\n| lat2_min    = 8\n| lat2_sec    = 17\n| lat2_dir    = N\n| lon2_deg    = 38\n| lon2_min    = 38\n| lon2_sec    = 20\n| lon2_dir    = E\n}}\n{{col-float-break|width=320px}}\n[[File:Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 crash site.png|thumb|upright=1.15|none|Presumed route ending in an area controlled by pro-Russian rebels according to ''The New York Times''<ref name=\"NYT Maps\" />{{efn|\"A United States official said the missile that shot down the plane was launched from a region near the towns of [[Torez]] and [[Snizhne]]\"<ref name=nytimes1/> See also several mentions of one or both of these towns in the [[#Cause of crash|''Cause of crash'']] section and elsewhere in this article}}]]\n\n{{col-float-end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of airliner shootdown incidents]]\n* [[List of aircraft accidents and incidents resulting in at least 50 fatalities]]\n<!-- Please do not add other airliner shootdown incidents. These are already covered in the list wikilink -->\n{{Portal bar|Aviation|Malaysia|Netherlands|Ukraine}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Malaysia Airlines Flight 17}}\n* [https://www.politie.nl/themas/flight-mh17/witness-appeal-crash-mh17.html MH17 Witness Appeal November 2019 with the release of further recorded conversations.]\n* [https://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/en/media/attachment/2018/7/10/debcd724fe7breport_mh17_crash.pdf MH17 Crash] \u2013 final report from Dutch Safety Board, 2015-10-13 {{in lang|en}}\n* [https://www.webcitation.org/6RWKfBUgD?url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/en/onderzoek/2049/investigation-crash-mh17-17-july-2014 Investigation crash MH17, 17 July 2014 Donetsk] \u2013 [[Dutch Safety Board]]\n* [https://www.om.nl/onderwerpen/mh17-crash/  MH17 crash] \u2013 the Joint Investigation Team (JIT) updates \u2013 [[Dutch Public Prosecution Service]]\n* [https://www.rechtspraak.nl/Uitspraken-en-nieuws/Bekende-rechtszaken/strafzaak-mh17/Paginas/criminal-case-MH17-EN.aspx  MH17-dossier] Dutch Court {{in lang|en}}\n* [http://www.malaysiaairlines.com/my/en/site/mh17.html Media Statement & Information on Flight MH17] \u2013 Malaysia Airlines\n* [https://web.archive.org/*/http://www.mot.gov.my/en/Newsroom/Pages/MH17.aspx Malaysia Airlines Flight 17] (Archive) \u2013 [[Malaysia Ministry of Transport]]\n* [http://www.malaysiaairlines.com/content/dam/malaysia-airlines/mas/PDF/MH17/MH17%20PAX%20AND%20CREW%20MANIFEST%20200714.pdf Official MH17 Passenger Manifest] \u2013 Malaysia Airlines\n* [https://www.flightradar24.com/data/pinned/mh17-3d6095b#3d6095b Full flight history for Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17] \u2013 [[Flightradar24]]\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/17/malaysia-airlines-plane-crashes-ukraine-live Malaysia Airlines plane MH17 'shot down' in Ukraine \u2013 as it happened], ''[[The Guardian]]''\n* [http://graphics.wsj.com/mh17-crash-map/ Map of a Tragedy: How MH17 Came Apart Over Ukraine] \u2013 ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''\n* [https://www.google.com/fusiontables/embedviz?q=select+col6+from+1vvwP22j0vhVmC7FmJRFlo9AVTTafY7ElwqRpCzJl&viz=MAP&h=false&lat=53.430059233929505&lng=5.924133995312445&t=1&z=8&l=col6&y=2&tmplt=2&hml=ONE_COL_LAT_LNG Google Fusion Tables], clickable Google map, that tells the story of every Dutch victim, created by newspaper ''[[Algemeen Dagblad]]'' {{in lang|nl}}\n\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in 2014}}\n{{Malaysia Airlines}}\n{{Ukrainian crisis navbox}}\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in Ukraine}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Malaysia Airlines Flight 17| ]]\n[[Category:2014 controversies]]\n[[Category:2014 in international relations]]\n[[Category:2014 in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:2014 in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:2014 in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving the Boeing 777]]\n[[Category:Airliner shootdown incidents]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2014]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 2014]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Donetsk People's Republic]]\n[[Category:History of Donetsk Oblast]]\n[[Category:Malaysia Airlines accidents and incidents|17]]\n[[Category:Malaysia\u2013Netherlands relations]]\n[[Category:Malaysia\u2013Ukraine relations]]\n[[Category:Netherlands\u2013Ukraine relations]]\n[[Category:War in Donbass]]\n[[Category:21st-century aircraft shootdown incidents]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:July 2014 events in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|July 2014 airliner downing in rebel-controlled Donetsk, Ukraine}}\n{{For|the aircraft that disappeared over the Indian Ocean in March 2014|Malaysia Airlines Flight 370}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox aircraft occurrence\n| name = Malaysia Airlines Flight 17\n| image = Boeing 777-2H6ER 9M-MRD Malaysian (6658105143).jpg\n| image_upright = 1.1591\n| alt = \n| caption = 9M-MRD, the aircraft involved, 2011\n| occurrence_type = Shootdown\n| date = {{start date|2014|07|17|df=y}}\n| summary = Shot down by a [[surface-to-air missile]] transported from Russia on the day of the crash<ref name=\"SMH JIT\"/><ref name=\"BBC News 28 September 2016\" />\n| site = Near [[Hrabove, Donetsk Oblast]], Ukraine\n| coordinates = {{Coord|48|8|17|N|38|38|20|E|type:event|display=inline,title}}\n| aircraft_type = [[Boeing 777#777-200ER|Boeing 777-200ER]]<!-- The aircraft model is Boeing 777-200ER. The customer code used at Boeing was \"777-2H6ER\". \"H6\" is the Malaysia Airlines customer code to indicate certain preferences. Consensus is to use \"Boeing 777-200ER\" as the model number. -->\n| aircraft_name = \n| operator = [[Malaysia Airlines]]\n| IATA = MH17\n| ICAO = MAS17\n| callsign = MALAYSIAN 17\n| tail_number = 9M-MRD\n| origin = [[Amsterdam Airport Schiphol]], the Netherlands\n| stopover = \n| destination = [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport]], Malaysia\n| occupants = 298\n| passengers = 283\n| crew = 15\n| fatalities = 298<!-- don't need to add \"(all)\", we already have survivors=0 -->\n| survivors = 0\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Ukrainian crisis}}\n'''Malaysia Airlines Flight 17''' ('''MH17'''){{efn|MH is the [[IATA airline designator|IATA designator]]. The flight was also marketed as [[KLM]] Flight 4103 (KLM4103) through a [[codeshare agreement|codeshare]], and has been commonly referred to as \"MH17\", \"Flight 17\" or \"Flight MH17\".}} was a scheduled passenger flight from [[Amsterdam Airport Schiphol|Amsterdam]] to [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur]] that was [[List of airliner shootdown incidents|shot down]] on 17 July 2014 while flying over [[eastern Ukraine]]. All 283 passengers and 15 crew were killed.<ref name=\"dsb1\"/> Contact with the aircraft, a [[Boeing 777-200ER]], was lost when it was about {{convert|50|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the [[Ukraine\u2013Russia border]], and wreckage of the aircraft fell near [[Hrabove, Donetsk Oblast|Hrabove]] in [[Donetsk Oblast]], Ukraine, {{convert|40|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the border.<ref name=telegraph>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10974050/Malaysia-Airlines-plane-crashes-on-Ukraine-Russia-border-live.html |title=Malaysia Airlines plane crashes on Ukraine-Russia border \u2013 live |date=17 July 2014 |first=Harriet |last=Alexander |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=17 July 2014 |archivedate=18 July 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718001608/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10974050/Malaysia-Airlines-plane-crashes-on-Ukraine-Russia-border-live.html}}</ref> The shoot-down occurred in the [[War in Donbass]], during the [[Battle in Shakhtarsk Raion]], in an area controlled by [[2014 pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine|pro-Russian rebels]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/10/world/europe/malaysian-airliner-ukraine.html |title=Malaysian Jet Over Ukraine Was Downed by 'High-Energy Objects,' Dutch Investigators Say |last=Higgins |first=Andrew |last2=Clark |first2=Nicola |date=9 September 2014 |website=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> The crash was [[Malaysia Airlines|Malaysia Airlines']] second aircraft loss during 2014, after the disappearance of [[Malaysia Airlines Flight 370|Flight 370]] on 8 March.<ref name=\"Official nationalities\">{{cite web|url=http://www.malaysiaairlines.com/my/en/site/mh17.html|title=Saturday, July 19, 07:30&nbsp;pm GMT +0800 Media Statement 7 : MH17 Incident|date=19 July 2014|website=Malaysia Airlines|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717232838/http://www.malaysiaairlines.com/my/en/site/mh17.html|archive-date=17 July 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe responsibility for investigation was delegated to the [[Dutch Safety Board]] (DSB) and the Dutch-led [[#Criminal investigation|joint investigation team]] (JIT), who concluded that the airliner was downed by a [[Buk missile system|Buk]] [[surface-to-air missile]] launched from pro-Russian [[Novorossiya (confederation)|separatist-controlled territory]] in Ukraine.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\" /><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |title=MH17 crash report: Dutch investigators confirm Buk missile hit plane \u2013 live updates |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2015/oct/13/mh17-crash-report-ukraine-live-updates |newspaper=the Guardian |accessdate=13 October 2015 |first=Matthew |last=Weaver|date=13 October 2015 }}</ref> According to the JIT, the Buk that was used originated from the [[53rd Anti-Aircraft Missile Brigade]] of the [[Russia|Russian Federation]]<ref name=\"BBC 5.24.18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-44235402|work=[[BBC News]]|title=MH17 missile owned by Russian brigade, investigators say|date=24 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN 5.24.18\">{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/05/24/europe/mh17-plane-netherlands-russia-intl/index.html|work=[[CNN]]|title=Missile that downed MH17 'owned by Russian brigade'|first1=Laura|last1=Smith-Spark|first2=James|last2=Masters|date=24 May 2018}}</ref> and had been transported from Russia on the day of the crash, fired from a field in a rebel-controlled area and returned to Russia afterwards.<ref name=\"SMH JIT\" /><ref name=\"BBC News 28 September 2016\"/><ref name=\"BBC 5.24.18\"/> On the basis of the JIT's conclusions, the governments of the Netherlands and Australia held Russia responsible for the deployment of the Buk installation and were  pursuing legal routes to formalise this {{As of|2018|May|df=|lc=y}}.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.government.nl/latest/news/2018/05/25/mh17-the-netherlands-and-australia-hold-russia-responsible|title=MH17: The Netherlands and Australia hold Russia responsible|last=Algemene Zaken|first=Ministerie van|last2=Buitenlandse Zaken|first2=Ministerie van|website=www.government.nl|language=nl-NL|access-date=25 May 2018|date=25 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Evidence in The Australian\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/mh17-shot-down-by-missile-from-russia-by-its-military-report-finds/news-story/d3d1cafaa0033e7acc42d9b9fc38dbf4|title=MH17 evidence points to 'rogue state' Russia, Tony Abbott says|last=Bunnik|first=Jacquelin Magnay|last2=Riordan|first2=Primrose|date=25 May 2018|website=The Australian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Russian government denies responsibility for shooting down the plane,<ref name=\"CNN 5.24.18\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tass.com/defense/1006070|title=No Russian air defense missile systems crossed Russia-Ukraine border \u2013 top brass|work=TASS|access-date=25 May 2018|language=ru}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-29140593|title=Ukraine crisis: Poroshenko offers rebels more autonomy|date=10 September 2014|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/europe/putin-claims-no-proof-russians-downed-mh17-20190621-p51ztv.html|title=Russians made a 'scapegoat' after MH17 report released, says Malaysia PM|last=Sipalan|first=Joseph|date=21 June 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-06-23}}</ref> and holds the Ukrainian government responsible for allowing civilian flights in a war zone.<ref>{{Citation|title=Putin Dismisses MH17 Charges|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/russia-putin-mh17/30010707.html|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> \n\nThe findings by the DSB and JIT are consistent with the earlier claims by American and German intelligence sources<ref name=\"LAtimes\"/><ref name=\"WaPoJuly22\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2014/07/20/the-evidence-that-may-prove-pro-russian-separatists-shot-down-mh17/ |title=The evidence that may prove pro-Russian separatists shot down MH17 |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> and claims by the Ukrainian government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/yatsenyuk-russia-is-not-planning-to-conduct-any-humanitarian-mission-live-361699.html|title=Yatsenyuk: 'We need to survive first'|date=22 August 2014|work=Kyiv Post}}</ref> \n\n==Aircraft==\nFlight 17, which was also marketed as [[KLM]] Flight 4103 (KL4103) through a [[codeshare agreement]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Statement Malaysia Airlines MH17 |url=http://news.klm.com/en/incident-with-malaysia-airlines-flight-mh017-e/ |website=[[KLM]] |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> was operated with a Boeing 777-2H6ER,{{efn|The aircraft is a Boeing 777-200ER (for Extended Range) model; Boeing assigns a [[List of Boeing customer codes|unique customer code]] for each company that buys one of its aircraft, which is applied as an [[infix]] in the model number at the time the aircraft is built. The code for Malaysia Airlines is \"H6\", hence \"777-2H6ER\".}} serial number 28411, registration 9M-MRD.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|30}} The 84th Boeing 777 produced, it first flew on 17 July 1997, exactly 17 years before the incident, and was delivered new to Malaysia Airlines on 29 July 1997.<ref name=\"airfleets1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.airfleets.net/ficheapp/plane-b777-28411.htm# |title=Malaysia Airlines 9M-MRD (Boeing 777&nbsp;\u2013 MSN 28411) &#124; Airfleets aviation |publisher=Airfleets.net |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Powered by two [[Rolls-Royce Trent 800|Rolls-Royce Trent 892]] engines and carrying 280 seats (33 [[Business class|business]] and 247 [[Economy class|economy]]), the aircraft had recorded more than 76,300 hours in 11,430 cycles before the crash.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|30}} The aircraft was in an airworthy condition at departure.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|31}}\n\nThe Boeing 777, which entered commercial service on 7 June 1995, has one of the best safety records among commercial aircraft.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/07/17/boeing-777-safe-track-record/12786181/ |title=Boeing 777 has excellent track record, experts say |author=Larry Copeland |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> In June 2014 there were about 1,212 aircraft in service, with 340 more on order.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://active.boeing.com/commercial/orders/displaystandardreport.cfm?cboCurrentModel=777&optReportType=AllModels&cboAllModel=777&ViewReportF=View+Report |title=777 Model Orders and Deliveries summary |publisher=Boeing |date=June 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Passengers and crew==\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"margin:0 0 0.5em 1em; float:right;\"\n|-\n|+People on board by nationality<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|27}}\n|-\n!Nation||data-sort-type=\"number\"|Number<!-- OFFICIAL LIST PER THE OFFICIAL DSB REPORT, DON'T MODIFY -->\n|-\n|Australia || style=\"text-align:center;\"|27\n|-\n|Belgium || style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|Canada{{efn|Including:\n* 1 dual Canadian-Romanian citizen}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Germany{{efn|Including:\n* 1 dual German-Dutch citizen}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|Indonesia || style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\n|-\n|Malaysia{{efn|28 passengers and 15 crew}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"|43\n|-\n|Netherlands{{efn|Including:\n* 1 dual Dutch-Belgian citizen\n* 1 dual Dutch-Israeli citizen\n* 1 dual Dutch-Italian citizen\n* 1 dual Dutch-American citizen\n* 1 dual Dutch-Malaysian citizen<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2014/09/09/remains-of-shell-worker-and-baby-coming-home-so-far-35-victims-have-been-brought-back/|title=Remains of Shell worker and baby coming home|newspaper=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|date=9 September 2014|accessdate=25 September 2017|quote=The 35, he added, included restaurateur Jenny Loh Yan Hwa, a passenger with dual citizenship, along with Dutch citizens Fan Shun Po and Paul Goes.}} \u2013 The Dutch-Malaysian <!--LOH/YANHWA MRS--> is counted as Dutch on [https://www.malaysiaairlines.com/content/dam/malaysia-airlines/mas/PDF/MH17/MH17%20PAX%20AND%20CREW%20MANIFEST%20200714.pdf the manifest]</ref>\n* 3 Dutch-Vietnamese citizen <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thanhniennews.com/society/vietnamese-family-friends-mourn-as-remains-of-mh17-victims-arrive-home-33948.html|title=Vietnamese family, friends mourn as remains of MH17 victims arrive home|date=13 November 2014|website=Thanh Nien Daily}}</ref>|name=|group=}}|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |193\n|-\n|New Zealand || style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Philippines || style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|United Kingdom{{efn|Including:\n* 1 dual British-South African citizen\n* 1 dual British-New Zealand citizen}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| '''Total''' || style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''298'''\n|}\n\nThe incident is the deadliest airliner shootdown incident to date.<ref name=reuters>{{cite news |url=http://www.financialexpress.com/news/malaysia-airlines-mh17-shot-down-top-5-deadliest-attacks-on-airliners/1271130 |title=Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17: Top 5 deadliest airliner shootdowns |agency=Reuters |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> All 283 passengers and 15 crew died.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|27}} By 19 July, the airline had determined the nationalities of all 298 passengers and crew.<ref name=\"Official nationalities\"/>\n\nThe crew were all Malaysian, while over two-thirds (68%) of the passengers were Dutch. Most of the other passengers were Malaysians and Australians, the remainder were citizens of seven other countries.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|27}}\n\nAmong the passengers were delegates en route to the [[XX International AIDS Conference, 2014|20th International AIDS Conference]] in Melbourne, including [[Joep Lange]], a former president of the [[International AIDS Society]], which organised the conference.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/crash-claims-top-aids-researchers-heading-to-melbourne-20140718-zuaw3.html |title=Crash claims top AIDS researchers heading to Melbourne |last=Lillebuen |first=Steve |date=18 July 2014 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> Many initial reports had erroneously indicated that around 100 delegates to the conference were aboard, but this was later revised to six.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Robin |first1=Myriam |title=100 AIDS researchers on MH17? Why and how the media got it wrong |url=http://www.crikey.com.au/2014/07/23/100-aids-researchers-on-mh17-why-and-how-the-media-got-it-wrong/ |website=[[Crikey]] |accessdate=23 July 2014 |date=23 July 2014}}</ref> Also on board were [[Senate (Netherlands)|Dutch Senator]] [[Willem Witteveen]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/2686/Binnenland/article/detail/3691664/2014/07/18/Senator-Witteveen-PvdA-omgekomen-bij-crash.dhtml |title=Senator Witteveen (PvdA) omgekomen bij crash \u2013 Binnenland \u2013 VK |work=De Volkskrant |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> Australian author [[Liam Davison]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Victorians among those killed in MH17 crash: Premier |url=http://www.bendigoadvertiser.com.au/story/2426085/victorians-among-those-killed-in-mh17-crash-premier/?cs=80 |work=[[Bendigo Advertiser]] |accessdate=19 July 2014|date=18 July 2014 }}</ref> and Malaysian actress [[Shuba Jay]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Malaysian actress, Dutch hubby and baby die with MH17 |url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/malaysian-actress-dutch-hubby-and-baby-die-with-mh17 |newspaper=The Malaysian Insider |accessdate=19 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140722064912/http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/malaysian-actress-dutch-hubby-and-baby-die-with-mh17 |archivedate=22 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\nAt least twenty family groups were on the aircraft and eighty passengers were under the age of 18.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/news/asia/south-east-asia/story/malaysia-airlines-mh17-crash-20-families-gone-one-shot-20140721 |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17 crash: 20 families gone in one shot |newspaper=[[The Straits Times]] |date=21 July 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RF430C7G?url=http://www.straitstimes.com/news/asia/south-east-asia/story/malaysia-airlines-mh17-crash-20-families-gone-one-shot-20140721 |archivedate=21 July 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Miranda |first1=Charles |first2=Cindy |last2=Wockner |first3=Ian |last3=McPhedran |author-link3=Ian McPhedran|first4=Jacquelin |last4=Magnay |url=http://www.news.com.au/world/mh17-train-in-kharkiv-as-tony-abbott-says-mh17-aftermath-is-evidence-tampering-on-industrial-scale/story-fndir2ev-1226996838429 |title=MH17 train in Kharkiv as Tony Abbott says MH17 aftermath is evidence tampering on industrial scale |publisher=[[News Corp Australia]] |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724092335/http://www.news.com.au/world/mh17-train-in-kharkiv-as-tony-abbott-says-mh17-aftermath-is-evidence-tampering-on-industrial-scale/story-fndir2ev-1226996838429|archivedate=24 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe flightcrew were captains Wan Amran Wan Hussin and Eugene Choo Jin Leong, and first officers Ahmad Hakimi Hanapi and Muhd Firdaus Abdul Rahim.<ref>\"[http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2014/08/22/The-crew-of-MH17/ The crew of MH17]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6S0tSU9RB?url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2014/08/22/The-crew-of-MH17/ Archive]). ''[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]''. 22 August 2014. Retrieved 22 August 2014.</ref>{{efn|The family name is Choo, as the Chinese name is Choo Jin Leong ({{zh|c=\u6731\u4ec1\u9686|p=Zh\u016b R\u00e9nl\u00f3ng}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.sina.com.cn/w/2014-07-18/170430543109.shtml |script-title=zh:MH17\u822a\u73ed\u534e\u88d4\u673a\u957f\u7236\u59bb\u5747\u66fe\u5c31\u804c\u9a6c\u822a |publisher=[[Sina Corp|Sina]] News |date=18 July 2014 |language=zh-hans <!--|archivelink=https://www.webcitation.org/6RWlHmVgT?url=http://news.sina.com.cn/w/2014-07-18/170430543109.shtml-->}} - The reference contains Choo's name in Chinese characters.</ref> - note that Ethnic Malays do not have family names.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2014/08/22/the-crew-of-mh17|title=The crew of MH17 &#124; The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my}}</ref>}}\n\n==Background==\n{{See also|2014 pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine|War in Donbass}}\n\nAn [[War in Donbass|armed conflict in Eastern Ukraine]] led some [[airlines]] to avoid eastern Ukrainian airspace in early March 2014 due to safety concerns.<ref name=20140718BBC>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-28356745 |title=MH17 crash: Airlines divert flights from eastern Ukraine |publisher=BBC |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/18/airlines-avoid-ukraine-airspace-mh17|title=Many airlines have avoided Ukrainian airspace for months|last=Neate|first=Rupert|last2=Glenza|first2=Jessica|date=18 July 2014|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=12 June 2018}}</ref> Military aircraft were deployed in the conflict, and [[List of Ukrainian aircraft losses during the Ukrainian crisis|several were shot down in the months and weeks preceding the MH17 incident]]. In April, the [[International Civil Aviation Organization]] warned governments that there was a risk to commercial passenger flights over south-eastern Ukraine.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|217}} The American [[Federal Aviation Administration]] issued restrictions on flights over [[Crimea]], to the south of MH17's route, and advised airlines flying over some other parts of Ukraine to \"exercise extreme caution\". This warning did not include the MH17 crash region.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/17/us-ukraine-crisis-airplane-warnings-idUSKBN0FM2BV20140717 |title=U.S. air carriers to avoid Russia-Ukraine border airspace |agency=Reuters |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=telegraph-20140717>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/law-and-order/10974823/Air-operators-belatedly-avoid-Ukraine-war-zone.html |title=Air operators belatedly avoid Ukraine war zone |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |first=Tom |last=Whitehead}}</ref> 37 airlines continued overflying eastern Ukraine and about 900 flights crossed the [[Donetsk Oblast|Donetsk region]] in the seven days before the Boeing 777 was shot down.<ref name=spiegel-981813>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/panorama/malaysia-airlines-mh17-lufthansa-ueberflog-ost-ukraine-56-mal-a-981813.html |title=Absturz von Flug MH17: Lufthansa flog zuletzt 56-mal \u00fcber Kriegsgebiet |trans-title=Crash of Flight MH17: Lufthansa lately flew 56 times over crisis region |work=Der Spiegel |language=German |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 June 2014, a [[Ukrainian Air Force]] [[Ilyushin Il-76]] military airlifter [[Ukrainian Air Force Ilyushin Il-76 shoot-down|was shot down]] on approach to [[Luhansk International Airport]], with loss of nine crew members and forty troops.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|183}} On 29 June, Russian news agencies reported that insurgents had obtained a [[Buk missile system]] after having taken control of a Ukrainian air defence base (possibly the former location of the 156th Anti-Aircraft Missile Regiment [156 zrp]).<ref name=vor-20140629>{{cite news |url=http://voiceofrussia.com/news/2014_06_29/Donetsk-militia-takes-control-of-Ukrainian-anti-air-installation-1561/ |title=Donetsk militia takes control of Ukrainian anti-air installation |newspaper=Voice of Russia |date=29 June 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=itar290614>{{cite news |url=http://itar-tass.com/mezhdunarodnaya-panorama/1287030 |script-title=ru:\u041e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0446\u044b \u0414\u041d\u0420 \u0432\u0437\u044f\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043b\u044c \u0432\u043e\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0443\u044e \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c \u041f\u0412\u041e \u0441 \u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u043d\u043e-\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0442\u043d\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043c\u0438 \"\u0411\u0443\u043a\" |trans-title=DNR militias seized an air defence base with anti-aircraft missile systems \"Buk\" |agency=[[Information Telegraph Agency of Russia]] |language=Russian |date=29 June 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ntv.ru/novosti/1085256/ |work=NTV News |publisher=[[NTV (Russia)|NTV]] |script-title=ru:\u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0446\u044b \u043e\u0431\u0437\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0441\u044c \u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u043d\u043e-\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0442\u043d\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043c\u0438 \"\u0411\u0443\u043a\" |trans-title=Donetsk militias acquired anti-aircraft missile systems \"Buk\" |language=Russian |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> On the same day, the [[Donetsk People's Republic]] claimed possession of such a system in a since-deleted [[Twitter|tweet]].<ref name=itar290614/><ref name=\"thediplomat\">{{cite news |url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/07/malaysian-airlines-flight-mh17-shot-down-over-donetsk-ukraine/ |title=Malaysian Airlines Flight MH17 Shot Down Over Donetsk, Ukraine |first=Ankit |last=Panda |date=17 July 2014 |work=The Diplomat |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 July 2014, a Ukrainian Air Force [[Antonov-26|An-26]] transport airplane flying at {{convert|6500|m|ft|abbr=on}} was shot down.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|183}} The militia reportedly claimed via social media that a Buk missile launcher had been used to bring down the aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vz.ru/news/2014/7/14/695525.html |title=\u041e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0446\u044b \u0441\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0438\u043b\u0438, \u0438\u0437 \u0447\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0441\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0410\u043d-26 |publisher=Vzglyad |quote=Today the self-defence destroyed An-26 airplane using SAM \"9\u041a37\u041c1\" (better known as 'Buk') ... said the militia, distributed in social networks [translation after ellipsis from Google translate] |date=14 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> American officials later said evidence suggested the aircraft had been shot down from [[Russia|Russian territory]].<ref name=\"BakerNYT\">[[Peter Baker (author)|Peter Baker]] (18 July 2014), [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/19/world/europe/malaysia-airlines-plane-ukraine.html U.S. Sees Evidence of Russian Links to Jet's Downing] ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref> On 16 July, a Ukrainian [[Sukhoi Su-25]] [[close air support]] aircraft was also shot down. The Ukrainian government said that the Russian military had shot down the aircraft with an [[air-to-air missile]] fired by a [[Mikoyan MiG-29|MiG-29]] jet in Russia; the [[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Russian defence ministry]] said that the accusations were false.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28345039 |title=Ukraine conflict: Russia accused of shooting down jet |date=17 July 2014 |work=BBC News |location=London |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"rfe/rl on rejection of accusation\">{{cite news |url=http://www.rferl.org/content/ukraine-russia-jet-shot-down-blame/25460575.html |title=Russia Rejects 'Absurd' Accusation Over Downed Ukrainian Jet |date=17 July 2014 |work=[[RFE/RL]] |publisher=RFE/RL |location=Prague |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> According to the Dutch newspaper ''[[De Telegraaf]]'', the Ukrainian government also warned the [[government of the Netherlands]] and other European countries about dangers in flying over the [[East Ukraine]] three days prior to the shootdown<ref>[http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2015/01/24/7056198/ Netherlands knew about dangers of flying over Donbas prior to the MH17 tragedy]. [[Ukrayinska Pravda]]. 24 January 2015</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150124134504/http://www.telegraaf.nl/binnenland/23592584/___Info_MH17_niet_geheim___.html Vertrouwelijkheid MH17 is onzin]. [[De Telegraaf]]. 23 January 2015</ref> due to the downing of the An-26 transport aircraft on 14 July.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150124134709/http://news.liga.net/news/politics/2526560-na_luganshchine_ischezla_svyaz_s_samoletom_ato_an_26.htm Communication was lost with the plane AN26 of ATO forces in the Luhansk region]. LIGANews. 14 July 2014</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150124135123/http://www.unian.ua/politics/939378-u-luganskiy-oblasti-boyoviki-zbili-ukrajinskiy-litak-lotchik-katapultuvavsya-ochevidtsi.html In Luhansk Oblast militants downed Ukrainian plane, pilot was ejected \u2013 witnesses]. [[Ukrainian Independent Information Agency]]. 14 July 2014</ref>\n\nOn 17 July, an [[Associated Press]] journalist saw a Buk launcher in [[Snizhne]], a town in [[Donetsk Oblast]], {{convert|16|km|mi|0}} southeast of the crash site. The reporter also saw seven separatist [[tank]]s near the town.<ref name=\"leonard\">{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/ukraine-air-force-jet-downed-russian-missile-102817809.html |author=Peter Leonard |title=Ukraine: Air Force jet downed by Russian missile |publisher=ABC News |agency=Associated Press |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113123101/http://news.yahoo.com/ukraine-air-force-jet-downed-russian-missile-102817809.html |archivedate=13 January 2016}}</ref> [[Associated Press]] journalists reported that the Buk M-1 was operated by a man \"with unfamiliar fatigues and a distinctive Russian accent\" escorted by two civilian vehicles.<ref name=Karmanau>{{cite news |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/what-happened-day-flight-17-was-downed |title=What happened? The day Flight 17 was downed |author1=Yuras Karmanau  |author2=Peter Leonard  |lastauthoramp=yes |work=Associated Press |date=25 July 2014 |accessdate=13 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009123439/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/what-happened-day-flight-17-was-downed |archivedate=9 October 2014}}</ref> The battle around [[Savur-Mohyla]] has been suggested as the possible context within which the missile that brought down MH17 was fired, as separatists deployed increasingly sophisticated [[anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft weaponry]] in this battle, and had brought down several Ukrainian [[jet aircraft|jets]] in July.<ref>Daily Telegraph, 14 November 2014,[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/11231333/The-unlikely-pilgrimage-site-of-Saur-Mogila.html the unlikely pilgrimage site of saur mogila]</ref>\n\nUkraine imposed restrictions to air traffic in the airspace of Donetsk Oblast, but did not close it. On 5 June 2014, traffic was restricted to altitudes above {{convert|26000|feet}} and on 14 July to above {{convert|32000|feet}}.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|179\u2013180}} This did not prevent commercial overflights as commercial traffic typically travels at altitudes of 33,000 to 44,000 feet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://traveltips.usatoday.com/altitude-plane-flight-100359.html|title=What Is the Altitude of a Plane in Flight?|website=traveltips.usatoday.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-24}}</ref> The Russian [[Air traffic control|ATC]] closed the [[airspace]] in the adjacent area over Russia below {{convert|53000|feet}}, effectively closing it to civilian traffic. The reason given was \"armed conflict in Ukraine\". The Dutch Safety Board asked for, but did not receive, a more detailed explanation for this restriction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/en/media/attachment/2018/7/10/debcd724fe7breport_mh17_crash.pdf |title=MH17 Crash|website=Dutch Safety Board|pages=180|access-date=16 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT Maps\">{{cite news |title=Maps of the Crash of Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/07/17/world/europe/maps-of-the-crash-of-malaysian-airlines-flight-mh17.html |date=21 July 2014 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref> As with other countries, Ukraine receives [[Freedoms of the air|overflight fees]] for commercial aircraft that fly through their borders and this may have contributed to the continued availability of civilian flight paths through the conflict zone over [[Flight level|FL]] 320.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/aviation/ukraine-responsible-for-airspace-safety-iata-20140720-zuzmp.html |title=Ukraine responsible for airspace safety: IATA |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |first=Jamie |last=Freed |date=20 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=smh-20140718>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/aviation/mh17-disaster-flights-over-war-zones-because-its-cheaper-20140718-zua0y.html |title=MH17 disaster: Flights over war zones 'because it's cheaper |author1=Tom Whitehead |author2=Nick Collins |author3=Martin Evans |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn the day of MH17 incident, a Ukrainian [[Antonov-26|An-26]] was scheduled to deliver [[paratrooper]]s to the battle arena.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.novayagazeta.ru/inquests/68762.html|title=17 \u0438\u044e\u043b\u044f \u0432 \u0437\u043e\u043d\u0443 \u0410\u0422\u041e \u0434\u043e\u043b\u0436\u0435\u043d \u0431\u044b\u043b \u0432\u044b\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0442\u044c \u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0410\u043d-26 \u0441 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u043c\u0438 \u0434\u0435\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043c\u0438|date=10 June 2015|language=Russian|trans-title=On 17 July an An-26 transport was to fly with Ukrainian paratroopers|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Crash==\n[[File:MH17 map-en.svg|thumb|upright=1.364|Route of Malaysia Airlines Flight 17]]\n[[File:MH17 Flight Route (en).svg|thumb|upright=1.364|Routes of Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 (MH17) and Singapore Airlines Flight 351 (SQ351), including airspace restrictions]]\n\nOn Thursday, 17 July 2014, Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 departed from [[Amsterdam Airport Schiphol]] Gate G3 at 12:13&nbsp;[[Central European Summer Time|CEST]] (10:13&nbsp;[[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]])<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|23}} and took off at 12:31 local time (10:31 UTC). It was due to arrive at [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport]] at 06:10 [[Time in Malaysia|MYT]], Friday, 18 July (22:10 UTC, 17 July).<ref name=BBCbothsides/>\n\nAccording to the original flight plan, MH17 was to fly over Ukraine at [[flight level]] 330 (33,000&nbsp;feet or 10,060&nbsp;metres) and then change to FL 350 around the Ukrainian city of [[Dnipropetrovsk]]. When it reached the area as planned, at 15:53 [[Eastern European Summer Time|local time]] (12:53&nbsp;UTC), [[Dnipropetrovsk]] Air Control (''Dnipro Control'') asked MH17 if they could climb to FL 350 as planned, and also to avoid a potential [[Conflict (air traffic control)|separation conflict]] with another flight, [[Singapore Airlines]] Flight 351 (SQ351), also at FL 330. The crew asked to remain at FL 330 and the air traffic controller approved this request, moving the other flight to FL 350. At 16:00 local time (13:00&nbsp;UTC), the crew asked for a deviation of {{convert|20|nmi|km}} to the left (north) off course, on [[Airway (aviation)|airway]] L980, due to weather conditions. This request was also approved by ''Dnipro Control'' [[Air traffic control|ATC]]. The crew then asked if they could climb to FL 340, which was rejected as this flight level was not available, so MH17 remained at FL 330. At 16:19 local time (13:19 UTC), ''Dnipro Control'' noticed that the flight was {{convert|3.6|nmi|km}} north of the centreline of approved airway and instructed MH17 to return to the track. At 16:19 local time (13:19&nbsp;UTC), ''Dnipro Control'' contacted Russian ATC in [[Rostov-on-Don]] (''RND Control'') by telephone and requested clearance to transfer the flight to Russian [[airspace]]. After obtaining the permission, ''Dnipro Control'' attempted to contact MH17 for handing them off to ''RND Control'' at 16:20 local time (13:20&nbsp;UTC), but the aircraft did not respond. When MH17 did not respond to several calls, ''Dnipro Control'' contacted ''RND Control'' again to check if they could see the aircraft on their radar. ''RND Control'' confirmed that the airplane had disappeared.<ref name=\"dsb1\"/>\n\nThe Dutch Safety Board reported a last flight data recording at 16:20 local time (13:20&nbsp;UTC), located west of the [[urban-type settlement]] Rozsypne (\u0420\u043e\u0437\u0441\u0438\u043f\u043d\u0435), near [[Hrabove, Donetsk Oblast|Hrabove]] heading [[Points of the compass|east-southeast]] (ESE, 115\u00b0) at {{convert|494|kn|km/h mph}}.<ref name=\"dsb1\"/>\n\nAt exactly 16:20:03 local time (13:20:03 UTC) a [[Buk missile system|Buk]] [[surface-to-air|ground-to-air missile]], which had been launched from an area east from the aircraft, detonated outside the aircraft just above the cockpit to the left. An [[Uncontrolled decompression|explosive decompression]] occurred, resulting in both the cockpit and tail sections tearing away from the middle portion of the fuselage. All three sections disintegrated as they fell rapidly towards the ground.\n\nThe majority of debris landed near [[Hrabove, Donetsk Oblast|Hrabove]], a village located north of [[Torez]] in eastern Ukraine's [[Donetsk Oblast]]. The debris spread over a {{convert|50|km2|mi2}} area to the southwest of Hrabove.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\" />{{rp|53}} The fireball on impact is believed to have been captured on video.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10975094/Malaysia-Airlines-crash-video-believed-to-show-moment-of-planes-impact.html |title=Malaysia Airlines crash: video believed to show moment of plane's impact |work=The Telegraph |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Photographs from the site of the crash show scattered pieces of broken [[fuselage]] and [[Aircraft engine|engine]] parts, bodies, and passports.<ref name=\"huffington\">{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/07/17/malaysia-airlines-mh17-passenger-jet-crashes-ukraine-near-russian-border_n_5595450.html |title=Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17 'Shot Down in Ukraine Near Russian Border' |first=Sara C |last=Nelson |date=17 July 2014 |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |location=United Kingdom |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Some of the wreckage fell close to houses.<ref name=\"Telegraaf22866550\">{{cite web |url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/buitenland/22866550/__Vliegtuig_crasht_in_Oekraine__.html |title=Maleisisch passagiersvliegtuig in Oekra\u00efne neergestort |trans-title=Malaysian passenger aircraft shot down in Ukraine |work=[[De Telegraaf]] |language=Dutch |accessdate=17 July 2014 |date=17 July 2014}}</ref> Dozens of bodies fell into crop fields, and some fell into houses.<ref>{{cite news |author=Cahal Milmo |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/malaysia-airlines-mh17-crash-no-forensic-investigators-coordination-or-body-bags-as-locals-are-left-to-scour-the-gruesome-scene-9615895.html |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17 crash: No forensic investigators, co-ordination or body bags as Ukraine locals are left to scour gruesome scene |work=The Independent |date=19 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThree other commercial aircraft were in the same area when the Malaysian airplane crashed: [[Air India]] Flight 113 (AI113), a [[Boeing 787]] en route from [[Delhi]] to [[Birmingham]], [[EVA Air]] Flight 88 (BR88), a [[Boeing 777]] en route from [[Paris]] to [[Taipei]], and the closest aircraft [[Singapore Airlines]] Flight 351 (SQ351) was {{convert|33|km|mi}} away, a Boeing 777 en route from [[Copenhagen]] to [[Singapore]].<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|41}}\n\n==Recovery of bodies==\n[[File:Arrival of corpses from MH17 at Eindhoven Airport.jpg|thumb|First arrival of bodies at [[Eindhoven Airport]]]]\nA Ukraine Foreign Ministry representative said that the bodies found at the crash site would be taken to [[Kharkiv]] for identification, {{convert|270|km|mi}} to the north. By the day after the crash, 181 of the 298 bodies had been found.<ref name=ap-20140718>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/world/official-181-bodies-found-at-mh17-crash-site/article6225245.ece |title=Official: 181 bodies found at MH17 crash site |agency=Associated Press |work=The Hindu |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> Some were observed being placed in [[body bag]]s and loaded onto trucks.<ref name=APBodies>{{cite news |title=Raw: Crews begin moving bodies at jet crash site |url=https://www.usatoday.com/videos/news/nation/2014/07/19/12883715/ |accessdate=19 July 2014 |work=[[USA Today]] |agency=Associated Press |date=19 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=SMHBodies>{{cite news |last1=Miller |first1=Nick |title=MH17: 'Unknown groups' use body bags |url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/mh17-unknown-groups-use-body-bags-20140719-3c8dl.html |accessdate=19 July 2014 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=19 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=GuardianBodies>{{cite news |last1=Grytsenko |first1=Oksana |title=MH17: armed rebels fuel chaos as rotting corpses pile up on the roadside |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/19/mh17-armed-rebels-chaos-corpses-ukraine |accessdate=19 July 2014 |work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nDutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte complained about the lack of respect shown to the personal belongings of the dead which were reportedly being looted. He initially announced his disgust about the handling of the bodies that were reportedly being \"dragged around\" and \"thrown\", but later stated they had been handled with more care than originally thought.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nu.nl/vliegramp-oekraine/3832485/rutte-geschokt-respectloos-gedrag-rampplek.html |title=Rutte geschokt over 'respectloos gedrag' op rampplek |publisher=[[Nu.nl]] |date=19 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |language=Dutch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/31522/Vliegtuigcrash-in-Oekraine/article/detail/3693688/2014/07/21/Rutte-Zorgvuldiger-met-lichamen-omgegaan-dan-werd-gevreesd.dhtml |title=Rutte: 'Zorgvuldiger met lichamen omgegaan dan werd gevreesd' |author=Laura de Jong |date=21 July 2014 |website=[[de Volkskrant]] |language=Dutch}}</ref> On 20 July, Ukrainian emergency workers, observed by armed separatists, began loading the remains of the passengers of MH17 into [[Refrigerated van|refrigerated railway wagons]] for transport and identification.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/some-bodies-removed-from-mh17-crash-site-1405849163 |title=Bodies Removed From MH17 Crash Site Human Remains Moved to Railcars at Torez Station |last=Sonne |first=Paul |author2=Alexander Kolyandr, Margaret Coker |date=20 July 2014 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 July, pro-Russian rebels allowed Dutch investigators to examine the bodies. By this time, 272 bodies had been recovered, according to Ukrainian officials.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28399406 |title=MH17 plane crash: Dutch experts examine bodies |publisher=BBC |date=21 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> Remains left Torez on a train on the evening of 21 July, en route to Kharkiv to be flown to the Netherlands for identification.<ref name=bbc-train>{{cite news |title=MH17 plane crash: Train with bodies leaves Ukraine station |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28411225 |work=BBC News |accessdate=21 July 2014 |date=21 July 2014}}</ref> On the same day, Malaysian Prime Minister [[Najib Razak]] announced that the Malaysian government had reached a tentative agreement to retrieve the remains of the Malaysians who died in the crash, following any necessary forensic work.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marlow |first1=Iain |title=MH17: Malaysia reaches 'behind the scenes' deal to recover bodies |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/mh17-malaysia-reaches-deal-to-recover-bodies-in-race-for-muslim-burials/article19692413/ |accessdate=21 July 2014 |work=The Globe and Mail |date=21 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Convoy of MH-17 victims on the highway.jpg|thumb|Convoy of 40 hearses heading to [[Hilversum]], while other traffic stopped]]\nIt was reported on 21 July that with 282 bodies and 87 body fragments found, there were still 16 bodies missing.<ref name=\"AljazeeraObama7-21\">{{cite news |title=Obama calls for Russia 'pivot' on Ukraine as MH17 investigation begins |url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2014/7/21/obama-ukraine-russia.html |accessdate=21 July 2014 |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=21 July 2014}}</ref> An agreement had been reached that the Netherlands would co-ordinate the identification effort. A train carrying the bodies arrived at the [[Malyshev Factory]], Kharkiv on 22 July.<ref name=nyt-20140722>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/23/world/europe/malaysia-airlines-jet-ukraine.html |title=Bodies of Crash Victims Safely Moved Out of Combat Area |first=Andrew |last=Higgins |newspaper=The New York Times |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> Dutch authorities stated that they found 200 bodies on the train when it arrived at Kharkhiv, leaving almost 100 unaccounted for.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/world/mh17-crash-families-worst-fears-realised-as-bodies-go-missing-20140723-zvv9x.html |title=MH17 crash: families' worst fears realised as bodies go missing |work=The Age |first=Paul |last=McGeough |date=23 July 2014 |accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> In late July, the UK [[Metropolitan Police]] sent specialist officers to Ukraine to assist with the recovery, identification and repatriation of bodies.<ref name=hp-20140719 />\n\nThe first remains were flown to [[Eindhoven]] in the Netherlands on 23 July,<ref name=\"bbc-bodies-kharkiv\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-28416973 |title=MH17 bodies leave Ukraine rebel area and reach Kharkiv |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014 |work=BBC News}}</ref> moved there with Dutch air force [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|C-130]] and Australian [[Boeing C-17 Globemaster III|C-17]] transport aircraft,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/netherlands-to-coordinate-mh17-victim-identification-efforts-114072100077_1.html |title=Netherlands to coordinate MH17 victim identification efforts &#124; Business Standard News |work=Business Standard |date=21 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-07-22/operation-launched-to-recover-and-identify-mh17-victims/5615332 |title=MH17: Tony Abbott announces Operation Bring Them Home to secure and identify victims of Malaysia Airlines disaster \u2013 ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> which landed at [[Eindhoven Airport]] just before 16:00 local time.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/mh17-crash-social-media--blackout-tribute-continues-as-first-bodies-are-to-be-flown-to-netherlands-from-ukraine-9622288.html |title=MH17 crash victims: First bodies arrive in Netherlands from Ukraine |author=Heather Saul |date=23 July 2014 |website=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> The day after, another 74 bodies arrived.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nos.nl/artikel/679047-weer-74-kisten-naar-hilversum.html |title=Weer 74 kisten naar Hilversum |date=24 July 2014 |work=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]] |language=Dutch}}</ref> The examination and identification of the bodies was conducted at the [[Royal Netherlands Army#Services|Netherlands Army]] medical regiment training facility in [[Hilversum]] and was coordinated by a Dutch forensic team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nieuws.nl/algemeen/20140722/hilversum-treft-voorbereidingen-voor-lichamen-mh17/ |title=Hilversum treft voorbereidingen voor lichamen MH17 |work=Nieuws.nl |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140723204451/http://www.nieuws.nl/algemeen/20140722/Hilversum-treft-voorbereidingen-voor-lichamen-MH17 |archive-date=23 July 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 August it was announced that a search and recovery mission, including about 80 forensic police specialists from the Netherlands, Malaysia and Australia, and led by Colonel Cornelis Kuijs of the [[Royal Marechaussee]], would use [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drones]], [[Detection dog|sniffer dogs]], [[Underwater search and recovery|divers]] and [[Satellite imagery|satellite mapping]] to search for missing body parts at the crash site.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/11005039/Dutch-and-Australian-police-to-use-drones-divers-and-sniffer-dogs-in-perilous-search-for-victims.html |title=Dutch and Australian police to use drones, divers and sniffer dogs in perilous search for victims |publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]] (London) |date=1 August 2014 |accessdate=3 August 2014 |first=Tom |last=Parfitt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/05/mh17-investigators-frustrated-at-limited-access-due-to-fighting |title=MH17 investigators frustrated at limited access due to fighting |work=The Guardian |accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> Australian officials had believed that as many as 80 bodies were still at the site,<ref name=\"Guardian AP\" /> but after some days of searching the international team had \"found remains of only a few victims\" and concluded that \"the recovery effort undertaken by local authorities immediately after the crash was more thorough than initially thought.\"<ref name=\"FortunatelyMoreWasDone\">Toby Sterling, [http://bigstory.ap.org/article/dutch-premier-halts-search-ukraine-victims \"Dutch premier halts search for Ukraine victims,\"] Associated Press, 6 August 2014. Retrieved 6 August 2014. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141118080619/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/dutch-premier-halts-search-ukraine-victims|date=18 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 August the Dutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte announced that the recovery operation would be temporarily halted due to an upsurge in fighting around the crash site threatening the safety of crash investigators and recovery specialists, and that all international investigators and humanitarian forces conducting searches would leave the country leaving behind a small communications and liaison team.<ref>{{cite web |author=Helen Davidson and agencies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/07/mh17-crash-search-for-remains-halted |title=MH17 crash: search for remains halted as Australia begins day of mourning |work=The Guardian |date=6 August 2014 |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 August the bodies of 20 Malaysians (of 43 killed in the incident) arrived in Malaysia.<ref name=MH17Guardian>{{cite news |title=MH17 bodies arrive in Malaysia |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/22/mh17-bodies-arrive-in-malaysia |accessdate=22 August 2014 |agency=Agence France-Presse in Kuala Lumpur |date=21 August 2014}}</ref> The government announced a National Mourning Day, with a ceremony broadcast live on radio and television.<ref>{{cite news |author=TheStar |title=MH17 day of mourning: White hearses arrive at KLIA |url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2014/08/22/MH17-Day-of-mourning-white-hearses-at-KLIA/ |date=22 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 October a spokesman for the Dutch national prosecutor's office stated that one victim had been found with an oxygen mask around his neck; a forensic investigation of the mask for fingerprints, saliva and DNA did not produce any results and it is therefore not known how or when that mask got around the neck of the victim.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|99}}\n\nBy 5 December 2014, the Dutch-led forensic team had identified the bodies of 292 out of 298 victims of the crash.<ref>{{cite news |last=Grindstad |first=Ingrid |title=Six MH17 victims remain unidentified |url=http://www.nltimes.nl/2014/12/05/six-mh17-victims-remain-unidentified/ |date=5 December 2014 |accessdate=6 December 2014 |newspaper=NL Times}}</ref> In February and April 2015 new remains were found on the site,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/02/02/ukraine-crisis-mh-idUSL6N0VC3GC20150202 |title=Dutch search team recovers remains, MH17 wreckage in Ukraine |author=Anthony Deutsch |agency=Reuters |date=2 February 2015 |accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=Remains2015>{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/dutch-investigators-recover-human-remains-mh17-crash-110138676.html |title=Dutch investigators recover human remains from MH17 crash site |date=21 April 2015 |accessdate=23 April 2015 |agency=Agence France-Presse}}</ref> after which only 2 victims, both Dutch citizens, had not been identified.<ref name=Remains2015 />\n\n== Reporting in the mass media ==\n''[[De Telegraaf]]'', a large-circulation Dutch tabloid, published on 19 July a front-page photo-collage of pro-Russian rebel leaders, including Igor Girkin, under the one-word headline \"Murderers\" (\"Moordenaars\").<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/malaysia-airlines-mh17-crash-dutch-newspapers-respond-with-anger-and-despair-as-wait-for-return-of-bodies-continues-9618753.html|title=Malaysia Airlines MH17 crash: Dutch newspapers respond with anger and despair as wait for return of bodies continues \u2013 Europe \u2013 World|author=Adam Withnall|date=21 July 2014|accessdate=22 July 2014|newspaper=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nIt was suggested on other media that credit and debit cards may have been looted from the bodies of the victims, and the Dutch Banking Association said it would take \"preventative measures\" against any possible fraud.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/ukraine-plane-crash/dutch-banks-respond-reports-mh17-victims-looted-credit-cards-n160246|title=Dutch Banks Respond to Reports of MH17 Victims' Looted Credit Cards|date=19 July 2014|accessdate=20 July 2014|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> There were also accusations that other possessions had been removed and that evidence at the crash site had been destroyed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10978577/MH17-Malaysia-Airlines-crash-victims-robbed-of-their-dignity-by-rebels.html|title=MH17: Malaysia Airlines crash victims robbed of their dignity by rebels|last1=Mendick|first1=Robert|date=19 July 2014|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=20 July 2014|last2=Sawer|first2=Patrick|last3=Ross|first3=Time}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/heartless-looters-raid-malaysian-airlines-flight-mh17-crash-site-article-1.1872047|title=Heartless looters raid Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17 crash site, swipe victims' luggage, personal items|last1=Wagner|first1=Meg|date=18 July 2014|work=Daily News|accessdate=20 July 2014|location=New York}}</ref> Dutch prime minister [[Mark Rutte]] acknowledged on 6 August that early reports of chaos and criminality around the site may have been exaggerated.<ref name=\"FortunatelyMoreWasDone\" /> One eyewitness observed that valuable items like shoes and bottles of alcohol were untouched in the wreckage.<ref>Shaun Walker with Harriet Salem and Josh Halliday, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/20/mh17-victims-crash-site-anger-russia-grows \"MH17: world's anger at Russia grows as bodies pile on to train at crash site,\"] ''The Guardian'', 21 July 2014. Retrieved 6 August 2014.</ref>\n\nOn 3 July 1988, the [[guided missile cruiser]] {{USS|Vincennes|CG-49|6}} accidentally shot down [[Iran Air Flight 655]], killing 290 passengers.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jeremy |last= Hammond |title=The 'Forgotten' US Shootdown of Iranian Airliner Flight 655 |url=https://www.foreignpolicyjournal.com/2017/07/03/the-forgotten-us-shootdown-of-iranian-airliner-flight-655%C2%AD/ |work=[[Foreign Policy]] |date=3 July 2017}}</ref> In July 2014, when Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 was shot down in Ukraine, some commentators noted the discrepancy of U.S. official position and media coverage of the two similar incidents.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kaplan |first1=Fred |title=America\u2019s Flight 17: The time the United States blew up a passenger plane\u2014and tried to cover it up. |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2014/07/the-vincennes-downing-of-iran-air-flight-655-the-united-states-tried-to-cover-up-its-own-destruction-of-a-passenger-plane.html |work=Slate}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Gusterson |first1=Hugh |title=In Malaysia Airlines tragedy, echoes of a US act |url=https://thebulletin.org/2014/07/in-malaysia-airlines-tragedy-echoes-of-a-us-act/ |work=[[Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists]] |date=27 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Samarth|last=Gupta|title=Hidden Hypocrisy|url=http://harvardpolitics.com/world/hidden-hypocrisy/|date=28 July 2014|publisher=[[Harvard Political Review]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927063213/http://harvardpolitics.com/world/hidden-hypocrisy/|archive-date=27 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|first=Paul R.|last=Pillar|author-link=Paul R. Pillar|title=Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 and Iran Air Flight 655|url=http://nationalinterest.org/blog/paul-pillar/malaysia-airlines-flight-17-iran-air-flight-655-10954|date=24 July 2014|magazine=[[The National Interest]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151013072644/http://nationalinterest.org/blog/paul-pillar/malaysia-airlines-flight-17-iran-air-flight-655-10954|archive-date=13 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nAbout 90 minutes after the incident, Ukraine closed all routes in Eastern Ukrainian airspace, at all altitudes.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|101}} The incident dramatically heightened fears about airliner shootdowns,<ref>{{cite news |title=Air India flight with 126 on board was right behind MH 17 |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Air-India-flight-with-126-on-board-was-right-behind-MH-17/articleshow/38601142.cms |date=18 July 2014 |work=The Times of India |accessdate=12 November 2014 |quote=<!--\"But such fears did not exist over Europe, at least till Terrible Thursday.\"-->}}</ref> leading to some airlines announcing they would avoid overflying conflict zones.\n\nShortly after the crash, it was announced that Malaysia Airlines would retire [[flight number]] MH17 and change the Amsterdam\u2013Kuala Lumpur route to flight number MH19 beginning on 25 July 2014, with the outbound flight unchanged.<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/07/18/malaysia-flight-17-retired-numbers/12827633/ |title=Malaysia will stop using No. 17 next week |first=Bart |last=Jansen |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014 |work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref><ref name=\"ABCAust001\">{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-07-21/mh17-malaysia-airlines-retires-flight-number-out-of-respect-/5610864 |title=MH17: Malaysia Airlines retires flight number after Ukraine crash |date=21 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> In association with the retirement of the Boeing 777 aircraft type from Malaysia Airlines' fleet, Malaysia Airlines terminated service to Amsterdam, opting to codeshare with [[KLM Royal Dutch Airlines|KLM]] on the KUL-AMS route for service beyond 25 January 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://airlineroute.net/2015/12/03/mh-amscdg-jan16cxld/ |title=Malaysia Airlines Cancels Amsterdam / Paris Routes from late-Jan 2016 |work=Airlineroute.net |date=3 December 2015 |accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref> On 18 July 2014, shares in Malaysia Airlines dropped by nearly 16%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/malaysia-airlines-shares-tank-2014-7 |title=Malaysia Airlines Shares Tank |website=Business Insider |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 July 2014, two Ukrainian military jets were hit by missiles at the altitude of {{convert|17000|ft}} close to the area of the MH17 crash. According to the [[National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine|Ukrainian Security Council]], preliminary information indicated that the missiles came from Russia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.trust.org/item/20140723154118-im9dy |title=Ukraine: missiles that brought down jets may have been fired from Russia |accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, Malaysia proposed that the [[United Nations Security Council]] set up an international tribunal to prosecute those deemed responsible for the downing of the airplane. The Malaysian resolution gained a majority on the Security Council, but was vetoed by Russia.<ref name=\"churkin\" /> Russia had proposed its own rival draft resolution, which pushed for a greater U.N. role in an investigation into what caused the downing of the aircraft and demanded justice, but their proposal would not have set up a tribunal.<ref name=\"veto\" />\n\nOn 9 June 2016, a Russian businessman claimed that the shooting down of the airplane put an end to [[Novorossiya (confederation)|hopes of a Russian nation in Ukraine]] and prolonged the War in Donbass.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Loiko|first1=Sergei|title=The Unraveling of Moscow's 'Novorossia' Dream|url=http://www.rferl.mobi/a/unraveling-moscow-novorossia-dream/27772641.html|website=Radio Free Liberty}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nTwo parallel investigations were led by the Dutch, one into the technical cause of the crash, and a separate criminal inquiry.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/11/us-ukraine-mh17-bodies-idUSKCN0IV1NJ20141111?feedType=RSS&virtualBrandChannel=11563 |title=Where are the bodies, MH17 families ask |author=Anthony Deutsch |agency=Reuters |accessdate=11 November 2014 |date=11 November 2014}}</ref> The technical report was released on 13 October 2015,<ref name=\"FinalReportDate\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/final-report-on-downing-of-malaysia-airlines-flight-mh17-due-october-1440675525 |title=Final Report on Downing of Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17 Due October |last=Wall |first=Robert |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=27 August 2015}}</ref> while the criminal investigation reported some of their findings in September 2016.<ref name=\"BBC News 28 September 2016\"/><ref name=\"NLTimesJIT\"/> According to the [[Convention on International Civil Aviation]], the country in which an aviation incident occurs is responsible for the investigation, but that country may delegate the investigation to another state; Ukraine has delegated the leadership of both investigations to the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite news |title=MH17 investigation \u2013 why is Malaysia excluded? |first=Julie |last=L\u00e9vesque |newspaper=eTN Global Travel Industry News |date=3 December 2014 |accessdate=21 December 2014 |url=http://www.eturbonews.com/53217/mh17-investigation-why-malaysia-excluded}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Parker |first1=Andrew |last2=Olearchyk |first2=Roman |title=Netherlands to lead MH17 investigation |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/19c29f34-10e1-11e4-b116-00144feabdc0,Authorised=false.html?_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2F19c29f34-10e1-11e4-b116-00144feabdc0.html%3Fsiteedition%3Duk&siteedition=uk&_i_referer= |accessdate=22 July 2014 |work=Financial Times |agency=Financial Times Ltd |date=21 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Bewerkt door: redactie |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/31522/Vliegtuigcrash-in-Oekraine/article/detail/3698000/2014/07/24/Nederlandse-leidersrol-krijgt-juridische-basis.dhtml |title=Nederlandse leidersrol krijgt juridische basis \u22120 Vliegtuigcrash in Oekra\u00efne \u2013 VK |work=De Volkskrant |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dutch Safety Board heads investigation: investigation effort in full swing, black boxes currently being read out |url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/uploads/fm/2014_07_23_PB_OVV_neemt_leiding_over_ENG_DEF.pdf |website=onderzoeksraad.nl |publisher=[[Dutch Safety Board]], The Hague |accessdate=24 July 2014 |date=23 July 2014 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ShCuUTie?url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/uploads/fm/2014_07_23_PB_OVV_neemt_leiding_over_ENG_DEF.pdf |archivedate=19 September 2014 }} ()</ref>\n\n===On-site investigation===\n<!--{{2013\u20132014 unrest in Ukraine}} Already covered and more appropriate at bottom of article in a collapsible bar anyway -->\nIn the hours following the crash, a meeting was convened of the [[Trilateral Contact Group on Ukraine|Trilateral Contact Group]]. After they had held a video conference with representatives of insurgents affiliated with the Donetsk People's Republic (who controlled the area where the aircraft crashed), the rebels promised to \"provide safe access and security guarantees\" to \"the national investigation commission\" by co-operating with Ukrainian authorities and OSCE ([[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]]) monitors.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.osce.org/home/121390 |title=Press statement by the Trilateral Contact Group |publisher=Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140908053442/http://www.osce.org/home/121390 |archivedate=8 September 2014 }}</ref> During the first two days of investigation, the militants prevented the OSCE and the workers of [[State Emergency Service of Ukraine|Ukrainian Emergencies Ministry]] from freely working at the crash site. [[Andrei Purgin]], a leader of the Donetsk People's Republic, declared later that \"we will guarantee the safety of international experts on the scene as soon as Kiev concludes a ceasefire agreement\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Walker |first1=Shaun |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/20/mh17-pro-russia-rebels-crash-site-kiev-ceasefire |title=MH17: pro-Russia rebels will allow access to crash site if ceasefire agreed |work=The Guardian |accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Investigation of the crash site of MH-17.jpg|thumb|Dutch and Australian police at the crash site on 3 August 2014]]\nBy 18 July 2014, the [[flight data recorder]] and the [[cockpit voice recorder]] had been recovered by separatists,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/07/18/malaysia-airlines-mh17-black-boxes-reportedly-recovered-russia-denies-it-will-take-them-from-rebels/ |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17 black boxes reportedly recovered, Russia denies it will take them from rebels |work=National Post |date=22 May 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> and three days later were handed over to Malaysian officials in [[Donetsk]].<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|44}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Walker |first1=Shaun |last2=Salem |first2=Harriet |title=Ukraine rebels hand over MH17 black boxes and let train carrying bodies leave |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/22/mh17-black-boxes-handed-over-pro-russia-rebels |accessdate=21 February 2019 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> The voice recorder was damaged but there was no evidence that data had been tampered with.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|45}}\n\nThe [[National Bureau of Air Accidents Investigation of Ukraine]], which led investigations, both off-site and on-site, during the first days after the crash,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbaai.gov.ua/news.html?id=6&lang=ua |title=\u0420\u043e\u0437\u0441\u043b\u0456\u0434\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0438 \u043b\u0456\u0442\u0430\u043a\u0430 Boeing 777 |publisher=NBAAI |date=18\u201325 August 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref> had by August 2014 delegated the investigation to the DSB because of the large number of Dutch passengers and the flight having originated in [[Amsterdam]].<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|14}}<ref>\"[http://onderzoeksraad.nl/en/onderzoek/2049/investigation-crash-mh17-17-july-2014/onderzoek/1559/questions-and-answers-concerning-the-investigation-into-flight-mh17#fasen Investigation crash MH17, 17 July 2014].\" [[Dutch Safety Board]]. Retrieved 22 August 2014. \"Ukraine has transferred responsibility for investigating the cause of the crash to the Dutch Safety Board. The request came from Ukraine. This request was made because the flight departed from the Netherlands, and due to the large number of Dutch nationals who died in the crash\"</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://nos.nl/nieuwsuur/artikel/2139769-mh17-misbruikt-voor-opvoeren-spanning-met-rusland.html |title=MH17 misbruikt voor opvoeren spanning met Rusland |access-date=17 July 2019 |work=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]] |date=26 October 2016 |language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 July 2014, a Malaysian team of 133 officials, search and recovery personnel, and forensics, technical and medical experts arrived in Ukraine.<ref>{{cite news |title=MH17 plane crash: Dutch experts examine bodies |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-28399406 |accessdate=22 July 2014 |publisher=BBC |date=21 July 2014}}</ref> Also Australia sent a 45-member panel headed by former [[Air chief marshal (Australia)|Air Chief Marshal]] [[Angus Houston]], who had earlier supervised the [[Malaysia Airlines Flight 370|MH 370 probe]].<ref>{{cite news |title=MH370 search coordinator to lead Australia's MH17 probe Panel |url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/07/mh370-search-coordinator-to-lead-australias-mh17-probe-panel/ |agency=Indo-Asian News Service |publisher=news.biharprabha.com |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> Approximately 200 special forces soldiers from Australia were also deployed to provide support for the JIT investigators.<ref name=\"smhabbotttroops\">{{cite web|last1=Wroe|first1=David|title=Tony Abbott's office floated sending Australian troops into Ukraine conflict, defence expert claims|url=https://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/federal-election-2016/tony-abbotts-office-floated-sending-australian-troops-into-ukraine-conflict-defence-expert-claims-20160612-gphbab.html|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=Fairfax Media|accessdate=13 October 2017|date=13 June 2017|quote=In the end, Australia quietly deployed about 200 special forces soldiers in a low-key role supporting police investigators.}}</ref> The United Kingdom sent six investigators from the [[Air Accidents Investigation Branch]] (AAIB) and the UK [[Foreign Office]] sent extra consular staff to Ukraine.<ref name=hp-20140719>{{cite news |title=Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17: British Investigators Join Probe in Ukraine Amid Fears of Evidence Tampering |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/07/19/malaysia-airlines-flight-mh17_n_5601582.html |accessdate=19 July 2014 |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=19 July 2014}}</ref> It took until late July before the full international team could start working at the crash site,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/01/mh17-investigators-reach-crash-site-ukraine-search-bodies |title=MH17 investigators reach crash site two weeks after plane brought down |work=The Guardian |date=1 August 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref> under the leadership of the [[Ministry of Defence (Netherlands)|Dutch Ministry of Defence]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.houseofrepresentatives.nl/sites/www.houseofrepresentatives.nl/files/news_items/140728ambtelijke_briefing_mh17_beknopt_engels_1.doc |title=Summary Report of a Briefing at Civil Service Level |publisher=[[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|House of Representatives]] |date=28 July 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 July 2014, a Ukrainian representative said that pro-Russian rebels had mined approaches to the crash site and moved heavy artillery.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/still-no-safe-passage-to-malaysia-airlines-crash-site-1406714025 |title=Still No Safe Passage to Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 Crash Site in Eastern Ukraine |first1=Alexander |last1=Kolyandr |first2=Gabriele |last2=Steinhauser |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |date=30 July 2014 |accessdate=2 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 August 2014, the experts left the crash site due to concerns about their safety.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Outlook India |agency=Press Trust of India |title=21 More MH17 Crash Victims Identified, Experts Leave Site |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/news/article/21-More-MH17-Crash-Victims-Identified-Experts-Leave-Site/854102 |date=8 August 2014 |accessdate=17 August 2014}}</ref> In mid-September they unsuccessfully attempted to regain access to the site.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!-- no author--> |title=Netherlands deploys more experts to probe MH17 crash |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/netherlands-deploys-more-experts-to-probe-mh17-crash/498540-2.html |agency=Press Trust of India |newspaper=CNN-IBNLive |date=13 September 2014 |accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.oneindia.in/international/additional-mh17-crash-investigators-return-to-netherlands-1525660.html#infinite-scroll-1 |title=Additional MH17 crash investigators return to Netherlands |publisher=[[Oneindia.in]] |date=20 September 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref> On 13 October 2014, a Dutch-Ukrainian team resumed recovery of victims' personal belongings.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newsweek.com/dutch-experts-help-recover-mh17-crash-items-despite-nearby-clashes-277024 |title=Dutch Experts Help Recover MH17 Crash Items Despite Nearby Clashes |work=Newsweek |date=13 October 2014 |accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref> In mid-November 2014, work was undertaken to remove part of the wreckage from the crash site. Earlier efforts by the recovery team to salvage the MH17 wreckage had been frustrated by disagreements with the local rebels.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-30000967 |title=MH17 crash: Dutch salvage team 'unable to start' |accessdate=2 December 2014 |publisher=BBC |date=11 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-26248275 |title=Ukraine crisis: Timeline |accessdate=2 December 2014 |publisher=BBC |date=13 November 2014}}</ref> The recovery operation took one week to complete. The debris was transported to the Netherlands where investigators reconstructed parts of the airplane.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-11-24/dutch-complete-mh17-wreckage-recovery-in-ukraine/5912572 |title=MH17: Dutch complete recovery of Malaysia Airlines wreckage in eastern Ukraine |date=24 November 2014 |accessdate=24 November 2014 |agency=Agence France-Presse |publisher=ABC News}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, possible [[Buk missile system|Buk missile launcher]] parts were found at the crash site by the Dutch led [[#Criminal investigation|joint investigation team]] (JIT).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dearden |first1=Lizzie |title=MH17 crash: Investigators find possible parts of Buk missile used to shoot plane down |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/mh17-crash-investigators-find-parts-of-buk-missile-possibly-used-to-shoot-plane-down-10450053.html |accessdate=11 August 2015 |work=The Independent |date=11 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Investigation into possible Buk-missile-parts |url=https://www.om.nl/vaste-onderdelen/zoeken/@90384/investigation-into/ | work=Landelijk Parket |publisher=Openbaar Ministerie (Dutch public prosecution service) |accessdate=11 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Cause of the crash===\n[[File:Buk-M1-2 9A310M1-2.jpg|thumb|upright|A mobile [[Buk missile system|Buk surface-to-air missile]] launcher, similar to that concluded to have been used in the incident]]\n<!-- The audio has been widely published/played in media coverage and is a significant & noteworthy piece of evidence. Discuss on the talk page section: \"Deletion of External Link to Wiretaps Audio\" and \"YouTube ref\" -->\n{{external media| float  = right| width  =| image1 =| audio1 = {{YouTube|BbyZYgSXdyw|Pro-Russian rebels discuss the shooting down of an aircraft}} Intercepted phone calls, verified with voice recognition by the National Security Agency,<ref name=\"Landay\"/> between rebels discussing which rebel group shot down the aircraft and initial reports that it was a civilian aircraft. Audio (in Russian) released by [[Security Service of Ukraine]] with English subtitles.<ref name=\"ONE News\"/><ref name=\"Demirjian\"/>}}\n\nSoon after the crash both American and Ukrainian officials said that a 9M38 series surface-to-air missile strike was the most likely cause.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ensor |first=Josie |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10977644/MH17-what-we-know-two-days-after-Malaysia-Airlines-crash-over-Ukraine.html |title=MH17: what we know two days after Malaysia Airlines crash over Ukraine |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=19 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> If so, then the missile was fired from a mobile Soviet-designed [[Buk missile system]] ([[NATO reporting name]]: SA-11 \"Gadfly\"). At the time, Buk was the only surface-to-air missile system known to be deployed in the region that was capable of reaching the cruising altitude of commercial air traffic.<ref name=\"BakerNYT\"/><ref>{{cite web |first=Wil |last=Thijssen |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/31522/Vliegtuigcrash-in-Oekraine/article/detail/3692229/2014/07/19/De-bewijsstukken-Wie-schoot-MH17-neer.dhtml |title=De bewijsstukken: Wie schoot MH17 neer? |newspaper=[[de Volkskrant]] |date=19 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |language=Dutch}}</ref><ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\">{{cite news |first1=Ralph |last1=Vartabedian |first2=W.J. |last2=Hennigan |title=High-tech spycraft tracked missile's path to Malaysia Airlines jet |url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-fg-satellites-ukraine-missile-20140717-story.html |accessdate=21 July 2014 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=17 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">Robert Mendick (27 July 2014) [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10993020/MH17-why-the-culprits-may-never-be-caught.html MH17: why the culprits may never be caught] ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''</ref><ref name=\"Aust-ABC002\">{{cite web |title=MH17 likely shot down by mistake by Russian separatists, US intelligence official says |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-07-23/mh17-likely-shot-down-by-accident-by-russian-separatists/5616748 |publisher=ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |date=23 July 2014 |accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"kyivpost1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/sbu-releases-more-conversations-implicating-russia-in-shooting-down-malaysia-airlines-flight-video-transcript-2-356778.html |title=SBU releases more conversations implicating Russia in shooting down Malaysia Airlines flight (VIDEO, TRANSCRIPT) |work=Kyiv Post |date=14 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> Such systems, unless they receive information from larger networks, have limited capacity to distinguish between military and civilian airplanes. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/529156/how-can-a-civilian-plane-accidentally-be-shot-down/|title=Design of Surface-to-Air Missile Systems Makes Accidents Far from Improbable|last=Majumdar|first=Dave|website=MIT Technology Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/the-flaw-in-the-buk-missile-system-2014-7|title=This Flaw In The Buk Missile System Makes It Really Easy To Accidentally Shoot Down A Passenger Jet|last=Rosen|first=Armin|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2014/07/18/did-the-ukrainian-rebels-even-know-they-were-shooting-at-a-civilian-aircraft/|title=Did the Ukrainian rebels even know they were shooting at a civilian aircraft?|last=Fung|first=Brian|last2=|date=|website=Washington Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-12|last3=}}</ref> \n\nAccording to defence analyst Reed Foster (from [[Jane's Information Group]]), the contour of the aluminium and the blistering of the paint around many of the holes on the aircraft fragments indicate that small, high-velocity [[Fragmentation (weaponry)|fragments]] entered the aircraft externally, a damage pattern indicative of an SA-11.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/07/21/world/europe/wreckage-offers-clues-on-why-flight-17-went-down.html |title=Wreckage Offers Clues on Why Flight 17 Went Down |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> Ballistics specialist Stephan Fruhling of the [[Australian National University]]'s [[Strategic and Defence Studies Centre]] concurred with this, explaining that since it struck the cockpit rather than an engine it was probably a radar guided, rather than heat seeking, missile equipped with a [[proximity fuze]]d [[warhead]] such as an SA-11.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/photo-of-mh17-wreckage-proves-missile-attack-claims-report-20140722-zvjur.html |title=Photo of MH17 wreckage proves missile attack, claims report |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |author=Rose Powell |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> \n\nShortly after the crash, [[Igor Girkin]], leader of the Donbass separatists, was reported to have posted on social media network [[VKontakte]], taking credit for downing a Ukrainian An-26.<ref name=\"VK Wall\">{{cite web|url=https://vk.com/wall-57424472_7256 |title=Wall \u2013 VK |date=17 July 2014 |work=archive.org |accessdate=22 October 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717155720/https://vk.com/wall-57424472_7256 |archivedate=17 July 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.interpretermag.com/evidence-of-separatists-possession-of-buk-system-before-downing-of-mh17/ |title=Evidence of Separatists' Possession of Buk System Before Downing of MH17 |work=The Interpreter Magazine |date=27 July 2014 |accessdate=25 February 2015 |author=Catherine A. Fitzpatrick}}</ref><ref name=\"Boroday20140813\"/> This news was repeated by channels in Russia, with LifeNews reporting \"a new victory of Donetsk self-defence who shot down yet another Ukrainian airplane\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bbc.com/russian/features-37496581|title=\u041a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0430 MH17: \u043a\u0430\u043a \u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u043b\u0438\u0441\u044c \u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0421\u041c\u0418|last=\u0411\u0443\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430|first=\u041e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0430|date=28 September 2016|newspaper=BBC \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430|language=en-GB|access-date=29 September 2016}}</ref> Russian news agency [[TASS]] also reported eyewitness accounts claiming that the Donbass militia had just shot down a Ukrainian An-26 military airplane with a missile.<ref name=tassan26/> The separatists later denied involvement, saying they did not have the equipment or training to hit a target at that altitude.<ref>{{cite news |author=Rick Feneley |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/attack-on-flight-mh17-after-the-tragedy-the-accusations-rain-down-20140718-zumq4.html |title=Attack on Flight MH17: After the tragedy, the accusations rain down |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/comment/smh-editorial/mh17-ultimate-responsibility-lies-with-putin-20140718-zuc0v.html |title=MH17: Ultimate responsibility lies with Putin |work=The Age |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Europe/2014/0717/Web-evidence-points-to-pro-Russia-rebels-in-downing-of-MH17-video |title=Web evidence points to pro-Russia rebels in downing of MH17 (+video) |work=The Christian Science Monitor |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref> Russian media also reported that [[Alexander Borodai]] called one of the Moscow media managers 40 minutes after the crash, saying that \"likely we shot down a civilian airliner\".<ref name=\"Boroday20140813\">{{cite web |url=http://www.interpretermag.com/novaya-gazeta-editor-boroday-called-moscow-press-about-downing-of-civilian-airliner/ |title=Novaya Gazeta Editor: Boroday Called Moscow Press About Downing of Civilian Airliner |work=The Interpreter Magazine |date=13 August 2014 |accessdate=25 February 2015 |author=Catherine A. Fitzpatrick}}</ref>\n\nWitnesses in [[Torez]] reported sightings on the day of the incident of what appeared to be a [[Buk missile system|Buk missile launcher]],<ref name=walker>{{cite web |last1=Walker |first1=Shaun |title=Ukrainians report sightings of missile launcher on day of MH17 crash |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/22/ukraine-sightings-missile-launcher-mh17?CMP=twt_gu |work=The Guardian |accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> and [[Associated Press|AP]] journalists reported sightings of a Buk system in separatist controlled [[Snizhne]].<ref name=Karmanau/> The witness reports backed up photographs and videos which had been posted online, of the Buk launcher in rebel-held territory.<ref name=walker/>\n\nOn 19 July 2014, Vitaly Nayda, the chief of the Counter Intelligence Department of the [[Security Service of Ukraine]] (SBU), told a news conference, \"We have compelling evidence that this terrorist act was committed with the help of the Russian Federation. We know clearly that the crew of this system were Russian citizens.\"<ref>{{cite news |agency=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/19/us-ukraine-crisis-intelligence-idUSKBN0FO0GD20140719 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |date=19 July 2014 |title=Ukraine says has 'compelling evidence' Russian crew shot down Malaysian plane |first1=Pavel |last1=Polityuk |first2=Elizabeth |last2=Piper|editor1-first=Louise|editor1-last=Ireland |archivedate=19 July 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719125225/https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/19/us-ukraine-crisis-intelligence-idUSKBN0FO0GD20140719}}</ref><ref name=espreso-20140719>{{cite news |url=http://espreso.tv/news/2014/07/19/raketnym_kompleksom_buk_yakyy_zbyv_boeing_777_keruvaly_rosiyany___sbu |title=\u0420\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043c \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u043e\u043c \"\u0411\u0443\u043a\", \u044f\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0437\u0431\u0438\u0432 Boeing-777 \u043a\u0435\u0440\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0456\u044f\u043d\u0438, \u2013 \u0421\u0411\u0423 (Missile complex \"BUK\", that shot Boeing-777 was managed by Russian citizens) \u2013 Espreso.tv (leading Ukrainian news agency) |agency=[[Espreso.tv]] |date=19 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Schofield |first=Matthew |url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/2014/07/19/233825/ukraine-video-claims-proof-of.html?sp=/99/100/&ihp=1 |title=Ukraine video claims proof of Russia-supplied anti-aircraft system |publisher=Mcclatchydc.com |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref> He cited what he said were recorded conversations in which separatists expressed satisfaction to Russian intelligence agents that they brought down an aircraft.<ref name=\"ForbesPRG1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paulroderickgregory/2014/07/18/smoking-guns-russian-separatists-shot-down-malaysian-plane/ |work=[[Forbes]] |title=Smoking Guns: Russian Separatists Shot Down Malaysian Flight MH17; Putin Must Be Held Responsible |first=Paul Roderick |last=Gregory |date=18 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ForbesPRG2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paulroderickgregory/2014/07/19/what-more-smoking-guns-are-needed-for-mh17-the-worlds-first-sam-terrorism/ |title=Here Are The Intercepted Transcripts Indicating Russian Rebels Shot Down Malaysian Flight MH17 |work=Forbes |first=Paul Roderick |last=Gregory |date=19 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> While one of the involved persons acknowledged that these conversations took place, the separatists denied that they were related to the crash of MH17 and blamed the Ukrainian government for shooting it down.<ref name=BBCbothsides>{{cite news |title=MH17 Malaysia plane crash in Ukraine: What we know |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28357880 |work=BBC News |accessdate=21 July 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718121104/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28357880 |archivedate=18 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0411\u0435\u0441 \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0433 \u043e\u0431\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0432 \u0443\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0442\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \"\u0411\u043e\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0430\" |url=http://lenta.ru/news/2014/07/18/bezler/ |publisher=[[Lenta.ru]] |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=APbothsides>{{cite news |title=Both sides in Ukraine deny shooting down plane |url=http://hosted2.ap.org/PASCR/a5050f4ad4f44dafab85bb41a15281cf/Article_2014-07-17-EU--Ukraine-Plane/id-080a6229c3e249c3b05226215d0da426 |work=Associated Press |accessdate=21 July 2014 |first1=Peter |last1=Leonard |first2=Mstyslav |last2=Chernov}}</ref><ref name=\"nationalpost1\">{{cite news |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/07/17/malaysian-passenger-plane-was-shot-down-by-rebels-intercepted-phone-calls-prove-ukraines-president-says/ |title=Malaysian plane was shot down by rebels, intercepted phone calls prove, Ukraine's president says |work=[[National Post]] |publisher=Associated Press via [[Postmedia Network]] |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> According to Nayda, a Buk launcher used in the shootdown was moved back into Russia the night after the attack.<ref name=Karmanau/> The SBU released another recording, which they said was of pro-Russian-separatist leader [[Igor Bezler]] being told of an approaching aircraft two minutes before MH17 was shot down. Bezler said the recording was real, but referred to a different incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/29/-sp-ukraine-rebel-igor-bezler-interview-demon |title=The Guardian 29 July 2014 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> The head of the SBU, [[Valentyn Nalyvaichenko]], later concluded that rebels intended to shoot down a Russian airliner in a [[false flag|false flag operation]] to give Russia a pretext to invade Ukraine, but shot down MH17 by mistake.<ref>{{citation |title=Separatists planned terrorist attacks against Aeroflot aircraft on day of MH17 crash as pretext for Russian invasion into Ukraine- SBU chief |work=[[Radio Ukraine International]] |date=7 August 2014 |accessdate=21 November 2014 |url=http://www.nrcu.gov.ua/en/148/573400/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129041421/http://www.nrcu.gov.ua/en/148/573400/ |archivedate=29 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ukraine Says Rebels Mistook Doomed Flight MH17 for Aeroflot Plane |first=Anna |last=Dolgov |newspaper=Moscow Times |date=8 August 2014 |accessdate=21 November 2014 |url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/ukraine-says-rebels-mistook-doomed-flight-mh17-for-aeroflot-plane/504793.html}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Terrorists and militants planned cynical terrorist attack at Aeroflot civil aircraft |work=[[Security Service of Ukraine]] |date=7 August 2014 |accessdate=7 June 2015 |url=http://www.sbu.gov.ua/sbu/control/en/publish/article?art_id=129860 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721074226/http://www.sbu.gov.ua/sbu/control/en/publish/article?art_id=129860 |archive-date=21 July 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nJournalists from the [[Associated Press]] in Snizhne, Ukraine reported seeing a Buk M-1 enter the town operated by a man \"with unfamiliar fatigues and a distinctive Russian accent\" escorted by two civilian vehicles, which then moved off in the direction where the shootdown later occurred.  According to Ukrainian counterterrorism chief, Vitaly Nayda, after downing the airplane under separatist direction, the launcher's Russian crew quickly moved it back across the border into Russia.<ref name=\"Karmanau\"/>\n\nOn 22 July 2014, a rebel fighter revealed to an Italian reporter that fellow separatists had told his unit the aircraft had been shot down under the assumption that it was Ukrainian.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.corriere.it/esteri/14_luglio_22/cosi-stato-colpito-l-aereo-0a7e5f9e-115f-11e4-affb-3320a03d21e8.shtml |title=Cos\u00ec \u00e8 stato colpito l'aereo |trans-title=So the plane was struck |language=Italian |newspaper=[[Corriere della Sera]] |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014 |first=Lorenzo |last=Cremonesi}}</ref> This information was verified and confirmed on the same day by a German newspaper.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/ausland/europa/separatisten-sollten-piloten-der-mh17-festnehmen-13059009.html |title=Separatisten am Abschussort sollten Piloten festnehmen |trans-title=Separatists at the crash site should capture pilots |work=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]] |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014 |author=Konrad Schuller}}</ref> Unnamed American intelligence officials stated that sensors that traced the path of the missile, [[Fragmentation (weaponry)|shrapnel]] patterns in the wreckage, voice print analysis of separatists' conversations in which they claimed credit for the strike, and photos and other data from social media sites all indicated that Russian-backed separatists had fired the missile.<ref name=\"WaPoJuly22\"/>\n\nAmerican officials said that satellite data from infrared sensors detected the explosion of Flight MH17.<ref name=\"ReutersIndia\">{{cite news |url=http://in.reuters.com/article/idINKBN0FN2QK20140718 |title=U.S scrambles to determine who fired Russian-made missile at jet |first=Phil |last=Stewart |first2=Mark |last2=Hosenball |date=19 July 2014 |agency=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> American intelligence agencies said that analysis of the launch plume and trajectory suggested the missile was fired from an area near Torez and Snizhne.<ref name=\"BakerNYT\"/><ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\"/> The British ''[[The Daily Telegraph|Daily Telegraph]]'' said: \"''The Telegraph''{{'}}s own inquiries suggest the missile, an SA-11 from a Buk mobile rocket launcher, was possibly fired from a cornfield about {{convert|12|mi|km|order=flip}} to the south of the epicentre of the crash site.\"<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/> Other sources suggest the missile was launched from the separatist-controlled town of Chernukhino.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/easternapproaches/2014/07/flight-mh17 |title=Flight MH17: The Evidence |author=M.J.S. |work=The Economist |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> Several other media outlets including ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and the ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]'' reported that the aeroplane is believed to have been downed by a rebel-fired missile.<ref name=\"Guardian AP\">{{cite news |agency=Australian Associated Press |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/01/australia-mh17-bodies-retrieved-from-crash-site-within-days |title=Australia says all MH17 bodies should be retrieved from crash site within days |work=The Guardian |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Washington Post Tharoor\">Ishaan Tharoor \u2013 [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2014/07/20/the-evidence-that-may-prove-pro-russian-separatists-shot-down-mh17/ The evidence that may prove pro-Russian separatists shot down MH17] \u2013 The Washington Post \u2013 20 July 2014. Retrieved 3 August 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Paul McGeough |url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/ukraine-war-zone-tempers-federal-police-attempts-to-access-mh17-crash-site-20140801-zzkxy.html |title=Ukraine war zone tempers Federal Police attempts to access MH17 crash site |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=14 June 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAn unnamed American intelligence official stated that Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17 may have been shot down in error by pro-Russian separatists, citing evidence that separatists launched an SA-11 surface-to-air missile that blew up the Malaysian airliner. They said it was possible the rebel was a former member of the [[Armed Forces of Ukraine]] who had [[Defection|defected]] to the pro-Russian separatists.<ref name=\"LAtimes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/world/europe/la-fg-ukraine-intelligence-us-20140722-story.html |title=U.S. officials believe attack against Malaysian plane was mistake |work=Los Angeles Times |date=22 July 2014}}</ref> The official dismissed Russian allegations that MH17 took evasive action and said the claim that the Ukrainian government had shot down MH17 was not realistic, as Kiev had no such missile systems in that area, which was rebel-controlled.<ref name=\"Aust-ABC002\"/> American intelligence officials also said that Russia was attempting to disguise the flow of weaponry it was delivering to the rebels by sending older weapons that matched Ukraine's inventory.<ref name=\"WaPoJuly22\"/> The British [[Foreign Office]] stated that it was \"highly likely\" that the missile was fired from an area controlled by Russian-backed separatists.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2014/07/26/ukraine-crisis-britain-mh17-plane-idINKBN0FV0J720140726 |title=Britain says highly likely MH17 shot down by Russian-supplied missile |agency=Reuters |date=26 July 2014 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Russian Ministry of Defence]] has maintained that American claims of separatist responsibility were \"unfounded\", and said that the American intelligence agencies have not released any of the data on which they based their conclusions.<ref>{{cite news |title=US Claims of Flight MH17 Downing by Militia Remain Unfounded \u2013 Russia's Defense Ministry |url=http://en.ria.ru/russia/20140724/191186319/US-Claims-of-Flight-MH17-Downing-by-Militia-Remain-Unfounded-.html |agency=RIA Novosti |date=24 July 2014 |quote=The United States has not yet provided any documented evidence to prove that the rocket that brought down the Malaysia Airlines Boeing 777 was launched from militia-controlled territory, Russian Deputy Defence Minister Anatoly Antonov said on Thursday.}}</ref> According to the Russian military, in what the ''[[New York Magazine]]'' called \"Russia's Conspiracy Theory\", MH17 was shot down by the Ukrainians, using either a surface-to-air missile or a fighter aircraft.<ref name=newyork>{{citation |title=Russia's 'Conspiracy Theory': MH17 Shot Down by Ukrainian Fighter Jet or Missile |work=New York |first=Margaret |last=Hartmann |url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2014/07/russia-mh17-downed-by-ukrainian-jet-missile.html |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=20 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Russia Presents Its Account of Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 Crash |first=Olga |last=Razumovskaya |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=21 July 2014 |accessdate=20 September 2014 |url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/russia-presents-its-account-of-malaysia-airlines-flight-17-crash-1405952441?mod=e2tw}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 July 2014, the Russian Ministry of Defence (MoD) held a press conference and said that while the Boeing 777 was crashing, a Ukrainian Su-25 ground-attack aircraft approached to within {{convert|3|to|5|km|mi}} of the Malaysian airliner. The MoD also claimed that satellite photographs showed that the Ukrainian army moved a Buk SAM battery to the area close to the territory controlled by the rebels on the morning of 17 July, hours before the crash. They said the installation was then moved away again by 18 July.<ref name=\"wsj russian version\">{{cite news |author=Razumovskaya, Olga |title=Russia Presents Its Account of Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 Crash |url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/russia-presents-its-account-of-malaysia-airlines-flight-17-crash-1405952441 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> Promoted by Russian media, the idea that a Su-25 could have downed the Boeing 777 with an [[air-to-air missile]] was dismissed by chief designer of the Su-25, Vladimir Babak.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uatoday.tv/news/general-designer-of-su-25-says-aircraft-couldn-t-have-shot-down-mh17-414628.html |title=General designer of Su-25 says aircraft couldn't have shot down MH17 |publisher=Ukraine Today |date=11 March 2015 |accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref> In 2015 [[Bellingcat]] purchased satellite photos from the same area and time as used by the MoD and demonstrated that they had used older photos (May and June 2014) in their presentation that were edited to make a Ukrainian Buk launcher appear as if it was removed after the attack.<ref>{{cite news |title=MH17-Absturz kontert Kritik mit neuen Satellitenbildern |url=http://www.zeit.de/politik/ausland/2015-06/bellingcat-russland-mh17-satellitenfotos-manipulation |language=German |date=12 June 2015 |accessdate=17 June 2015 |newspaper=De Zeit}}</ref> In the report published by the Dutch Safety Board, an air-to-air missile strike was ruled out.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nIn an interview with [[Reuters]] on 23 July 2014, [[Alexander Khodakovsky]], the commander of the pro-Russian [[Vostok Battalion (Donbass)#Vostok Battalion|Vostok Battalion]], acknowledged that the separatists had an anti-aircraft missile of the type the Americans had said was used to shoot down the aircraft, and said that it could have been sent back to Russia to remove proof of its presence;<ref name=\"ReutersKho\">{{cite news |agency=Reuters |date=23 July 2014 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/23/us-ukraine-crisis-commander-exclusive-idUSKBN0FS1V920140723 |title=Ukraine rebel commander acknowledges fighters had Buk missile |author=Anton Zverev}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Shaun Walker in Donetsk |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/23/mh17-ukraine-separatists-buk-missile-system |title=MH17: Ukraine separatist commander 'admits' rebels had Buk missile system |work=The Guardian |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Buckley |first=Neil |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/26fe789c-126e-11e4-a581-00144feabdc0.html |title=Separatist leader admits Ukraine rebels held Buk missile system |work=Financial Times |date=4 July 2014 |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> he later retracted his comments, saying that he had been misquoted and stating that rebels never had a Buk.<ref name=\"GuardianKho\">{{cite web |last1=Walker |first1=Shaun |title=MH17: Ukraine separatist commander 'admits' rebels had Buk missile system |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/23/mh17-ukraine-separatists-buk-missile-system |work=The Guardian |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> In November 2014 he repeated that the separatists had a Buk launcher at the time, but stated that the vehicle, under control of fighters from Luhansk, had still been on its way to Donetsk when MH17 crashed. It was then withdrawn to avoid being blamed.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lanting |first=Bert |title=Wij hadden raket, maar haalden MH17 niet neer |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/dossier-rampvlucht-mh17/wij-hadden-raket-maar-haalden-mh17-niet-neer~a3782013 |language=Dutch |newspaper=de Volkskrant |date=4 November 2014 |accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 July 2014, Ukrainian security official Andriy Lysenko announced, at a press conference, that black box recorder analysis had revealed that the aircraft had been brought down by shrapnel that caused \"massive explosive decompression.\" Dutch officials were reported to be \"stunned\" by what they saw as a \"premature announcement\" and said that they had not provided this information.<ref>{{cite news |author=Natasha Culzac |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/mh17-crash-black-boxes-show-plane-suffered-massive-explosive-decompression-following-shrapnel-hit-9632881.html |title=MH17 crash: Black boxes show plane suffered 'massive explosive decompression' following shrapnel hit \u2013 Europe \u2013 World |work=[[The Independent]] |date=28 July 2014 |accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 September 2014, the [[BBC]] released new material by [[John Sweeney (journalist)|John Sweeney]] who cited three civilian witnesses from Donbass who saw the Buk launcher in the rebel-controlled territory on the day when MH17 crashed. Two witnesses said the crew of the launcher and a military vehicle escorting it did not have local accents and spoke with [[Moscow|Muscovite]] accents.<ref name=bbc29109398>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-29109398 |title=MH17 disaster: Russians 'controlled Buk missile system' |work=BBC News |date=8 September 2014 |accessdate=9 September 2014 |author=Sweeney, John}}</ref> On the same day Ignat Ostanin, a Russian journalist, published an analysis of photos and films of Buk units moving in Russia and Ukraine in the days before and after the MH17 crash. According to Ostanin, the markings on the specific launcher suspected of being used to shoot MH17, together with the number plates of the [[large goods vehicle]] that carried the launcher, suggested that it belonged to the 53rd Anti-Aircraft Missile Brigade of the Air Defence Forces of the [[Russian Ground Forces]].<ref name=\"FBS2APRIL\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paulroderickgregory/2015/04/02/is-the-mh17-joint-investigation-team-avoiding-the-question-of-kremlin-guilt/ |title=Is The MH17 Joint Investigation Team Avoiding The Question of Kremlin Guilt? |work=Forbes |date=2 April 2015 |accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ostanin\">{{cite web |url=https://bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2014/09/08/images-show-the-buk-that-downed-flight-mh17-inside-russia-controlled-by-russian-troops/ |title=Images Show the Buk that Downed Flight MH17, Inside Russia, Controlled by Russian Troops |publisher=[[Bellingcat]] |date=8 September 2014 |accessdate=9 September 2014 |last=Ostanin |first=Iggy}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 October 2014 the president of the German [[Bundesnachrichtendienst|Federal Intelligence Service]] (BND) gave a presentation about MH17 to a German parliamentary committee overseeing intelligence activities.  According to ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', the report contained a detailed analysis which concluded that pro-Russian separatists had used a captured Ukrainian Buk system to shoot down Flight MH17. The report also noted that \"Russian claims the missile had been fired by Ukrainian soldiers and that a Ukrainian fighter jet had been flying close to the passenger jet were false\".<ref name=spiegel-bnd-de>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/mh17-laut-bnd-waren-separatisten-fuer-absturz-verantwortlich-a-997885.html |title=Ostukraine: BND macht Separatisten f\u00fcr MH17-Absturz verantwortlich|trans-title=Eastern Ukraine: BND says separatists are responsible for MH17 crash |work=Der Spiegel |language=German |date=19 October 2014 |accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2014/10/20/world/germany-says-ukraine-rebels-downed-mh17-seized-missiles-report/ |title=Germany says Ukraine rebels downed MH17 with seized missiles: report |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=20 October 2014 |accessdate=20 October 2014}} \"He also said Ukrainian photos had been \"manipulated\", the magazine reported but did not elaborate on what the pictures showed, who had provided them or altered them.\"</ref> The [[Attorney General of Germany]] opened an investigation against unknown persons due to a suspected [[war crime]].<ref name=spiegel-bnd>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/german-intelligence-blames-pro-russian-separatists-for-mh17-downing-a-997972.html |title=Deadly Ukraine Crash: German Intelligence Claims Pro-Russian Separatists Downed MH17 |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |date=19 October 2014 |accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nBetween November 2014 and May 2016, UK-based investigative collective [[Bellingcat]] made a series of conclusions, based on their examination of photos in social media and other open-source information. Bellingcat said that the launcher used to shoot down the aircraft was a Buk 332 of the Russian [[53rd Anti-Aircraft Missile Brigade]] based in [[Kursk]], Russia, which had been transported from [[Donetsk]] to [[Snizhne]] and was controlled by separatists in Ukraine on the day of the attack.<ref name=\"Bellingcat\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Origin-of-the-Separatists-Buk-A-Bellingcat-Investigation1.pdf|title=MH17: Source of the Separatists' Buk|author=Bellingcat MH17 Investigation Team|date=8 November 2014|publisher=Bellingcat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109132619/https://www.bellingcat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Origin-of-the-Separatists-Buk-A-Bellingcat-Investigation1.pdf|archive-date=9 November 2014|url-status=live|access-date=16 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/journalists-find-solid-russian-ties-to-missile-that-hit-mh17-371161.html|title=Journalists find 'solid' Russian ties to missile that hit MH17|last=Gorchinskaya|first=Katya|date=9 November 2014|work=Kyiv Post|accessdate=18 June 2015|last2=Lavrov|first2=Vlad}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/meet-eliot-higgins-putins-mh17-nemesis-345485|title=Meet Eliot Higgins, Putin's MH17 Nemesis|last=Tucker|first=Maxim|date=22 June 2015|work=Newsweek|accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/bellingcat-new-evidence-against-russian-soldiers-on-mh17/a-18959585|title=Bellingcat: New evidence against Russian soldiers on MH17|work=DW.COM|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2016/05/03/the_lost_digit/|title=bellingcat \u2013 The Lost Digit: Buk 3x2 \u2013 bellingcat|work=bellingcat|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 December 2014 the Dutch news service [[RTL Nieuws]] published a statement of an unnamed local resident who witnessed the shooting down of MH17, indicating that the aircraft was shot down by a missile from rebel territory. He took photographs of what appeared to be the vapour trail of a ground-launched missile which he passed to the [[Security Service of Ukraine|SBU]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rtlnieuws.nl/nieuws/binnenland/ooggetuige-mh17-mijn-doel-rechtvaardigheid |title=Ooggetuige MH17: 'Mijn doel is rechtvaardigheid' |trans-title=Eyewitness of MH17: \"My goal is justice\" |newspaper=RTL News |date=22 December 2014 |accessdate=23 December 2014 |language=Dutch}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New Competing Claims on Downing of MH17 |publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |date=24 December 2014 |url=http://www.rferl.org/content/new-competing-claims-on-downing-of-mh17/26760591.html}}</ref> On 24 December Russia's state-operated domestic news agency [[RIA Novosti]] quoted the leader of the self-proclaimed Donetsk People's Republic, [[Alexander Zakharchenko]], saying he saw MH17 shot out of the sky by two Ukrainian jets.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0413\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u0414\u041d\u0420 \u043e \u043a\u0440\u0443\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 MH17: \"\u042f \u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043b, \u043a\u0430\u043a \u044d\u0442\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0441\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043b\u043e\" |trans-title=Head of the DPR about the crash of MH17: \"I saw how it happened\" |date=25 December 2014 |accessdate=26 December 2014 |language=Russian |newspaper=RIA News |url=http://ria.ru/mh17/20141225/1040130183.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Kremlin-backed insurgent leader claims personally witnessing Ukrainian aircraft shooting down MH17 |newspaper=Ukraine Today |date=25 December 2014 |url=http://uatoday.tv/news/kremlin-backed-insurgent-leader-claims-personally-witnessing-ukrainian-aircraft-shooting-down-mh17-399664.html}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015 a report produced by the German investigative team CORRECT!V concluded a Buk surface-to-air missile launcher operated by the [[53rd Anti-Aircraft Missile Brigade]] shot down MH17.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/kyiv-post-plus/new-report-says-it-proves-russian-forces-downed-flight-mh17-377063.html |title=New report says it proves Russian forces downed flight MH17 |date=10 January 2015 |first=Maxim |last=Tucker |work=Kyiv Post |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> Large amounts of other [[circumstantial evidence]] were presented separately by various parties that supports this version, identifying specific launcher vehicle, operator name, truck transporting it and its alleged route through Russia and Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/evidence-mounts-that-russia-supplied-the-missiles-that-shot-down-mh17-in-ukraine-2015-5?IR=T |title=Evidence mounts that Russia supplied the missiles that shot down MH17 in Ukraine |website=Business Insider |date=13 May 2015 |accessdate=13 June 2015 |author=Robert Coalson}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015 Reuters published statements from named witnesses from Chervonyi Zhovten ({{lang-uk|[[:uk:\u0427\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0416\u043e\u0432\u0442\u0435\u043d\u044c|\u0427\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0416\u043e\u0432\u0442\u0435\u043d\u044c]]}}), a village close to Torez and Snizhne, who said they saw the Buk rocket passing over the village when it was fired from a field around 1.5&nbsp;km away. It also published a statement from a witness who was said to be a separatist fighter (referred to by first name only) who confirmed that the launcher was placed in that area on the day of the Boeing crash to prevent Ukrainian airstrikes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/12/us-ukraine-crisis-airliner-idUSKBN0M81XF20150312 |title=Exclusive: From 'Red October' village, new evidence on downing of Malaysian plane over Ukraine |agency=Reuters |accessdate=12 March 2015 |author=Anton Zverev}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, [[News Corp Australia]] published the transcript of a 17-minute video recorded at the scene shortly after the crash. The transcript and published segments of the video indicated that Russian-backed rebels arrived at the crash site in the expectation of finding the wreckage of a military aircraft and of locating crew that had parachuted from the aircraft.<ref name=\"NC150717\">{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/full-transcript-russian-backed-rebels-ransack-the-wreckage-of-mh17-in-shocking-17-minute-video/story-e6frfkp9-1227444629703|title=Full transcript: Russian-backed rebels ransack the wreckage of MH17 in shocking 17-minute video|date=17 July 2015|accessdate=17 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150717004444/http://www.news.com.au/national/full-transcript-russian-backed-rebels-ransack-the-wreckage-of-mh17-in-shocking-17-minute-video/story-e6frfkp9-1227444629703|archive-date=17 July 2015|url-status=dead|work=[[news.com.au]]}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, [[Stratfor]] released satellite imagery taken 5 hours before the crash which showed a Russian Buk system travelling on a flatbed truck east through the town of [[Makiivka]], 40&nbsp;km away from Snizhne. Stratfor's concluded that a Buk system had moved from the Russian border toward Donetsk on 15 July 2014, and then moved back to the east on the afternoon of 17 July 2014, hours before Flight MH17 was shot down.<ref>{{cite news|title=Examining the Evidence of Russia's Involvement in a Malaysia Airlines Crash|url=https://www.stratfor.com/analysis/examining-evidence-russias-involvement-malaysia-airlines-crash|accessdate=16 May 2016|publisher=Stratfor}}</ref>\n\n===Dutch Safety Board reports===\n====Preliminary report====\nOn 9 September 2014, the preliminary report was released by the Dutch Safety Board (DSB).<ref name=\"dsb1\">{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/09/09/world/europe/netherlands-ukraine-mh17-report/index.html?hpt=hp_t2 |title=Report: MH17 hit by burst of 'high-energy objects' from outside |date=9 September 2014 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=25 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"dsbprelim\">{{citation |title=Preliminary report \u2013 Crash involving Malaysia Airlines Boeing 777-200 Flight MH17 |work=DSB |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=24 September 2014 |url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/uploads/phase-docs/701/b3923acad0ceprem-rapport-mh-17-en-interactief.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|16}} This preliminary report concluded that there was no evidence of any technical or operational failure in the aircraft or from the crew prior to the ending of the [[Flight recorder|CVR and FDR]] recordings at 13.20:03 hrs (UTC). The report also said that \"damage observed on the forward fuselage and cockpit section of the aircraft appears to indicate that there were impacts from a large number of high-energy objects from outside the aircraft\". According to the investigators, this damage probably led to a loss of structural integrity that caused an in-flight break-up first of the forward parts of the aircraft and then of the remainder with an expansive geographic spread of the aircraft's pieces.\n\n[[Tjibbe Joustra]], Chairman of the Dutch Safety Board, explained that the investigation thus far pointed \"towards an external cause of the MH17 crash\", but determining the exact cause required further investigation. They also said that they aimed to publish the final report within a year of the crash date.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Prof. mr. dr. Erwin Muller |title=Investigation crash MH17, 17 July 2014 Donetsk |url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/en/onderzoek/2049/investigation-crash-mh17-17-july-2014/preliminary-report/1562/preliminary-report-points-towards-external-cause-of-mh17-crash#fasen |website=Dutch Safety Board |publisher=Onderzoeksraad voor Veiligheid |accessdate=14 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Final report====\n[[File:MH17 Missile Impact.webm|thumb|thumbtime=43|right|upright=1.273|Narrated reconstruction of the missile impact, produced by the [[Dutch Safety Board]]]]\nThe Dutch Safety Board (DSB) issued its final report on the crash on 13 October 2015. The report concluded that the crash was caused by a [[Buk missile system|Buk 9M38-series surface-to-air missile]] with a 9N314M [[warhead]]. The warhead detonated outside and above the left-hand side of the cockpit. The impact killed the three people in the cockpit and caused structural damage to the airplane leading to an in-flight break-up resulting in a wreckage area of 50 square kilometres and loss of the lives of all 298 occupants.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/> Based on evidence they were able to exclude meteor strikes, the airplane having technical defects, a bomb, and an air-to-air attack as causes of the crash. The DSB calculated the trajectory of the missile and found it was fired within a {{convert|320|km2|sqmi|adj=on}} area southeast of [[Torez]]. Narrowing down a specific launch site was outside the DSB's mandate.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\">{{cite report|url=https://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/en/media/attachment/2018/7/10/debcd724fe7breport_mh17_crash.pdf |title=Crash of Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17 |publisher=[[Dutch Safety Board]] |date=13 October 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6cFSGnsRg?url=http://cdn.onderzoeksraad.nl/documents/report-mh17-crash-en.pdf |archivedate=13 October 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref>{{rp|147}} The findings do not specify who launched the Buk missile but according to Al Jazeera, the area identified by the DSB was controlled by separatists at the time of the downing.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2015/10/dutch-board-russian-missile-downed-mh17-151013112210934.html |title=Dutch board says Russian-made missile downed MH17 |date=13 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the technical investigation, the selection of the flight route was also investigated by the DSB.<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigation crash MH17, 17 July 2014 |url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/en/onderzoek/2049/investigation-crash-mh17-17-july-2014/onderzoek/1543/dutch-safety-board-heads-investigation-investigation-effort-in-full-swing-black-boxes-currently-being-read-out |website=onderzoeksraad.nl |publisher=[[Dutch Safety Board]] |accessdate=24 July 2014 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ShD1V2ae?url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/en/onderzoek/2049/investigation-crash-mh17-17-july-2014/onderzoek/1543/dutch-safety-board-heads-investigation-investigation-effort-in-full-swing-black-boxes-currently-being-read-out |archivedate=19 September 2014 }} ()</ref> Many airlines had avoided the Eastern Ukrainian airspace for months prior to the MH17 disaster. Many others, including 62 operators from 32 countries, continued to use this route.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|224}}<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Abeyratne|first1=Ruwantissa|title=Flight MH 17 and State Responsibility for Ensuring Safety and Security of Air Transport|journal=Journal of Transportation Security|date=1 December 2014|volume=7|issue=4|pages=347\u2013348|doi=10.1007/s12198-014-0148-0|language=en|issn=1938-7741}}</ref> The DSB stated that authorities should have closed the airspace above eastern Ukraine prior to the incident due to the ongoing conflict.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dutch Safety Board: MH17 brought down by missile in airspace that should have been closed |url=https://news.aviation-safety.net/2015/10/13/dutch-safety-board-mh17-brought-down-by-missile-in-airspace-that-should-have-been-closed/ |accessdate=4 October 2019 |publisher=ASN News |date=13 October 2015}}</ref> It recommended that states involved in armed conflicts should exercise more caution when evaluating their airspace, and operators should more thoroughly assess the risks when selecting routes over conflict areas.<ref name=\"BBC13OCT15_1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-34518473 |title=MH17 report: Five key findings from the Dutch Safety Board |newspaper=BBC News |accessdate=13 October 2015|date=13 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===Criminal investigation===\nThe criminal investigation into the downing of MH17 is being led by the [[Openbaar Ministerie|Public Prosecution Service]] of the [[Dutch Ministry of Justice]], and is the largest in Dutch history, involving dozens of prosecutors and 200 investigators.<ref name=\":0\">{{citation |title=MH17 criminal investigation largest ever in the Netherlands |agency=Xinhua News Agency |date=15 August 2014 |accessdate=27 October 2014 |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/world/2014-08/15/c_126873336.htm |editor=Mu Xuequan |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826002055/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/world/2014-08/15/c_126873336.htm |archive-date=26 August 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Investigators interviewed witnesses and examined forensic samples, satellite data, intercepted communications, and information on the Web.<ref>{{citation |title=MH17 crash: Investigation focuses on '25 metal shards' |publisher=BBC News |date=12 September 2014 |accessdate=27 October 2014 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-29180887}}</ref> Participating in the investigation along with the Netherlands, are the four other members of the [[joint investigation team]] (JIT),<ref name=\"TheStarJIT\" /> Belgium, Ukraine, Australia, and lastly, Malaysia,<ref>{{cite news |title=Speculation on MH17 is damaging to investigations |newspaper=Free Malaysia Today |agency=[[Bernama]] |date=22 November 2014 |accessdate=22 November 2014 |url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2014/11/22/speculation-on-mh17-is-damaging-to-investigations/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129091900/http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2014/11/22/speculation-on-mh17-is-damaging-to-investigations/ |archive-date=29 November 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> which joined in November 2014.<ref name=\"TheStarJIT\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2014/12/01/mh17-malaysia-to-be-part-of-investigating-team/ |title=MH17: Malaysia accepted as full member of probe team |newspaper=The Star |location=Petaling Jaya, Malaysia |date=1 December 2014 |accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref> Early in the investigation, the JIT eliminated accident, internal terrorist attack or air-to-air attack from another aircraft as the cause of the crash.<ref name=\"SMH JIT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/malaysia-airlines-flight-mh17-was-shot-down-from-prorussian-rebel-controlled-territory-investigation-finds-20160928-grqter.html|title=Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17 was shot down from pro-Russian rebel controlled territory, investigation finds|first=Nick|last=Miller|date=29 September 2016|work=Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, in a letter to the [[United Nations Security Council|Security Council]], the Netherlands [[United Nations|UN]] representative wrote that \"The Dutch government is deliberately refraining from any speculation or accusations regarding legal responsibility for the downing of MH17.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Letter to President of the UNSC |first=Karel J.G |last=van Oosterom |date=16 December 2014 |accessdate=21 December 2014 |url=http://www.tweedekamer.nl/downloads/document?id=adbae747-b7f0-4713-ad97-1a7e1b75dcd2&title=Brief%20van%20Permanent%20Representative%20of%20the%20Kingdom%20of%20the%20Netherlands.pdf }}</ref> Also in December, the assistant secretary of the [[United States Department of State]]'s European and Eurasian Affairs said America had given all of its information, including classified information to the Dutch investigators and to the [[ICAO]].<ref>{{cite news |title=US Submits Classified Information on MH17 to Investigators: State Dep't |newspaper=[[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] |date=17 December 2014 |accessdate=21 December 2014 |url=http://sputniknews.com/military/20141217/1015956748.html}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March 2015, the JIT released a Russian-language video calling for witnesses in the [[Donetsk Oblast|Donetsk]] and [[Luhansk Oblast|Luhansk regions]] who might have seen a [[Buk missile system]].<ref name=\"JITMH17\">{{cite web |url=http://jitmh17.com/ |title=Call for witnesses |publisher=Joint Investigation Team |accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref> The video included some previously undisclosed recordings allegedly of tapped phone conversations between rebel fighters about the Buk. In one recording, of a conversation a few hours after the shoot down, a fighter says that a member of the Buk's accompanying crew had been left behind at a checkpoint. In another recording, dated the day after the shootdown, a rebel allegedly says the Buk system and its crew had been brought from Russia by \"the Librarian.\"  The video presents a \"scenario\" whereby a Buk missile was transported on a [[Volvo]] low loader truck from Sievernyi (\u0421\u0454\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0439), a town located within a kilometre of the Russian border (near [[Krasnodon]]), to [[Donetsk]] during the night of 16/17 July.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=olQNpTxSnTo MH17] ''Politie [Police]''  International Joint Investigation Team</ref>\nIn the week following the public appeal, the JIT received more than 300 responses resulting in dozens of \"serious witnesses\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/binnenland/23903198/__Bruikbare_tips_over_daders_MH17__.html|trans-title=Dozens of useful tips about MH17 |title=Tientallen bruikbare tips over MH17 |last=van der Graaf |first=Jolande |language=Dutch |newspaper=De Telegraaf |date=9 April 2015 |accessdate=17 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nltimes.nl/2015/04/09/hundreds-respond-to-call-for-mh17-witnesses-tips/ |title=Hundreds respond to call for MH17 witnesses |last=Van Jaarsveldt |first=Janene |date=9 April 2015 |accessdate=17 June 2015 |newspaper=NL Times}}</ref> In 2016 the presence of the [[transloading|transloader]] of matching color with a Buk missile was confirmed on a satellite photo of the area taken just a few hours before the downing of the airplane, which was described as \"correlating with other evidence\" by [[Stratfor]] who found the photo in [[DigitalGlobe]] archive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stratfor.com/analysis/examining-evidence-russias-involvement-malaysia-airlines-crash|title=Examining the Evidence of Russia's Involvement in a Malaysia Airlines Crash|website=Stratfor|access-date=13 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/travel/travel-updates/incidents/mh17-the-satellite-images-russia-doesnt-want-us-to-see/news-story/8c03f8e87971d36f70b5402ffbda16ff|title=The image Russia doesn't want the world to see|website=NewsComAu|access-date=16 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April 2015 Dutch authorities made available 569 documents concerning the shoot-down. Personal information and official interviews had been redacted. A further 147 documents were not made public.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rtlnieuws.nl/nieuws/binnenland/wat-we-niet-mogen-zien-147-documenten-mh17-blijven-geheim |title=Wat we niet mogen zien: 147 documenten MH17 blijven geheim |work=RTL Nieuws |accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Findings of the joint investigation team (JIT)====\nOn 28 September 2016, the JIT gave a press conference in which it concluded that the aircraft was shot down with a [[Buk missile system|9M38 Buk missile]] fired from a rebel-controlled field near Pervomaisky (\u041f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439), a town {{convert|6|km|mi|abbr=on}} south of [[Snizhne]].<ref name=\"NLTimesJIT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nltimes.nl/2016/09/28/jit-mh17-shot-down-by-a-9m38-buk-missile-from-russian-origin/|title=JIT: MH17 shot down with missile fired from pro-Russian rebel controlled field}}</ref> It also found the Buk missile system used had been transported from Russia into Ukraine on the day of the crash, and then back into Russia after the crash, with one missile less than it arrived with.<ref name=\"SMH JIT\"/><ref name=\"BBC News 28 September 2016\">{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-37495067 |title= MH17 missile 'came from Russia', Dutch-led investigators say |author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 28 September 2016|website= [[BBC News Online]] |publisher= [[BBC]] | accessdate= 2 October 2016 }}</ref> The JIT said they had identified 100 people, witnesses as well as suspects, who were involved in the movement of the Buk launcher, though they had not yet identified a clear chain of command to assess culpability, which was a matter for ongoing investigation. The Dutch chief prosecutor said \"the evidence must stand before a court\" which would render final judgement.<ref name=\"SMH JIT\"/> During the investigation, the JIT recorded and assessed five billion internet pages, interviewed 200 witnesses, collected half a million photos and videos, and analysed 150,000 intercepted phone calls.<ref name=\"NLTimesJIT\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.om.nl/onderwerpen/mh17-crash/@96066/presentation/|title=Presentation preliminary results criminal investigation MH17 28-09-2016}}</ref> According to JIT head prosecutor Fred Westerbeke the criminal investigation is based on \"immense body of evidence,\" including testimonies of live witnesses who saw the \"Buk\" launcher, primary radar data, original photos and videos.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.novayagazeta.ru/articles/2017/10/16/74192-the-purpose-is-to-bring-this-matter-to-court|title=\"The purpose is to bring MH17 matter to court\"|work=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u2013 Novayagazeta.ru|access-date=16 October 2017|language=ru-RU}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Engineering Technologies 2010 Part3 0031 copy.jpg|thumb|A Buk SAM of the type used by the [[53rd Anti-Aircraft Missile Brigade]]]]\nOn 24 May 2018, after extensive comparative research, the JIT concluded that the Buk that shot down the flight came from the Russian [[53rd Anti-Aircraft Missile Brigade]] in [[Kursk]].<ref name=\"jit\">{{cite web | url =https://www.om.nl/onderwerpen/mh17-crash/@103196/update-criminal-0/ |title=Update in criminal investigation MH17 disaster|publisher=[[Openbaar Ministerie]]| date=24 May 2018| accessdate =24 May 2018}}</ref> The head of the National Investigation Service of the Dutch police asked the eyewitnesses and insiders to share information about the identities of the Buk crew members, the instruction the crew members followed and persons responsible for the operational deployment of the involved Buk on 17 July 2014.<ref name=\"jit\"/> According to Dutch [[Openbaar Ministerie|Public Prosecution Service]], by 24 May 2018 \"the authorities of the Russian Federation have ... not reported to the JIT that a Buk of the 53rd Brigade was deployed in Eastern Ukraine and that this Buk downed flight MH17.\"<ref name=\"jit\"/> In response, Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] stated that Russia will analyze the JIT conclusion, but will acknowledge it only if it becomes a party in the investigation.<ref name=\"kommersant\">{{cite web | url = https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/3638260|title=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u043f\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0449\u0430\u043b \u0438\u0437\u0443\u0447\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0432\u044b\u0432\u043e\u0434\u044b \u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0438\u044f \u043e \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0435 Boeing MH17|work=[[Kommersant]]| language=Russian|date=24 May 2018| accessdate =24 May 2018}}</ref> The [[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Russian Ministry of Defence]] in turn stated that no Russian Buk crossed the border with Ukraine.<ref name=\"kommersant\"/>\n\nOn 25 May 2018 the governments of the Netherlands and Australia issued a joint statement in which they laid responsibility on Russia \"for its part\" in the crash.<ref name=\":1\" /> The Netherlands and Australian foreign ministers stated that they would hold Russia legally responsible for shooting the airliner down. Netherlands Foreign Minister [[Stef Blok]] stated that \"the government is now taking the next step by formally holding Russia accountable,\" and, \"The Netherlands and Australia today asked Russia to enter into talks aimed at finding a solution that would do justice to the tremendous suffering and damage caused by the downing of MH17. A possible next step is to present the case to an international court or organization for their judgment.\"<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/netherlands-australia-flight17-statement-russia-1.4677473|title = Netherlands, Australia holding Russia 'accountable' for downing of MH17|access-date = 25 May 2018|author=[[The Associated Press]] |work = [[CBC News]]|date = 25 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeveral other countries and international organisations expressed their support for the JIT's conclusions and the joint statement by the Netherlands and Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2233506-internationale-reacties-op-mh17-rusland-moet-verantwoordelijkheid-nemen.html |title=Internationale reacties op MH17: Rusland moet verantwoordelijkheid nemen |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]] |date=25 May 2018 |language=Dutch}}</ref> UK Foreign Secretary [[Boris Johnson]] said the United Kingdom \"fully supports Australia and the Netherlands,\" calling on Russia to cooperate.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/foreign-secretary-statement-on-the-mh17-investigation |title=Foreign Secretary statement on the MH17 investigation |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[Foreign & Commonwealth Office]] |date=25 May 2018}}</ref> High Representative [[Federica Mogherini]] of the EU stated that the European Union \"calls on the Russian Federation to accept its responsibility\" and to cooperate as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2018/05/25/declaration-by-the-high-representative-on-behalf-of-the-eu-on-the-findings-of-the-joint-investigation-team-on-the-downing-of-flight-mh17/ |title=Declaration by the High Representative on behalf of the EU on the findings of the Joint Investigation Team on the downing of flight MH17 |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[European Council]] |date=25 May 2018}}</ref> The German government called on Russia to \"fully explain the tragedy.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bundesregierung.de/Content/DE/Artikel/2018/05/2018-05-25-ukraine-mh17-gutachten.html |title=Die Schuldigen ermitteln |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[Bundesregierung]] |date=25 May 2018 |language=German}}</ref> The US Department of State issued a statement saying that the United States \"strongly support the decisions by the Netherlands and Australia,\" requesting Russia to acknowledge its involvement and to \"cease its callous disinformation campaign.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2018/05/282502.htm |title=Calling Russia To Account for Malaysia Airlines Flight MH-17 |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[United States Department of State]] |date=25 May 2018}}</ref> NATO Secretary General [[Jens Stoltenberg]] called on Russia to \"accept responsibility and fully cooperate ... in line with [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 2166]].\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_154585.htm |title=Statement by the NATO Secretary General on MH17 investigation |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[NATO]] |date=25 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the JIT's conclusions, Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] reiterated that the Russians are \"not involved in it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/57556 |title=St Petersburg International Economic Forum plenary session |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[Kremlin]] |date=25 May 2018}}</ref> Following release of the JIT report, Malaysian Prime Minister [[Mahathir Mohamad|Mahathir]] said the JIT was making Russia a \"scapegoat\" and that he did not believe the Russians whom the JIT had charged were involved. Conversely the Malaysian prosecutor supported the investigation by saying the findings \"are based on extensive investigations and also legal research\".<ref name=\"reuters_20-06-2019\">{{cite news |last1=Sipalan |first1=Joseph |title=Malaysian PM says Russia being made a scapegoat for downing of flight MH17 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-ukraine-crisis-mh17-malaysia/malaysian-pm-says-russia-being-made-a-scapegoat-for-downing-of-flight-mh17-idUSKCN1TL0OW |accessdate=5 July 2019 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Proposed international tribunal====\nIn June 2015, the Netherlands, supported by the other JIT members, sought to create an international tribunal to prosecute those suspected of downing the Malaysian airliner, which would take up the case after the closing of the criminal investigation. The Dutch hoped that an international tribunal would induce Russian cooperation, which was considered critical.<ref>{{cite news |title=Exclusive: International tribunal looks like best chance for MH17 justice \u2013 Dutch sources |agency=Reuters |date=23 June 2015 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/06/23/us-ukraine-crisis-mh-idUSKBN0P326E20150623 |first=Anthony |last=Deutsch |accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> In late June 2015, the Russian government rejected a request by the five countries on the investigative committee to form a UN tribunal which would try those responsible for the shooting down of the aircraft, calling it \"not timely and counterproductive.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jun/26/russia-rejects-calls-for-un-tribunal-malaysia-airlines-flight-mh17 |title=Russia rejects calls for UN tribunal to prosecute MH17 suspects |work=The Guardian |agency=Agence France-Presse |accessdate=28 June 2015 |date=26 June 2015}}</ref> On 8 July 2015, Malaysia, a member of the [[UN Security Council]], distributed a draft resolution to establish such a tribunal. This resolution was jointly proposed by the five JIT member countries. Russian UN Ambassador [[Vitaly Churkin]] responded, \"I don't see any future for this resolution. Unfortunately, it seems that this is an attempt to organize a grandiose, political show, which only damages efforts to find the guilty parties.\"<ref name=churkin>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/malaysia-airlines-mh17-russia-rebukes-push-for-un-tribunal-1.3146029 |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17: Russia rebukes push for UN tribunal |date=10 July 2015 |publisher=[[CBC News]] |accessdate=10 July 2015}}</ref> Russia later circulated a rival resolution which criticised the international investigation's lack of \"due transparency\" and demanded those responsible be brought to justice, but which did not call for a tribunal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Russia's UN Draft on MH17 Crash Doesn't Call for Tribunal |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/russias-draft-mh17-crash-call-tribunal-32575088 |agency=Associated Press |date=20 July 2015 |author=Edith M. Lederer |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722201823/http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/russias-draft-mh17-crash-call-tribunal-32575088 |archivedate=22 July 2015 }}</ref> In a vote, Malaysia's resolution gained majority support of the UNSC, but was [[United Nations Security Council veto power|vetoed]] by Russia.<ref name=veto>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/07/29/us-ukraine-crisis-mh17-un-idUSKCN0Q32GS20150729 |title=Russia vetoes bid to set up tribunal for downed Flight MH17 |author=Michelle Nichols |agency=Reuters |date=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Criminal prosecution====\nIn a statement made on 5 July 2017 by the Dutch Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Bert Koenders]], it was announced that the JIT countries would prosecute any suspects identified in the downing of flight MH17 in the Netherlands and under Dutch law.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.government.nl/latest/news/2017/07/05/statement-by-the-minister-of-foreign-affairs-on-mh17-5-july-2017 |title=Statement by the minister of Foreign Affairs on MH17, 5 July 2017 |work=Government of the Kingdom of the Netherlands |agency=Ministry of Foreign Affairs |date= 7 July 2017}}</ref> A treaty between the Netherlands and Ukraine made it possible for the Netherlands to prosecute in the cases of all 298 victims, regardless of their nationality. This treaty was signed on 7 July 2017,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.government.nl/topics/mh17-incident/news/2017/07/07/minister-of-security-and-justice-signs-mh17-treaty-with-ukraine |title=Minister of Security and Justice signs MH17 treaty with Ukraine |work=Government of the Kingdom of the Netherlands |agency=Ministry of Security and Justice |date= 7 July 2017}}</ref> and went into force on 28 August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zoek.officielebekendmakingen.nl/trb-2018-162.HTML|title=Verdrag tussen het Koninkrijk der Nederlanden en Oekra\u00efne inzake internationale juridische samenwerking met betrekking tot misdrijven die verband houden met het neerhalen van vlucht MH17 van Malaysia Airlines op 17 juli 2014|date=7 September 2018|website=Tractatenblad van het Koninkrijk der Nederlanden}}</ref> On 21 March 2018, the Dutch government sent legislation to the parliament, allowing the suspects involved to be prosecuted in the Netherlands under [[Law of the Netherlands|Dutch law]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-21/legislation-clears-way-for-mh17-trials-in-the-netherlands|title=Legislation Clears Way for MH17 Trials in the Netherlands|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=21 March 2018|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=22 March 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.unian.info/world/10052111-dutch-court-may-be-allowed-to-prosecute-those-involved-in-mh17-crash-by-video-link.html|title=Dutch court may be allowed to prosecute those involved in MH17 crash by video link|agency=[[Ukrainian Independent Information Agency|UNIAN]]|access-date=13 April 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nA joint investigation between Bellingcat, ''The Insider'' and McClatchy DC Bureau identified another person of interest to the investigation. The person known as 'Andrey Ivanovich', or by the call sign 'Orion', according to Bellingcat, is a Russian [[GRU (G.U.)|GRU]] officer named Oleg Vladimirovich Ivannikov.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2018/05/25/mh17-russian-gru-commander-orion-identified-oleg-ivannikov/|title=MH17 - Russian GRU Commander 'Orion' Identified as Oleg Ivannikov|date=25 May 2018|website=bellingcat|accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref> Ivannikov has a distinct, high-pitched voice. The Kremlin denied this allegation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/europe/how-an-online-purchase-helped-find-the-russian-blamed-for-downing-mh17-20180526-p4zho2.html|title=How an online purchase helped find the Russian blamed for downing MH17|first=Kevin|last=Hall|date=26 May 2018|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 June 2019, the [[Dutch Public Prosecution Service]] charged four people with murder in connection with the shooting down of the aircraft: three Russians, [[Igor Strelkov (officer)|Igor Girkin]], Sergey Dubinsky, and Oleg Pulatov, and one Ukrainian, Leonid Kharchenko. International arrest warrants were issued in respect of each of the accused.<ref name=\"BBC48691488\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-48691488|title=Four charged with shooting down MH17 plane|work=BBC News Online|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> Their [[trial in absentia]] is scheduled to be held on 9 March 2020 in the District Court of [[The Hague]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.om.nl/onderwerpen/mh17-crash/@106096/prosecution-four/|title=Prosecution of four suspects for downing flight MH17|date=19 June 2019|publisher=[[Openbaar Ministerie]]|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019 SBU arrested Vladimir Tsemakh, head of air-defence in DPR-controlled Snizhne during the attack on MH17. [[Bellingcat]] described him as an important eye-witness to the events surrounding the downing of flight MH17. Bellingcat analysed his possible role and said that a video showed Tsemakh making \"what appears to be a damning admission to his personal involvement in hiding the Buk missile launcher in the aftermath of its use on 17 July 2014\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2019/07/09/the-arrest-of-vladimir-tsemakh-and-its-implications-for-the-mh17-investigation/|title=The Arrest of Vladimir Tsemakh and Its Implications for the MH17 Investigation|date=9 July 2019|website=bellingcat|language=en-GB|access-date=31 August 2019}}</ref> In August 2019 Russia reportedly added Tsemakh to its list in a previously agreed exchange of prisoners of war with Ukraine. In an article, ''The Insider'' website commented on Russia's motives in requesting the exchange of a Ukrainian citizen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theins.ru/politika/173069|title=\u041a\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043b\u044c \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043b \"\u0441\u0432\u043e\u0438\u043c\" \u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f \"\u0411\u0443\u043a\u0430\" \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043c\u0430\u0445\u0430 \u0438 \u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0443\u0435\u0442 \u043e\u0431\u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c \u0435\u0433\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u0421\u0435\u043d\u0446\u043e\u0432\u0430|date=30 August 2019|website=The Insider|language=ru-RU|access-date=31 August 2019}}</ref> On 4 September 2019, an appeals court in Kiev ruled to release Tsemakh.<ref name=MoscowTimes20190907>{{cite news|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2019/09/07/signaling-readiness-for-thaw-russia-and-ukraine-swap-prisoners-a67090|title=Signaling Readiness for Thaw, Russia and Ukraine Swap Prisoners: The exchange brings peace talks between the neighboring countries closer, analysts say.|newspaper=[[The Moscow Times]]|last=Gershkovich|first=Evan|date=7 September 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref> On 7 September 2019, Volodymyr Tsemakh was released during a Ukraine-Russia prisoner exchange.<ref name=CNN20190907>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/07/europe/ukraine-russia-prisoner-swap-intl/index.html|title=Film director Oleg Sentsov and MH17 suspect among those freed in Russia-Ukraine prisoner swap|work=[[CNN]]|last1=Lapin|first1=Denis|last2=Pavlova|first2=Olga|last3=Britton|first3=Bianca|last4=Dean|first4=Sarah|date=7 September 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref> According to the [[List of Ministers of Foreign Affairs of the Netherlands|Dutch Foreign Minister]] [[Stef Blok]], the exchange had been delayed for a week so that Vladimir Tsemakh could be questioned by the Dutch Public Prosecution Service as a witness about the events surrounding the downing of flight MH17.<ref name=CNN20190907/> The [[Dutch Prime Minister]] [[Mark Rutte]], the [[List of Ministers of Justice of the Netherlands|Minister of Justice and Security]] [[Ferdinand Grapperhaus|Ferd Grapperhaus]], the JIT, and Blok added that the Netherlands regretted Tsemakh, who is a 'person of interest', being included in the exchange due to pressure on Ukraine from Russia.<ref name=MoscowTimes20190907/><ref name=CNN20190907/><ref>{{cite news| last1=Olearchyk| first1=Roman | last2=Foy| first2=Henry| url=https://www.ft.com/content/1cf7478e-cfbf-11e9-99a4-b5ded7a7fe3f| title=Ukraine court releases man of interest to MH17 probe on bail: Move raises speculation he could be part of imminent prisoner swap between Kiev and Moscow| work=[[Financial Times]]| date=5 September 2019| access-date=13 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=AD20190907>{{cite news| url=https://www.ad.nl/buitenland/nederland-vraagt-rusland-om-mh17-verdachte~a953df4d/| title=Nederland vraagt Rusland om MH17-verdachte: Het Openbaar Ministerie heeft Rusland gevraagd MH17-verdachte Vladimir Tsemach uit te leveren. Dat liet het OM de nabestaanden van de vliegramp vanmiddag weten. Nederland betreurt zeer dat Oekra\u00efne de Oekra\u00efense separatist \u00fcberhaupt aan Rusland heeft overgedragen| trans-title=The Netherlands asks Russia for MH17 suspect: The Public Prosecution Service has asked Russia to extradite MH17 suspect Vladimir Tsemach. The OM informed the relatives of the plane crash this afternoon. The Netherlands deeply regrets that Ukraine has handed over the Ukrainian separatist to Russia at all.| work=[[Algemeen Dagblad|AD.nl]]| language=Dutch| date=7 September 2019| access-date=13 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Dutch did question MH17 witness before he was returned to Russia: minister |url=https://www.dutchnews.nl/news/2019/09/dutch-did-question-mh17-witness-before-he-was-returned-to-russia-minister/ |accessdate=9 September 2019 |work=DutcNews.nl |date=8 September 2019}}</ref> Others including Chairman Piet Ploeg of Stichting Vliegramp MH17 which is the organization of the victims' relatives called the release of Tsemach \"unacceptable\".<ref name=AD20190907/> The Dutch Public Prosecution Service (OM) requested that Tsemach, who is not a Russian citizen, be extradited from Russia to the Netherlands.<ref name=AD20190907/> On 14 November 2019 the JIT published a new witnesses appeal and simultaneously released a number of recorded conversations of rebel leaders. JIT was particularly interested in \"the command structure and the role that Russian government officials may have played.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=MH17 Witness Appeal November 2019 |url=https://www.politie.nl/themas/flight-mh17/witness-appeal-crash-mh17.html |website=politie.nl |accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=MH17 disaster: Phone-taps 'show Russia directed Ukraine rebels' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-50419669 |accessdate=15 November 2019 |work=BBC News |date=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Dutch Prosecution formally charged four suspects and summoned them for investigation. One of them, Lieutenant Colonel Oleg Pulatov, expressed his intention to join the legal process by being represented in court. The trial began on 9 March 2020, with none of the accused in attendance.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-polytics/2868589-netherlands-public-prosecution-service-brings-charges-against-four-suspects-in-mh17-case.html|title=Netherlands Public Prosecution Service brings charges against four suspects in MH17 case|accessdate=4 February 2020 |work=Ukrinform |date=3 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-polytics/2863987-one-of-suspects-in-mh17-case-wants-to-join-legal-proceedings.html |title =One of suspects in MH17 case wants to join legal proceedings|accessdate=4 February 2020 |work=Ukrinform |date=4 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=MH17 trial starts with four accused facing murder charges |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/mh17-trial-start-accused-facing-murder-charges-200309000652546.html |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Al Jazeera |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==British ISC report==\nOn 20 December 2017, the [[Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament|Intelligence and Security Committee]] of the UK Parliament published its annual report. It contains a short section entitled \"Russian objectives and activity against UK and allied interests\" which quotes MI6 as stating: \"Russia conducts information warfare on a massive scale... An early example of this was a hugely intensive, multichannel propaganda effort to persuade the world that Russia bore no responsibility for the shooting down of [Malaysian Airlines flight] MH-17 (an outright falsehood: we know beyond any reasonable doubt that the Russian military supplied and subsequently recovered the missile launcher)\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Toler|first1=Aric|title=British Intelligence Report Confirms Russian Military Origin of MH17 Murder Weapon|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2017/12/20/british-intelligence-report-confirms-russian-military-origin-mh17-murder-weapon/|website=Bellingcat|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=ISCP Annual Report 2016-2017|url=https://b1cba9b3-a-5e6631fd-s-sites.googlegroups.com/a/independent.gov.uk/isc/files/2016-2017_ISC_AR.pdf?attachauth=ANoY7cqS8WVJqzXucCjkPcD1PkT4M4RJspBV9tHBYEJAZLobTFw2rG67hpLh55zoZsZ9_9Xrmtqiq4CzbwmhAUpzCTh3AW-lBjOdmWFYJds1-EYzBgJGRmPWubVpg_Yl0SrMUrYTcKGn-8HtPvf5AARiu60msxtT2SpjJfdv78EEeqkINZBUythVem1KHFtKbbziZLQNdiiOymaCinv1pUa1FIpSVaHOkjNwmyfFteiMvnTRX00Qz_0%3D&attredirects=0}}</ref>\n\n==Civil cases==\nIn July 2015 a writ was filed in an American court by families of 18 victims accusing the separatist leader Igor Girkin of \"orchestrating the shootdown\" and the Russian government of being complicit in the act. The writ was brought under the [[Torture Victim Protection Act of 1991]].<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/11742865/MH-17-Russian-separatist-leader-sued-for-900-million-by-crash-victims.html]. MH-17-Russian-separatist-leader-sued-for-900-million-by-crash-victims</ref> In May 2016 families of 33 victims of the crash filed a claim against Russia and president Vladimir Putin in the [[European Court of Human Rights]], arguing Russian actions violated the passengers' right to life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-36350520|title=MH17 crash: Victims' families sue Putin and Russia|website=BBC News|access-date=22 May 2016}}</ref><ref>Blakkarly, Jarni (22 May 2016). [http://in.reuters.com/article/australia-mh-idINL3N18J00O UPDATE 1-Australian firm names Russia, Putin in MH17 compensation claim -report.] ''Reuters.'' Retrieved: 22 May 2016.</ref> A group of 270 relatives of Dutch victims joined the claim in May 2018 after the JIT concluded that Russia was involved.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2233480-nabestaanden-mh17-naar-europees-hof-voor-schadeclaim-tegen-rusland.html|title=Nabestaanden MH17 naar Europees Hof voor schadeclaim tegen Rusland|work=NOS|access-date=30 May 2018|date=25 May 2018|language=Dutch}}</ref> In July 2016, Malaysia Airlines was sued in Malaysia by 15 passengers' families in two separate writs, each brought under the [[Montreal Convention]], arguing that the airline should not have chosen that route.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/mh17-kin-sue-malaysia-airlines-seek-damages-ahead-of-lawsuit-deadline|title=MH17 kin sue Malaysia Airlines, seek damages ahead of lawsuit deadline|author=Yap Tzu Ging|date=15 July 2016|newspaper=Malay Mail Online}}</ref> A month earlier, a separate lawsuit was brought by the families of 6 crew members who alleged negligence and breach of contract by the airline.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/missing-malaysia-plane-crew-lawsuit-1.3612177|title=Malaysia Airlines sued by relatives of MH17 crew shot down over Ukraine|agency=The Associated Press|date=2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n{{main|International reactions to the Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 shootdown}}\n<!--PLEASE DON'T ADD ANY PICTURES OF WORLD LEADERS IN THIS SECTION A/P TALK PAGE DISCUSSION AND ARCHIVES-->\n<!-- Please don't add \"condolences\" per WP:MEMORIAL. Please don't add tiny flags or bullet points; consensus is that it is better as prose. Thanks. -->\n\n===Countries===\nUkrainian President [[Petro Poroshenko]] called the crash the result of an act of terrorism, and also called for an international investigation into the crash.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10974784/Malaysia-Airlines-crash-President-Poroshenko-calls-shooting-down-of-Malaysian-plane-an-act-of-terrorism.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |title=Malaysia Airlines crash: President Poroshenko calls shooting down of Malaysian plane an 'act of terrorism' |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nMalaysian Deputy Foreign Minister [[Hamzah Zainuddin]] said that the foreign ministry would be working with the Russian and Ukrainian governments with regard to the incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.cri.cn/12394/2014/07/18/2941s836537.htm |title=Malaysia to Work with Russia, Ukrainian Governments on MH17 |publisher=English.cri.cn |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Najib Razak]] said that Malaysia was unable yet to verify the cause of the crash but that, if the airplane was shot down, the perpetrators should be swiftly punished.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.voanews.com/east-asia/malaysian-pm-demands-swift-justice-if-plane-was-shot-down |title=Malaysian PM Demands Swift Justice if Plane Was Shot Down |publisher=[[Voice of America]] |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref> The [[Government of Malaysia|Malaysian government]] flew the [[Flag of Malaysia|national flag]] at [[half-mast]] from 18 July until 21 July.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stasiareport.com/news/asia/south-east-asia/story/malaysia-airlines-mh17-crash-flags-fly-half-mast-over-next-three-day |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17 crash: Flags to fly at half-mast over next three days, says Najib |author=Yong Yen Nie |publisher=Straits Times Asia Report |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Nederlandse vlag halfstok voor stadhuis Hoorn.jpg|thumb|upright|Flag at half mast in front of [[Hoorn]] city hall during the national day of mourning on 23 July]]\n\nDutch Prime Minister [[Mark Rutte]] and King [[Willem-Alexander]] voiced their shock at the crash,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/binnenland/22867019/__Verklaring_Rutte_over_MH17__.html |title=Verklaring premier Rutte over crash MH17 &#124; Binnenland |language=Dutch |work=De Telegraaf |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://dc.the-netherlands.org/news/2014/07/statement-king-willem-alexander.html |title=Statement of His Majesty King Willem-Alexander on Malaysian Flight MH17 |work=Kingdom of the Netherlands |publisher=The Netherlands Embassy in Washington, D.C., United States |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718002846/http://dc.the-netherlands.org/news/2014/07/statement-king-willem-alexander.html |archive-date=18 July 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Frans Timmermans]] joined the Dutch investigation team sent to Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/2668/Buitenland/article/detail/3691806/2014/07/18/Timmermans-mee-met-onderzoekers-naar-Oekraine.dhtml |title=Timmermans mee met onderzoekers naar Oekra\u00efne |language=Dutch |work=ANP |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> Dutch government buildings flew the flag at half-mast on 18 July.<ref name=\"nieuws.nl\">{{cite web |url=http://nieuws.nl/algemeen/20140717/vlaggen-overheidsgebouwen-halfstok-na-vliegramp/ |title=Vlaggen overheidsgebouwen halfstok na vliegramp |language=Dutch |author=Novum |publisher=Nieuws.nl |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726214011/http://www.nieuws.nl/algemeen/20140717/Vlaggen-overheidsgebouwen-halfstok-na-vliegramp |archive-date=26 July 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Music was cancelled and festivities were toned down on the last day of the [[Nijmegen Marches]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nieuws.nl/algemeen/20140718/vierdaagse-nijmegen-muziek-geschrapt-wegens-vliegramp/ |title=Vierdaagse Nijmegen: muziek geschrapt wegens vliegramp |language=Dutch |author=Novum |publisher=nieuws.nl |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402114956/http://nieuws.nl/algemeen/20140718/vierdaagse-nijmegen-muziek-geschrapt-wegens-vliegramp/ |archive-date=2 April 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref> On 21 July the Netherlands opened a war crimes investigation on the downing of the aircraft and a Netherlands public prosecutor went to Ukraine as part of this investigation. Rutte threatened tough action against Russia if it did not help in the investigation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/netherlands-opens-investigation-airliner-shoot-down-131650202.html |title=Netherlands opens war crimes investigation into airliner downing |author1=Thomas Escritt |author2=Angus MacSwan |date=21 July 2014 |website=[[Yahoo! News]]}}</ref> On the same day, Timmermans spoke at the UN Security Council Meeting, after the Council had unanimously condemned the shooting down of MH17.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2014/07/22/terugluisteren-en-lezen-de-bewogen-speech-van-timmermans-a1423587|title=Terugluisteren en -lezen: de indrukwekkende speech van Timmermans |author=Marije Willems |date=22 July 2014 |website=[[NRC Handelsblad|NRC]]}}</ref> An increase in negative emotions and somatic complaints was observed in the Dutch population during the first four days after the MH17 crash.<ref>{{Cite journal |author= Jeronimus|display-authors=etal| year = 2018 | title = Acute stress responses after indirect exposure to the MH17 airplane crash| journal = British Journal of Psychology| volume = 0 | pages = 1\u201324 | doi=10.1111/bjop.12358}}</ref>\n\nAustralian Prime Minister [[Tony Abbott]] said in an address to parliament that the aircraft was downed by a missile which seemed to have been launched by Russian-backed rebels.<ref name=DT>{{cite news |last1=Maiden |first1=Samantha |title=MH17: Russia says Tony Abbott 'operating only on speculation' in his tough stance over separatist involvement in plane tragedy |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/mh17-russia-says-tony-abbott-operating-only-on-speculation-in-his-tough-stance-over-separatist-involvement-in-plane-tragedy/story-fni0cx12-1226994356506 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=Australia |date=19 July 2014}}</ref> [[Julie Bishop]], the Australian Minister for Foreign Affairs, said in an interview on an Australian television programme that it was \"extraordinary\" that her Russian counterparts had refused to speak to her over the shootdown after the Russian ambassador was summoned to meet her.<ref name=DT/> The Russian government was critical of Abbott's response; Abbott was one of the first world leaders to publicly connect the shootdown to Russia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-07-19/russia-says-abbott-comments-mh17-downing-unacceptable/5608852?pfm=ms |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17: Russia says Tony Abbott's comments blaming separatists are 'unacceptable', Julie Bishop criticises Moscow for lack of talks \u2013 ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> Abbott later criticised the recovery efforts as \"shambolic\", and \"more like a garden clean-up than a forensic investigation\"; Bishop publicly warned separatist forces against treating the victims' bodies as hostages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-07-21/government-considers-declaring-mh17-disaster-a-terrorist-act/5610908?pfm=ms |title=MH17: Prime Minister Tony Abbott hits out at 'shambolic' recovery effort; Government considers listing outrage as terrorist act; rebels move bodies to refrigerated train \u2013 ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> Abbott also said in an interview on 13 October 2014, in anticipation of Russia's President [[Vladimir Putin]]'s attendance at the [[2014 G20 Brisbane summit|2014 G20 summit]], scheduled for mid-November 2014 in [[Brisbane]], Australia: \"Australians were murdered. They were murdered by Russian-backed rebels using Russian-supplied equipment. We are very unhappy about this.\"<ref>{{cite news |author1=Sabra Lane |title=Tony Abbott promises to 'shirtfront' Putin at G20 Summit |url=http://www.abc.net.au/7.30/content/2014/s4106143.htm |accessdate=14 October 2014 |work=7:30 |date=13 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nRussian President Putin said that Ukraine bore responsibility for the incident which happened in its territory, which he said would not have happened if hostilities had not resumed in the south-east of Ukraine.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://ria.ru/society/20140718/1016472533.html|script-title=ru:\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d: \u0437\u0430 \u0430\u0432\u0438\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0443 \u043d\u0435\u0441\u0435\u0442 \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0430 |trans-title=Putin: Ukraine responsible for the crash |language=Russian |date=18 July 2014 |agency=RIA Novosti |quote=\"\u0411\u0435\u0437\u0443\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e, \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e, \u043d\u0430\u0434 \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0435\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043e \u044d\u0442\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u043e\u0448\u043b\u043e, \u043d\u0435\u0441\u0435\u0442 \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0437\u0430 \u044d\u0442\u0443 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0448\u043d\u0443\u044e \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0433\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044e\", \u2013 \u0441\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u0420\u0424 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"biden\">{{cite news |url=https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/biden-malaysia-airlines-crash |publisher=MSNBC |title=Joe Biden: Malaysia Airlines flight 'apparently' shot down |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> He also said that it was important to refrain from reaching hasty conclusions and politicised statements before the end of the investigation. He said that Russia would help an international inquiry led by the ICAO.<ref name=RT-live>{{cite news |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17 plane crash in Ukraine LIVE UPDATES |url=http://rt.com/news/173628-malaysian-plane-crash-ukraine/ |accessdate=21 July 2014 |publisher=RT |date=17 July 2014}}</ref> At the end of July a [[Duma]] deputy [[Ilya Ponomarev]] said in an interview for ''[[Die Welt]]'' that the separatists had shot down the airplane by mistake and that Putin now realised he had supplied the weapon to the \"wrong people\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.welt.de/politik/ausland/article130579514/Putin-realisiert-dass-er-die-Falschen-bewaffnete.html |title=Putin realisiert, dass er die Falschen bewaffnete |work=Die Welt |language=German |date=26 July 2014 |accessdate=1 August 2014 |author=Silke M\u00fclherr und Inga Pylypchuk}}</ref> The [[Danish Institute for International Studies]] has pointed out to the similarities of Russian reaction to the downing of [[Korean Air Lines Flight 007|Korean Airlines flight KAL-007]] in 1983 where the USSR initially denied any involvement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pure.diis.dk/ws/files/950041/DIIS_RP_2017_6_web.pdf|title=Russian Hybrid Warfare|website=Danish Institute for International Studies|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824221700/http://pure.diis.dk/ws/files/950041/DIIS_RP_2017_6_web.pdf|archive-date=24 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nUnited States President [[Barack Obama]] said the United States would help determine the cause.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/> In a press statement, White House spokesman [[Josh Earnest]] called for an immediate ceasefire in Ukraine to allow for a full investigation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mason |first1=Jeff |last2=Holland |first2=Steve |title=White House urges Ukraine ceasefire for plane probe, Obama talks to Putin |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/18/us-ukraine-crisis-obama-idUSKBN0FN0D420140718 |accessdate=18 July 2014 |agency=Reuters |date=18 July 2014}}</ref> Vice-President [[Joe Biden]] said the airplane appeared to have been deliberately shot down, and offered American assistance for the investigation into the crash.<ref name=\"biden\"/> [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations|American&nbsp;Ambassador to the United Nations]] [[Samantha Power]] called on Russia to end the war.<ref name=nytimes1>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/19/world/europe/malaysia-airlines-plane-ukraine.html |title=Obama Points to Pro-Russia Separatists in Downing of Malaysia Airlines Plane |first=Michael D. |last=Shear |first2=Somini |last2=Sengupta |first3=Sabrina |last3=Tavernise |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> The British government requested an emergency meeting of the [[United Nations Security Council]] and called an emergency [[Cabinet Office Briefing Room|Cobra]] meeting after the incident.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leonard |first1=Peter |title=Ukraine: 295 on Malaysia plane shot down over east |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/official-malaysian-plane-shot-down-over-ukraine |work=Associated Press |publisher=The Big Story |accessdate=17 July 2014 |ref=APBigStory |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717190514/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/official-malaysian-plane-shot-down-over-ukraine |archivedate=17 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10975874/MH17-plane-crash-David-Cameron-urges-those-responsible-for-downing-jet-to-be-held-to-account.html |title=MH17 plane crash: David Cameron urges those responsible for downing jet to be 'held to account' |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> Chairman of the US [[Joint Chiefs of Staff]] [[Martin E. Dempsey]] said that instead of backing away from supporting the rebels in the wake of the airliner shootdown, Putin had \"taken a decision to escalate.\"<ref>David M. Herszenhorn (25 July 2014), [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/26/world/europe/russian-artillery-fires-into-ukraine-kiev-says.html ''Russia Steps Up Help for Rebels in Ukraine War,''] ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\n[[File:Nationaal Monument MH17.jpg|thumb|Memorial for the victims of Flight MH17 located in [[Vijfhuizen]], the Netherlands]]\n\nOn 17 July 2017, exactly three years after the crash, a [[memorial]] in memory of the victims was unveiled in [[Vijfhuizen]], the Netherlands. The opening of the memorial, which is located just outside Schiphol Airport, was attended by more than 2000 relatives of victims, King Willem-Alexander and his wife [[Queen M\u00e1xima of the Netherlands|Queen M\u00e1xima]], Dutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte, Minister of Security and Justice [[Stef Blok]] and the speakers of the Dutch Senate and House of Representatives. The memorial includes 298 trees, one tree for each victim.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2183659-onthulling-nationaal-monument-mh17-deze-dag-sloeg-een-gat-in-ons-leven.html |title=Onthulling Nationaal Monument MH17: 'Deze dag sloeg een gat in ons leven' |access-date=17 July 2019 |work=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]] |date=17 July 2017 |language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\n===Organisations===\nOn 17 July the European Union's representatives [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso]] and [[Herman Van Rompuy]] released a joint statement calling for an immediate and thorough investigation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_STATEMENT-14-231_en.htm?locale=en |title=EUROPA PRESS RELEASES \u2013 Press release \u2013 Joint statement by the President of the European Commission, Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso, and the President of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy, on the crash of the Malaysian airliner in Ukraine |publisher=Europa (web portal) |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> The EU officials also said that Ukraine has first claim on the aircraft's black boxes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/malaysian-plane-mh17-crash-investigators-face-struggle/1/373127.html |title=Malaysian plane MH17 crash investigators face struggle : Asia, News |work=India Today |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[International Civil Aviation Organization]] announced, on 18 July, that it was sending its team of experts to assist the [[National Bureau of Air Accidents Investigation of Ukraine]] (NBAAI), under Article 26 of the [[Convention on International Civil Aviation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.icao.int/Newsroom/Pages/Ukraine-requests-ICAO-assistance-in-MH17-accident-investigation.aspx |title=Ukraine Requests ICAO Assistance in MH17 Accident Investigation |publisher=ICAO |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref> The [[United Nations Security Council]] adopted [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 2166|Resolution 2166]] on 21 July, regarding an official crime investigation into the incident. On 24 July 2014 the ICAO issued a State Letter reminding signatory states of their responsibilities with respect to the safety and security of civil aircraft operating in airspace affected by conflict.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.icao.int/Newsroom/Pages/ICAO-clarifies-State-responsibilities-arising-from-conflict-zones.aspx |title=ICAO Clarifies State Responsibilities Arising from Conflict Zones |publisher=ICAO |date=24 July 2014 |accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Amsterdam Airport- Flight MH17 Memorial (14675744526).jpg|thumb|A makeshift memorial at [[Schiphol Airport]] for the victims of Flight MH17]]\nAfter the crash, memorial services were held in Australia<ref name=\"itv-memorial\">{{cite news |url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2014-07-20/memorial-service-held-for-mh17-victims-in-australia/ |title=Australia mourns MH17 victims at memorial service |work=ITV News |date=20 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> and in the Netherlands, which declared 23 July, the day when the first victims arrived in the country, a [[national day of mourning]], the first since 1962.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nu.nl/binnenland/3834822/woensdag-23-juli-dag-van-nationale-rouw.html |title=Woensdag 23 juli dag van nationale rouw &#124; nu.nl/binnenland &#124; Het laatste nieuws het eerst op |publisher=Nu.nl |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ibt-mourning\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/netherlands-declares-national-day-mourning-mh17-victims-1457454 |title=Malaysian Airlines Flight MH17: Netherlands Declares National Day of Mourning For MH17 Victims |work=International Business Times |date=20 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> The opening ceremony of the AIDS 2014 conference, on 20 July, of which several delegates had been on board Flight MH17, began with a tribute to the victims of the crash.<ref name=\"starobserver\">{{cite news |url=http://www.starobserver.com.au/news/local-news/aids-2014-opening-ceremony-tinged-with-sombre-mood/125442 |title=AIDS 2014 opening ceremony tinged with sombre mood |first=Elias |last=Jahshan |work=Star Observer |date=20 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> In Malaysia, makeshift memorials were created in the capital city of [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref name=\"bbc memorials\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-28397889 |title=MH17 crash: Malaysians mourn at makeshift memorials |work=BBC News |first=Sharanjit |last=Leyl |date=21 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Russian media coverage==\n{{See also|Media portrayal of the Ukrainian crisis}}\nIn July 2014, shortly after the crash, the liberal Russian opposition newspaper ''[[Novaya Gazeta]]'' published a headline in Dutch that read \"Vergeef ons, Nederland\" (\"Forgive Us, Netherlands\").<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/world/russian-newspaper-novaya-gazeta-prints-frontpage-apology-for-mh17-disaster-in-dutch/story-fndir2ev-1227001958997|title=Russian newspaper Novaya Gazeta prints front-page apology for MH17 disaster in Dutch|date=25 July 2014|accessdate=25 July 2014|work=News.com.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2014/07/25/russian_paper_issues_front_page_apology_to_netherlands_for_mh17|title=Russian Paper Issues Front Page Apology to Netherlands for MH17|last1=Groll|first1=Elias|date=25 July 2014|website=Foreign Policy|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nCoverage by official media and bodies has however differed from coverage in most other countries and significantly changed over time<ref>{{cite news |title=Russia offers alternate scenarios for Malaysia Airlines crash |url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2014/07/22/Russia-offers-alternate-scenarios-for-Malaysia-Airlines-crash/2701406045751/ |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=2 November 2014 |first=Ed |last=Adamczyk |agency=United Press International |quote=Russian media offers explanations conflicting with the information provided by the rest of the world.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ioffe |first1=Julia |title=The Russian Public Has a Totally Different Understanding of What Happened to Malaysia Airlines Flight 17: And it's more of a problem than you think |url=https://newrepublic.com/node/118782 |accessdate=21 July 2014 |work=New Republic |date=20 July 2014 |quote=The picture of the catastrophe that the Russian people are seeing on their television screens is very different from that on screens in much of the rest of the world, and the discrepancy does not bode well for a sane resolution to this stand-off |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140721015346/http://www.newrepublic.com/node/118782 |archive-date=21 July 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> usually in response to new evidence published by DSB and the investigation team.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2018/01/05/kremlins-shifting-self-contradicting-narratives-mh17/|title=The Kremlin's Shifting, Self-Contradicting Narratives on MH17 - bellingcat|date=5 January 2018|work=bellingcat|access-date=5 January 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the poll conducted by the [[Levada Center]] between 18 and 24 July in 2014, 80% of Russians surveyed believed that the crash of MH17 was caused by the Ukrainian military. Only 3% of respondents to the poll blamed the disaster on pro-Russian separatists in eastern Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.levada.ru/30-07-2014/katastrofa-boinga-pod-donetskom|title=\u041a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0430 \"\u0411\u043e\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0430\" \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u043e\u043c|date=30 July 2014|publisher=Levada.ru|accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/30/mh17-vast-majority-russians-believe-ukraine-downed-plane-poll|title=MH17: vast majority of Russians believe Ukraine downed plane, poll finds|last1=Luhn|first1=Alec|work=The Guardian|accessdate=2 August 2014|agency=Guardian News and Media Limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/more-than-80-of-russians-blame-ukrainian-army-for-malaysia-airlines-crash/504333.html|title=More Than 80% of Russians Blame Ukrainian Army for MH17 Crash|work=The Moscow Times|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, the Russian portal ''The Insider'', the news agency [[McClatchyDC]], and Bellingcat performed a joint investigation that confirmed the identity of a high-rank military officer using a call-sign \"Dolphin\" to be colonel general Nikolai Fedorovich Tkachev. Tkachev is frequently heard in the wiretaps acquired by JIT supervising the operation of \"Buk\" delivery and set-up.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2017/12/08/russian-colonel-general-delfin/|title=Russian Colonel General Identified as Key MH17 Figure \u2013 bellingcat|date=8 December 2017|work=bellingcat|access-date=8 December 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/world/article188720184.html|title=Russian general ID'd in activity around shootdown of Malaysian passenger jet|website=mcclatchydc|accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Initial reactions and \"An-26 downing\" version ===\nOn the evening of the crash, the [[Life (news agency, Russia)|LifeNews]] portal released a statement from the separatists saying that a \"Ukrainian Air Force [[An-26]] transport plane\" had been shot down by a missile and crashed.<ref name=\"lifenews 136801\">{{cite news|script-title=ru:\u041e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0446\u044b \u0441\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043e \u0441\u0431\u0438\u0442\u043e\u043c \u0410\u043d-26 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a\u0435 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u044b |url=http://lifenews.ru/news/136801 |quote=On July 17 near the village of Rassypnoye over the Torez city in Donetsk region an An-26 transport plane of Ukrainian Air Force was taken down, said the militia. According to them, the plane crashed somewhere near the \"Progress\" mine, away from residential areas. According to one of the militias, at about 17:30 local time an An-26 flew over the city. It was hit by a rocket, there was an explosion and the plane went to the ground, leaving a black smoke. Debris fell from the sky |accessdate=17 July 2014 |date=17 July 2014 |language=Russian}}</ref> [[ITAR-TASS]] and [[RIA Novosti]] also reported that an An-26 had been shot down by the separatist militia near Torez at around 16:00 local time in what it described as \"yet another victory of DPR self-defence\".<ref name=\"tassan26\">{{cite news|title=Donetsk People's Republic militia downs another Ukraine's An-26 plane \u2013 eyewitnesses |url=http://en.itar-tass.com/world/741164 |accessdate=18 July 2014 |agency=[[Information Telegraph Agency of Russia]] |date=17 July 2014 |ref=TASS2 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RA3m6ZDd?url=http://en.itar-tass.com/world/741164 |archivedate=18 July 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=\u0422\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0410\u043d-26 \u0441\u0431\u0438\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a\u0435 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u044b, \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043e\u0447\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0446\u044b |url=http://ria.ru/world/20140717/1016409306.html |website=ria.ru |agency=RIA Novosti |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=13 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RR2Ynt9a?url=http://ria.ru/world/20140717/1016409306.html |archivedate=29 July 2014 }}</ref> There was no evidence about altitude and weapons used.\n\nShortly after it became evident that it was a civilian aircraft which had crashed, the separatist media denied any responsibility and possession of anti-aircraft missiles capable of reaching the necessary altitude.<ref name=\"vk.com\">{{cite web |title=\u0421\u0432\u043e\u0434\u043a\u0438 \u043e\u0442 \u0421\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044f \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447\u0430 |url=http://vk.com/strelkov_info |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717152222/http://vk.com/strelkov_info |archivedate=17 July 2014 |website=VKontakte |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Arthur Bright\">{{cite web |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Europe/2014/0717/Web-evidence-points-to-pro-Russia-rebels-in-downing-of-MH17-video |title=Web evidence points to pro-Russia rebels in downing of MH17 (+video) |author=Arthur Bright |date=17 July 2014 |website=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\" />\n\n=== Conspiracy theories ===\nOn 18 July, Commander of the [[Donbass People's Militia]] [[Igor Strelkov (officer)|Igor Girkin]] was quoted as stating that \"a significant number of the bodies weren't fresh\". He followed up by saying \"Ukrainian authorities are capable of any baseness\"; and also claimed that blood serum and medications were found in the airplane's wreckage in large quantities.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/rebel-leader-gives-bizarre-account-plane-crash-182256709.html|title=Rebel leader gives bizarre account of plane crash|date=18 July 2014|accessdate=18 July 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140721032149/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/rebel-suggests-malaysia-plane-victims-long-dead|archivedate=21 July 2014|url-status=dead|work=Yahoo! News|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Girkin also claimed that some of the passengers had died a few days before the crash.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rusvesna.su/news/1405676334|author=\u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044c \u0421\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u043a\u043e\u0432|date=18 July 2014|publisher=RusVesna|language=Russian|script-title=ru:\u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044c \u0421\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u043a\u043e\u0432: \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043b\u044e\u0434\u0435\u0439 \u0438\u0437 \u0411\u043e\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0430 \u0443\u043c\u0435\u0440\u043b\u0438 \u0437\u0430 \u043d\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043a\u043e \u0441\u0443\u0442\u043e\u043a \u0434\u043e \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u044b|trans-title=Some of the Boeing's passengers died a few days before the crash|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RBLozt4P?url=http://rusvesna.su/news/1405676334|archivedate=19 July 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Russian government-funded<ref>{{cite news |last=Squires |first=Nick |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10976920/British-journalist-working-for-Russian-TV-resigns-over-bias-in-Ukraine-MH17-coverage.html |title=British journalist working for Russian TV resigns over bias in Ukraine MH17 coverage |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> outlet [[RT (TV network)|RT]] initially said that the airplane may have been shot down by Ukraine in a failed attempt to assassinate Vladimir Putin, in a plot which was organised by Ukraine's \"Western backers\". This was quickly dismissed as Putin's flight route was hundreds of kilometres north of Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wyborcza.pl/1,75477,16347795,Moskwa_obwinia_Ukraine.html?piano_t=1 |title='Zamach na Putina', 'Ile odszkodowa\u0144 zap\u0142ac\u0105 Ukrai\u0144cy' i zmiany w Wikipedii. Ofensywa propagandowa Moskwy |language=Polish|trans-title=\"The attempt on Putin\", \"How much compensation will pay Ukrainians\" and changes in Wikipedia. Moscow's propaganda offensive |url-access=subscription  |work=Gazeta Wyborcza |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |first=Wac\u0142aw |last=Radziwinowicz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.co.id/rt-malaysia-airlines-ukraine-2014-7/ |title=Here's The Ridiculous Way Russia's Propaganda Channel Is Covering The Malaysia Airlines Crash |last1=Szoldra |first1=Paul |website=Business Insider |date=18 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720054152/http://www.businessinsider.co.id/rt-malaysia-airlines-ukraine-2014-7/ |archivedate=20 July 2014  }}</ref>\n\nOther conspiracy theories propagated by Russian media included that the Ukrainians shot down the airplane by mistake, drawing parallels to downing [[Siberia Airlines Flight 1812]] in 2001 (reported in July{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} and in December 2014<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-30597555 |title=MH17: Russia reveals 'witness' who blames Ukraine pilot |publisher=BBC |date=24 December 2014 |accessdate=27 December 2014}}</ref>); that Ukrainian air traffic controllers purposefully redirected the flight to fly over the war zone (proven false by the DSB investigation); and that the Ukrainian government organised the attack on the airplane to bring infamy upon the pro-Russian rebels.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/russians-fed-conspiracy-theories-ukraine-crash-064400429.html |title=Russians Fed Conspiracy Theories on Ukraine Crash |work=Yahoo News |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014 |first=Laura |last=Mills |agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref>\n\nThe number of alternative theories disseminated in Russian mass media started growing as the DSB and JIT investigations increasingly pointed towards the separatists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://buran.ru/htm/mh17.htm|title=\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u043c\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0431 \u0440\u0435\u0439\u0441 \u041c\u041d17 \u043d\u0430\u0434 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0431\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043e\u043c? \u0411\u0440\u0438\u0444\u0438\u043d\u0433 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|website=buran.ru|access-date=6 August 2016}}</ref> On 15 November 2014, Russia's [[Channel One Russia|Channel One]] reported on a supposedly leaked spy satellite photo which showed the airplane being shot from behind by a Ukrainian Su-25 fighter jet.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.1tv.ru/news/social/271864 |title=\u0421\u043d\u0438\u043c\u043e\u043a \u043c\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0439\u0437\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \"\u0411\u043e\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0430\", \u0441\u0431\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u043e\u043c, \u043e\u0431\u0441\u0443\u0436\u0434\u0430\u044e\u0442 \u0432\u043e \u0432\u0441\u0435\u043c \u043c\u0438\u0440\u0435 |date=15 November 2014 |website=Channel One Russia}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Russia's Channel One show satellite photo evidencing MH17 was downed by fighter jet |work=TASS |date=14 November 2014 |accessdate=15 November 2014 |url=http://en.itar-tass.com/world/759835}}</ref> Many other Russian media reprinted the photo but its authenticity was immediately dismissed as the airplanes were out of scale which indicated poor copy-and-paste.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/world/sensational-russian-photo-of-mh17-being-shot-debunked-by-citizen-journalist-group-20141115-11nbqs.html |title='Sensational' Russian photo of MH17 being shot debunked by citizen journalist group |last=Miller |first=Nick |date=15 November 2014 |accessdate=15 November 2014 |newspaper=The Age}}</ref> Later it was disclosed, that the photo had been initially emailed to the Vice-President of the [[Russian Union of Engineers]] by a self-described aviation expert who had found it on a Russian online forum.<ref name=\"BUZZnov2014\">{{citation |title=Russian TV Airs Clearly Fake Image To Claim Ukraine Shot Down MH17 |first=Max |last=Seddon |date=15 November 2014 |accessdate=15 October 2014 |work=BuzzFeed |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/maxseddon/russian-tv-airs-clearly-fake-image-to-claim-ukraine-shot-dow}}</ref> The aviation expert later apologised, saying that he was unhappy with how the information had been used.<ref name=\"BUZZnov2014\" /> In a later interview by magazine ''[[The New Yorker]]'', Channel One CEO [[Konstantin Ernst]] admitted that reporting on the satellite photo was a \"simple error\", saying that it was a human mistake not made on purpose.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/12/16/the-kremlins-creative-director|title=The Kremlin\u2019s Creative Director|date=9 December 2019|work=The New Yorker|first=Joshua|last=Yaffa|accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, Sara Firth, who had worked as a correspondent with RT for the previous five years, resigned in protest at the channel's coverage of the crash, which she described as \"lies\".<ref name=\"sarafirth\">{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/travel/travel-updates/mh17-fallout-russian-reporter-sara-firth-quits-over-ukraine-lies/story-fnizu68q-1226994372531|title=MH17 fallout: Russian reporter Sara Firth quits over Ukraine 'lies'|date=28 March 2014|work=News.com.au|accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> RT said Firth had left to take another job.<ref name=\"ReporterResigns\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/jul/18/mh17-russia-today-reporter-resigns-sara-firth-kremlin-malaysia|title=Russia Today reporter resigns in protest at MH17 coverage|work=The Guardian|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Dutch newspaper ''[[NRC Handelsblad]]'' described how false stories about the MH17 crash had been propagated with the support of [[Christian Democratic Appeal]] politician [[Pieter Omtzigt]], who introduced a Russian-speaking Ukrainian man as an \"eyewitness\" to the crash on a public expert debate in May 2017. The man, who was an asylum-seeker from Ukraine, did not witness the crash and his speech, texted to him by Omtzigt prior to the interview, repeated the Russian-promoted version that Ukrainian jets downed the Boeing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2017/11/10/hoe-twijfel-rond-mh17-in-de-hand-wordt-gewerkt-13959091-a1580806|title=Hoe twijfel rond MH17 in de hand wordt gewerkt|work=NRC|access-date=13 November 2017|language=nl}}</ref>\n\n=== The \"Ukrainian Buk\" version ===\nIn May 2015, ''Novaya Gazeta'' published a report by \"a group of Russian military engineers\" that came to the conclusion that the airplane was shot down by a [[Buk missile system|Buk-M1 launcher]] with 9M38M1 missile. The authors also analysed the visible impact traces on the surface of the airplane and suggested that the missile couldn't have been fired from [[Snizhne]], but was instead fired from [[Zaroshchenske]] and claimed that a Ukrainian anti-air unit was located there at that time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.novayagazeta.ru/inquests/68332.html |title=\u042d\u0442\u043e \u0431\u044b\u043b \"\u0411\u0443\u043a-\u041c1\" |publisher=Novaya Gazeta |date=5 May 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2015 |trans-title=This was \"Buk-M1\"}}</ref> In June 2015, the report was the subject of a press conference and was attributed to Mikhail Malisevskiy, chief engineer at Moscow-headquartered [[Almaz-Antey]], the Buk missile manufacturer.<ref name=\"TheAgeAlmaz\">{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/world/mh17-plane-was-shot-down-by-a-buk-missile-russian-weapons-manufacturer-says-20150602-ghfdco.html |title=MH17 plane was shot down by a Buk missile, Russian weapons manufacturer says |author=Nick Miller |date=2 June 2015}}</ref> The [[Security Service of Ukraine]] said that there were inaccuracies in this version, and called part of the report a fake.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stopfake.org/sbu-novye-dokazatelstva-krusheniya-boeing-na-donbasse-osnovany-na-fejkovyh-snimkah/ |title=\u0421\u0411\u0423: \u041d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \"\u0434\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430\" \u043a\u0440\u0443\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f Boeing \u043d\u0430 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0431\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0435 \u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u044b \u043d\u0430 \u0444\u0435\u0439\u043a\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u043d\u0438\u043c\u043a\u0430\u0445 |date=6 May 2015 |accessdate=6 May 2015 |website= |publisher=StopFake.org|trans-title = SBU called the Russian analysis on Boeing based on fake photos}}</ref> Russian military expert Vadim Lukashevich argued on [[TV Rain]] that the spatial orientation of the rocket at the moment of explosion did not exclude the possibility that it was launched from Snizhne, as the report claimed. Lukashevich also noted that the report admitted a Buk missile as the cause of the crash, discrediting the previous theories about the crash (Su-25 etc.) circulated in Russian media.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.tvrain.ru/teleshow/here_and_now/ja_ne_uvidel_v_etom_doklade_ekspertov_vpk_aviatsio-386961/ |title=\u042f \u043d\u0435 \u0443\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043b \u0432 \u044d\u0442\u043e\u043c \u0434\u043e\u043a\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0435 \u044d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u0412\u041f\u041a\". \u0410\u0432\u0438\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u044d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0442 \u041b\u0443\u043a\u0430\u0448\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u043e \u0442\u043e\u043c, \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0438 \u0437\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043c \u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043b \u0434\u043e\u043a\u0443\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442, \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0434\u043e\u0431\u044b\u0442\u044b\u0439 \"\u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0439 |date=6 May 2015 |accessdate=6 May 2015 |website= |publisher=TV Rain |last=Lukashevich |first=Vadim|trans-title = \"I haven't seen military experts in that report\", aviation expert Lukashevich who and why published the report leaked by Novaya Gazeta}}</ref> ''[[Ukrainska Pravda]]'' questioned claims about the Ukrainian anti-aircraft unit and stated that Zaroshchenske was under control of pro-Russian forces on the day of shootdown.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2015/05/6/7066943/ |title=\u0417\u041c\u0406: \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0456 \u0435\u043a\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0438 \u0432 \u0441\u0435\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0442\u043d\u0456\u0439 \u0434\u043e\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u0456 \u043f\u0456\u0434\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0434\u0438\u043b\u0438, \u0449\u043e \u0411\u043e\u0457\u043d\u0433 \u0437\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0437 \"\u0411\u0443\u043a\u0430\" |date=6 May 2015 |accessdate=6 May 2015 |website= |publisher=Ukrainska Pravda|trans-title = Media: Russian experts confirmed in secret report, that Boeing was shot by \"Buk\"}}</ref> ''Novaya Gazeta'' published a long analysis by Mark Solonin, also denying the Almaz-Antey version,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.novayagazeta.ru/inquests/68376.html |title=\u0421\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043c \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0438 |date=12 May 2015 |website=Novaya Gazeta |last=Solonin |first=Mark}}</ref> interviewed inhabitants of Zaroshchenske who denied claims that Ukrainian forces and Buk launchers were present in the village at that time.<ref>{{cite web |title=There Was No Buk in Our Field |url=http://www.interpretermag.com/there-was-no-buk-in-our-field/ |website=The Interpreter |accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u041d\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0448\u0435\u043c \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0435 \"\u0411\u0443\u043a\u0430\" \u043d\u0435 \u0431\u044b\u043b\u043e. \u041d\u0438 \u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0430 \u2013 \u043d\u0438 \u043e\u0442 \u0433\u0443\u0441\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0446, \u043d\u0438 \u043e\u0442 \u0432\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0441\u0438\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0430 |url=http://www.novayagazeta.ru/inquests/68728.html |accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref> According to [[Bellingcat]], Russia's satellite images were from June and showed signs of editing.<ref name=\"Bell150531\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2015/05/31/mh17-forensic-analysis-of-satellite-images-released-by-the-russian-ministry-of-defence/ |title=MH17 \u2013 Forensic Analysis of Satellite Images Released by the Russian Ministry of Defence |work=Bellingcat |date=31 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"DW150601\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dw.de/forensic-report-russia-faked-mh17-satellite-photos/a-18490259 |title=Forensic report: Russia faked MH17 satellite photos |first=Conor |last=Dillon |publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]] |date=1 June 2015}}</ref> ''[[Bild]]'' described the Russian satellite image as \"fake\".<ref name=\"Bild150508\">{{cite news |url=http://www.bild.de/politik/ausland/flug-mh-17/russische-beweise-gefaelscht-40861842.bild.html |title=BILD entlarvt falsche Satellitenaufnahme |language=German |trans-title= BILD exposes false satellite image |first=Julian |last=R\u00f6pcke |work=[[Bild]] |date=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 September 2018, Russia's Ministry of Defence held a press conference that aimed to cast doubt on Moscow's culpability for the tragedy. Lt. Gen. Nikolai Parshin, chief of the Missile and Artillery Directorate, said that after Dutch investigators displayed parts of the missile and their serial numbers, they studied and declassified archives at the research center that produced the Buk missiles. Parshin said the Russian archives show that the missile that was made of these parts was transported to a military unit in western Ukraine in 1986, and to Russia's knowledge never left Ukraine. Officials also claimed that video evidence presented by the Joint Investigation Team (JIT), in which the missile that allegedly shot down the airplane was shown being moved from Russia into Ukraine, was fabricated.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/09/17/world/europe/ap-eu-russia-mh17.html |title= Russia: Missile That Shot Down Flight MH17 Was Ukrainian |date= 17 September 2018 |work= The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nJIT responded that it had requested details about recovered missile parts from Russia in May 2018, but had received no answer. It said, information from the Russian Ministry of Defence would be carefully studied as soon as the documents were made available, as requested in May 2018 and required by [[United Nations Security Council|UNSC]] in 2016. JIT stated it had always carefully analysed information provided by Russia, but information presented to the public was inaccurate on several points. Russia had given differing accounts over time of how MH17 was shot down; for example claiming to have evidence (radar images) that a Ukrainian fighter fired an air-to-air missile at MH17.<ref>{{cite news |title=MH17 crash: Dutch ask Russia to submit new claims |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45546611 |accessdate=18 September 2018 |work=BBC News |date=18 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= Landelijk Parket |title=Reaction JIT to press conference of Russian Ministry of Defense |url=https://www.om.nl/actueel/nieuwsberichten/@104053/reaction-jit-to/ |website=Openbaar Ministerie |accessdate=18 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Oleksandr Turchynov]], secretary of [[National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine]], said in September 2018 that Russia's claim was \"yet another failed fake report that the Kremlin made up in order to cover up their crime that has been proven by the official investigation as well as independent experts.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.newsweek.com/russian-propaganda-moscow-releases-audio-blaming-ukraine-downing-mh17-flight-1124371 |title= Russian propaganda? Moscow releases audio blaming Ukraine downing MH17 flight that killed almost 300 |date= 17 September 2018 |work= Newsweek}}</ref>\n\n==Maps==\n{{col-float|width=320px}}\n{{Location map many\n| Afro-Eurasia\n| relief      = 1\n| width       = 300\n| float       = none\n| caption     = Location of departure, crash site and destination\n| alt         = Location of crash site; departure and destination airports\n| <!--first label/marker-->\n| label1      = {{nowrap|Amsterdam Airport Schiphol}}\n| label1_size = <!-- or: label_size -->\n| position1   = <!-- or: position, pos1, pos -->\n| background1 = <!-- or: background, bg1, bg -->\n| mark1       = Green pog.svg\n| mark1size   =\n| link1       = <!-- or: link -->\n| lat1_deg    = 52\n| lat1_min    = 18\n| lat1_sec    = 29\n| lat1_dir    = N\n| lon1_deg    = 4\n| lon1_min    = 45\n| lon1_sec    = 51\n| lon1_dir    = E\n| <!--second label/marker-->\n| label2      = Crash site\n| label2_size =\n| position2   = bottom\n| background2 = <!-- or: bg2 -->\n| mark2       = Airplane Crash.svg\n| mark2size   = 10\n| link2       =\n| lat2_deg    = 48\n| lat2_min    = 8\n| lat2_sec    = 17\n| lat2_dir    = N\n| lon2_deg    = 38\n| lon2_min    = 38\n| lon2_sec    = 20\n| lon2_dir    = E\n| <!--third label/marker-->\n| label3      = {{nowrap|Kuala Lumpur}} {{nowrap|International 